<SLUG> BC-TEN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: CROATIA, ITALY, SLOVAKIA, RUSSIA, N.J.)  
 TENNIS NOTEBOOK: SHOPPING AT THE U.S. OPEN; SUING OVER THE U.S.
OPEN; LONG SHOTS AT THE U.S. OPEN; THE N.J. OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Open tennis championships, which began Monday, are akin
to a two-week trip to the mall, with forehands and backhands added.
</P>
<P>
   At the sprawling National Tennis Center, there was tennis, to be
sure. There was also an orgy of things to buy, notably leisure
clothing, food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   Strips of shops outside the courts offered rackets _ Prince from
$55 to $290, Yonex from $99 to $240, stringing included. From the
US Open Collection, there were sweatshirts from $58 to $105,
polo-style shirts from $52 to $70 and baseball caps from $20 to
$23. For $120, Bolle was selling sunglasses that muted all colors
except optic yellow, a boon for players using yellow tennis balls.
</P>
<P>
   At the food court, you could buy a kosher hot pastrami sandwich
for $10.50 or 10 Buffalo chicken wings for $9.75 or a chicken
Ceaser (that's the way it was spelled) salad for $7.95. You could
wash that down with a strawberry daiquiri ($7) or a Pepsi ($3.25).
Pepsi is a sponsor, so there was not a Coke to be had. The
well-connected ate at the U.S. Open Club (``Occupancy by more than
649 persons is dangerous and unlawful.''). The Grand Buffet was
$28.95, the chicken Caesar (spelled correctly) salad $14 and the
Pepsi still $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   As for the tennis, it was everywhere simultaneously, from the
22,500-seat Arthur Ashe Stadium, the scaled-down, 10,000-seat Louis
Armstrong Stadium, the 5,000-seat grandstand and the 15 field
courts, where seating ranged from 288 to 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   As usually happens during the first few days of the tournament,
most spectators roamed the grounds. They watched such seeded
players as Dominique Van Roost, Barbara Schett and Amelie Mauresmo
winning on the field courts and Andre Agassi and Alexandra
Stevenson practicing. When Venus Williams rushed through a
54-minute victory over Tatiana Poutchek, at least half of the seats
in Arthur Ashe Stadium were empty.
</P>
<P>
   PROTESTING FOR INNER CITIES
</P>
<P>
   William Washington, a tennis coach and father, filed a complaint
Friday in U.S. District Court in New York against the U.S. Tennis
Association, which governs American tennis and conducts the Open.
Washington, an African-American, said there was a lack of player
development in inner cities and discrimination in selecting Olympic
and Davis Cup teams.
</P>
<P>
   His tennis-playing children were given three of the 16 wild-card
berths in the Open. Mashiska, 25, ranked 312th in the world among
men, lost Monday to Jan Kroslak of Slovakia, 6-1, 2-6, 7-6 (7-3),
7-5. Mashona, 23, ranked 159th among women, will play Jelena
Kostanic of Croatia Tuesday. MalaVai, 31, the Wimbledon men's
runner-up in 1996, withdrew last week after reinjuring a knee.
</P>
<P>
   Mashiska Washington had no comment on the complaint. But he said
he definitely felt his first-round performance justified his wild
card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all American players should have an opportunity to
play America's tournament,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also made it clear that his father's campaign opened the door
for him. He said: ``Would I be drinking from the same water
fountain you would if certain people wouldn't have protested? Do
things come up voluntarily or do things accidentally happen?
Self-explanatory.''
</P>
<P>
   A PITCH FOR TEEN-AGERS
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov on whether 19-year-old Marat
Safin, his Davis Cup teammate from Russia, will match up well
against No. 1-seeded Pete Sampras: ``I would think so. He's got
nothing to lose. It's a perfect, perfect position for him to be in.
Nobody really expects him to win. Perhaps he has a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen-year-old Philip King of Long Beach, Calif., the U.S.
boys' 18 champion, after losing to 12th-seeded Richard Krajicek:
``When I was in elementary school, I worked a couple of nights a
week in my dad's fish-and-chips shop. I was cashier. I didn't do
any cooking. I wasn't tall enough back then. I couldn't reach over
the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE TO HOME FOR GIMELSTOB
</P>
<P>
   For Justin Gimelstob, one of the young hopes in American tennis,
playing in the U.S. Open so close to his home state, New Jersey,
has advantages and disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always get good support here,'' said Gimelstob, who defeated
Andrea Gaudenzi of Italy, 6-1, 6-3, 6-2, in the first round. ``I
have to understand how to use that as an advantage, not as
something that works against me.'' He said he had taken steps to
cut down on distractions during the two weeks of the Open. He said
callers to his cellular phone get a recorded message, saying:
``Hey, how you doing, you've reached Justin, blah, blah, blah. If
you've called about tickets, call someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob admitted that the victory over Gaudenzi meant a little
more after the Davis Cup loss to Italy in last year's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff sticks with me more than it should,'' Gimelstob
said. ``They stuck it to us pretty good.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
