<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Streak ends at 10 as Reds sock Glavine
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ After finding every possible way to win for 10
games, the Braves found a bunch of ways to lose Monday night _ and
most of them were aimed over Tom Glavine's head _ as their longest
winning streak in seven years came to a screeching halt in an 11-3
pounding by the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   With Glavine as the whipping boy for two of their three home
runs, the Reds opened a three-game series with their first win in
seven games against the Braves this season. The Braves' NL East
lead slipped to 2 1/2 games over the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be the guy who ends (the streak), but with
every win the law of averages is bound to catch up with you,'' said
Glavine, who lost to the Reds for the first time since 1996 and for
only the third time in 17 decisions at Cinergy Field. ``I don't
feel like I pitched as badly as the line score indicated, but
unfortunately that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine gave up six earned runs in four innings, his shortest
and least effective outing since giving up a career-high nine runs
to Milwaukee on May 24. He dropped to 11-10, but the loss was the
first for the Braves in his last eight starts. Home runs by Walt
Weiss and Andruw Jones in the fourth inning cut Cincinnati's lead
to 4-3, but Glavine couldn't hold back the Reds. That was evident
when he gave up a single to Barry Larkin and a two-run homer to
Sean Casey in the bottom of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, he just didn't look comfortable out there,''
Chipper Jones said of Glavine. ``He got behind hitters and when
he's forced to come over the plate, people are going to hit him.
You've got to give credit to their hitters. Tommy's great at
expanding the strike zone. They didn't swing at any bad pitches all
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' bats were chilled by a series worth of good pitching
from the Braves last week, but they made up for it with the most
runs off Atlanta pitching since an 11-6 loss in Toronto on July 20.
Denny Neagle earned his first win in three tries this year against
his former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any loss to end a streak is going to be painful,'' Chipper
Jones said. ``We were probably due to play a poor game. As long as
it doesn't carry over into tomorrow, we can accept it and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
