<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT ATHLETICS 7-4  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.,   Mass.)   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aside from one speedbump, the Yankees continued to
steamroll toward the postseason Monday night, rallying from a 4-0
deficit to defeat the Oakland Athletics, 7-4, after being held
hitless and scoreless into the fifth inning at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu labored for the second straight game, though,
allowing four runs on four hits in 4 1/3 innings. He has struggled
in his last two starts. After winning eight straight decisions
earlier this season, Irabu has been hit hard and often since the
7-3 loss at Texas last week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Irabu got beat up again. When he left the game,
the Yankees were trailing by 4-0. Even on ground outs and fly outs,
Irabu's pitches were hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets behind in the count,'' said Yankees manager Joe Torre.
``The splitter just wasn't there tonight. That's the pitch that got
him in trouble. He has to keep working on it. We just need to find
that splitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Irabu's recent struggles are reminiscent of his
problems during the second half of last season, Torre said: ``I
think he's a better pitcher that he was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But it could not have been a comforting sight for the Yankees,
who continue to steamroll toward the postseason. Irabu struggled
the second half of last season and was left off the postseason
pitching roster. Postseason rosters for this season must be
considered soon.
</P>
<P>
   While Irabu struggled, his counterpart, rookie Tim Hudson, was
cruising through the Yankees lineup. Hudson held the Yankees
hitless through 4 2/3 innings in front of 32,712 fans at the
Stadium. But after controlling the game early on, Hudson (8-2)
inexplicably fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind by 4-0 early in Monday night's game, the
Yankees came back to tie the game in the fifth inning at 4-4 and
then put the game away in the eighth inning, scoring three runs as
the A's pitching completely unraveled. A's reliever Buddy Groom
allowed three crucial runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees started the comeback in the fifth inning, scoring
four runs on five straight hits off Hudson to tie the score at 4-4.
Chuck Knoblauch hit a three run home run, nailing a Hudson changeup
over the leftfield wall with Jorge Posada and Luis Sojo aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees bullpen was solid again. Allen Watson was
outstanding in middle relief, Jeff Nelson shutdown the A's and
Mariano Rivera came in to close out the game.
</P>
<P>
   The A's took a 2-0 lead in the second inning on a two-run home
run by Miguel Tejada. Irabu left a changeup about waist high, right
over the middle of the plate and Tejada drilled inside of the
rightfield fair pole. Ben Grieve, the A's leftfielder, was on base.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu was hit hard again in the fourth inning, surrendering two
more runs as the A's lead grew to 4-0. Irabu was relieved by Allen
Watson, who bailed out the Yankees, striking out Ben Grieve and
getting Tejada to ground out, with A's on first and third. Watson
has pitched 7 2/3 straight scoreless inning in his last three
relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The A's, whose offense has exploded for a league-best 192 runs
in August, are a major player in the American League wild card
race. Entering Tuesday night's game, the A's (71-59) were one game
behind Boston (72-58). Should the A's capture the wild card, and
the Yankees win the AL, these two teams could meet in the first
round of the playoffs. But Torre downplayed any relevance the
four-game series, which began Monday night, could have on the
postseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
