<SLUG> BC-NY-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WIELDING HAMMER FATALLY SHOT BY POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mentally disturbed man wielding a hammer was shot
at least seven times and killed by police in the Borough Park
section of Brooklyn Monday night, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting of the man, an Orthodox Jew identified by police as
Gidone Busch, brought several hundred angry Jews into the street to
protest what they said was excessive force by police. The
protesters chanted ``justice,'' strained against barricades and
occasionally threw objects at police, but no one was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   An officer who tried to subdue the man was hit several times
with the hammer and hurt his arm, police said, but the officer was
not seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Busch, 29, was known on his block of 46th Street in Borough Park
for his outbursts, and had been the subject of many calls to police
before, neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   Police were called to Busch's house, at 1619 46th St., about
6:40 p.m. Monday, said Detective Robert Samuel, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   When the four officers reached the house, Busch confronted them
with the hammer, Samuel said. Police ordered Busch to drop it and
one officer sprayed him with tear gas, but the man lunged at an
officer with the hammer, and police opened fire, Samuel said.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator at the scene said the officers fired seven to 15
shots. Busch was dead on arrival at Maimonides Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   A witness who would give his name only as Leo said that police
warned Busch three times to drop the hammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time, he came out swinging,'' the man said. ``He
jumped out of the basement swinging. He had a hammer in one hand
and something else in the other hand. Before they shot him, he held
it up as a cross. They pulled out their guns. They warned him a
second time. The third time he swung it like a baseball bat. Then
they started shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Police and other officials at the scene said Busch was from New
Jersey and had moved to Borough Park six months ago. Officials said
that when he was shot, he was wearing a prayer shawl and teffilin _
leather boxes hung from straps and containing pieces of scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Borough Park's city councilman, Noach Dear, called on the crowd
not to rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of rumors out there,'' Dear said above the noise
of shouts and banging. ``We need to have a full investigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
