<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS BEATS WIND AND OPPONENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS Agassi and Hingis winning in 4th through 6th grafs , edits to
conform) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN      
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All bluster and no balm, the U.S. Open, inarguably
the most chaotic Grand Slam, got under way Monday at the National
Tennis Center. Those who coped with the ball-bullying breezes moved
one round closer to a record $750,000 payday. Those who couldn't
cope moped home with their $10,000 condolence checks.
</P>
<P>
   And anybody in the crowd of 27,809, a record for an Open day
session, who neglected to tote a windbreaker along with their
binoculars was doomed to shiver just the way third-seeded Venus
Williams did in her backless blue dress. No wonder she made like a
gale-force wind and whipped through her initial assignment in a
scant 54 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the Arthur Ashe Stadium, the upsets occurred inside the
players' minds _ as exasperated tennis technicians watched
textbook-executed shots spirited up and out of bounds _ but not on
the scoreboard. First, 10th-seeded Arantxa Sanchez &UR; - &LR; Vicario, the
Open's 1994 champion, then eighth-seeded Carlos Moya, the 1998
French Open champion, and finally Williams, still a Grand Slam
champion wannabe, used the adverse conditions to handcuff their
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   In the night session, an inspired Andre Agassi provided his own
whirlwind: The second-ranked Las Vegan pulverized Nicklas Kulti of
Sweden, 10 years ago the world's No.1 junior but relegated Monday
night to the role of a prop in the Agassi show, 6-0, 6-1, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the place to be; this is the place so much great
tennis played this year is coming down to,'' said Agassi, this
year's French Open champion and the U.S. Open's most enthusiastic
leading man. ``It brings focus of its own, being here. I love the
energy of the crowd. It almost feels like theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Agassi's evening, Martina Hingis's was slow to resolve
itself. It took her almost as long to play two sets as Agassi took
for three. After a nearly flawless first set, the top-seeded
Hingis, intent on doing remedial work for her failures at the
French Open and Wimbledon, scrambled out of a 3-0 second-set
deficit and then had to serve twice for the match before
eliminating 74th-ranked Kveta Hrdlickova, &QC; 6-1, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very windy, and I had to improvise some,'' said
Williams, whose shotmaking, whether rote or inventive, was too much
for 145th-ranked Tatiana Poutchek, a ponytailed Belarussian now
coached by Natasha Zvereva's father, Marat Zverev. Despite
acquitting herself favorably in the Open's qualifying rounds,
Poutchek bowed out of her first-ever visit to a Grand Slam
tournament's main draw, 6-1, 6-2, a victim of the 19-year-old
Williams' superior brawn and court coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Venus is a favorite'; people actually think Venus
is going to win,'' said Williams, whose Open fan club includes
athletes Ricky Williams, Keyshawn Johnson and Rickey Henderson and
is headed up by her loquacious coach and father, Richard, who has
been telling anyone who will listen that his daughters will be
locking horns in the final in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Very much to their liking, Venus Williams and her younger
sibling, the seventh-seeded Serena, landed on opposite sides of the
draw here, and Monday Venus defended the family's tactic of
scheduling its two stars for different tournaments except at the
Grand Slam events. ``If it's a crime, I should be arrested,'' she
joked about her preference for avoiding matches with her sister.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old Poutchek, who spent 1994 in the United States
taking her tennis training at the Brooklyn Racquet Club, never got
the chance to avoid Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't difficult at all, especially since I knew I
was much more experienced than her; whenever I faced a break point
or she had a game point, I knew exactly what to do with the ball,''
said Williams, who described herself as eight titles and 61 ranking
spots better than the unseeded rookie who gilded her phenom status
by reaching the 1997 final. ``I have a bigger serve, make better
decisions, cover the net more, things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Williams did not underestimate her unpolished opponent the
way she did this year at the French Open, where another
inexperienced qualifier, 125th-ranked Barbara Schwartz of Austria,
upended her in the fourth round. ``I've learned my lesson; I had to
learn it the hard way, in a Grand Slam,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's most prolific champion, the 27-year-old
Sanchez &UR; - &LR; Vicario, administered a lesson of sorts to Australia's
Jelena Dokic, the Belgrade native who as a 16-year-old qualifier
rode a wave of upsets, including a victory over Hingis in the first
round, to this year's Wimbledon quarterfinals. Down by 4-1 in the
first set, the Spaniard accepted the wind factor, adjusted her
patience quotient, and started making Dokic, last year's Open
junior champion, do all the running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried never to get upset,'' Sanchez &UR; - &LR; Vicario said of her
7-5, 6-1 victory. ``It was difficult with the wind. You have to be
looking at the ball really careful, be very concentrated. As long
as you feel you can compete with them, it's fine,'' she said of the
influx of teen-agers that's rejuvenated the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic, limited by the Women's Tennis Association's age
eligibility rules to 10 events plus the Grand Slam tournaments,
blamed her defeat on a loss of patience brought on by a lack of
sufficient match play. ``I started making errors and just gave a
lot away,'' she said. ``Knowing you've got five tournaments for the
next eight months, that's a big difference compared to most of the
players who can play as much as they want. At Wimbledon I came
through qualifying, which is much tougher; it was a different
story. It was a different player.''
</P>
<P>
   What Spain's top male player, the eighth-seeded Moya, contended
with Monday was a player with a history of making life difficult
for stars at Grand Slam events. But fortunately for Moya,
22nd-ranked Dominik Hrbaty of Slovakia did not temper his game in
the swirling conditions, made 60 unforced errors and paid an
obvious price, a 7-6 (7-4), 6-3, 6-4 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very windy and very fast, and when you play with windy
conditions, you have to be more conservative because the ball
doesn't go where you want the ball to go,'' Moya said. ``If it's
windy, if it's not windy, he's hitting so hard, he doesn't care
about anything. When he plays well, everything is in; when he plays
bad, he doesn't try to change his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia, in a scramble here
with second-seeded Agassi for Pete Sampras' top ranking, was
harried by the wind and a human ball machine of an opponent,
Alberto Martin, but escaped with a 6-1, 3-6, 6-3, 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind makes my life so miserable, I had to struggle,''
Kafelnikov said, ``but I'm glad I got through.''
</P>
<P>
   The only seeded player who did not get through the first round
Monday was No. 6 Amanda Coetzer of South Africa, who fell by 6-1,
7-5 to Irina Spirlea, the contentious Romanian who exchanged the
infamous semifinal changeover bump with Venus Williams in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
