r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     08-31 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENNETT HAS JITTERS, BUT ISN'T WORRIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA quarterback Drew Bennett figures he'll be as
nervous for his first college start as he was for his first high
school start in 1995. That's good and bad news for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw three (interceptions),'' Bennett recalled, ``but we
won.''
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-year junior, Bennett isn't worried about his
performance Saturday against Boise State. He knows the system and
the personnel. He's excited, he's eager, and yes, he's nervous. But
he's not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could all change when I get in the game, but right now I
think I'm prepared,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he'll be thinking as kickoff approaches, Bennett
said: ``I just hope my palms are dry enough to throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his family will attend the game, he said: ``I told my
brother, who goes to Arizona, to come. In a worst-case scenario,
this could be my only start.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Bennett hasn't lost his sense of humor. Then again,
Cade McNown, whose grit Bennett hopes to emulate, never joked about
failing _ not even during his freshman season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins aren't concerned about Bennett's grasp of the
offense, his athleticism or his arm, which was inconsistent in
training camp. But they don't know what to make of his head: Is he
tough enough? How will he react to the pressure? Will he make the
proper decisions?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``That's the
thing that makes it exciting. He hasn't looked great in practices,
but in scrimmages, he's turned it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers: Less than half of UCLA's 1992-93 freshman class
graduated within six years, according to graduation rates released
Monday by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The figures represent a significant drop from the previous year.
While 63 percent of the 1991-92 entering freshman graduated, only
49 percent of the 1992-93 class earned degrees.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA credited part of the decline to the elimination of men's
swimming and men's gymnastics in June of 1994, which prompted a
slew of athletes to transfer. (Transfers count as non-graduates
from their originating school, whether they graduate somewhere else
or not.)
</P>
<P>
   The football team's graduation rate dropped from 65 percent for
the 1992 freshman class to 53 percent for the 1993 class. The men's
basketball team increased its graduation rate from 50 percent for
the 1992 class to 67 percent for the 1993 class: Kevin Dempsey and
Marquis Burns received degrees, while Ike Nwankwo did not.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer update: UCLA will remove the protective boot from
receiver Danny Farmer's sprained left ankle today, and he'll jog
lightly for the first time since suffering the injury 10 days ago.
He's listed as doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Two for two-way: After two weeks of experimentation, it's
official: tailback DeShaun Foster will play safety and receiver
Freddie Mitchell will play cornerback Saturday in passing
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Farmer also practiced with the secondary but will
not play defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
