<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TEACHER-SHORTAGE-1STL     08-31 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-SHORTAGE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY DISTRICTS COPE WITH SEVERE SHORTAGE OF TEACHERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS that qualified teachers tend to clustered in Midwest in 9th
graf of 2nd take.) 
(ATTN: Texas, Fla., D.C., Minn., Wis., Calif., N.Y., Mass.)   (jw) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As children across the United States swarm back to school,
principals from the nation's capital to Palm Beach, Fla., and from
Houston to Los Angeles say they face the most serious teacher
shortage in recent memory, one that has been caused by swelling
enrollments and a push to reduce class sizes while more teachers
are retiring.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not a depleted pool of teachers nationwide: there
are at least 180,000 recent graduates with teaching degrees and
about 80,000 veterans looking for new jobs, enough to fill the
estimated 200,000 teaching vacancies posted in the nation's public
schools since last school year, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The driving issues are geography and expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers in states where there are sometimes hundreds of
applicants for one teaching slot, including Minnesota and
Wisconsin, have been largely unwilling to move to those states most
in need, including Texas and California. And even those teachers
game for a change of scenery are often untrained in the subjects
where shortages are greatest: mathematics, science, special
education and bilingual studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is true that at this point, more districts are
feeling the increase in demand,'' said Linda Darling-Hammond, a
professor of education at Stanford University and the director of
the National Commission on Teaching and America's Future, a private
organization that has studied the issue closely. ``In some cases
they haven't planned ahead and done aggressive recruiting, and in
others there really is a shortfall.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact has been felt in places large and small, from Texas,
where there are an estimated 20,000 openings, to Belle Glade, Fla.,
a town of migrant citrus farmers near Palm Beach, which was still
searching for two first-grade teachers Monday, two weeks after the
school year began.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of teachers, to say nothing of those trained to teach
in specific subjects, districts and states have stepped up the
competition for candidates in ways that mirror the private sector
and were unheard of even five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Washington, D.C., began offering $1,000 signing
bonuses to applicants certified to teach in the general classroom,
$2,000 for those with a background in special education and $3,000
for anyone demonstrating proficiency in special education and an
additional specialty. These incentives come on top of a $3,700
raise for starting teachers _ to $31,000 this fall from $27,300
last year _ and assorted other sweeteners like $500 for relocation
assistance and $250 for school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, desperate districts persuaded the state Legislature to
pass a law permitting them to rehire recent retirees _ while
allowing the retirees to keep drawing their pensions.
</P>
<P>
   And in the New Haven Unified School District in Union City,
Calif., a district of 14,000 students outside of Oakland, the
effort to attract out-of-town talent has gotten so sophisticated
that candidates are directed to the nearest Kinko's copy shop to be
linked live with district recruiters over video-conferencing lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hired a special-ed teacher from New York through the
video interviewing,'' said Jim O'Laughlin, the personnel director
for the district. ``We've met her on TV, which is the same as
sitting across the table.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City _ which has tended to be among the last
districts in the nation to complete its hiring each year, limiting
its choices _ three early job fairs and a statewide recruiting push
have paid a dividend: the city Board of Education believes it has
has hired enough teachers to reduce class sizes to 25, from 28 or
so, in the fourth through eighth grades in its 40 lowest-performing
schools, district officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But administrators say they have all but abandoned the goal of
replacing hundreds of unlicensed math, science and
special-education teachers in those schools, and elsewhere in the
five boroughs, because of a shortage of interested, qualified
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, numerous factors have conspired to place
other districts in similar straits.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's public-school population, for example, continues to
bulge, with the 50 million students who occupied classrooms in 1995
expected to grow to 54.3 million by 2007, an average increase of
about 358,000 annually, Dr. Darling-Hammond said.
</P>
<P>
   To meet that need, districts would have to add 300,000 teachers,
raising the national teaching staff to 3.3 million by 2007, from 3
million in 1995, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that effort is already being hobbled by retirements from
faculties that are unmistakably aging: nearly 1 million teachers
are between the ages of 45 and 53, with hundreds of thousands
expected to retire when they reach 55, if not sooner. In New York
City alone, union officials estimate that 17,000 teachers will
retire after this school year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the widening movement to reduce class sizes.
In California, for example, a mandate to hold class sizes to 20 in
kindergarten through third grade, as well as in ninth-grade English
and math, has been augmented this year to include eighth-grade
English.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Marubayashi, the associate director of the California
Center for Teaching Careers, a state agency, said that about 10
percent of teachers hired by districts statewide, in part to meet
such goals, do not have the proper credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, she said, districts have been hiring candidates
they rejected earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sad story,'' she said. ``But you have to have
someone in front of the class.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Unified School District, which has hired 1,658
teachers for a new school year that starts in two weeks, still has
2,500 to go, district officials said. Of those hired, 58 percent
don't have teaching credentials, the district said.
</P>
<P>
   Many were hired based solely on their experience leading church
or camping groups, said Antonio Garcia, the district's director of
recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked a lot of the field dry last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in combing the nation's young work force for teachers,
districts are often hopelessly outgunned in a thriving economy by
technology and other companies that can sometimes triple a starting
teacher's salary. School districts and such companies are often
competing for the same dwindling pool of students who choose to
major in science or math.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers who specialize in the subjects that are in demand
often would have to move thousands of miles to the nearest
available job. That is because the surpluses of teachers tend to be
clustered in the Midwest, where enrollment is grow- ing more
slowly, while the vacancies  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  are elsewhere,
often in states and inner-city districts that have experi- enced an
influx of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Further aggravating the crisis, those students who do commit to
teaching tend to choose elementary education, English or biology,
among other subjects, where the demand is less acute. And those
most qualified to teach in shortage areas are often among those
least willing to relocate, sometimes thousands of miles to the
nearest available teaching job, particularly if they live in the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fairly high percentage of people who do graduate from
teacher prep programs, it may be upwards of 40 percent, don't go
into teaching,'' said Elizabeth Fideler, the executive vice
president and chief operating officer of Recruiting New Teachers, a
Massachusetts firm that works with states and districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiantown Middle School in Indiantown, Fla., near
Okeechobee, needed to hire 17 teachers this year _ to reduce class
sizes, but also to bring in fresh bodies to combat another opponent
that has plagued schools across the country: low test scores.
</P>
<P>
   The school succeeded in filling all jobs, but not without a
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting was very difficult this year because there is such
a shortage out there,'' said Debra Harper, the school principal.
``We had to go outside the county and even the state. Florida was a
major draw for some teachers, and location helped us bring them
down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas has not been as lucky, and has had to turn back the clock
to fill its vacancies _ an estimated 20,000 statewide, 300 of them
in Houston alone.
</P>
<P>
   Under an article imploring ``adults 50 and older'' to learn more
about communicating via computer, the Aug. 26 edition of the
``Teacher Retirement System News'' beckons retirees of the Texas
school system to ``return to teaching on as much as a full-time
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a recently passed state law, the retirees must be
qualified in a shortage area, and have been out of the classroom
for as long as 12 months, to keep their pension payments flowing.
State officials had no immediate sense of how many retirees had
taken districts up on the offer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
