<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFT IN BULLPEN WORKOUTS PAYS OFF FOR DREIFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers pitching coach Claude Osteen
said right-hander Darren Dreifort has pitched well for the past
month because of improved bullpen work.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort said that improvement stems mostly from his shifting
the day he throws in the bullpen from the second to third day after
a start.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort has strengthened his chances of remaining in the
starting rotation when manager Davey Johnson and general manager
Kevin Malone sit down to discuss the matter in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Dreifort took the loss in allowing four earned runs
in 71/3 innings, he's been everything scouts thought he would be as
a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Osteen said if he were asked for a recommendation on whether
Dreifort should be a starter or reliever, right now he'd speak in
favor of starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got here he would throw a pen and was all over
the place,'' Osteen said. ``Now he comes down there and throws it
(with pinpoint accuracy). It comes from controlling himself.
Darren's a big guy, and there's a lot of leg work, a lot of timing.
He's gotten nothing but better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort is trying not to overanalyze why he's pitched well
lately _ he has a 3.59 ERA in his past six starts _ but it
definitely relates to his success in the bullpen between starts.
After the All-Star break he changed his workout pattern, and that's
when he began to feel a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm feels like (garbage) the second day, and the third day
it feels great,'' Dreifort said. ``On the second day my arm is
tired and I'm not able to throw the ball and feel it. Now, it feels
much better and your work is much better then.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's inability to bounce back quickly after pitching is,
ironically, what has kept him in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thought about using Dreifort out of the bullpen before
the season, but the team's medical staff advised against it.
Dreifort missed the 1995 season after having reconstructive surgery
to repair a torn medial collateral ligament in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The question lingers, but Dreifort has pitched into the eighth
inning in each of his past three starts. He's 2-1 with a 2.59 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The progress he's made in the last three or four starts, where
he's gone deep into the game with a low pitch count, that's a
starter,'' Johnson said. ``The overthrowing, throwing 110 pitches
in five or six innings, that's a reliever.''
</P>
<P>
   Minimal call-ups: The Dodgers have apparently scrapped plans to
call up middle infielders Adam Riggs, Alex Cora and Juan Castro
when rosters are expanded Wednesday, primarily because there won't
be much playing time for them since the Dodgers are already
overloaded in that area.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers do call the three up, it will be interesting to
see if any of those names surface in trade talks during the
offseason. Johnson has said on numerous occasions he wants to be
able to take a look at any player who could help the club in the
future in order to avoid another Roger Cedeno incident. Cora, Riggs
and Castro would fit into that category, even though playing time
would be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding roster: The Dodgers are expected to activate infielder
Tripp Cromer, on the disabled list since July 6 (retroactive to
July 5) with an irregular heartbeat, when rosters expand. Triple-A
Pitchers Jeff Kubenka, Jamie Arnold, Jeff Williams, Carlos Perez
and Double-A pitcher Eric Gagne are also expected to join the
Dodgers. But the team could wait until Triple-A Albuquerque ends
its season next week to promote players.
</P>
<P>
   In closing: The Dodgers announced they renewed working
agreements one more season with Double-A San Antonio, Single-A San
Bernardino, short-season Single-A Yakima and Great Falls of the
rookie Pioneer League.... Devon White, mired in a 4-for-47 slump,
returned to the lineup after resting for two days.
</P>
</TEXT>
