<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT &LR;      08-31 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFONZO'S 3 HOMERS LEAD METS IN 17-1 ROUT OF HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ To see the out-of-town scoreboard from the visitors'
dugout at the Astrodome, the New York Mets have to crane their
necks hard to the left, but only if they are willing to concede
that they have a tiny bit of interest in a series being played
between Cincinnati and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   No Met has been willing to admit to scoreboard watching in
recent weeks, but Edgardo Alfonzo gave his teammates frequent
excuses to swing their heads in that direction Monday night,
hitting three home runs over the left field wall in a display that
had his otherwise bored teammates leaping off their bench with
astonishing regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Using a barrage of power as deadening and insistent as punches
in a heavyweight bout, the Mets bludgeoned Houston, 17-1, at the
Astrodome. Alfonzo had a record-breaking night, going 6 for 6,
knocking in five runs and scoring six times. His six hits broke a
Mets single-game record by one, and his 15 total bases surpassed by
two the previous record.
</P>
<P>
   With Cincinnati's 11-3 win over Atlanta, the Mets gain a game on
the Braves and are just 2 1/2 behind in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who set season highs for runs scored and hits (21),
remain three games up on the Reds in the wild card race.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo had never had a three-home-run game before and he picked
a propitious time to become a McGwiresque slugger. The Mets had
been staggered a bit by two losses to Arizona _ a potential
postseason opponent _ but Alfonzo had been hitting well on this
road trip, going 4 for 13 before this game. Still, the Mets had
cause for concern. They had lost ground to the Braves in the last
two days.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to manager Bobby Valentine's concerns was Mike Piazza's
sore left shoulder; Valentine waited until batting practice to see
if Piazza was feeling loose enough for him to be in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo soon eased Valentine's fears. With his first swing of
the bat on the second pitch he saw from Shane Reynolds in the first
inning, Alfonzo single-handedly produced as many runs as all the
Astros would in the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds faced the Mets last week at Shea Stadium and lost
there, too. Alfonzo's solo shot opened up a gusher of offense that
the Astros were helpless to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton opened the second inning with a home run and,
after Roger Cedeno singled, advanced on a Masato Yoshii sacrifice
and then stole third (his first successful steal since Aug. 10).
Rickey Henderson then drove in the Mets' third run of the game.
Alfonzo was back for a single and he and Henderson came home on an
Olerud double.
</P>
<P>
   Up came Piazza, who said before the game that his sore shoulder
was fine. To prove his point, he blasted a batting-practice- like
bomb for the Mets' sixth and seventh runs.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo was hitting .311 before the game, and he had set a
career high with his 18th home run on Aug. 15. But Alfonzo is
primarily a singles hitter. He is regarded as a delightful teammate
who gracefully embraced the arrival of Robin Ventura, which forced
his move to second base this season, and he is a defensive whiz in
a spectacular infield. A potential most- valuable-player? Sure. But
a threat to go deep every night? No. Before this season, he had
never hit more than 17 home runs or driven in more than 78 runs.
Those figures have now been obliterated. With his five RBIs Monday
night, he has 94 already this season.
</P>
<P>
   Of his 159 hits entering the game, only 36 were doubles and 20
were home runs. So who could have foreseen that Alfonzo would
singlehandedly give everyone a reason to keep paying attention to
this snoozer. With Rickey Henderson already on base in the fourth,
Alfonzo smashed a 1-2 pitch for his second home run, which gave him
the club record for home runs by a second baseman. In the sixth
inning, Alfonzo hit his 23rd home run of the season for his fourth
hit of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He tied a club record for three home runs in the game _ the last
person to do it was Gary Carter in 1985 _ and his 16 total bases
(he had two singles and a double in addition to the homers in a 6-6
evening) broke a record Darryl Strawberry set in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
