<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHAT MCGWIRE'S MISSING OUT ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND) 
(mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark McGwire, who last year had the single greatest
home run-hitting season in baseball history and is threatening to
go there again, is envious of Jason Giambi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said it a lot of times,'' Giambi said. Not that he is
envious, Giambi said, but the reason for his envy. ``When he was
here, he'd say there's nothing like being on a winning team. In the
situation he's in, he's not winning. We talk once or twice a week.
He talks about it all the time. He's so excited for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Giambi is an integral part of the Oakland Athletics' success
this season, the kind of success McGwire's Cardinals have not had.
The Athletics, for whom McGwire used to play, are near the front of
the American League wild-card race. The Cardinals, despite
McGwire's 51 home runs, are fighting a losing fight to have a .500
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics are one of the best stories of the season, maybe
the best. They came to New York Monday night with a 25-man roster
that earns $20 million this season. They opened a four-game series
with the Yankees, whose 25-man roster earns $86 million. Yet these
same teams could meet again at Yankee Stadium the first week of
October in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Giambi, the team leader in batting
average (.316) and runs batted in (99). ``This is my fifth year and
just about every year we finished last. Now to be here, especially
not to have been picked to be here, when people said we were going
to lose 100 games and we were going to be a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The joke is on those teams like the Baltimore Orioles and the
Los Angeles Dodgers, who have payrolls flirting with $80 million
and can't play well enough to salvage their dignity. Here is the
team with the fifth-lowest payroll in the major leagues, and it has
a good chance to play postseason baseball.
</P>
<P>
   They are in this position because of ``veterans'' like Giambi
and Matt Stairs, a reclamation project like John Jaha, young
players like Miguel Tejada, Eric Chavez and Ben Grieve and a
starting pitching rotation that has led the Athletics to the No. 3
spot among the league's lowest earned run averages.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hudson, at 24 years old the youngest of the team's starting
pitchers, began the series against the Yankees Monday night, taking
an 8-1 record and team-leading 3.27 era into the game. (The Yankees
won the game, 7-4.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody with the mound presence he has,''
Giambi said. ``He never gets rattled. Of course, he's never pitched
in New York. That's a big difference. But he went up against Pedro
Martinez and beat Pedro, and he went up against Randy Johnson and
beat him. That's pretty good to put on your resume in your first
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Oakland resume that is undergoing perhaps the most
impressive upgrading this season is the one belonging to the
general manager, Billy Beane. Taking the meager amount of money at
his disposal, Beane has scrapped and scrambled and dealt his way up
the ladder, surpassing the relatively inept efforts of general
managers with far more millions to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Beane, only 37 years old and 10 years removed from his own
playing career, did some of his best scrambling in the past several
weeks, making a series of trades for the starting pitchers Kevin
Appier and Omar Olivares, relievers Jason Isringhausen and Greg
McMichael, second baseman Randy Velarde and outfielder Rich Becker.
The trades cost the Athletics only two established players _
starter Kenny Rogers and Billy Taylor, who had been the team's
closer.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't simply that Beane made those trades; it was how he
went about them that also explains one of the strengths of these
Athletics. He actually solicited the opinion of two players, Giambi
and Stairs, before making the moves. ``We had a hand in every
trade,'' Giambi said. ``That Billy Beane has that much respect for
us is unbelievable. What do you think? Is it going to kill team
chemistry. What about this guy, what about that guy?''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Phillips, whose signing had represented another of Beane's
shrewd off-season moves, broke a leg earlier this month, and Beane
immediately consulted his two players. ``He came to us,'' Giambi
said, ``and said, `I have four guys on the table I can get right
now. Which guy do you like?' We picked Rich Becker. We said that's
who we want, and he went out and got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks earlier, Beane consulted Giambi and Stairs about a
more sensitive and critical matter. Rogers, the team's No. 1
pitcher, had asked to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called us in Seattle and told us Kenny wanted to be
traded,'' Giambi said. ``He said, `Is it going to kill the team
chemistry?' At the time, all he could get was two minor leaguers.
He wanted to know how the team would feel about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beane made the trade with the Mets and then turned around and
acquired Olivares and Appier. The Athletics won nine of 10 games
after their arrival, moving from four games back to one game behind
in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the man overseeing the Athletics' climb had also been
the subject of a conversation between the general manager and the
players. Manager Art Howe's contract was up at the end of last
season, and he appeared to be on his way out. ``Jason and I decided
to go to Billy and tell him what we thought,'' Stairs said. ``If we
were going to be around for the next three years, we wanted to know
what was going on with the manager. We wanted to tell him how we
felt toward skip.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Athletics reach the playoffs with their $20 million
payroll and Beane is named executive of the year, he might have to
share the award with Giambi and Stairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
