<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-STUTTERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: LEARNING TO BE AT EASE WITH STUTTERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Reitzes has stuttered for as long as he can
remember, which is just about all of his 27 years. Until a few
years ago, his was a life of avoidance.
</P>
<P>
   In school, he found ways to lie low if he thought the teacher
would call on him. He would not approach girls for fear of
embarrassing himself. Like many stutterers, he steered clear of any
problem-laden word. He would not say ``Freud'' in a college
psychology course because getting past the ``F'' was like wrestling
with the devil.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes his stutter determined what he ate, said Reitzes, who
is pursuing a master's degree in speech therapy at New York
University. ``I'd go to a restaurant and order a hot dog even
though I may have wanted spaghetti,'' he said. ``The only reason
was that I could say `hot dog.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuttering is more about what you don't say than what you do
say,'' he said at a picnic that two dozen New Yorkers went to on
Sunday in Commack, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   This gathering was no different from countless late-summer
barbecues, except in one respect. Just about everyone in Tom and
Lee Caggiano's back yard stuttered, including their son, Michael,
16. Or they were relatives of stutterers, and knew what it was like
to see loved ones live for years with a deep sense of shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, we just couldn't talk about stuttering,''
said David Steiner, 41, a New York lawyer. ``It was this dirty
little secret, only it really wasn't much of a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   But that part is history, he said. The same goes for Reitzes.
Not that his stutter is gone. Hardly. But he has come to allow
himself to stutter as he may, instead of avoiding words and awkward
situations. Now that he stutters openly, he finds himself
stuttering much less often. The paralyzing fear is gone.
</P>
<P>
   How immobilizing can that fear be? C. Woodruff Starkweather, a
speech-language pathologist, told of a man he knew who endured
terrible headaches because his eyeglass prescription was wrong. The
reason, Starkweather said, was that when this man read an eye
chart, he would identify only the letters he could say, not those
he could see.
</P>
<P>
   If that kind of pain was on the picnic menu, so were triumphs.
Reitzes said that he had improved so much that he sometimes
stammered deliberately, as he does on his answering machine. ``Take
as much time as you n-n-need,'' his recorded message begins. He
went out of his way to stumble on ``need,'' he said, to alert
stuttering callers that they were in friendly territory.
</P>
<P>
   The picnic was sponsored by two support groups: the
well-established National Stuttering Project, and a relatively new
organization, Friends, which is aimed at young stutterers like
Michael Caggiano.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there are support groups for every imaginable
disorder. But the stutterers said they felt that they especially
needed one because they had spent long years in isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very alone when growing up,'' said Jeff Shames, 43, who
is working on a television documentary called ``Stutter Step.'' It
was a remark heard from more than one picnicker. As a boy, Shames
thought that stuttering was ``a basic flaw'' and that ``I wasn't
worth people's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he avoids _ most of the time, anyway _ the common
tendency to switch words when stuck. ``It's my right,'' Shames
said, ``to take as much time as I need to get the word out.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing a support group does is help people see that their
problem does not necessarily rule out success. There have been many
famous stutterers, from Winston Churchill (who could surely turn a
phrase) to James Earl Jones (just try making fun of Darth Vader).
</P>
<P>
   The hows and whys of stuttering are ``all so individual,'' Rina
Moskowitz, a kindergarten teacher in Manhattan, said at the picnic.
Some people do not stammer on the phone, others all the time. Some
stutter horribly when angry, others never. Ms. Moskowitz has no
problem when talking to her pupils _ ``maybe because they're not
judgmental,'' she said. Conversations with parents are another
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The picnickers said that, sure, they would love to wake up
tomorrow with tongues unknotted. But that is unlikely to happen.
``Nowadays, we are more interested in being accepted as stutterers
instead of chasing the fluency god,'' Steiner said, a point that
Reitzes echoed.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, he was eating a hot dog. He really wanted one. It
was not merely a substitute for spaghetti.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
