<SLUG> BC-CEO-PAY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT LOOKS AT WIDENING WAGE GAP BETWEEN WORKERS AND CEOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If entry-level wages had risen this decade on par with the
skyrocketing pay of U.S. chief executives, the minimum wage would
be $22.08 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   It's $5.15.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the pay disparities cited by United for a Fair
Economy and the Institute for Policy Studies in a jointly published
report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another:
</P>
<P>
   ``If average production worker pay had risen at the same rate as
CEO pay between 1990 and 1998, (average production) worker pay
would be $110,399 today, rather than the current $29,267.''
</P>
<P>
   The report continues the groups' efforts to fight the widening
income gap between America's wealthiest bosses and the rank and
file.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, CEO pay jumped 481 percent from 1990 to
1998, compared with a 28 percent increase in average worker pay.
Corporate profits rose 108 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations' sixth annual executive compensation survey,
this year titled ``A Decade of Executive Excess: The 1990s,'' draws
from several national surveys to blast the widening wage gap. For
example:
</P>
<P>
   - Business Week magazine found that in 1998, CEOs at the 365
largest U.S. corporations were paid 419 times the average
blue-collar worker's pay _ $10.6 million compared with $25,000. In
1990, the ratio was 120-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   - Towers Perrin, a benefits and management consulting firm,
found that CEOs of U.S. firms with annual revenue of $250 million
to $500 million made 123 percent more than their peers in 22 other
industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much is enough?'' the report asked, pointing out the
phenomenal wealth of some CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999, Microsoft CEO Bill Gates, Berkshire Hathaway CEO
Warren Buffett, and Microsoft alumnus Paul Allen had combined
wealth of $156 billion,'' the report said. ``This topped the
combined GNPs of the poorest 43 nations on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Salary and bonus accounted for only 20 percent of CEO
compensation, with exercised stock options making up the biggest
share. (Even Buffett is on record criticizing the mushrooming of
CEO pay through stock options.)
</P>
<P>
   Researchers who compiled ``Executive Excess'' said CEOs of large
U.S. companies received an average compensation package of $10.6
million in 1998, up 36 percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Average blue-collar wages rose 2.7 percent in the same
year-to-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The report summarizes the timeworn debate about measuring an
individual's worth:
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of top CEO pay say proven business leaders create
billions of dollars in shareholder value and are worth what they're
paid. Critics argue that workers who produce the goods and services
are the real creators of shareholder value and should be rewarded
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   But workers wages have not kept pace with the productivity gains
of U.S. businesses, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the average hourly wage had tracked the 32.8 percent
increase in productivity between 1973 and 1998, it would have been
$18.10 an hour in 1998, rather than $12.77,'' the authors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The groups contend that failure to reign in U.S. executive pay
puts the nation's businesses at a financial disadvantage to global
competitors, that stock option compensation places undue emphasis
on short-term results and that there's a depressing effect on
workplace morale when the CEO prospers out of proportion to the
work force.
</P>
<P>
   While dumping on ``undeserving'' CEOs, the report also
recognized two CEOs for refusing bonuses at times when their
employees were being laid off or hadn't received raises in years.
But Boeing CEO Phil Condit and US Airways CEO Stephen M. Wolf still
earned $3 million and $10.9 million without their bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Graef Crystal, author of the Crystal Report and a national
authority on executive compensation, says the focus on CEO pay is
appropriate. Overpaying CEOs, he contends, leads to overpaying
other officers down the line and, eventually, the sum of
overpayments hurts the company's profits or stock value.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of the full report are available for $5, plus $1.50
shipping, by writing to 1998 Executive Excess Report, United for a
Fair Economy, 37 Temple Place, 5th Floor, Boston, MA 02111.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
