<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WIELDING HAMMER FATALLY SHOT BY POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mentally disturbed man wielding a hammer was fired
upon at least 12 times and killed by the police in Borough Park,
Brooklyn, Monday evening, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting of the man, an Orthodox Jew identified by the
police as Gidone Busch, brought several hundred angry residents of
the largely Hasidic neighborhood into the streets to protest what
they said was excessive force by the police. The protesters chanted
``Justice,'' strained against police barricades and occasionally
threw objects at officers, but no one was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   An officer who tried to subdue Busch was hit several times in
the arm with the hammer, the police said, but the officer was not
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Busch, 29, was known on his block of 46th Street in Borough Park
for his outbursts. The police said a neighbor filed a complaint on
Sunday saying that a man believed to be Busch had attacked him with
a hammer. In a telephone interview last night, Busch's mother said
a serious kidney ailment had been diagnosed in Busch in 1991 and he
had grown increasingly depressed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   While Busch's neighbors agreed that he was emotionally
disturbed, many of the people who poured into the streets last
night complained that the police could have subdued him far less
violently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sick, and he did things that were strange, but it's not
right to shoot him so many times,'' said Mochie Klein, 28, one of
the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents also demanded to know why Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
who has enjoyed strong support in the city's Hasidic neighborhoods,
did not go to Brooklyn Monday night to address their concerns.
Their anger could pose a delicate political challenge for the
mayor, who has generally been a staunch defender of the Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel, said the mayor ``is
confident that the NYPD is handling the investigation
appropriately.'' Members of the mayor's Community Assistance Unit
were at the scene talking to residents and officials.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's fatal shooting prompted countless comparisons by
Borough Park residents to the killing of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed
African immigrant who was shot 19 times by officers in his Bronx
doorway in February. Diallo's death further increased anger among
critics, particularly members of minority groups, who say the
police force is overly aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday night at the 66th Precinct station
house, Assistant Chief Joseph P. Raguso, the commander of Patrol
Borough Brooklyn South, said the police had received an anonymous
911 call about 6:40 p.m. Monday reporting that a man at Busch's
address, 1619 46th Street, had been threatening a boy on his block
with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Six officers went to Busch's house, and in the basement
apartment, he threatened them with the hammer and took a swing or
two at them, Raguso said. The officers then ordered Busch to drop
the hammer, but instead he backed into the street, and the officers
followed him onto the sidewalk, the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   On the sidewalk, Officer Daniel Gravitch sprayed him with pepper
spray, which Raguso said only irritated Busch further.
</P>
<P>
   Another officer, Sgt. Terrence O'Brien, tried to block Busch's
path, and Busch hit him several times in the left arm with the
hammer, prompting four of the officers _ Gravitch, Officer Martin
Sanabria, Sgt. Joseph Memoly and Officer William Loshiavo _ to open
fire, Raguso said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they were not sure Monday night how many rounds
had been fired, but 12 shell casings were found at the scene, along
with the hammer. Busch was struck in the torso and was dead on
arrival at Maimonides Medical Center in Borough Park. O'Brien was
treated for cuts and released.
</P>
<P>
   Busch, who was from Dix Hills, N.Y., moved to Borough Park
several months ago, in part to get in touch with his religious
roots, neighbors and officials said. When he was shot, Busch was
wearing a prayer shawl and tefillin _ leather boxes hung from
straps and containing pieces of Scripture, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Busch's mother, Doris Busch Boskey, 62, described him as
``sweet, talented and brilliant,'' a former medical student who
left Mount Sinai Medical School in 1991 because of a kidney
ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spiritual awakening that led him to Israel and an
interest in Orthodox Judaism, he became progressively more
depressed and troubled, she said. He did not seek medical attention
for either his kidney disease or his increasingly depressed and
emotional state, although Mrs. Boskey's current husband, Howard
Boskey, attempted to persuade him to seek counseling. Neighbors in
Borough Park said he often walked around talking to himself and
wearing heavy clothes in the middle of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Boskey learned of her son's death on the television news
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it happened,'' she cried. ``I don't why they
couldn't have found another way. I don't know why they had to kill
my son.
</P>
<P>
   She said he had been visiting Israel for long periods of time
for the last five years. He joined what she called ``a cult, a very
extreme group,'' whose philosophy was ``hard to explain,'' she
said. But her son said they had hypnotized him there ``and that can
be very bad if you don't know what you're doing if you're
untrained,'' Mrs. Boskey said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year and a half, her son had lived with her and
Boskey, who tried to dissuade him from moving to Borough Park. ``He
was adamant about moving to a more religious community. But he
needed help. He was just depressed over finding a place for
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Handling mentally disturbed people is a constant challenge for
the police. Last October, a Queens resident, Kevin Cerbelli, was
shot dead in a police precinct station house after attacking
officers with a screwdriver and a knife.
</P>
<P>
   The City Councilman in Borough Park, Noach Dear, also said he
had questions about the shooting, but urged residents of Borough
Park to reserve judgment of the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of rumors out there,'' Dear said above the noise
of shouts and banging. ``We need to have a full investigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
