b x BC-OZ-PROJECT-KAN &LR;      08-31 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ-PROJECT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OZ ENTERTAINMENT PROVIDES DETAILS ON THEME PARK FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACE HOBSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESOTO, Kan. _ Oz Entertainment Co. documents released Monday
provide a detailed look at how the company plans to finance a $761
million theme park big and bold enough to rival Disney.
</P>
<P>
   The company's financing plan for the Wonderful World of Oz
involves $433.6 million in private financing and investment and
$327.5 million in property and sales tax bonds, public grants and
infrastructure improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The net economic effect (of Oz) is extraordinarily positive
for all levels of government and the economy, so a public-private
partnership is a reasonable request,'' said David Westbrook, an Oz
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But one new part of the Oz financing plan could create
controversy. The company plans to ask for a property tax abatement.
Johnson County officials, who in the past have been skeptical of
property tax breaks, would have to approve the abatement.
</P>
<P>
   The company would pay about $2.25 million a year in property
taxes to the De Soto School District, as required by state law, and
would pay a fee to the county for some services. But it wants the
county to waive all other county property taxes. How much that
would save Oz is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The Oz financing plan was contained in a binder of documents the
company provided Friday to the Kansas Development Finance
Authority. The documents were released to the public Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The authority will use the documents _ including a feasibility
study and a redevelopment plan _ to decide whether to issue the tax
increment financing bonds and sales tax revenue bonds for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The authority has been negotiating with the federal government
and Oz for a year to allow Oz to acquire the U.S. Army's former
ammunition plant at Sunflower near De Soto in exchange for cleaning
it of environmental hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal, and the Oz company's financing package, are
nearing completion, according to state officials and Oz
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Under the latest plan, Oz would agree to buy $8.8 million in
insurance to guarantee that the cleanup gets done. Oz plans to
spend an additional $32 million to $40 million on the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   If the cleanup is less than $32 million, Oz would have to pay
the federal government the difference. That means Oz must pay at
least $32 million for the 9,065-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   The state finance authority board is scheduled to vote Sept. 10
to issue a resolution of intent to create a redevelopment district
at Sunflower. The step is necessary for the authority to issue
bonds for the project but does not mean the board will approve the
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds are a key part of the Oz financing plan, a complex mix
of equity, bank debt, tax-exempt bonds, public infrastructure
improvements and economic development grants.
</P>
<P>
   The total project cost is now estimated at $761 million, down
slightly from previous estimates of $771 million.
</P>
<P>
   The financing plan includes:
</P>
<P>
   - $202,048,000 in sales tax revenue bonds to be issued by the
Kansas Development Finance Authority. The bonds, commonly known as
STAR bonds, would be repaid with sales tax revenue at the park and
all of the Sunflower site, once it is developed. The bonds would be
issued to private investors and would not carry any guarantees from
the state.
</P>
<P>
   - $70,461,000 in property tax increment financing bonds. This is
a new request; Oz has said for the last year that it did not plan
to ask for tax increment financing. Oz will ask the state's finance
authority to issue bonds to be repaid with 60 percent to 80 percent
of the property tax assessed on the theme park, RV park, campground
and Emerald Resort, which includes a hotel and golf course.
</P>
<P>
   - $222,355,000 in senior construction debt and $24,731,000 in a
senior construction debt service reserve fund.
</P>
<P>
   This debt could come in the form of bank financing, possibly a
traditional financial institution; privately placed bond debt
issued to investors; and//or first mortgage bonds, in which the
bondholder takes a lien on the theme park property.
</P>
<P>
   - $56,409,000 in stock.
</P>
<P>
   - $57,252,000 in leases from vendors at the park, such as ride
companies that rent space.
</P>
<P>
   - $5 million in infrastructure financing by a vendor who would
build an energy plant at the site for heating, cooling and
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   - $20 million in economic development incentives from the
federal and Kansas governments in the form of investment tax
credits.
</P>
<P>
   - $67,874,000 in financing by a developer of the resort project.
Oz plans to work with another developer to build the resort.
</P>
<P>
   - $35 million in state and local financing for infrastructure
improvements. The state would spend $23 million to improve a Kansas
10 interchange near the park; the county would spend $4 million to
build an east-west arterial road near the park; and the county or
the city of De Soto would spend $8 million for sewers at the site.
The spending has not been approved.
</P>
<P>
   Oz originally estimated it would need $270 million in STAR
bonds. The amount was lowered to $202 million because interest
rates have increased 1.5 percent in recent months, Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the higher interest rate, the expected sales tax
revenue would not be enough to cover $270 million in bonds; the new
market could support only $202 million, Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   Oz is asking for tax increment financing bonds because of the
interest rate increases and the decrease in the STAR bond request,
Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   The tax increment is the increase in property taxes assessed on
the land due to the new development. Because the land was federal
property and was not taxed, the increment in this case is 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the balance of property taxes, Oz would pay the
county a set fee for fire, ambulance and police protection at the
site. The report released Monday estimates that the fee would be
$1.8 million once attendance at the park stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   The development authority would not issue any tax increment
financing bonds without the county's approval, said Rebecca Floyd,
the authority's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   County Commissioner Johnna Lingle, whose district covers the
Sunflower site, said she remained opposed to granting Oz a property
tax break.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I said before, `Just what part of ``no'' don't you
understand?' '' Lingle said. ``But I can only speak for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lingle said the property tax abatement was inappropriate because
Oz would get other state and local financing help, including the
STAR bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Other commissioners could not be reached for comment Monday or
said they did not know enough about the plan to comment.
</P>
<P>
   County Counselor Don Jarrett said the County Commission
historically has not favored property tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Oz expects the theme park and resort to generate $195 million
its first year, based on projections of 3.2 million visitors. Oz
plans to open the park in May 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Once attendance stabilizes at 3.8 million guests by 2005,
revenue should be $266 million, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   To break even, the park and resort would need to generate $139
million in the first year and $165 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The feasibility study included in the documents estimated that
the project would bring in $161 million to Kansas and $230.5
million a year to the metropolitan region in economic activity _
after the cost of all public financing.
</P>
<P>
   The project would have an economic return to the Kansas City
area eight times the annual public investment, according to the
study.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said the finance authority plans to hire an accounting
firm to review the study and examine whether its predictions of Oz
revenues and attendance were reasonable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
