<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S CHOICE : SETTING ASIDE HISTORY FOR THE ECSTASY OF THE
MOMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Ill.)   By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pierre Boulez's association with Deutsche Grammophon has given
him fine recording conditions under which to reconsider much of his
favorite music with some of the world's great orchestras: Debussy
and Messiaen with the Cleveland Orchestra, Bartok and Stravinsky
with the Chicago Symphony, Ravel and Webern with the Berlin
Philharmonic. He has also had opportunities to record new works of
his own and of composers he admires, notably Gyorgy Ligeti and
Harrison Birtwistle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a decade of perhaps predictable achievement, come
some surprises. Boulez's latest releases focus on composers who
have hitherto had a marginal place in his scheme of things:
Scriabin and Richard Strauss. He seems not to have conducted
anything by either of them until the early 1970s, when he was
expanding his repertory rapidly as music director of the New York
Philharmonic. Scriabin's ``Poem of Ecstasy'' then appeared on one
of his programs and was recorded by Columbia, but after that the
composer's name disappeared again from his repertory for nearly a
quarter of a century until Boulez returned to the ``Poem of
Ecstasy'' and added the Piano Concerto and ``Prometheus'' for
concerts with the Chicago Symphony leading to the new recording (DG
289 459 647).
</P>
<P>
   Of Strauss, he conducted ``Till Eulenspiegel'' and ``Also Sprach
Zarathustra'' in New York in 1973, and other works have
occasionally appeared on his programs, but his distance from
Strauss seems to be greater than in the case of Scriabin. In
Boulez's evolutionary picture of music, Scriabin has a place behind
Stravinsky, and his recording of the ``Poem of Ecstasy'' points up
many sources for ``The Firebird.'' Strauss, on the other hand, led
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But such historical concerns seem to interest be occupying
Boulez less now than the sheer joy, here in the present, in the
scores of two master orchestrators. His performance of the ``Poem
of Ecstasy'' is thrilling from first to last, the textures at once
sumptuous and clear, the melodies imposing and enticing by turns
(blessed especially by triumphant trumpet playing) and the
sequences of relaxation well gauged to support the rise toward a
golden conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Boulez cannot do quite so much for the Piano Concerto, which
comes from before Scriabin's best period, or for ``Prometheus,''
which always seems to promise more than it delivers, but both
performances are full of incidental pleasures from the orchestra
and from the soloist, Anatol Ugorski.
</P>
<P>
   Boulez's first Strauss recording occupies just half a CD (DG 457
649) because he couples ``Zarathustra'' with ``Totenfeier,'' the
early version of the first movement of Mahler's Second Symphony.
Again the orchestra is the Chicago Symphony, which plays
magnificently.
</P>
<P>
   In the Strauss, there is the special delight of hearing the work
not being taken entirely seriously except where its strenuous
demands are concerned. The fast sections go at top speed,
streamlined, and the contrapuntal virtuosity is all on display. The
effect is almost comic, and not inappropriately so: perhaps this is
what Nietzsche, Strauss' mentor, meant by happy science.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
