<HEADLINE>
NEW YEAR, NEW OUTLOOK FOR KANSAS CITY SCHOOL DISTRICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Students will return today to a Kansas City
School District that some administrators are hoping is much better
than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   From more rigorous academic and behavior standards to tough new
attendance and truancy policies, officials overseeing the area's
largest school system are expecting more from students.
</P>
<P>
   Recent staff shake-ups at four underperforming schools and new
leadership at several others are indications that the district is
holding teachers and principals to the same new high standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic,'' said John Murphy, Desegregation
Monitoring Committee chairman. ``Hopefully, (students) are
returning to a safe, orderly environment in which all teachers
believe that all students can be successful academically. But
everyone has to keep in mind that you're not going to see a
miracle. You're going to see incremental change, and that's the key
to a successful turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiatives are part of the district's ongoing efforts to
boost student achievement. The district is under pressure to
improve its poor academic performance if it hopes to win full state
accreditation and freedom from federal court control.
</P>
<P>
   By far, officials say, the most important changes this year are
aimed at the district's expected enrollment of 35,000 students. And
getting them in their seats is at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   Test results clearly indicate that class attendance leads to
improved performance. District statistics also show that too many
students miss too much class. Last year, on average, district high
school students were absent nearly one in every four days of
school. Middle school numbers weren't much better. District
officials estimated that between 2,000 and 3,000 district students
were truant every day.
</P>
<P>
   This year the district is stepping up efforts to get children
off the streets and into classrooms. For the first time in many
years, district security personnel have authority, along with the
police, to pick up truants. The district plans to take truants to a
transition center at Manual High School, formerly Metro Tech High
School.
</P>
<P>
   At Manual, parents will be called and students will meet with a
counselor who will help develop an educational plan designed to get
the student back on track. The goal is to quickly get the student
back to his or her home school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope when students get back to school they're going to find
it's a place that's rewarding and enticing to them,'' said Cynthia
Kupka, a district instructional director.  &LR; brk:Tough attendance
policy
</P>
<P>
   A new attendance policy also is in effect this year. District
officials held a press conference Monday to emphasize how important
it is for students to attend school, especially the first day.
</P>
<P>
   The district has a history of large numbers of students failing
to show up for the first several days of classes.
</P>
<P>
   Elementary students who miss more than 20 days may be
automatically retained in the same grade. Middle and high school
students will be allowed 13 absences per semester before losing
course credit. More than 10,000 of the district's nearly 36,000
students last year would have been retained if the policy had been
in effect.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the district is combating absences by directing more
attention at parents.
</P>
<P>
   Students who miss school today can expect a phone call to their
home. Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr. will be on the line with a
prerecorded message on the importance of school attendance and an
explanation of the new policy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, each school is expected to make a personal call to
the home of any absent student. The district will then mail a
letter to the residence explaining the policy and the penalties for
failing to attend school.
</P>
<P>
   Parents also are being asked to sign a statement saying they are
aware of the new policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical piece is parents,'' Kupka said. ``They need to
work with us and know what's going on. Parents need to help by
getting their kids in school. Students should be there ready to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Students also will take several new standardized tests to better
gauge their academic performance and growth. Teachers will then be
expected to use the more detailed data to tailor instruction for
each student. Participation on the state's Missouri Assessment
Program tests is mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Students at several underperforming schools may not recognize
all of the teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd Elementary School, Central Middle School and Southeast and
Lincoln College Prep high schools all underwent staff overhauls
this summer to spur improvement. The district assigned new
principals to about a dozen other schools.  &LR; brk:Transportation
changes
</P>
<P>
   Not all the changes this year are aimed at improving
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   More children will be walking, and bell times at many schools
have changed to save busing costs. Last year, the district provided
transportation for students living more than one mile from their
neighborhood school. This year, only students living more than 1.5
miles from their school will receive transportation. Officials
estimate the change will cut between 2,500 and 3,000 students from
bus routes and will help the district make up for a $2 million
overrun in last year's transportation budget.
</P>
<P>
   In Sugar Creek, parents will begin to see long-sought changes in
the grade configuration of one school, which should make it easier
on some families.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Sugar Creek Elementary served only kindergarten
through third grades. Students then often transferred to Mount
Washington Elementary for fourth and fifth grades, then to another
school for middle school. That created a burden for many families
who have children attending different schools.
</P>
<P>
   The district also is reinstituting use of surveillance cameras
in middle and high schools and establishing a hot line for students
to report campus problems. The measures are designed to make
buildings safer and students feel more secure. Some schools
operated video monitors in the past, but few have been in use in
recent years because the district could no longer afford staff to
monitor the cameras full time.
</P>
<P>
   The new system is designed to save money by allowing one person
to monitor all of the buildings from a central location.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kid is less likely to do something to another kid or do
something that is dangerous if he knows there is video
monitoring,'' said John Coleman, the district's security director.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the changes are driven by new accountability and
assessment practices developed as part of a broad plan to turn
around the long-troubled district. The recent selection of Demps as
superintendent should help ensure continued improvement, Murphy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy will have a key voice in the decision on whether the
court next year should end the long-running desegregation lawsuit
and return the district to local control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that you've got some consistency at the helm and a vision
for where we're going, you're going to see some changes,'' Murphy
said. ``The key is it's coming. It's on its way. I'm not only
optimistic about this year but also about the future of Kansas City
schools.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
