<SLUG> BC-FURROW-TRIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURROW GIVEN DATE FOR MURDER TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A federal judge ordered Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr.
to stand trial Oct. 12 in the killing of a postal worker in Los
Angeles after a shooting rampage that wounded five people at a
Jewish community center.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old white supremacist, wearing an orange jail outfit
and glasses, appeared before U.S. Magistrate Judge Stephen Hillman
as relatives of slain postal worker Joseph Ileto looked on from the
audience gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow answered ``yes'' when Hillman asked whether he understood
his rights and had read the indictment against him. When his
attorney, Deputy Public Defender Sean Kennedy, told Hillman the
defense didn't intend to enter a plea, the magistrate entered a
plea of not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow's hands were handcuffed in front of him and he was
flanked by Kennedy and Deputy Public Defender Marilyn Bednarski
throughout the 10-minute proceeding. He did not look at the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Hillman selected U.S. District Court Judge Richard Paez through
a random assignment process to hear Furrow's trial and set the
trial date.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted Furrow for killing Ileto, a
Filipino-American letter carrier, while he was delivering mail in
Chatsworth and using a 9mm handgun during a violent crime that
resulted in death, charges that carry a potential death sentence.
The indictment also charges Furrow as a felon in possession of a
firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Ileto was shot about 11:55 a.m. Aug. 10, little more than an
hour after three boys, a teen-age counselor and a receptionist were
shot at the community center.
</P>
<P>
   Between the shootings, Furrow allegedly dumped his van behind a
sandwich shop and demanded the keys to a woman's car at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow turned himself in to the FBI in Las Vegas the day after
the attacks and authorities said he confessed to the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow faces separate state charges of attempted murder in the
shootings of the boys, the counselor and the receptionist at the
community center. The Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office
also charged Furrow in the Ileto killing, added hate crime
allegations in the shootings, and charged him with carjacking.
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal murder charges carry a potential death
penalty, but neither side has yet decided whether to seek capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   If prosecutors seek the death penalty, there would be a trial to
determine guilt and whether Furrow planned the attacks and a trial
to determine the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal prosecutors have decided that the federal
trial will go first. At least one deputy district attorney will
join the federal team as a specially designated assistant U.S.
attorney, but that selection has not been made, said Sandi Gibbons,
spokeswoman for the District Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office is considering adding civil rights
violations to Furrow's indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to investigate this case and there could be
additional charges,'' said Thomas Mrozek, spokesman for the U.S.
Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Terrell, is
a veteran of its major crimes unit. He is joined by Assistant U.S.
Attorney Michael Gennaco, who leads its civil rights division, and
Assistant U.S. Attorney Caroline Wittcoff, also with the division.
</P>
<P>
   Paez was the first Latino member of the federal bench in Los
Angeles when President Clinton appointed him in June 1994. Paez had
served 13 years as a Los Angeles Municipal Court judge, and for
nearly a decade before that did legal aid work in the Central
Valley and Los Angeles, according to reference works.
</P>
<P>
   Paez presided over the cases against former Rep. Jay C. Kim,
R-Diamond Bar, and Democratic fund-raisers John Huang and Maria
Hsia.
</P>
<P>
   He also blocked a city ordinance that would have banned
``aggressive panhandling.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
