<HEADLINE>
KARROS, BROWN LIFT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eric Karros could have been in Anaheim now, but
the Los Angeles Dodgers insisted the Angels also take Eric Young,
so the Angels backed out.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are going nowhere now, but think where they would be
if Karros weren't around.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers' season went from bad to worse, Karros
performed his best, and continues to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' two-run homer and a complete game from Kevin Brown
lifted the Dodgers to a 6-1 win against the Milwaukee Brewers in
the first of a three-game series Monday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (15-6) struck out five and allowed nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling to win the first game of a series throughout
the season, the Dodgers have won the initial game in their last
four series. They can also win their fourth straight series by
winning either today or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Karros leads the Dodgers with 29 homers and 90 RBI and is en
route to the best season of his career. The numbers rank third
among NL first baseman behind Mark McGwire and Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Karros has already established a career-high with 35 doubles. He
hit 34 homers and drove in 111 runs in 1996, and is on pace to
reach those marks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after a typically dismal April, Karros has done nothing
but produce in July and August. He drove in 26 runs in July, one
short of his career-high for a month, and has 24 RBI heading into
the last day of August.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, this is the first time since '93 we went into
August not in the middle of a playoff, so this is different,''
Karros said recently. ``It's frustrating to come to the park and
not be able to look up and see you're not a game ahead, or a game
behind, and see what the other teams are doing. You still look at
the scoreboard, but it's not like, `Oh, boy, hopefully, they lose
so we gain ground.' ''
</P>
<P>
   However, whether the Dodgers are in the middle of a pennant
chase or just playing out the string, Karros approaches things the
same way. He'll be under the stadium taking extra batting practice
nearly every day, and when the season ends Karros will have 30 or
so homers and 100 or so RBI.
</P>
<P>
   A knee injury at the beginning of last season cost Karros his
fourth straight such season, but even after missing a month with a
knee injury that sent him to the disabled list for the first time
in his career, Karros finished with 23 homers and 87 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' fifth-inning homer against the Brewers broke open a 3-0
game and gave Brown, who has won six straight decisions, plenty of
room to work.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Brown's last start, in which he allowed a grand slam to
Jose Valentin and wasted a 5-2 lead before getting a no-decision,
he made this one stick.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting a 1-0 lead in the third, Brown got out of a
first-and-third, one-out jam when he retired Jeromy Burnitz on a
pop-up and Jeff Cirillo on a fly to right.
</P>
<P>
   After being two-hit the previous day by Chicago no-name Kyle
Farnsworth, the Dodgers increased their lead 3-0 on Brown's
bases-loaded, fielder's-choice bunt and Young's fielder's-choice
groundout.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers left five runners on base in the first three
innings, then had two baserunners in the next five innings before
Kevin Barker and Brian Banks had one-out singles in the ninth. Alex
Ochoa's bases-loaded groundout in the ninth ruined Brown's shutout
bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5357 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     08-31 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS FAMILY FOLLOWS PLAN WORTH EMULATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The revolution is hardly over. It takes time to
change the dynamics of race and the culture of tennis. But on the
first day of the 1999 U.S. Open, Richard Williams made a
prediction:
</P>
<P>
   His daughters, Venus and Serena Williams, will meet in the
finals of this Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to the draw that has the third-seeded Venus on one
side of the bracket and the seventh-seeded Serena on the other,
there is room for such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I don't see nothing that can stop those two
girls at all. Not at all. I think (what) we're going to see for the
first time is an all-black final,'' Richard Williams said moments
after 19-year-old Venus cruised past Tatiana Poutchek 6-1, 6-1 in
her opening match.
</P>
<P>
   ``For tennis, I think it will be the greatest thing that could
actually happen. I think the fans want it. I think the media needs
it. I think the United States needs it. I think it would be great
for tennis, and I think the world needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his unorthodox methods and parental interests, it is
tough to dismiss Richard Williams' prescription for dragging tennis
out of its racial, economic, sociological box.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it is entirely possible that Serena could handle Monica
Seles, should Seles advance to the quarterfinals, and either Mary
Pierce or the hard-hitting Lindsay Davenport in the semis.
</P>
<P>
   And Venus, who should meet no major obstacle until No. 1 Martina
Hingis in the semis, appears concerned that her failure to win a
Grand Slam title so far in her starry career is something she
should take care of now _ even if it means facing her sister in
that final match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we can do that,'' Venus said. ``That would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williams sisters already have met in one final, but that was
at last spring's Lipton Classic, not a Grand Slam event.
</P>
<P>
   This is the biggest stage for tennis, at least for America,
which seems to keep an ear to the loud events that take place at
Flushing Meadows during the two weeks when soap operas, story lines
and power shifts take place in this game that is better off for the
Williams' family revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Such a women's final as Richard Williams predicts for this Open
is something his family has always planned, going back to the the
lessons Richard gave his girls on the public tennis courts in
Compton, Calif., and the way he refused to be part of the tennis
system, instead keeping his girls off the junior circuit because it
was more important to be educated, to spend time as a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I wanted to do was to build confidence in my
girls because I never seen girls with confidence before. I built
their confidence by telling them they were the best thing that ever
happened in the world. You're the best person in anything,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never told them you're the best person in tennis because I
thought that would be limiting in my kids. I told them they were
the greatest students and they believed it because (when) Venus and
Serena were 9 and 10 years old, they were students at Morningside
High School in Englewood, California, making A's in algebra and
mathematics. So they believed it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in spite of being pegged as the ultimate tennis father
_ and that is hardly ever a compliment _ and in spite of his
penchant for spreading his version of the truth about professional
tennis, Williams is actually much more removed from the careers of
Venus and Serena, ranked No. 4 and 8 in the world, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Williams said he did not watch Venus' opening match
because he was too busy eating lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost me six dollars for a hamburger. Now I don't have a lot
of money, so I decided that for six dollars, I was going to take 90
minutes to eat this hamburger,'' he said, amused.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he does not have great expecations about what his girls
can accomplish on the court. He said his girls can run ``faster
than the other girls'' and they are so much stronger than almost
every player except Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the end, after all the talk about a tennis revolution,
Williams' ultimate lesson for his daughters does not seem to be
primarily about race or about beating your opponent. It's about
being the best you can possibly be, and if along the way you can
further open America's eyes, that's a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see Venus quit at 23, but I think Venus is
going to play longer than that,'' her father said. ``But I want her
to quit because I think she should go and finish her education.
She's too smart to be a tennis player,'' he said, adding the
clincher:
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus is like an unbelievable lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the prediction about the all-black, all-Williams final,
which is a fine idea. It's these words of praise that are the real
Williams' story.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
