<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, August 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-SHORTAGE (undated) _ As the nation's children swarm back
to school, principals from Baltimore to Palm Beach, Fla., and from
the Texas panhandle to inner-city Los Angeles, say they are
grappling with perhaps the most acute teacher shortage in recent
memory, with student enrollments continuing to swell and a rising
tide of educators flowing out of their classrooms to retirement.
The problem is not a depleted national supply of teachers, but
rather geography and qualification. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-DEATHS (Undated) _ Death rates from AIDS in the United
States slowed again in 1998. But they are no longer falling nearly
as rapidly as they did from 1995 to 1997, after the introduction of
combination drug therapy, health officials said at a meeting in
Atlanta. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SKY-MYSTERY (Undated) _ Astronomers think they have solved
the mystery of the mysterious object that has confounded them ever
since its discovery three years ago. It's not any kind of star or
galaxy. Nor is it some entirely new celestial phenomenon. As a few
astronomers had suspected, the object is almost certainly an
extremely rare type of quasar. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TREE-OF-LIFE (Undated) _ As part of an outpouring of
research that is revolutionizing notions about the genetic,
biochemical, structural and evolutionary relationships among living
things, fungi like mushrooms have now been revealed as being closer
to animals like humans than to plants like lettuce. The revelation
is just one of many emerging new ideas about family ties in the
upper reaches of the earth's 3.8-billion-year-old tree of life, in
particular ties among plants and between them and other higher
forms of existence. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVERMORE-RESIGN (Undated) _ The head of the National
Ignition Facility at Lawrence Livermore resigns when it is
disclosed that he had never received the doctorate he claimed. The
division he headed is the cornerstone of U.S. nuclear fusion
research with a $1.6 billion budget. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEB-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Scores of misleading, inaccurate
statements about cancer and other diseases can now be downloaded in
moments by anyone with computer access to the Internet. A
University of Michigan team analyzed 371 Web page references to one
particular cancer to determine their accuracy. Their search
revealed errors that the authors called ``shocking,'' with about a
third of the references lacking any indication that the information
had been deemed accurate by independent experts through the
time-honored process of peer review. Six percent of the web pages
that were not peer-reviewed contained ``clearly erroneous''
information. In other cases, the information was seriously outdated
or misleading. By Jane E. Brody. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ This year some 25.5 million
Americans are expected to turn to computers for answers to their
health questions. When the federal government established an online
health information initiative several years ago, 4.8 million people
visited the site in its first 30 days of operation. Health issues,
not weather or stock reports, are the single biggest reason people
now log on to the Internet. But chances are, too, that much of the
information and advice they glean from the computer screen will be
biased, inaccurate and, in some cases, downright dangerous. By Jane
E. Brody. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MULTICELL-AMOEBAS When times are good and there are plenty
of bacteria to eat, Dictyostelium discoideum _ a species of soil
amoebas _ are loners. These microscopic one-celled animals are
content to crawl through their environment, absorbing whatever food
they come across. But when famine or other catastrophes strike,
something remarkable happens: using their protruding false legs for
propulsion, the amoebas seek each other out and stick together to
create a multicelled creature that can sense light and heat and can
travel faster and farther than any of its component cells traveling
alone. By Malcolm W. Browne. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ARCTIC-REDTAPE (Undated) _ Of all the adversaries of the
Arctic explorers of the 19th century, the most dangerous foe was
government bureaucracy, according to researcher who found many more
perils as part of government missions. By Michael Pollak. (450
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RUSSIA-ANTARCTIC (Undated) _ As Russia's impoverished
scientific institutions face ever more severe cuts in funding,
Moscow's main station on the Antarctic continent has been forced to
close. If the participation of Russian institutions in Antarctic
research is to continue, scientists say, they will require
increasing international support. By Malcolm W. Browne. (870 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WHALES-HIPPOS (Undated) _ The whale's closest cousin is the
hippopotamus, new DNA testing show. The latest of these studies,
published in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences,
is based on the viruslike elements that have copied themselves
throughout the genomes of many species. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EINSTEIN-PAPERS (Undated) _ This spring the eighth and
thickest installment of the Collected Papers of Albert Einstein was
published by the Princeton University Press in two parts totaling
1,118 pages, carrying Einstein through four of the most heroic and
stormy years of his life, from 1914 to 1918 when, among other
things, he finished work on his crowning achievement, the general
theory of relativity. By Dennis Overbye. (2150 words)
</P>
