   SCI-WOMEN-HEART (Undated) _ Women do not need to jog, much less
run marathons, to reduce their chances of heart disease. A survey
of more than 72,000 women ages 40 to 65, published last week in The
New England Journal of Medicine, showed that women who either
walked briskly (20-minute miles or faster) for a minimum of three
hours a week, or who exercised vigorously at least 90 minutes a
week, had a 30 to 40 percent reduction in their risk of heart
disease. By Alisha Berger. (525 words)
