<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5361 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-31 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT-HITTING MARTINEZ SPARKS DOUBLEHEADER SWEEP OF WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The opponents' pinstripes changed Monday night, and
the Mariners reacted accordingly. Facing a middling team instead of
a strong one, the M's again looked as if maybe, just maybe, they
can get into the American League wild card race.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees spent the weekend exposing the Mariners'
flaws. The Chicago White Sox spent six hours Monday helping Seattle
ease the pain. The M's took a doubleheader at Comiskey Park, 5-2
and 14-6, and can return to .500 with a win Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several slumbering hitters awoke for Seattle, but one who's been
alert for a month was the star. Designated hitter Edgar Martinez,
batting .392 for August, started the scoring with a two-run homer
in the first game and ended it with a grand slam in the nightcap.
For the day, he was 4-for-8 with seven runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made SportsCenter,'' he said, but not for any of his
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was speaking of his rumbling-stumbling-bumbling steal
of second in the fifth inning of Game 2. At first base after a
single, he took off on a 3-2 count as Tom Lampkin struck out.
Catcher Brook Fordyce fired to shortstop Mike Caruso breaking in,
and Martinez stopped, anticipating a rundown that would allow Alex
Rodriguez to score from third base. But the M's designated hitter
fell and crawled to second _ and it went for a double steal, since
Rodriguez scored as the ball skipped away from Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez suffered some sore neck muscles, but his ego was hurt
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have picked up the base, held it up and said, `I'm
the greatest,''' joked Ken Griffey Jr. to Martinez after the game.
``Now you can say, `I'm so fast, that when I stop, my momentum
takes me to the base.'''
</P>
<P>
   Several other Mariners also could smile about their performances
at the plate. In the first game, Russ Davis had three hits,
including a two-run single that doubled his August RBI total, and
Dan Wilson had his third two-hit game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgent Brian Hunter had three hits in the second game and
is 10-for-29 since ending a 3-for-52 slide. Another hitter who had
been slumping, Raul Ibanez, also had three hits in Game 2, when
every M's starter but Davis had a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few days we haven't taken any batting practice at all
_ how about that _ and we've swung the bats better,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``We might just continue to do that the rest of this
trip. But it's good to see us put some runs on the board. We
haven't done that in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   With the 14 runs in the nightcap, the Mariners scored in
double-digits for just the second time since the All-Star break and
gave right-hander Ken Cloude the chance to pitch aggressively in
his first M's start since May.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude (4-4) worked quickly, and while he gave up two homers by
challenging hitters, he also had some highlights, such as a
fifth-inning strikeout of Frank Thomas after falling behind in the
count, 2-0. That came after the second of three four-run innings
for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what sequence of pitches I would have thrown
had we not had a lead like we did,'' said Cloude, who worked 52/3
innings. ``But we had a big lead (8-3 at the time), and that
allowed me to go right at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Garcia started and won the opener, improving to 14-7,
just one win shy of the single-season record for wins by a
Venezuelan pitcher (done twice by Wilson Alvarez).
</P>
<P>
   However, it was nothing like the 12-strikeout, six-hit shutout
he tossed his previous outing. Garcia threw 139 pitches that night,
but he was lifted after 105 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie was tired, and it showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he lost his stuff today, he lost it very quickly. I
probably should have taken him out one batter sooner,'' said
Piniella, who let Garcia finish last week despite his concerns over
the pitch count. ``It goes to show you, the fans in Seattle love
the 139 pitches and the shutout, but it shows for a start or two
afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Chicago runners at first and second and the M's
leading 4-2 in the sixth, Piniella called for Jose Paniagua _
earlier than he'd prefer. Paniagua induced a double play on a soft
liner, then worked a scoreless seventh and eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a superb job,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Jose Mesa retired the first two hitters on ground
balls, then allowed a single to Ray Durham and walked Mike Caruso
on four pitches. That brought up Thomas as the potential tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was booed throughout the games by the 17,190 fans, and
his Hall of Fame pace has declined sharply. He batted .265 last
year, and though his average has improved, his power has
disappeared. Since connecting off Paul Abbott at Safeco Field Aug.
11, he has been stuck on 15 home runs, startling from a hitter who
averaged 37 the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa fell behind 2-0, but he attacked Thomas' weak spot with
inside fastballs that reached 96 mph. He worked the count to
3-and-2, then buzzed one past the two-time MVP's fists for strike
three.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa pointed to the sky after the game, apparently exulting over
his 30th save. (He no longer talks to the media, for reasons
unexplained). The free agent signee, who saved 46 games in 1995 and
39 the next year for Cleveland, became the second Mariner to record
30 saves. Mike Schooler did it in 1989 (33) and 1990 (30).
</P>
<P>
   Of his 30 saves, Mesa has put at least one runner on base 25
times. His blown saves have been memorable, but he has converted
all but four chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mesa gets the job done,'' Piniella said. ``He makes it a
little exciting at times, I'll grant you that. But he gets it
done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
