<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER NOTEBOOK: U.S. WOMEN; U.S. MEN; EUROPEAN LEAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; U.S. Women:
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The American women, who have been busy with endorsements and
promotions since winning the World Cup, will return to the field
Saturday afternoon for the first time since their triumph in the
final on July 10 in Pasadena, Calif. They will play Ireland at
Foxboro Stadium near Boston as part of a double-header involving
the New England Revolution and the Tampa Bay Mutiny of Major League
Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tony DiCicco will take 16 of the 20 players on the World
Cup roster, including the world's career international scoring
leader, Mia Hamm, and the world's career international appearance
leader, Kristine Lilly. The game against Ireland will be televised
on tape delay by ESPN2 at 1 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will use the game against Ireland to prepare for
the Nike U.S. Women's Cup that will be staged in October at three
sites. The tournament starts on Oct. 3 with a sold-out doubleheader
at the 23,000-seat Columbus Crew Stadium in Columbus, Ohio (Brazil
vs. Finland and South Korea vs. the United States).
</P>
<P>
   Arrowhead Stadium in Kansas City, Mo., will be the host of the
second doubleheader, with the United States playing Finland after
Brazil meets South Korea, on Oct. 7. The last double-header will be
played at Louisville, Ky., Sunday, Oct. 10, with South Korea
playing Finland before the Americans clash with Brazil in the
round-robin tournament.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Men
</P>
<P>
   The 18-player roster that was named Monday by coach Bruce Arena
for the game against Jamaica Sept. 8 at Kingston includes eight
players who have never played for the national team. The roster
includes only one player from overseas, Steve Cherundolo of
Germany's Hanover 96, and four members of the Olympic team, which
in April will try to qualify for the 2000 Olympic Games in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebuilding the national team is a long-term process,'' Arena
said. ``In order to insure success down the road, our younger,
talented players need to be exposed to the international game. The
Jamaica game will give me the opportunity to look at some new
faces, as well as bring back some players with previous national
team experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Cherundolo, all the players are from Major League
Soccer, with Chicago, D.C. United and Miami leading all teams with
three representatives each. Billy Walsh of the MetroStars is one of
the eight players called to the national team for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The most experienced players on the roster are Brian McBride of
the Columbus Crew with 34 national appearances and Eddie Pope of
D.C. United with 28. Eddie Lewis of the San Jose Clash is next,
with 12 of his 13 appearances taking place in the last 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   With World Cup qualifying starting next year, Arena wants to
look at as many players as possible. Along with the newcomers to
the national team, Arena will also look at a number of other
promising young players.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Jamaica game in Kingston will be part of a
double-header, featuring the two nations' under-17 national teams
in the preliminary match. Both nations have qualified for the FIFA
Under-17 World Championship in New Zealand in November. The only
player from the Northeast on the under-17 team, which is coached by
John Ellinger, is Jordan Chila of Jericho High School on Long
Island, N.Y. He is the son of Renato Chila, the former star of the
defunct New York Arrows of the Major Indoor Soccer League.
</P>
<P>
   European Leagues
</P>
<P>
   Christian Vieri, the world's most expensive player with a $49.5
million transfer fee, sent a strong message that he was the
front-runner for leading scorer in the Italian League. Vieri scored
all three goals in Inter's 3-0 triumph over Verona in the opening
game of the season on Sunday. While Fiorentina, another candidate
for the title, opened with a 1-0 victory over Bari, defending
champion A.C. Milan squandered a lead and settled for a 2-2
deadlock at newly promoted Lecce.
</P>
<P>
   In England, Andy Cole scored four goals for Manchester United in
a 5-1 triumph against struggling Newcastle United, whose Dutch
manager Ruud Gullit resigned last week after four defeats in five
matches. Liverpool presented more evidence that it is on the way
back to its glory days with a 2-0 victory over Arsenal on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, Steve McManaman notched his first goal for Real Madrid
on Sunday in a 4-1 victory at home to Numancia. Real's victory was
its second in as many games and put it ahead of Barcelona on goal
difference after the Catalans' 2-1 victory against Racing
Santander. Kasey Keller posted his second victory in as many games
with his new team, Rayo Vallecano, the third Madrid-based team in
the Spanish First Division.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Frankfurt missed an opportunity to take over the
lead after a 2-2 tie with lowly Duisburg. After winning its
previous six, Frankfurt could not get the better of Duisburg, which
is without a victory this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
