<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARNER SUSPENDED FOR VIOLATING TEAM RULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A seemingly quiet training camp apparently wasn't
so serene, as the second USC football player has been suspended for
violating team rules, according to coach Paul Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Junior wide receiver Troy Garner of Notre Dame High has been
suspended for two weeks, Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Garner is the second Trojan to be suspended during training
camp. Sophomore linebacker Michael Pollard was suspended one week
for missing curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett would not divulge which rules Garner broke, but
according to sources, Garner got into an argument with strength
coach Matt Schiotz last week at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Garner is not allowed to attend workouts or practices during the
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to come back and see me in two weeks,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garner could not be reached for comment. He is sitting out this
season after tearing ligaments in his left knee in spring practice.
Pollard is also sitting out after tearing ligaments in his left
knee in spring drills. He returned from his one-week suspension
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cassel visits: Chatsworth quarterback Matt Cassel visited USC's
practice Sunday at the Coliseum. Cassel, who has grown to
6-foot-4{, orally committed to USC last spring. His little brother,
Justin, who will be a freshman defensive end/quarterback for the
Chancellors, also visited.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-ons awarded scholarships: Three walk-on players were given
scholarships Sunday night: Freshman cornerback Kevin Arbet, the son
of former USC wide receiver Jeff Simmons; junior free safety John
Morgan and senior cornerback Antoinne Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett has never given a freshman walk-on a scholarship, but
Arbet has been impressive in the preseason. Because he will receive
a scholarship, he will not redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real story is (Arbet),'' Hackett said. ``From the time he
got here, he's caught everybody's eye. He's at No. 2 cornerback.
He's done everything. He's had a great two weeks. He's going to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   No kicking decision: Little was decided during Sunday's practice
regarding the kicking battle between David Bell and David Newbury.
Both missed 47-yard attempts at the Coliseum under game conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is way too close to call,'' Hackett said. ``I'd really like
to make a decision before the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: The sprained ankles of defensive tackles Bernard
Riley and Aaron Williams have healed and Hackett said both will
play against Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Darrell Rideaux was bothered by back spasms Sunday,
but is expected to be OK. Freshman tailback Sultan McCullough
tweaked his knee but it was not serious.
</P>
<P>
   Two-position player: Hackett said freshman Troy Polamalu has
been switched from safety to outside linebacker because the
coaching staff envisions him as a David Gibson-type player who can
play either position without much adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Hawaii in a run-and-shoot, most of his work would be at
linebacker,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Polamalu is technically considered a backup to Markus Steele at
weak-side linebacker, with Henry Wallace switching to middle
linebacker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
