<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RUSSIAN-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE RUSSIAN MONEY TRAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The suspected Russian laundering of billions of dollars through
the Bank of New York is giving the world a disquieting look into
some of the darkest corners of Russian life. The financial threads
that American and Russian investigators are now tugging on seem to
lead most directly to the international operations of the Russia
mafia. But even more important is the possibility that the inquiry
will uncover evidence of corruption at top levels of the Russian
government, including illegal diversion of loans from the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the sensitivity of the investigation, and the
political fallout it may produce as elections approach in both
Moscow and Washington, it is critical that the inquiry be
unflinching but fair. Politicians in both countries are already
rushing to apportion blame for misconduct that has yet to be
formally alleged, much less proved. There will be ample time to
review the performance of Russian officials, and the Clinton
administration's handling of Russia, if high-level corruption in
Moscow is confirmed. For now, the need is to investigate thoroughly
and without fear of where the evidence may lead.
</P>
<P>
   So far the only firmly established information is that at least
$4.2 billion and possibly as much as $10 billion from Russia passed
through the Bank of New York last fall and winter. Bank executives,
eager to expand their overseas business, initially seemed happy to
receive the deposits, even though the gusher of money should have
raised suspicions. Investigators believe the banking transactions
were designed in part to launder dollars collected by the Russian
mafia, a varied array of criminal organizations that feast off the
chaotic Russian economy. But the scale of the operation suggests
that other sources of money were involved as well.
</P>
<P>
   One theory, advanced by Mikhail Khodorkovsky, a Russian
businessman under investigation in the inquiry, is that Russian
officials used the bank to shield profits earned from the
manipulation of government securities before the ruble devaluation
a year ago. Another line of speculation is that some of the
billions of dollars in IMF loans to Russia this decade were
siphoned off by Russian politicians. In Moscow's hothouse
atmosphere, these suggestions have added to charges,
unsubstantiated so far, that President Boris Yeltsin, his family
and his closest aides have secretly shipped millions of dollars
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   It is premature to judge any of these assertions. Certainly,
conditions conducive to high-level corruption abound in Russia.
Criminal syndicates are active, law enforcement is lax and in
recent years a small group of government leaders has managed the
transfer of billions of dollars' worth of state assets to private
hands. But the presumption of corruption in general, which is a
reasonable belief, is far different from proving actual criminal
conduct by specific individuals.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a leap to suggest at this early stage in the
investigation that the case shows the Clinton Administration has
mishandled relations with Russia by supporting Yeltsin and his
government. The White House would have been irresponsible if it
failed to assist the first democratically elected government in
Russian history. Whether the administration was sufficiently
sensitive to corruption problems in the Kremlin can and should be
debated as the presidential campaign here unfolds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
