<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CHILDREN-NYT &LR;      08-31 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHILDREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: HELPING EMBATTLED CHILDREN IN AMERICA'S
CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (mk) 
 By DUDLEY CLENDINEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For almost 20 years, Paramjit Joshi, a pediatrician and child
psychiatrist at Johns Hopkins University Medical School, has
treated black children who suffer from the lives they lead in East
Baltimore. It is the poorest, most violent, drug-ridden part of the
city, a place of little hope, low employment and high teen-age
maternity rates, where guns and murder are familiar, but fathers
are not.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect it is like parts of Atlanta, Los Angeles,
Milwaukee, Boston, Philadelphia and much of the rest of urban
America. But it was not until about five years ago, when Dr. Joshi
began going to help children caught in the ethnic warfare in Bosnia
and Croatia, that she realized how much worse off the children of
East Baltimore were than some of the children of the Balkans. For
all the terror they had suffered from guns and bombs, from the loss
of fathers and homes and communities in the ethnic wars, the
Croatian and Bosnian children showed a resilience, an ability to
cope and recover, because they came from stable lives and families,
from childhoods based on love and trust. For them, war was an
aberration. But for the thousands of children from East Baltimore
that Dr. Joshi saw at her clinic at the Hopkins Children's Center,
life was an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   They had schoolmates and family members killed, and taken away
to prison too. But they could not trust that things would be all
right. They did not feel safe in the streets, in the schools or at
home. They lived not only in acutely dysfunctional families, but in
dysfunctional neighborhoods, in large dysfunctional metropolitan
areas. Love-starved, abandoned by fathers, driven to distraction by
drug-addicted mothers or sisters or brothers, they clung to the
families they had, even as family problems became more severe.
</P>
<P>
   For some, a grandmother or great-grandmother is the only source
of strength and love. But those women, devoted to their church and
families, are dying off, and one of the critical questions for
American culture has been what to do to help children caught in
conditions that stem from chronic poverty. What therapy could be
given on such a scale? How could it be delivered? How would the
children respond? From East Baltimore, some answers have begun to
come.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, with a grant from an agency of the Federal Department
of Health and Human Services, a pilot program of counseling began
to be offered through social service agencies, the juvenile justice
system and the schools. For several years now, in each of 15 poor
black elementary schools, two middle schools and two high schools,
there has been a trained mental health counselor, with a master's
degree or doctorate in psychology, and with a private office, a
computer and a phone. And each week a psychiatrist, able to review
the case files and prescribe medications, visits each school.
</P>
<P>
   What they have found, says Gayle Porter, the Johns Hopkins
medical school psychologist who administers the program, is
broad-scale depression and hostility, what therapists call
oppositional/defiant disorder. Almost half the children in those
schools need counseling, she says, more than a third of them
long-term. What the therapists offer is counseling for them and
their families, and workshops for the teachers. They can see any
child once without parental permission. Almost half the therapists
are white, and one is from Ireland, but time has shown, Dr. Porter
says, that the children are receptive to help across cultural
lines.
</P>
<P>
   There is drug abuse in perhaps 70 percent of the families of the
children they see. Most of those children do not see their fathers
regularly. Many, bouncing from foster home to foster home, do not
see their mothers. In one high school a group of children asked the
counselor if they could have a group meeting on Mother's Day. Other
children had mothers, and they wanted someone themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the counselor in an elementary school noticed
that the signatures looked identical on five of the second-graders'
parental permission slips. She called the children in to ask why,
and they began to snuffle, and confess. They wanted counseling, but
their mothers wouldn't sign or weren't around, so the 7-year-olds
had hired a third-grader who could write in longhand to sign the
forms.
</P>
<P>
   In 25 to 30 percent of the cases in which parents are drug
abusers, the parents are persuaded to come in for counseling, Dr.
Porter says, and in about half those cases they are persuaded to
seek treatment. But it is the effect of the counseling on the
children that excites her.
</P>
<P>
   This last school year, for the first time, they checked the
report cards of a sample of 130 elementary students who had been in
counseling for 60 days or more, after beginning the year with
unsatisfactory marks in conduct, math and reading. By the third
quarter, she said, 50 percent of them were achieving at a
satisfactory level. That is a gain that could hold promise for
children and educators everywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
