<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPN-STORES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY SET TO END SPORT RETAILING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Walt Disney Co. pulled the plug Monday on its
trio of ESPN Stores, ending the entertainment giant's 2-year-old
venture into sports retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which originally planned to open hundreds of ESPN stores
as a way of taking advantage of the cable network's powerful brand
name, will redirect its efforts toward its two-outlet ESPN Zone
restaurants, Internet operations and its licensing program. A third
ESPN Zone will open Sept. 14 in New York City, and an expanded
ESPNstore.com Web site, offering more than 15,000 items, will
launch next month.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which began a corporationwide cost-cutting program four
months ago, will close its flagship ESPN outlet at the Glendale
Galleria, along with stores at MainPlace in Santa Ana and Del Amo
Fashion Center in Torrance by the end of September. About 40
employees, including managers and corporate staff, will be
pink-slipped, although some will be transferred to The Disney Store
chain.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttering the stores is a humbling admission by Disney that its
well-tuned marketing machine was unable to deliver on the promise
of attracting free-spending males between ages 18 and 34 -- the key
ESPN viewer -- to malls. The stores feature video monitors, team
apparel, collectibles and interactive kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your target market may be hard to find at malls, and when they
are there, they tend to get in and get out,'' said sports
consultant David M. Carter. ``They don't spend the whole afternoon
at the mall. In fact, there's a compelling case that Disney should
invest every spare dollar in e-commerce because that's where their
target customers are spending their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment analyst Linda Bannister of Edward Jones said
Disney is making the right decision to ditch the ESPN Stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the stores were living up to their expectations,
and I applaud Disney for taking a hard look at some of their more
recent investments,'' she said. ``They are clearly not going to
roll out things that don't make sense from a financial
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney stock fell 62.5 cents Monday to $28.50. Company
management has been under pressure from Wall Street to boost share
price, and cost-reductions efforts have included hundreds of job
cuts in its TV, movie and video operations and the sale of its
Fairchild magazines for $650 million.
</P>
<P>
   A Disney spokesman said the announcement has no impact on the
720-outlet Disney Stores chain, which is planning a redesign of
mall-based stores, or on Disney's year-old licensing deal with
Sears Roebuck for stores-within-stores selling ESPN-branded
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Disney moved into retail in 1987 with the launch of the first
Disney Store at the Glendale Galleria. That chain became one of the
best examples of Chairman Michael Eisner's dedication to the
strategy of synergy -- using one part of the company to boost
awareness of another.
</P>
<P>
   It ditched the idea of moving into fast food when it closed a
pair of mall-based Mickey Kitchens after a year in the early 1990s.
But it has launched a wide array of other ventures in recent years
aside from the ESPN Zones, including a cruise line, the new Animal
Kingdom theme park, the DisneyQuest interactive park and the Club
Disney indoor play parks.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
