<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5427 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-QUAKE-SILVER-LINING-E     08-31 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-SILVER-LINING-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE EMERGES FROM THE RUBBLE OF TURKEY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 775-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 28 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the ghastly scale of the death toll in Turkey's earthquake
became apparent in the days after the tremor, so did the tardiness
of the official rescue and relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   After the shock and grief of last week, the predominant
sentiment in Turkey this week was anger. Anger at the government
for not reacting swiftly enough to rescue and help survivors. Anger
at the army for not pulling into action sooner. And anger at the
country's bureaucrats for allowing the poorly constructed
buildings, which crumbled like sand castles, to have been put up in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this anger is properly directed. But some of it could
lead to the wrong conclusions about how to avoid such appalling
loss of life _ 13,000 dead by the middle of this week, with many
thousands more believed dead under the rubble _ next time.
</P>
<P>
   It seems incredible that Turkey, which sits on a geological
fault line, had no dedicated rescue team. Not only did the
government fail to train and equip such a force, it also failed to
mobilize the one institution whose strength and discipline are
legendary: the army.
</P>
<P>
   As skilled foreign technicians bored, chiselled and hacked their
way into the mounds of compacted debris, and as Turkish volunteers
ferried in food and dug desperately with their own machinery, tools
and hands, their government froze.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until Saturday, fully four days after the quake, that
the army _ admittedly reeling from casualties of its own _ went
into action.
</P>
<P>
   For these two failures, the blame lies squarely with the
government. More complicated, however, is the matter of the flimsy
buildings, a big contributor to the heavy death toll.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the comment since the quake, both in Turkey and the
West, has centered on the need for tougher regulation of the
building industry. In the aftermath of such a catastrophe, that is
an easy demand to make. But Turkey had building regulations: they
were evaded (with official collusion) or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed is more effective regulation, which is a
different and more difficult thing.
</P>
<P>
   If rules are to prevent the shoddy and reckless work that has
cost many lives _ blocks built on shallow foundations, cement mixed
with too much sand _ they must be designed so that they are
feasible both to obey and to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   Regulations that were merely ``tougher'' could be quickly
introduced, but in all likelihood would be neither.
</P>
<P>
   There is another problem. The lessons from the earthquakes in
Los Angeles in 1994 (54 deaths) and Kobe, Japan, in 1995 (6,500
deaths) suggest that _ other things being equal _ the critical
factor determining the death toll is the nature of the building
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Weight is the killer: Turks were crushed by the collapsing
structures above their heads. In Japan, heavy-roofed buildings put
up to withstand the frequent typhoons also proved lethal. In
California, timber-framed houses with light roofs, bolted to a
concrete foundation, rode out the tremors.
</P>
<P>
   Before Turkey and foreign well-wishers rush to rebuild heavy
high-rise cement buildings, they might do well to consider
old-fashioned timber.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, of course, that all things are far from equal. The
harsh and unavoidable fact is that natural disasters kill more
people in poor countries than they do in rich ones.
</P>
<P>
   Shoddy construction is one of the deprivations of poverty. And
though the poor world has no monopoly of bureaucratic corruption,
enforcing rules designed to make buildings safer (and dearer) will
always be easier in countries that are richer and which have more
accountable governments.
</P>
<P>
   This week's outburst of popular Turkish anger at their state for
failing them has been startling. Could it become a force for
change?
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, if it prompts more of the humility shown by at least
one member of the government this week _ and if this translates
into a willingness to allow greater openness and freedom in Turkey,
even in ways that challenge the secular creed bequeathed by Kemal
Ataturk in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Turkey's best prospects of becoming a better
governed and more prosperous place may lie in the embrace of the
European Union. Here too some hope emerges from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   EU governments have repeatedly snubbed Turkey, refusing to take
seriously its hope of membership and huddling conveniently behind
the objections of its old antagonist, Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Eventual Turkish membership would be a matter for delicate
negotiation. But the generous hand held out to Turkey by Greece
this week offers a hope that objections to opening such talks may
yet be overcome. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 775-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5428 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ABORTION-AZR &LR;      08-31 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION CHALLENGE DROPPED; ARIZONA LAWMAKERS WANT INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER AND MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Gov. Jane Hull on Monday dropped any challenge of a
controversial Arizona Supreme Court decision that allowed a
14-year-old girl to seek a late-term abortion in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, criticized by abortion foes, effectively ends the
appeals process in Arizona courts, and dimmed any prospect of an
appeal in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a state lawmaker asked the attorney general for an
investigation into how supposedly confidential information about
the girl and her situation leaked to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative hearings will be conducted soon to try to discover:
</P>
<P>
   _Why the girl was allowed to have a late-term abortion.
</P>
<P>
   _Why the man who raped the girl and caused the pregnancy has not
been prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   _How government funds are being used for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   _How the girl's situation was allowed to become a political
football. One lawmaker said such leaks should be considered
felonies, not misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Hull also is asking for an investigation into how confidential
information leaked.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who is 24 weeks pregnant and a ward of the Arizona
Department of Economic Security, was headed under court order to
Kansas for an abortion because Arizona's time limit for ending a
pregnancy is 20 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The story was leaked to abortion opponents last week. State
officials appealed and temporarily halted the procedure. But the
Arizona Supreme Court on Sunday voted 3-2 to allow the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going any further,'' said Francie Noyes, Hull's
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Hull said she remains concerned that
allowing the girl to go out of state for the procedure could
violate Arizona laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed by the Supreme Court's decision yesterday,''
Hull said. ``I have read that there may be legal efforts under way
to go to federal court. My office is not part of any of these
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   John Jakubczyk, president of Arizona Right to Life, said Hull's
decision effectively ended legal efforts to stop the abortion. He
said he could not appeal to federal court because he has no legal
standing in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not an avenue in the federal courts,'' he said, adding
that Hull's decision to drop the appeal was a ``major
disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to try and fail,'' Jakubczyk said. ``It's
another thing not to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull vowed a ``complete'' review of the case, including an
investigation into how confidential information was leaked about
the girl's case to groups opposing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not come to any decision on how that review will be
conducted,'' Noyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull also wants to review the policies and decisions made by
Child Protective Services, a division of DES.
</P>
<P>
   Because the information could have come from state child welfare
officials, the Attorney General's Office or Maricopa County
Superior Court, conflict-of-interest rules may require any criminal
investigation to be conducted by a law enforcement agency outside
of Maricopa County.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights supporters continue to press for a thorough
inquiry into the release of the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just amazing the information that has dribbled out,''
said Bryan Howard, president of Planned Parenthood of Central and
Northern Arizona. ``There are lots of legal questions to be asked
about leaks and confidentiality.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Health Committee Chairwoman Sue Grace, R-northeast
Phoenix, asked Attorney General Janet Napolitano to prosecute
whoever leaked the information on the pending abortion to abortion
opponents and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the attorney general will start that investigation
today,'' Grace said Monday. ``We need to find out who broke the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Burke, special assistant attorney general, was reviewing
requests for an investigation from several people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take appropriate action and respond to those
requests,'' Burke said. ``We'll begin with our own attorneys
looking into it _ to figure out if any releasing of records to the
public or press violated any Arizona laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Releasing confidential information on state wards is a
misdemeanor, punishable by up to four months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be a felony,'' Grace said. ``Her rights were
violated. It clearly affected her health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fallout continued from the Supreme Court's decision
to overturn a stay on the abortion issued Saturday by state Court
of Appeals Judge Michael Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stanley Feldman, Ruth McGregor and Frederick Martone
voted to overturn the stay, with Chief Justice Thomas Zlaket and
Vice Chief Justice Charles Jones saying no.
</P>
<P>
   John MacDonald, a Supreme Court spokesman, said the justices
would not discuss their ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Critics accused Feldman of conflict-of-interest rules, citing a
1973 case in which Feldman represented Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald said Planned Parenthood wasn't a party to the case of
the 14-year-old girl. Before Sunday's hearing, Feldman said he had
once represented Planned Parenthood and offered to recuse himself.
</P>
<P>
   After answering several questions about the 1973 case, MacDonald
said, attorneys in the case said they did not object to Feldman
remaining on the case. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
