<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-BAD-BOY-POLITICS-ECON     08-31 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-BOY-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH: FAIR IS FOUL, FOUL IS FAIR, HOVER THROUGH THE FILTHY HEIR?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 725-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 28 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stir over whether George W. Bush, the governor of Texas, has
used cocaine is not the first and will not be the last example of
America's unique ferocity in testing its elected politicians to
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Before the country takes another lurch towards regarding moral
ambiguity as a disqualification from office, it makes sense to ask:
which questions are legitimate for voters to ask? Which aren't?
</P>
<P>
   Private matters become public depending on what a candidate says
and the nature of the question in hand. For example, adultery in
itself is not a legitimate matter of electoral scrutiny. It becomes
one if a politician, rather than remaining silent on the subject,
proclaims his fidelity or makes great play of ``family values.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to speak out is vital because voters have a right
to know whether somebody is lying, and a lie about a personal
matter is a valid gauge of truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Many people argued during the Monica Lewinsky affair that Bill
Clinton was justified in lying in public because it was a private
matter, and anyone would tell lies to protect their marriage. But
lying in public means deceiving the voters and is a legitimate
matter for scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate's willingness to speak out also helps decide how far
back enquiry can reasonably go. If he or she talks about the
distant past, it opens that period up to legitimate investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's case, that means the past 25 years, the period he says
he has not taken drugs. So far, there is no evidence that he is
telling lies _ and no one has come forward with accusations about
his behavior. On these grounds, then, voters ought to be satisfied
with his answers so far.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the issue also matters. Not all actions deserve
the same degree of scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, many people have argued that, since possession of
cocaine is a felony, Bush should reassure voters that he has never,
ever, taken coke.
</P>
<P>
   His friends might reply that, when it comes to setting a
political statute of limitations, there are different kinds of
offense. A crime of violence, for example, is worse than possession
of cocaine, even though both are felonies.
</P>
<P>
   And it is true that Bush's incomplete statements reflect a wider
ambivalence in the public attitude towards drugs. Since so many
Americans have taken them, they are more tolerant of this
particular felony than of others.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Lewinsky affair, journalists have justified
any and all enquiries on the grounds that, because candidates have
been talking about restoring the honor and dignity of the
presidency, anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   The public seems to disagree. But even if a candidate is not
lying, and even if the issue might not justify public scrutiny,
there remains a further test: voters are entitled to ask whether a
candidate is a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's case, two questions about double standards were
pertinent. First, could he pass the background drugs tests required
of federal employees? Second, and more significant, did his
personal history invalidate his policies towards drugs?
</P>
<P>
   As governor of Texas, Bush has approved a law that allows judges
to imprison people convicted of selling or possessing less than one
gram of cocaine. In the United States, thousands are in jail for
this, some as young as 14.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine for a minute that he had sniffed cocaine before he was
24. Would it be wrong of him to support mandatory jail sentences
for young cocaine users now?
</P>
<P>
   Candidates should be able to change their minds in good faith,
and voters should be willing to let them. Bush ought to be allowed
to say that he has learned from his mistakes and has concluded that
tough anti-drugs laws work (mistaken as he may be about that).
</P>
<P>
   It would certainly have been more convincing if he had said that
he had used cocaine, that that was the temper of the times and it
was this experience which had persuaded him of the need for tough
anti-drugs policies. But he has not done so.
</P>
<P>
   Bush simply refuses to confirm or deny. He has chosen to be less
than candid. It is indeed a kind of hypocrisy _ one with which the
American public, not for the first time, seems happy to go along. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 725-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
