r a BC-MIDWEST-FARM-CRISIS-1     08-31 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDWEST-FARM-CRISIS-1100&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDWEST'S FAMILY FARMERS SHRIVEL UP LIKE AUGUST CORN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Midwest Editors)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 28 August 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
STANDS IN 1,100 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,500.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, IOWA _ ``I am convinced from evidence in our house
that my husband listened to the grain markets at noon, as he
usually did, heard them go lower, and then committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have enclosed a copy of the letter he left me. It reads:
`The only thing I will regret is leaving (the children) and you.
This farming has brought me a lot of memories, some happy, but most
of all grief. All I ever wanted was to farm since I was a little
kid, and especially this place. I know now that is never going to
happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   This stark letter, written by a farmer's widow to the governor
of Iowa, is an extreme expression of the most severe agricultural
downturn in America since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's Iowa State Fair, one of the country's
agricultural showpieces, the talk is gloomy. ``It's the start of
the end of family farming. We can't cover our costs and many will
go to the wall,'' says Leland Fynaardt, of Searsboro.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Severin of Lowden agrees. ``The big guys are coming into
this business,'' he says, while staring bleakly at Rumpelstiltskin,
the winner of the fattest pig in the fair (487 kilos, or 1,071
pounds), who looks like a pink zeppelin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are squeezing the heck out of the small farmer and the
consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Washington, the same message is blaring forth: ``It is
not an overstatement to say,'' declares Byron Dorgan, the
Democratic senator from North Dakota, ``that we are approaching the
end-game for family-based agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   If that were true, it would be a huge change in what is still
America's second-largest exporting industry.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, family farms _ a few hundred acres looked after by
a man, his wife and their sons _ have been the weft and weave of
the Midwest. But is family farming really dying?
</P>
<P>
   ``The romantic view of one family, with some corn, a few cows,
pigs and chickens on 200 acres _ that died out in the 1960s,'' says
Ray Bardole, who farms 1,400 acres (560 hectares) in Rippey, in
central Iowa's billowing landscape of black earth and waving corn.
</P>
<P>
   He is right: since 1950, the number of farms has fallen from 5.6
million to 2.2 million. Thousands of farmers continue to leave the
land every year, responding to technological changes that have
doubled agricultural productivity over the past half century.
</P>
<P>
   Two things are different this year. There are unnerving
parallels with the farm crisis of the mid-1980s, which gutted
communities throughout the central states.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, three years of good weather produced bumper crops,
and deep price falls when demand fell in world markets at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   This year has been worse. Soybean farmers are harvesting their
third record crop in a row, even while prices have hit their lowest
since 1972, about $4 a bushel. This is less than most farmers' cost
of production. Two years ago, soybeans fetched $8 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in meat prices has been even more dramatic. Last year,
the pork price fell to just $8 a hundredweight. This was even less
than during the Great Depression and a third of the cost of
production.
</P>
<P>
   Some family farmers will not survive for long. Bankers in the
Midwest are already asking for next year's financial plan even
before this year's harvest is in.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers have only survived this long because, in one respect,
they are better off than during the 1980s crisis. Then, the
increase in farm incomes in earlier years had bid up the price of
land, which in parts of Iowa trebled to $4,000 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the farm woes occurred when the Federal Reserve
raised interest rates to cool off the Reagan expansion, making it
impossible for thousands of farmers to service the debts they had
taken out to buy land at inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Fed raised interest rates this week, farmers'
financing costs are still low compared with what they were in the
1980s. Then farmers' debt-service costs were around 14 percent of
production expenses; they are now 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, then, farmers are in better shape than they were
the last time things got really tough. Still, with prices so low a
renewed shakeout is inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1981 and 1987, the number of farms fell by 250,000. If
the same thing were to happen again, the number would fall to 1.94
million by 2005 _ a 12 percent decline in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of most industries, that would count as a
modest decline. But farmers are not like most other workers _ their
way of life, self-respect and sense of identity are often
intimately entwined with their job.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even those that remain on the land fret that the
relentless growth of corporate farming will leave them as little
more than hired tractor-drivers, a prospect most find humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   John Gilbert of the Iowa Farmers' Union explains: ``Turkey and
eggs used to be an essential part of diversified farming. It was
how you learned the business. That's been taken over by one or two
processors. Then came beef. Now three or four packers buy most of
the cattle. Everyone thought it would never happen to pigs. They
were too diversified and easy to raise. But look at it now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the pig industry has been transformed. Family
pig farms in Iowa, the main hog-producing state (and the
second-largest farm state after California), used to have up to 500
sows, each producing about 20 piglets a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, industrial-scale pig warehouses are appearing, with 16,000
sows raising 320,000 piglets a year. The stench from these huge
battery pig farms spreads for miles. But they are only the most
visible and smelliest evidence of change.
</P>
<P>
   More significant is the way in which pigs are marketed. Where
family farmers used to take their piglets straight to market, they
now raise them on behalf of the large warehouse farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, a tenth of America's pigs were raised in this
way, under contract. Now two thirds are.
</P>
<P>
   It is this contract-farming system that the family owners now
fear as much as bankruptcy. They have seen poultry, beef, and pig
farming swallowed by the system. The next domino to fall could be
grain.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the firms involved in agriculture, the largest are
already the grain traders and seed producers, most of the latter
owned by big chemical firms. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,100. OPTIONAL COPY FOLLOWS TO 1,500) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Last year, Cargill, one big firm, bought the grain-trading
operations of another, Continental. For many, this exemplified the
trend toward greater concentration and monopoly purchasing
threatening farmers. They fear being crushed between these
corporate millstones, and that the big companies will then buy up
their farms.
</P>
<P>
   That is possible. But the pattern of rapidly increasing
consolidation is not quite the unstoppable, Darwinist expansion
that it seems.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there is nothing relentless or rapid about the
growth of the biggest beef companies. Although a few big firms
dominate slaughtering, it took them 30 years to get to the point
where they slaughter about two-thirds of all cattle, and they still
have only about 22-24 percent of cattle under contract. That share
has been stable for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   For another, there is nothing mysterious about the rise of these
operations. They succeed where they have a price advantage, as in
the pork business, where superior feeding, veterinary and other
techniques are important. But they do not have this advantage
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, calf raising, which is largely a matter of looking
after cows and calves as they forage, is run by small farmers. It
seems likely that the family grain farms are more like the
calf-foraging operations than the pork factories.
</P>
<P>
   There is no obvious advantage to size. A typical Midwestern
grain farm is roughly the acreage that one family can farm.
Improvements to tractors or fertilizers make it possible for one
person to look after a slightly larger area each year, so farms get
bigger and a few more people leave.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no technological gain to dramatic increases in
scale. So family farms should survive. But not unaltered.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bardole shows how they are changing. His farm provides an
income for himself and his family, and his two sons and their
families. About half the money comes from soybeans and corn. But
one daughter-in-law works in a day-care center; one is a speech
therapist.
</P>
<P>
   He runs a pig nursery for a large hog producer. He rents out a
special piece of farm-drilling equipment. And about half of his
soybeans are grown under contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I use contract farming as a tool,'' he concludes,
``it's a good deal. If a big company is using me as a tool, then
it's a problem.'' &QL; 
