<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBIN-HOOD-PENSION-FUND-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIAA-CREF: IS DO-GOODER PENSION FUND GOOD ENOUGH?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Indiana _ note 4th graf)   (This 500-word ``separate buy'' financial story is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By TED C. FISHMAN  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIAA-CREF, the largest pension fund in the world, was founded on
the progressive instincts of Andrew Carnegie. When the steel tycoon
found out how low the salaries of college professors were, he was
shocked. The threat of poverty, he felt, would dissuade talented
individuals from entering academia and thus deny the nation a vital
resource.
</P>
<P>
   His remedy: a $1 million gift in 1918 to start a pension fund
for professors.
</P>
<P>
   Now a group of professors wants Carnegie's pension fund to
strike out against the poverty of others _ but the giant is
resisting.
</P>
<P>
   The growing campaign, led by Neil Wollman and Abigail Fuller,
married professors at Manchester College in Indiana, proposes to
commit more pension money to enterprises ``that are models of
social and environmental responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, they've gotten nowhere: TIAA-CREF rejects the plan as
both impracticable and potentially damaging to returns.
</P>
<P>
   The money Wollman and Fuller are fighting for would come out of
the pension plan's Social Choice Account, an investment pool that
already bars from its portfolio companies that fail a set of
screens in such things as environmental safety or that make
products such as weapons or alcohol. But the portfolio does not
actively identify companies that can change the world for the
better.
</P>
<P>
   Most participants in the Social Choice Account, Wollman and
Fuller say, want their money to do more good for others, and they
argue that returns probably wouldn't be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Ethical debate is not new to TIAA-CREF. The fund serves over two
million participants, the majority of whom work in higher
education. That group, says Tom Pinto, the fund's director of media
relations, ``is a little more interested in social issues'' than
the average investor.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, TIAA-CREF inaugurated its Social Choice Account
only after a five-year campaign by the rank and file, Wollman says.
Today, it's the world's largest socially responsible fund, with
around $3.6 billion in assets. In the past five years, it has
returned an annual average of 18.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wollman cites a TIAA-CREF internal survey conducted four years
ago in which 81 percent of current contributors supported investing
in companies that have an ``outstanding record of good performance
on social issues'' rather than pass negative screens.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be invested mostly in small- and micro-company
stocks, as well as in inner-city banks and community-development
corporations _ companies that are usually off the radar of fund
managers.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-six percent of plan participants would accept more
``financial risk in (their) investments if they created more
desirable social change.''
</P>
<P>
   Wollman's use of the study has ticked off TIAA-CREF officials,
who say it was conducted for internal review only and have now
distanced themselves from it. But Pinto says a proactive socially
responsible fund is just not feasible.
</P>
<P>
   Wollman disagrees. ``TIAA-CREF created a socially responsible
fund when participants demanded it,'' he explains, ``but now that
we want to do better with our money, the fund is reverting to its
old stance and running our money its own way.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Ted C. Fishman is a contributor editor of
``WORTH.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 500-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
