r f BC-MONEY-MESSAGE-BOARDS-     08-31 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-MESSAGE-BOARDS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL MESSAGE BOARDS WITH CIVILITY, NOT SPITBALLS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance Editors)   (This excellent 1,150-word ``separate buy'' financial story is from
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By RAVI DESAI  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Uncle, you cried this before, go ahead, short it, short as
much as you can. go on. have a ball. you bought in at 18 my left
leg. ive read your old posts, who are you trying to kid?''
(``Hroark'' on the Bidnow.com board at Raging Bull) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, now that I know you are a Mr. Know-it-All
Zero-Personality social idiot, it won't happen again.'' (``E.
Graphs'' on the Razorfish board at Silicon Inventor) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, financial message boards represent what is worst
about the Internet: irresponsible anonymity, blatant
rumor-mongering, personal attacks, atrocious writing.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who has spent the barest amount of time on these
boards knows, much of the discussion consists of small-company hype
(usually written entirely in capital letters) followed by
hysterical finger-pointing when the tip, inevitably, turns out to
be less than wildly profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Even barring pure fraud, as in the case of the PairGain employee
who has been charged with dummying up a fake Bloomberg News page
about his company's imminent takeover and linking to it from Yahoo
Finance, stock message boards represent an extraordinarily
unreliable source of insight.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the dubious quality of most messages, the sheer volume
can be overwhelming. And for the most part there is no way of
telling which messages contain a nugget of knowledge and which
consist merely of speculation and uninformed opinion.
</P>
<P>
   To unearth anything of value, you typically have to read through
dozens of screens of utterly useless boosterism.
</P>
<P>
   Why even bother? Well, for one thing, lying in the murky depths
is often some real insight.
</P>
<P>
   Most financial journalists can't tell a fiber-optic cable from a
strand of spaghetti, but on the financial message boards, some of
the most active participants are employees of tech companies. (It's
no coincidence that the most active boards focus on the technology
sector. This may also explain why the writing on the boards is so
spectacularly bad.)
</P>
<P>
   When enough of these techies gather in a place and when they
manage to restrain themselves from foaming at the mouth, some truly
powerful insights emerge.
</P>
<P>
   When I worked for a major hard-disk-drive manufacturer, I
regularly trawled the boards for insight into the market conditions
for drives. The cataclysmic fall in disk-drive stocks in 1997 was
predicted at least a month in advance on Silicon Investor, as
employees of the component suppliers started whispering about
orders drying up and technology problems with the next generation
of heads.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to pay attention: Most of the participants on the
boards are individual investors. This means their insights have a
longer shelf life than those spun out by Wall Street analysts,
since the volume of trading around any insight is typically fairly
small.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, while the odds of any small investor's being able to
capitalize on Mary Meeker's upgrades or downgrades are minuscule,
most of the money made off Internet message boards accrues to
holders of small discount-brokerage accounts rather than to some
underregulated hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   Still, panning for gold in this particular stream can be
exhausting. In a thoroughly unscientific test, I compared four
message boards recently, using two large-company stocks (AT&AMP;T and
Novell) and two Internet stocks (Razorfish and eBay) as test cases.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the boards are old mainstays of this form: Yahoo
Finance (quote.yahoo.com), Silicon Investor (www.techstocks.com),
and the venerable pioneer of the genre, Motley Fool (www.fool.com).
The fourth is a newcomer, Raging Bull (www.ragingbull.com).
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Investor is the only one with a fee: $10 a month if you
want to post messages; nothing just to read them.
</P>
<P>
   I looked for ease of use, the quality of the average and best
messages, the sheer number of interesting messages, and a catch-all
category I called ``other goodies'' _ which enabled me to skew the
outcome of the competition whichever way I wanted.
</P>
<P>
   First, a caveat. The experiences were, to one extent or another,
frustrating, and all in reasonably similar and predictable ways:
Far too many messages in total, a truly awful ratio of interesting
to utterly worthless messages, disturbing numbers of spitball
fights.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I found something of value about each of the companies _
and in no instance did it take me more than 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most cogent discussion I've seen anywhere _
including in the press _ of AT&AMP;T's proposed acquisition of Media
One cropped up on Raging Bull; that site also featured a thoughtful
explanation of Novell's strategy for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   I found on Yahoo a penetrating discussion of Razorfish posted
within minutes of its red-hot initial public offering and, on
Silicon Inventor, an entertaining _ if anecdotal _ comparison of
the various auction sites (including eBay, uBid, Bidnow, and
others), based on the experience of buying identical Pez dispensers
from all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites, the clear winner was Raging Bull, whose tools
streamline the experience in a noticeably superior way. It's simple
to customize the site to your preferences, including screening out
messages from habitually annoying participants _ a sort of twit
filter.
</P>
<P>
   The site also features a highlighted list of ``Top Posts'' every
day and makes it easy to reach boards that have topics of wide
interest (``Hot Stock Tips'' or ``Top 40'' boards). And as a nice
freebie, it tosses in unlimited free real-time stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important distinction between Raging Bull and the
other sites is one of character.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Raging Bull's ridiculous name and logo, both redolent of
the hype preceding a market crash, its members seem somewhat calmer
and more introspective than those at other sites.
</P>
<P>
   While this is by no means universal _ witness the message at the
beginning of this story _ most of the participants seem to have
chosen Raging Bull based on some common belief in insight and
relative civility.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Retroavia,'' a regular user of Raging Bull, writes, ``There
are quite a few very savvy investors posting here,'' and ``if you
sort through the B.S. (pun intended), you can reap the benefits of
synergism.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the site is ``a great word picture of the mood of
the investors in stocks of interest to me. You can almost feel
their adrenaline rush or their fury and frustration at times from
their posts.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the kernels of knowledge, this may in fact be the
most useful function of financial message boards. As individual
investors play a larger role in the market, judging their sentiment
has become increasingly important. But it's no mean task: With
millions of investors spread across the country, calling a few
pundits or watching CNBC is of little use.
</P>
<P>
   Raging Bull is almost always a nice, if somewhat unscientific,
weather vane and occasionally quite a bit more _ a democratic and
observant analyst report. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Ravi Desai (rdesai(at)scient.com) is a managing
director at Scient and WORTH's regular ``Net Investor'' columnist.
He is work on a book.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this interesting 1,150-word ``WORTH'' magazine
article, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
