<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-BOS &LR;      08-31 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a Red Sox team five weeks away from reaching the playoffs
for the second straight season, there can be no better sight than
Pedro Martinez in the full bloom of health.
</P>
<P>
   That was underscored yet again in Monday night's 9-1 mismatch
against the Kansas City Royals, Boston's fourth straight win, in
which Martinez struck out 11, walked just one, and didn't allow a
runner past first base after the second inning. Jimy Williams
dismissed him after the sixth inning, ahead, 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who gave up just four hits, is 3-1 with a 1.74 ERA in
five starts since coming off the disabled list at the start of the
month. He is 19-4, matching his 1998 win total with potentially six
starts left. The Royals' only run scored on a second-inning wild
pitch after a double by Jermaine Dye and single by Mike Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day I'm feeling better and better,'' said Martinez, who
yielded to John Wasdin and Mark Guthrie after throwing 103 pitches.
``Stronger and healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Sox are banking on a refreshed Martinez to carry
them down the stretch, they may be forced to reclaim their
wild-card spot without John Valentin. The third baseman, who
already had missed three of the last five games with a sore left
knee, departed after four innings Monday night and admitted he may
be finished for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible, sure,'' Valentin said. ``I hate to say it, but
yeah, it's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who replaced Valentin with rookie Donnie Sadler, all
but conceded that reinforcements are on their way. Asked about
Trenton third baseman Wilton Veras, who played splendidly when
Valentin was on the DL earlier this season after a beaning,
Williams said, ``I'm not making that decision now, but that's
pretty good speculation. We called him up before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox would not have to make a move to add Veras Wednesday,
when rosters can be expanded beyond their normal 25-man limit. But
if the Sox intend to have Veras eligible for postseason play, they
may decide to place Valentin on the DL Tuesday and have Veras on
board in time for Tuesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to take him out of a game,'' Williams said. ``That's
not good. No collision, nothing. We need to get him checked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the team has been home for five days, Valentin still
has not undergone a magnetic resonance imaging, which presumably
would show whether there is an injury requiring surgery. Valentin
was scheduled to have an MRI last Friday but according to him the
machine was malfunctioning. He's scheduled to go this morning, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Bret Saberhagen, meanwhile, flew to New York Monday
morning for an MRI with his own doctor, had the results analyzed
while he was there (frayed rotator cuff), and was still back in the
clubhouse three hours before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Why the apparent absence of urgency with Valentin?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a comment for you,'' Valentin said. ``We'll take
care of it (Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhat my fault, to basically have blown off the fact
that my knee hurts. When you're a player, you just want to play. I
basically go out there and if I can walk, I can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not working, which is very, very, very frustrating.
If I would have said something, I probably should have said
something in spring training, but I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin said over the weekend that he has been hurt since
midseason a year ago, but after the season was told by the Sox
medical staff that only rest was required. But only a couple of
weeks into spring training, the condition flared up, but he didn't
say anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it was just temporary,'' he said. ``But it
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, after playing four games on the artificial turf in
Toronto, he said he intended to go home and have an MRI, but never
did. He said at that time that the medical staff told him it was
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've got to play with,'' Valentin said at the
time. ``Does it feel better? Well, it doesn't bother me when I
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   In 12 games since Aug. 15, Valentin's play has declined
noticeably. He is batting .122 (5 for 41) in that span, with more
than twice as many strikeouts (11) as hits (5) and as many errors
(2) as RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   After waving at a ground ball single by Joe Randa in the fourth
inning, Valentin came into the dugout and told trainer Jim Rowe
that he couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do it no more,'' Valentin said. ``I tried. Shoot. It's
just been like this for the longest time. I've been playing in pain
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler reached and scored in Boston's four-run fifth when an
opponent bobbled his sacrifice bunt attempt for the second time in
two days. He also singled and scored in the two-run sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, fresh off a three-game sweep of Mo Vaughn's Angels, had
14 hits, four by Jose Offerman, while taking the measure of another
former teammate, Royals pitcher Jeff Suppan. They moved 15 games
above .500 for the first time this season while increasing their
their lead over Oakland in the AL wild-card race to two games with
31 left.
</P>
<P>
   It's play like this that will carry the Sox to the playoffs.
Valentin, meanwhile, pondered the possibility that he'll be reduced
to the role of spectator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been affecting my play all year,'' he said. ``But you
still try to rise above it. You want to help your team to the
playoffs. There isn't anyone who doesn't want to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0237EDT &QL; 
