<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS UNDER ATTACK AS CRIMINALS SEEK EASY PREY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CLAY THOMPSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ They are the least among us, broken by poverty,
illness or addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the men and women who scratch out their existences in
Phoenix's homeless district are increasingly finding themselves
easy prey for criminals who take by force what little the homeless
have.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police report that aggravated assaults in the area are
up about 15 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 56 assaults in the downtown area near the
railroad tracks. There have been 40 attacks in the first seven
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The area is heavily peopled by the homeless, but it is not
possible to determine how many of the victims were street people.
Those records aren't kept. And police say they can't explain the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who live on the streets or frequent the shelters
or cheap hotels downtown say many of the attacks are against them,
and increasingly, they're fueled by drug traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not safe down here. You get a guy with $5 or $13 or $20
and and somebody will rob him for it,'' Mike Moss of Phoenix said
over lunch at the St. Vincent de Paul dining room downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's drugs. There are a lot of drugs and robberies around
here. It's just a crime-infested area. There are too many people
hanging out on the streets,'' said Moss, who is not homeless but
takes advantage of the dining room's free meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``And 90 percent of the time, the guy won't tell the police.
They don't want to get known as a snitch.'' &QL; 
`GETTING MORE AGGRESSIVE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The director of Central Arizona Shelter services, a homeless
shelter in the area, said he recently has been receiving many
complaints about area violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be getting more and more aggressive out on the
streets here,'' Mark Holleran said. ``Our clients complain of being
threatened, we had a staff member punched today and I had a man
threaten to beat me. It's been pretty bad and I'm not sure why.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a loosely organized group of seven men were
arrested following early morning robberies of three people in the
area, one of whom was shot, police said. Phoenix police said they
believe the group is responsible for a series of similar attacks
over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When 4 (p.m.) comes, you can't walk around outside here.
They're dealing (drugs) out here. There are cars coming and going
all the time,'' said Irene Molina as she and Carol Woodord walked
from the dining room back to the CASS homeless shelter on Madison
Street. Both are CASS clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here a week, at CASS,'' Woodord said. ``I'm scared
to death to go out at night. Even during the day it's not safe.'' &QL; 
`VERY VULNERABLE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For criminals, the pickings are slim but easy along Madison
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Street people ``are very, very vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are carrying everything they own. Many of them are
mentally ill. Some are physically disabled,'' said Kay Martin, who
runs an ecumenical ministry for street people at First Presbyterian
Church, 402 West Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens often, too often,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Without bank accounts, the homeless carry what cash they have
with them and in a neighborhood filled with desperation, you can
get rolled for a quarter. Identification cards, a necessity for
getting welfare or help from agencies that aid the homeless, are a
popular target for thieves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of predators,'' homeless advocate Louisa Stark
said. ``It's horrible, horrible. Almost every crime there is
committed against them.`
</P>
<P>
   Muggings are especially numerous around ``Mother's Day,'' the
day welfare checks arrive at a postal substation across the street
from the St. Vincent de Paul dining room. &QL; 
MANY CRIMES UNREPORTED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But many of the crimes are never even reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gerald Roseberry, a retired Presbyterian minister and a
homeless advocate who once lived on the streets of Phoenix and
Tucson for a month, said homeless people often are reluctant to
turn to the police for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't necessarily look on the police as their friends,''
he said. ``They don't always trust the police (like) an averaged
middle-class person does.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Bob Ragsdale, a Phoenix police spokesman, said street
people, especially illegal immigrants, may be anxious to avoid
contact with the police, even to report a crime against themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, police respond swiftly when notified.
</P>
<P>
   Officers were on the scene of last week's shooting in the
homeless district within one minute of getting the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will evaluate every incident on its merit,'' he said. &QL; 
Republic writer William Hermann contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
