<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5468 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-REWRITE-L     08-31 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN LIFTS DODGERS TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown is a huge Star Wars fan. He
understands hype, and the inability to live up to it when it
reaches the level the Phantom Menace did.
</P>
<P>
   He also understands it's virtually impossible to live up to
expectations after signing for $105 million. For the 15th time in
21 decisions as a Los Angeles Dodger, Brown won, and yet more seems
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by Eric Karros' two-run homer, Brown was a 6-1
complete-game winner against Milwaukee at Dodger Stadium on Monday,
but it wasn't that easy. Nothing's been that easy for Brown this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not having the type of year I'd like to have,'' said
Brown, who is 15-6 with a 3.24 ERA. ``It's not easy for me, every
year you don't click. There's been a lot of tough games where
there's been tough breaks. I've pitched bad in some games and in
some games you need to get breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has won six straight decisions, hasn't lost since July 5
and his mannerisms and work ethic have begun to wear off on others
on the Dodgers staff. He has failed to pitch at least seven innings
in just one of his past nine starts, and since his last loss his
ERA is 2.44; that includes seven earned runs in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as comfortable (as last season),'' Brown said. ``I'm
not as consistently locked in. Overall, I don't feel as good as I
did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown came very close to his first shutout as a Dodger on a
potential double-play grounder. He still leads the staff in any
positive category you can come up with for a starter, but he admits
all isn't rosy.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening-day start against Arizona in which he allowed
five runs in 52/3 innings, to the four-start stretch in which he
went without a win a few months ago, to the grand slam he allowed
to Milwaukee's Jose Valentin in his last start, there has always
been something that has cropped up this year that wasn't there in
Brown's last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He led Florida to the 1997 World Series title by going 16-8 with
a 2.69 ERA. Last year he was 18-7 with a 2.38 ERA in taking San
Diego to the World Series before losing to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all haven't seen the best of him yet,'' Dodgers left fielder
Gary Sheffield said. ``I'm living proof of that. I saw him in
Florida. He's pitching great, but I've seen him better. I think his
competitive desire is great no matter what. When it's the playoffs,
he takes it to another level. It's like, just get him a run.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said, Brown has tried to
shoulder too much of the responsibility in helping to develop the
rest of the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was the time Brown sat and talked with Chan Ho Park
for a few hours after Park was hit hard in a start. Darren Dreifort
talked about watching Brown's work ethic and ability to bear down
in crucial situations, and learning from it.
</P>
<P>
   During a 16-inning loss to Arizona in the second week of the
season, Brown asked to pitch in relief. Johnson balked at it. Brown
has asked a few times since, and been turned down each time.
</P>
<P>
   But that desire also prompted Johnson to let Brown finish the
ninth inning after two one-out singles. Brown, who threw 126
pitches in his third complete-game of the season, nearly got Alex
Ochoa to ground into a double play with the bases loaded. A run
scored to make it 6-1, but Marquis Grissom grounded to short to end
the game.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also the matter of the last time Brown pitched. He
blew a 5-2 lead and allowed a Jose Valentin grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complete game, yeah, but I don't like to push him too
far,'' Johnson said of why he left Brown in. ``I had to let him get
that shot at the shutout.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
