<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE CITY OF WALKING DANEROUSLY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rather than look at San Francisco's driver-pedestrian wars as
horrifying chaos, I prefer to view them as performance art, a
street ballet.
</P>
<P>
   You're not a pedestrian, you're a bullfighter, only without the
skin-tight, embroidered pants.
</P>
<P>
   I have long been fascinated by the bravery of pedestrians,
especially those who exhibit a sleepwalking nonchalance in the face
of imminent death, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Top Gun walkers not only don't look at oncoming traffic
before meandering into the street, they look the  &UR; other way. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dave Grenley has pondered this phenomenon and come up with three
possible explanations:
</P>
<P>
   1. In an effort to stay at the forefront of the human potential
movement, pedestrians use blind trust to connect with total
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   2. The walkers are stripping drivers of the bluff card. You
can't scare a pedestrian out of the street if he won't look at you.
</P>
<P>
   3. These pedestrians are stupid, and this is what
evolution/natural selection looks like in action, except in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ASHES TO ASPHALT: An interesting story came out of a small town
in Colorado, where a woman dumped her dead husband's ashes into a
load of street-paving asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked the smell of asphalt,'' she said, ``so by God, he can
smell it forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Do I detect a bit of an edge in that statement?
</P>
<P>
   But when the road begins to deteriorate, will the man's widow
know his ash from a pothole in the ground?
</P>
<P>
   Here in San Francisco, we skip the cremation middleman and embed
the person into the pavement with the wheels of our cars.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not all the fault of the drivers. Scott McKellar
wonders why it is we send bad drivers to driving school to brush up
on safety and courtesy, but we don't send jaywalkers to walking
school.
</P>
<P>
   If a pedestrian is a three-strikes jaywalker, let's make him or
her wear a pair of Denver boots.
</P>
<P>
   A BILLBOARD in Berkeley reads: ``Just because you survived drugs
doesn't mean your children will.''
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the message used to be. Audrey Newell
noticed that someone has crossed out ``drugs'' and painted in
``Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably some noncompassionate liberal.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S SAY you're driving around in your Lincoln Navigator and
you get lost. Would you have the guts to stop and ask directions?
</P>
<P>
   Judging from a magazine ad for the Navigator, the
battleship-class SUV, there is potential for geographical &LR; 
 &LR; confusion. In the ad photo, spotted by Jerry Olmsted, a Navigator
is climbing the road into the Marin Headlands, and in the distant
background is the familiar S.F. skyline.
</P>
<P>
   In the foreground is the Bay Bridge, which, if memory serves,
does not connect the city with the Marin Headlands.
</P>
<P>
   The Navigator is no vehicle for the traditionalist.
</P>
<P>
   IN OTHER car news, a silver BMW cruises the city with the
license plates: CLNUPSF (spotted by Deb Elam).
</P>
<P>
   Cop? Neat freak? FBI agent? Batman? Investigative reporter?
Evangelist? Street sweeper?
</P>
<P>
   WHO WANTS to be a Millionaire? That's the name of the new TV
quiz show hosted by Regis Philbin, and if you haven't seen it, this
won't make much sense.
</P>
<P>
   The show is way overdone; the set looks like the cockpit of a
UFO, and the music is right out of ``Psycho.'' But it's strangely
compelling, like frosted pretzels, maybe because people like you
and me sit down for 10 minutes and rake in tons of money.
</P>
<P>
   But here's my beef: If a contestant is stumped on one of the
multiple-choice questions, he or she can poll the audience, one
time. With alarming frequency, a guy will poll the audience, and 97
percent will say the answer is ``B,'' Cheryl Ladd.
</P>
<P>
   Then the guy will scratch his head and spend two minutes
deciding whether to go with the audience and its obviously correct
answer, or go down in flames with a lame guess.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're a contestant, know that if you pull this particular
stunt, we viewers will pool our individual karmas and you will not
only lose, but as a lovely parting gift, you will face a lifetime
of relentless remorse and ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   EUREKA: Cisco Systems recently bought out Cerent, a Petaluma
high-tech company, for $6.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's an average killing of $7 million per Cerent employee.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the AP story notes that: ``No layoffs are
planned.''
</P>
<P>
   AT STARBUCKS, a barista told a customer, ``The small is tall,''
which probably makes sense to a hookah-smoking caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only that,'' says Glen Farmer, ``but McDonald's no longer
sells small fries. Did they lose the recipe?''
</P>
<P>
   No, Glen. McDonald's simply wants to encourage people to think
big. To dream the impossible cholesterol count.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
