<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LATINOS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA'S LATINOS A DIFFERENT CHALLENGE FOR BUSH  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ GOP presidential front-runner Gov. George W.
Bush has had some electrifying success courting Latino voters in
his home state of Texas, winning nearly 40 percent of their vote in
the last election.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush rides into California this week to begin wooing the
state's 2.3 million Latino voters _ and political insiders here say
he'd better get used to a whole different landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Latino vote in Texas is very different from the Latino
vote in California,'' said California GOP strategist Michael
Madrid, whose studies show that Latinos here tend to be younger and
newer to the United States and have a different economic profile.
``The question is: Can the magic be transferred?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is betting it can.
</P>
<P>
   With seven months before California's March 7 presidential
primary, Bush's efforts to court the state's fastest-growing _ and
arguably most-courted _ group of voters underscore the fierce fight
looming over Latino loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   Latino voters make up almost 40 percent of all new voters in the
nation's most populous state, and their numbers are expected to
explode to 2.8 million in the next two years, Madrid's studies
show.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why the GOP front-runner arrives in California
tomorrow to make his first major appearance before a Latino
organization as a presidential candidate. Starting Thursday
morning, the Texas governor will visit an Inglewood elementary
school, where he is slated to produce ``the first of a series of
educational policy proposals,'' his campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he will head to the Los Angeles Convention Center to
deliver a luncheon address to 3,000 entrepreneurs of the Latin
Business Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand (it) will be a substantive message directed at
our community and our business owners,'' said the organization's
chairman, Hector Barreto. ``The Bush people are really going to
contest California, and ... they feel they have a really good shot
at enrolling people to their side and getting out their message.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's efforts to reach out to Latinos in California come
with formidable challenges, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   For a start, there are the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Republican Bush got 39 percent of the Latino vote in
the 1998 gubernatorial election _ less than half that of California
Democratic Gov. Gray Davis, who reaped a whopping 84 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the demographic and political differences:
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a different country from California,'' said Patricia
Perez, a partner in Valencia, Perez &AMP; Echeveste, a Pasadena-based
public relations agency, and an officer in the Latin Business
Association. ``Here, people consider (Latino voters) to be
Democratic and liberal. In Texas, it's a very established
community, middle-class, educated, affluent and business owners.
And it tends to be Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, California's Latinos encompass waves of new immigrants
each year _ thousands more Spanish speakers working more
entry-level jobs. One of four Latino voters here is under age 30,
and the vast majority have been voting only since 1994, said
Madrid, who has long tracked the demographic, economic and
political patterns of the state's Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   And California's Democratic Party has successfully reached them
with campaigns stressing education, labor issues like the minimum
wage and 40-hour workweeks, health care and child care, said
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   But in Texas, three-quarters of Latino voters were born in the
United States and have third- and fourth-generation American roots.
Fewer speak Spanish as a first language, and they tend to be older,
more upwardly mobile and better educated. The Latino small business
owners and professionals tend to be more receptive to Republican
messages about taxes, less government and family values, said
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   California, far more than Texas, has experienced grave political
fallout from the recent immigration wave. ``It's resentment. It's
`They Keep Coming,' '' said Madrid, referring to an infamous
television ad for Proposition 187, the 1994 anti-illegal
immigration measure, which whipped up support by using clips of
Mexicans scurrying across the border.
</P>
<P>
   That divisive ad, and anger at GOP former Gov. Pete Wilson's
role in the 187 campaign, drove thousands of Latinos to register
Democratic, recalled California's Democratic Lt. Gov. Cruz
Bustamante, a first-generation Californian and the state's
highest-ranking Latino elected official.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the problems for Republicans in California.
They've missed the opportunity,'' said Bustamante, who won nearly
90 percent of the state's Latino vote last year. ``They've not
thought of Latinos in the same way as everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign, sensitive to the criticism, appears to be
distancing itself from Wilson, publicly dismissing reports that a
role for the former governor in the Bush effort is ``a done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Wilson, the Spanish-speaking Bush has used
advertising that appeals to Latinos. In his last campaign, Bush's
media director, Lionel Sosa, chose ads heavy on values; one
included Bush sitting on a porch and talking to Latinos
heart-to-heart. ``It was, `mi casa es su casa,' '' said Leslie
Goodman, editor in chief of politicalaccess.com, a leading
political Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Others Bush ads omitted mention of party altogether. ``The
message was, `We have a lot in common. We think alike,''' Sosa has
said. ``It's very subtle. ... We never say: Vote Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante acknowledges that Bush's outreach to Latinos has
shown him as ``a charming and affable man. ... He's appointed a
Latino to the (Texas) Supreme Court, and that's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But ... the thin veneer is starting to flake off ... and the
symbolism will fade quickly,'' the Democrat predicts. Bush will
``have to answer some tough questions, like `Why is drug use in
Texas up among teenagers? Why is it that college attendance is down
for Latinos, and even the number of Latinos going to law school is
down (in Texas)?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP strategist for a rival presidential campaign said that
if Bush wants the Latino vote, he'll have to answer the questions _
and work for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latino voters in California have a long memory,'' the
strategist warned. ``And their detectors are acutely tuned for
Republican candidates offering platitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Madrid, the former spokesman for the state GOP, insists that
the appeals of GOP candidates _ like Bush and U.S. Sen. John
McCain, who also has successfully wooed Latinos _ mean ``you will
see a genuine battle for the Latino vote here, which is exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, ``what drove Latinos from the Republican fold is
what will bring them back,'' Madrid said _ ``a candidate that
sells.'' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
