<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX     08-31 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Art that fits my taste
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Stuffy art critics laugh down their snide
sleeves at we plebeians who view art with an unjaundiced eye. They
ridicule our naive honesty when we confess to knowing little more
about art than what we like. But that's OK, they don't hurt my
feelings. Let 'em snicker.
</P>
<P>
   I know enough about painting to know that Wyeth is good; Elvis
on velvet doesn't move me; and my Aunt Bessie should have had her
brush taken away from her. I appreciate Matisse and Renoir, but I
can't afford them. Picasso was a genius, I'm sure, and so was
Warhol, but I just haven't the yen to live with a green-bellied,
orange-nosed woman or a Campbell's soup can in the living room.
Neither match the rug.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not I fall in love with a painting depends strictly
on how it makes me feel when I stand in front of it. If it tries to
educate me, forget it. But if the flower garden beckons me to sit a
spell on the stone bench, or if the cottage nestled beside the
stream invites me for tea in front of the fire, I become involved.
I want to crawl inside the frame and live there.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to me this morning. The day began
innocently enough and things looked pretty smooth until after my
bath. I was rummaging around the bedroom looking for something
baggy to wear when I caught sight of myself in the full-length
mirror _ the one I should have taken down 15 years ago when I
bought the house.
</P>
<P>
   GET THYSELF TO A GYM! I screeched at the saggy mess staring back
at me. Time to shift the fat and make an attempt to move certain
body parts back where they belong _ if I could still remember where
they came from.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's how I happened to be parked on the main street of
a nearby town in front of a body shop for old broads _ right across
the street from an art gallery/cafe.
</P>
<P>
   I climbed the stairs to the second floor of a 100-year-old,
high-ceilinged building (87 steps _ if you make it up there you
obviously have a strong heart so they sign you up automatically)
and confessed to the lady in short pants (my breathing and her gym
clothes) that I needed help. She did not question the validity of
my demands and immediately chained me to a bicycle that goes
nowhere and told me to start pedaling.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway to Ashtabula, the woman with the whip released me and
made me promise
</P>
<P>
   to come back on Thursday for more. I left feeling pretty smug.
Surely I'd burned enough calories to slip in across the street for
a latte and a browse.
</P>
<P>
   And there it was _ a painting I couldn't live without. No matter
I'd have to sell the house and mortgage the cats to pay for it, I
had to have it.
</P>
<P>
   To the casual observer, the scene might look like nothing more
than a simple painting of any evening in an everyday neighborhood
of the '30s. It's drizzling. The street is narrow and the sidewalks
are the stone kind I remember roller skating on. In one yard is a
Dauber Dog (Dalmatian) like the one Mrs. Bartel, the artist on the
corner, had. On the porch next door is a scotty like President
Roosevelt's Fala that I'd seen in the newsreels every Wednesday
night at the Broadview.
</P>
<P>
   There are no dark windows, just lacy-curtained, yellow-lighted
ones, and although I can't see inside, I know there's a father
sitting in an old Morris chair reading the news. Mom's in the
kitchen mashing potatoes, and all is right with the world.
</P>
<P>
   When I look at this painting I know someone in there is waiting
for me to come home. It's the street I used to live on and the
place I'd like to go back to just one more time. It's my kind of
art.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'll hang it where the mirror used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
