<HEADER>
A5598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SHARP-DRIVING01-COX     08-31 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cast of parts keep cooling system cool
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Your vehicle's cooling system is a working example of
the rule of physics stating that heat will always move toward a
cooler area or object.
</P>
<P>
   The coolant absorbs the intense heat created by the engine. The
water pump's job is to circulate the coolant, up to 7,500 gallons
an hour, throughout the cooling system. It moves the hot coolant
from the passages in the engine out to the radiator, where the
liquid gives up its heat to the air flowing through it. The
``cooled'' coolant is returned to the engine, and the whole cycle
starts over.
</P>
<P>
   As simple as this may sound, the entire production depends on a
cast of supporting parts. If one of them falls down on the job, the
whole system suffers and your car overheats.
</P>
<P>
   Most water pumps are attached to a pulley driven by a belt,
commonly called a fan belt or serpentine belt. Some pumps, however,
are driven by the engine's timing belt. In either case, it is
imperative that the belt has the correct tension and grip.
</P>
<P>
   Serpentine belts with self-adjusting, spring-loaded tensioners
used on most never vehicles have taken the guesswork out of this
area. However older vehicles using narrow ``V'' belts were subject
to problems, many starting from the time new belts were installed.
Just because a fan belt looks right and fits OK and is the right
length doesn't mean it will do the job 100 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   V belts grip the pulley at the sides of the V. If the belt is
too narrow or too wide, the contact area will be wrong, and it will
slip on the pulley under load. Misadjusted belts are a very common
problem. A loose belt will slip (usually accompanied by a
high-pitched squeal), and a belt that has been overtightened will
cause premature water pump failure.
</P>
<P>
   All belts _ serpentine, V and timing _ should be free of cracks
and glaze. This is best accomplished by adhering to the
manufacturer's maintenance schedule on belt replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Often, shops will suggest replacing the water pump when the
timing belt is replaced, even though there is no apparent problem
with the pump. This is not a rip-off sales pitch. A timing belt
replacement is labor-intensive and usually the most expensive part
of that job. Replacing a timing-belt-driven water pump at the same
time actually saves money on labor in the event the pump fails
before the belt is to be replaced again. Although it will add some
cost to timing belt job, it is cheaper than doing it later.
</P>
<P>
   The thermostat does not keep the engine cold. It is responsible
for correct engine-operating temperature. The thermostat is
designed to stay closed until the engine has reached a specific
temperature, when it begins to open. Once fully opened, maximum
coolant circulates between the engine and radiator with efficient
temperature maintained.
</P>
<P>
   A thermostat stuck in the closed position restricts flow,
resulting in engine overheating. Too often, the quick and dirty
repair for this is to install a ``cooler'' thermostat (one with a
lower temperature rating) or to remove it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   That's the wrong move. Hotter coolant flowing through the
radiator actually gives up heat faster. In addition, a
``cold''-running engine wastes fuel, contaminates engine oil, plays
havoc with the engine's computer system and will fail an emissions
test in a heartbeat. Although thermostats occasionally fail of
their own accord, lifespan is usually proportional to the amount of
maintenance the cooling system receives.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor and an ASE master automobile
technician/L1. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
