A5600 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SHARP01-DRIVING-COX     08-31 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP01-DRIVING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Applauds to BMW for driver ed program
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a person who has spent more than two decades in the
driver-training business, I know as well as anyone the benefits
that can be gained from proper instruction in the use of a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   It continues to amaze me that automobile accidents remain the
No. 1 preventable cause of death of our youth, but we seem to be
unwilling to do anything significant about it.
</P>
<P>
   People point out that automakers are making cars safer, that air
bags are common and more people are using seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   Give me a break. This attitude will never solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers are not the problem. Accidents are only rarely caused
by the car. The majority of the time, they are caused by the person
behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   An uneducated driver is almost like an accident waiting to
happen. For years, whenever I can bend the ear of an automaker, I
have tried to interest them in doing driver training, especially
for teenagers. It is a bit disappointing that the new school at the
BMW facility is limited to students 18 years and older.
</P>
<P>
   Any additional driver education opportunity is a plus, but I
wish someone _ especially auto manufacturers _ would be willing to
help address this issue. Not only would the education process
benefit the driving public, fewer accidents could lead to less
litigation against automakers.
</P>
<P>
   BMW should be applauded for its efforts. The adults who attend
the BMW facility can pass along the skills they have learned to
their children.
</P>
<P>
   With any skill, you usually are only as good as the person who
taught you. The BMW program provides serious, quality driver
education with quality, professional instructors. The classes are
not high-speed thrill courses, but provide a quality basis for
driving techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only more automakers were willing to do likewise, we
might just raise the bar for driving skills on our roadways.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp's column is written exclusively for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
