<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-BREEZE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plymouth's refreshing Breeze
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Plymouth is really is headed for the end of its road, then
the 1999 Breeze is a reasonably nice stopping point. But its
rumored demise is likely to alarm only one market segment:
budget-conscious loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Breeze, which was introduced in 1996, is a plucky midsize
sedan, one that has twice made it onto Automobile magazine's 10
best list for obvious reasons. It's roomy, has decent power,
handles well and while not particularly striking, has sensible
styling that won't become offensive over time.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing starts at $15,115, and the Breeze comes with enough
features and so few available options that the ``inferno red''
tester _ fully loaded, so to speak _ totaled $17,625. That included
a $375 Expresso package with cassette player, special interior and
exterior trim and wheel covers.
</P>
<P>
   The big bumps were the four-speed automatic transmission that
added $1,050 and the $710 package that included power windows and
locks and heated mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a mostly comfortable sedan, although the front
seats aren't that pleasing for large people because of the way the
seats are shaped. The rear will seat three adults, but how long
they could travel together is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Three four-cylinder powerplants are available, and the test
Breeze's 2.4-liter version had ratings of 150 horsepower at 5,200
rpm and 167 pounds-feet torque at 4,000 rpm. That's enough power
for the 3,000-pound Breeze, but using all of it is a noisy process.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed manual that accompanies the base four-cylinder
can't be had with the line-topping motor, which would really make
for a peppy combination. But the four-speed automatic functioned
satisfactorily despite being slow to downshift when traffic
dictated speeding up.
</P>
<P>
   The handling, of course, is one of the Breeze's strong points.
The ride is not bump-proof, but the Breeze feels stable, maneuvers
well and doesn't do a lot of rebounding after hitting a bump. The
brakes aren't particularly strong, but work well during the type of
driving for which a Breeze is intended.
</P>
<P>
   The instrumentation is basic but very visible, and the view from
behind the tilt steering wheel _ a standard feature _ is open.
There's a lot of plastic, which is hardly unusual for a car in the
Breeze's class, and the special Expresso cloth is hardly designer
level, but it's certainly not offensive.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're looking for upscale appointments and performance,
look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking for a reasonably competent midsize sedan
with a fair amount of features and room for a family, the Breeze
can be an economical way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Plymouth Breeze front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $17,625 (includes discounts not always
available, base price: $15,115)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: optional 2.4-liter four-cylinder engine with 16
valves ($455), optional four-speed automatic overdrive transmission
($1,050)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, side-impact beams,
height-adjustable front shoulder belts, power brakes with front
discs and rear drums
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: Expresso trim package with
cassette player, bucket seats with patterned cloth, special wheel
covers, $375; package with power windows and locks, power heated
mirrors, floor mats, $710; red tinted clearcoat paint, $200
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 21 mpg regular unleaded city, 30 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
