<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5606 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX     08-31 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Government can be many things, but can't be masses' pulpit
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ As mercury vapors start to bathe Friday nights in
light, as pads start popping and vendors get to hawking, we know
what's on everyone's lips.
</P>
<P>
   Religion, of course.
</P>
<P>
   We'll get to football shortly. But first, can a community employ
its school district and its sound system to impart religion on
assembled saints and sinners? No. A thousand times, no.
</P>
<P>
   That's how many times judges may have to say it before people
will understand it.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that courtroom pageantry will continue as veritable
marching bands assert, usually against a courageous band of one,
that government is a rightful religious mouthpiece for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Three news stories serve as seasonal fodder. At Santa Fe High
School in Galveston County, a student elected to lead prayer before
football games pulled back under orders by the school district. It
has appealed to the Supreme Court a U.S. Fifth Circuit ruling
barring student-led prayer at games.
</P>
<P>
   In Andrews near Odessa, school trustees have decided to continue
student-led prayer at least until a lawsuit forces it to stop.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that this will be happening across Texas. School
districts will be wagering that no one will challenge the legality
of such prayers. Most will win the wager. But that doesn't justify
it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prior to kicking off a Friday night game in
Stephenville, 15 students led an unauthorized prayer over a
smuggled-in loudspeaker.
</P>
<P>
   While disavowing any district role in what happened,
Stephenville Superintendent Larry Butler applauded the students
who'd staged the impromptu prayer, ``I think the entire community
of Stephenville believes in school prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Butler is right, presumptuous as it sounds. But as
superintendent of schools he's not hired to be superintendent of
faith and religion, which is what school prayer supporters want.
</P>
<P>
   What would have been the audience reaction to a smuggled-in P.A.
that broadcast readings from the Torah? Would the superintendent
have applauded? What if the students with the smuggled P.A. were to
recite the teachings of L. Ron Hubbard?
</P>
<P>
   Would Stephenville ISD make allowances for dueling barkers
before kick-off?
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to control the expressions of a football crowd,
but that's not what the Fifth Circuit ruling was about. It was
about the government telling everyone in a captive sporting
audience, ``Hush up one moment. It's time to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Such prayer can be defended only as a provincial tradition, not
as a right. And though it is well-meant, it is this kind of
tradition that America's earliest immigrants fled _ of people in
authority presuming to know how ``the community'' feels on matters
as personal as faith, and enforcing it with a nod.
</P>
<P>
   Once ensconced on these shores, history tells us that people
fleeing religious persecution bunched together in near-homogeneous
bodies and found ways to persecute those who bucked the homogeneity
on matters of faith.
</P>
<P>
   The blunt truth is that state-established religion sounds OK
only to those who believe themselves to be homogeneously bunched.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill of Rights for this wide and diverse nation prohibits
it. Religion thrives when government keeps its hands off it, the
founders wagered. Everybody won.
</P>
<P>
   When students or townfolks say that they are deprived of their
right to pray before football games, they are providing false
witness. Someone has called their hand on a communal tradition, a
hold-over from state-established religion of yore, not on the
exercising of their individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, if you want a state religion, sail back to England and
enjoy the scrum. This is America. Play football.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
