<P>
   LAST WEEK'S TRANSMISSION:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOK EXCERPT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MONEY TALKS: INVESTMENT MANAGEMENT. This is the third and final
excerpt from the book ``Money Talks'' by Juliette Fairley (John
Wiley &AMP; Sons Inc.). Fairley, a personal finance writer, has
interviewed prominent black leaders in such areas as banking,
financial planning and investment. In this excerpt, John Rogers,
president of Ariel Capital Management, offers tips on how to grow
your personal portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   NEW `DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL' GUIDELINES: TOO LITTLE, TOO LATE.
``To say that the `don't ask, don't tell, don't pursue' policy on
gays in the military is not working is an understatement,'' writes
columnist Chuck Colbert, himself a former naval officer. Colbert
cites the recent murder of Pfc. Barry L. Winchell, a 21-year-old
gay soldier at a Naval base in Fort Campbell, Ky., who was
bludgeoned to death with a baseball bat. What is the president and
defense secretary doing about such abuses to the policy? Colbert
argues that their recently issued policy directives won't end to
the military's anti-gay culture of hostility.
</P>
<P>
   LATINOS UPSET BY PROPOSITION 187 MEDIATION. It was it watershed
issue in California politics, impelling record numbers of Latinos
to register to vote. It also has strained United States-Mexican
relations for five years. But Proposition 187, which sought to deny
public education and health services to undocumented families, is
not dead yet. Gov. Gray Davis of California, who once vilified the
measure, has changed his tune, reports Victor Mejia in this excerpt
from Hispanic magazine. In April, Davis asked a federal appellate
court to mediate the measure and find a solution that will appease
both the opponents and supporters of the 1994 ballot initiative. In
this commentary, Mejia offers all sides in the debate over
Proposition 187.
</P>
<P>
   A DOUBLE STANDARD ON DRUGS. ``This is a tale of the two ways the
Gainesville (Fla.) Police Department enforces narcotics violations.
Or, at the very least, it is a tale about the perception of dual
enforcement _ one for the city's black residents, the other for
whites,'' writes columnist Bill Maxwell. During a recent Police
Community Committee meeting, angry black residents told members
that they are sick and tired of cops' harassment and physical
abuse. Several young men described being stopped, searched and
detained for no legitimate reasons _ other than ``standing still
while black.'' Why not case the nearby rave clubs _ filled with
mostly white kids? And what would they find? Ecstasy, ketamine,
GHB, cocaine, heroin, methamphetamine, marijuana, LSD ... and the
list goes on. ``And what is happening here in Florida's leading
college town happens throughout the nation,'' Maxwell writes.
</P>
<P>
   JUST A LITTLE RED DOT. Long before bindis _ once the traditional
mark of married Hindu women _ began to dot the faces of Hollywood,
a school teacher used them to educate children about culture. Five
years ago, Mitra Sen, a fifth-grade school teacher in Scarborough,
Canada, began to notice how the girls in her class who were wearing
bindis on their foreheads were teased and taunted by their
classmates. She saw this as a learning opportunity, and came up
with a plan to have her students ``educate'' their schoolmates
about other people's cultures. Inspired by her success, she wrote,
directed and produced ``Just a Little Red Dot,'' an award-wining
documentary about her experiences with her class. Writer Sandip
Roy-Chowdhury talks to the Sen and some of her students in this
feature from A. Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION ABOUT NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE -- AND TO
SIGN UP FOR A FREE TRIAL -- please contact sales representative Ana
Pena by phone, (212) 499-3333, or fax, (212) 499-3382.
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks!
</P>
