<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     08-31 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATE THE GIFTS THE WILDERNESS ACT HAS GIVEN US 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   The
Wilderness Act turns 35 years old on Sept. 3. Secretary of the
Interior Bruce Babbitt calls it ``one of the most important
environmental laws of the past half-century.'' Anyone who loves the
outdoors, wildlife and pristine wilderness must agree.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Wilderness Act created the National Wilderness Preservation
System.
</P>
<P>
   More than 104 million acres of federal public lands have been
classified as wilderness areas under the act, so far. Congress must
approve the designation of any federal land as a wilderness area.
</P>
<P>
   The act required the secretary of the interior and the secretary
of agriculture to review, within 10 years of the passage of the
act, every roadless area of 5,000 acres or more in the federal
lands system to determine the suitability of such areas for a
designation and preservation as wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness is defined by the act as ``an area where the earth
and its community of life are untrammeled by man, where man himself
is a visitor who does not remain.'' It is further defined as ``an
area of underdeveloped federal land retaining its primeval
character and influence, without permanent improvements or human
habitation, which is protected and managed so as to preserve its
natural conditions,'' and that ``appears to have been affected
primarily by the forces of nature, with the imprint of man's work
substantially unnoticeable.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Babbitt explained the act further: ``The
fundamental premise of the Wilderness Act is that the process of
building roads is a death sentence for an ecosystem. There are all
kinds of scientific studies which show that roads fragment habitat
in a way that leads to the disintegration of the ecosystem. The
grizzly bear is a great example. The grizzly cannot tolerate a
fragmented habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt continued: ``The results of the act in terms of
wilderness speak for themselves. We have fabulous, fabulous lands
which are now protected in perpetuity for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been very little action to approve wilderness areas in
the last two sessions of Congress. And Babbitt expressed his
chagrin at the politics that has held up wilderness designations:
``Too much of the time, it has become an ideological flash point,
rather than an opportunity to work together. We've made almost no
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal agencies that manage public lands _ the National
Park Service, the Bureau of Land Management, the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service and the U.S. Forest Service _ each manage whatever
lands in their jurisdiction that have been included in the National
Wilderness Preservation System.
</P>
<P>
   The BLM was not authorized to designate wilderness areas by the
Wilderness Act. It had to wait until the Federal Land Policy
Management Act was passed in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   FLPMA required the BLM to identify wilderness areas. At present,
the BLM manages 622 wilderness study areas (17 million acres) and
only 136 designated wilderness areas (5.3 million acres). Study
areas await congressional action to become wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four federal land agencies, the BLM manages the fewest
wilderness areas. Over a third of the USFWS public lands are now
wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming has no wilderfess areas managed by the BLM. The state
has 42 wilderness study areas comprising less than 600,000 acres
out of the 18 million acres managed by the BLM in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The wilderness areas managed by the National Park Service and
the USFWS are subject to greater restrictions than those managed by
the Forest Service or the BLM. But the Wilderness Act mandates that
all these lands ``shall be administered for the use and enjoyment
of the American people in such a manner as will leave them
unimpaired for future use and enjoyment as wilderness, and so as to
provide for the protection of these areas, the preservation of
their wilderness character, and for the gathering and dissemination
of information regarding their use and enjoyment as wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   In wilderness areas managed by the BLM, one may hunt and fish,
hike, ski, snowshoe, ride horses, take river trips and camp. In
general, no motorized vehicles are allowed in wilderness areas.
That means no off-road vehicles, no snowmobiles and no skidoos.
</P>
<P>
   One cannot hunt in a national park; therefore, hunting is
prohibited in wilderness areas managed by the National Park
Service. The same restriction applies to wilderness areas managed
by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   One may hunt on Forest Service lands; therefore, one may hunt in
wilderness areas managed by the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the restrictions applied to public use of wilderness
areas are consistent with the restrictions that the managing agency
applies to federal lands under its jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness areas are the most protected landscapes in the
federal system. And they are large enough areas to be refuges for
plants and animals. They allow ecological forces to work unimpeded
and allow the natural fluctuation of animal and plant populations.
</P>
<P>
   Clean water in New Mexico, in large measure, comes from
wilderness areas. Clean air in Arizona is protected by that state's
wilderness areas. Clean water for Denver and Seattle, again, thank
the wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness preserved is a gift to each and all of us. Even a
brief visit to a wilderness area can wash away the burdens and
pressures of modern life. Wilderness areas not only protect the
values inside them _ the land, wildlife, air and water -- they also
preserve our connection to all living things and our connection to
the deepest part of ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the 35th anniversary of the Wilderness Act, write
your congressional delegation and tell them we need more wilderness
areas and less political partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-30-99 1602EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
