 Tuesday, Aug. 31, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-TRANSMISSION (San Francisco) _ On a fateful day in August
1899, a three-word message in Morse code printed the first message
transmitted by radio. A commemoration of the event marked not only
the momentousness of the occasion, but how far the world has come
in wireless communication. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-EXAMINER (San Francisco) _ There are approximately 2,100
police officers and 1,600 firefighters in San Francisco. Serving
the same population are Graham Cowley and 12 other investigators in
the San Francisco medical examiner's office. The portion of their
job the public sees, retrieving the dead, is actually the easy
part. By PETER HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   DIXIE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Dixie Chicks are easily the
freshest act to emerge in country music in the last two years. The
group's bluegrass-inflected sound _ born and bred on the Texas club
circuit in the early `90s _ proved immediately accessible to
contemporary country audiences. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-FISHING (Undated) _ The experiences of American
presidents with lures, flies and bait is the topic of an intriguing
book by Bill Mares, ``Fishing with the Presidents.'' The book's
charming collection of editorial cartoons and photographs
supplement the author's witty style to produce a history of
presidential angling that fishing fans and presidential history
buffs will enjoy. By CHARLES J. LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A lot of employers still don't
appreciate how much skill is involved in any job _ if it is done
well. You don't need a college degree to shine shoes or drive a cab
or serve coffee, but you need a lot of skills if you want to do the
job well. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-STOKES (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ J.J. Stokes of the San
Francisco 49ers hadn't matured into the mesmerizing talent so many
people expected him to be at the end of last season. This season
could offer him a break, a shot at acceptance, something he has
never had with the 49ers. For Stokes, that could be comparable to
paradise. By JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS-BIEKERT (Alameda, Calif.) _ Greg Biekert is a
linebacker for the Oakland Raiders. That's a big responsibility.
It's almost expected that Raiders linebackers will be either
slightly wacky or totally unhinged. Craziness used to be part of
the job description. But when he is on the field, Biekert is all
business. By FRANK BLACKMAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
