<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5644 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-EXTREME-GOES-MAINSTRE     08-31 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTREME-GOES-MAINSTREAM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINSTREAM EXTREME  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ELENA ROMERO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The extreme lifestyle, which was once strictly subculture, is
now translating into mainstream acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic growth in the youth participation of inline skating,
snowboarding, roller hockey and off-road mountain biking has made
the X-sports the fastest-growing youth sports of the 1990s,
according to data in the 1998 Sports Participation studies produced
by the National Sporting Goods Association (NSGA).
</P>
<P>
   Further, ``extreme sports have crossed over to MTV, ESPN and NBC
with the upcoming Gravity Games,'' said Scott Kelliher, director of
marketing at Blades, Board &AMP; Skate, a 21-unit extreme sport chain
operation.
</P>
<P>
   And as these sports have garnered more interest, fashion
companies have followed the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the styles of the sports are exposed to more people, more
people want to get on to those looks,'' adds Kelliher. ``The sports
themselves are appealing, daring, new and cutting-edge. The fashion
around them go along the same line. These sports say `I'm cool' and
the fashions have the same image associated to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is taking bits and pieces from particular sports
styles and interpreting that into their mainstream look,'' said
Neil Mossberg, men's merchandiser for www.hipO.com, an e-commerce
site for fashion-forward youth. ``For example, motocross jerseys,
logo T's and even lengths of shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Mossberg, the recreational customer ``tries to keep
up on brands and pull off that extreme sports look.'' He added that
they will mix extreme style into their everyday looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``An example of that would be rap artists wearing motocross
jerseys on award shows, which later filters down to the street
level,'' he said. ``For spring 2000, the market can expect to see
the growth of technical fabrics and the emergence of smaller
extreme sports labels reaching a much larger audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Daniel, vice-president of trend merchandising and product
development of Hayward-based Mervyn's California, said extreme
sports have become a big part of Gen Y's lifestyle and it's had a
profound impact on its business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen the influence growing but it's been a factor for
the past 18 months,'' he said. ``It's impacted pretty much every
young men's and boys' category, to some degree. The biggest
influences are skateboarding, BMX biking, all of the sports on
wheels. We also include surfing. We've increased our surf-related
products like board shorts. The last time I saw this was in the
'70s when I was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mervyn's, brands are secondary to the look. This year within
its back-to-school mix, 35 percent of its assortment has roots in
extreme sports, especially in the skating and BMX biking
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our assortment is inspired and not authentic,'' he
said. ``But staying close to extreme sports is the key to
understanding young men. Longer shorts, which are skate, are a
fast-emerging category and essentially led to the whole length
story, from below the knee to four inches above the ankles. Surf
bottoms have been huge and we think they'll be huge through
back-to-school. In tops, it's mostly a knit story in raglan
sleeves, which has been driven by what's going on in skate as well
as a resurgence of graphics.''
</P>
<P>
   A variety of sportswear brands including 33 Degrees, Lugz, Boss
by I.G. Design and Brittania are taking notice of the popularity of
extreme sports. ``Many manufacturers have finally realized that
there is a whole other consumer lifestyle that, when targeted, will
gravitate toward your product,'' said Maria Roberson, merchandiser
for the Boss by I.G. Design brand. ``When we began to design
(spring), we wanted to take a portion of the line and categorize it
into sports-related apparel. Out of that `NEX' (New Era Extreme)
was born. We target all sports, including extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   While Boss by I.G. Design is not particularly targeting a
specific sport for spring 2000, it is looking to address comfort
and function. Its designs reflect a mix of authentic and inspired
extreme looks in synthetic meshes, cotton rip-stop and nylon
rip-stop fabrications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we've reduced has been the leg length in our
cargo pants,'' said Ray Marquez, vice-president of marketing at 33
Degrees, a three-year-old sportswear company. ``That comes from
bikers and allows baggy pants to not get caught in their spokes.
Our bottoms have three different options _ one with a pull cord,
the other at calf length and we have knee lengths as well.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Marquez, fashion companies are giving importance to
extreme sports because the athletes have become somewhat of role
models for the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being that these athletes are similar to the actual kids
themselves, there's identification through that and their successes
are examples,'' he said. ``The kids that are doing these extreme
sports on a professional basis had set the trends for how they
wanted the gear designed athletically and from a fashion aspect _
baggy pants, big T-shirts and ID work shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, when snowboarding was so big, we, as a lot of
others, found it represented major portions of our line,'' said
Stuart Ullman, vice-president of Lugz apparel. ``For the immediate
future, we're looking at what we call wheeled racing _ which is
apparel inspired by BMX, motocross and even auto racing. The
influence from racing sports could be as simple as graphic
inspiration on a T-shirt or as advanced as nylon and leather
motocross racing jackets.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittania sees some inspirations of extreme sports in its
designs. It currently is involved in sponsorship of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a Team Brittania that consists of athletes that
perform at the X Games in San Francisco,'' said Frans van Zeeland,
director of marketing at Brittania, a division of VF Jeanswear.
``We've been sponsoring bike, in-line and skate athletes for the
past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Extreme sports have become so popular because kids want to be
individuals,'' said Travis Blasingame, director of apparel for
Vans. ``Tony Hawk did a 900 rotation at the X Games and the kids
see the amount of risk involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Blasingame agrees that the demand for the look is on
the rise, he said too many apparel companies are caught up in the
``tech world'' aspect of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't need to be technical as much as it has to be
functional,'' he said. ``The fit and styling are important. It's
got to be cool, but what if you could add zip vents for better
ventilation or side adjustments on the waistband. The consumer is
better educated and knows the difference between a five-ounce and
nine-ounce twill. They want perceived value.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Elena Romero os a staff reporter for Fairchild
Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
