<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-WRITERS-OF-GEN-Y-NYTS     08-31 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITERS-OF-GEN-Y-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JUNIOR LITERATI  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE B&AMP;W SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By ANNE D'INNOCENZIO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They're too young to rent a car. In some cases,
they're too young to buy a drink. But these kids have good reason
to feel like grown-ups in the literary world. That is, if you call
a six-figure book contract a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the writers of Generation Y.
</P>
<P>
   Gen-Xers' younger brothers and sisters, who have already
infiltrated Hollywood and the music industry, are now being courted
by book publishers in search of marketable young literary talents.
And when the publishing execs come calling, they don't skimp on the
red-carpet treatment usually reserved for more seasoned celebrity
authors.
</P>
<P>
   Multibook deals, major publicity campaigns and movie-rights
negotiations are all part of the package. (First-time novelists
more typically get between $5,000 to $10,000 per book).
</P>
<P>
   Granted, at least two of these well-hyped literary lion cubs
were born to literary families. Erica Jong's 20-year-old daughter,
Molly Jong-Fast, is completing a novel called ``Girl,'' to be
published by Villard next May, and Anne Rice's son Christopher, 21,
is putting the finishing touches on his ``A Density of Souls,'' to
be released next spring as part of a two-book deal by Miramax's
Talk Books.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the young writers come with no such pedigrees.
</P>
<P>
   The ``it'' boy of the international junior literati right now is
Londoner Richard Mason, a 21-year-old Eton grad and Oxford student
whose novel ``The Drowning People'' caused a fierce bidding war in
the States. Time Warner finally snatched it up in a two-book deal
for $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   The novel, published in May, was backed by an advertising
campaign that cost several hundred thousand dollars, including a
15-second television spot aired last month in New York and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign rights were sold in 21 countries, and Mason's agent is
negotiating a film deal in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, with his Hugh Grant looks, has also won high marks for
his fashion style _ he wears custom-made suits from London clothier
Favourbrooke for ``glam occasions'' and slips into a pair of Ralph
Lauren linen trousers for casual book readings.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two-year-old Australia native Suneeta Peres da Costa
wrote a novel called ``Homework'' that is the lead fiction title
for Bloomsbury USA's fall list.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jenn Crowell, then 19, reportedly struck a
two-book deal with G.P. Putnum that was worth $800,000, including
TV and foreign rights. Her first novel, ``Necessary Madness,'' was
published in 15 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in young talent is nothing new. But in the past, only a
few writers have managed to hit it big _ and also win critical
respect _ while still in their early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   John Cheever was 23, Bret Easton Ellis 21 and Joyce Maynard 20
when they published their first works. Today, things may be
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have always been young writers, but I'm seeing that they
are definitely finding their groove earlier,'' said John Burnham,
president of Miramax's Talk Magazine Books, which plans to put a
lot of muscle into promoting Rice, a babyfaced Billy Idol.
</P>
<P>
   The new generation, according to its promoters, is far different
from former literary brat packers like Bret Easton Ellis, Jay
McInerney and Tama Janowitz, who chronicled the freewheeling '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are definitely taking on greater themes,'' Burnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's book, for example, is told from the perspective of a
70-year-old who just murdered his wife, while Crowell's is about a
woman whose husband dies of leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   But while the material is definitely mature, the inspiration
behind it may not be. Jong-Fast, for instance, turns to Nintendo's
``Gameboy'' to get her creative juices flowing. Rice likes jumping
up and down on his mini trampoline at his parents' house in New
Orleans' Garden District, where his first novel takes place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing it in my bedroom, but the plaster started falling
down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The five are also finding their own voices in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started writing because I wanted to feel like a grown-up,''
said Jong-Fast. ``In my family, you couldn't sit at the kitchen
table unless you were a writer.''''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jong-Fast said she's overwhelmed by her success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I would go on to a lackluster existence,''
she said. ``I saw myself just living on the Upper East Side,
wasting away and shopping at Eileen Fisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she got six figures, including a two-book deal in
England with Hodder &AMP; Stoughton.
</P>
<P>
   Jong-Fast has already written a few magazine articles about her
battle with an eating disorder and she sees herself as mentor for
the ``lost 17-year-old.'' Her novel, ``Girl,'' is about the social
pressures facing a 19-year-old New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a place where everyone was perfect all the
time,'' said Jong-Fast, who went to the Riverdale Country School
and grew up in a townhouse on the Upper East Side. ``If you were
fat, or if you had bad hair or if you had last season's coat, the
question was: `What was going to happen to you?'''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, whose novel examines how a group of high school friends
reacts to one character's emerging homosexuality, hopes to become
part of a pack of young literary gay writers who appeal to a
mainstream audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay fiction is a little too insular,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   His next book will be set on a Northeastern college campus,
inspired by his two semesters at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he's been able to strike a ``perfect balance''
between his mom's ``lush prose'' and the ``succinct style'' of his
dad, poet Stan Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom is into the supernatural,'' Rice said. ``My novel is
more seedy, more morally corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Rice, Mason said he doesn't want to be identified with a
particular genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each work is my own enterprise,'' said the writer, who is
getting ready to promote his first novel in Norway, Sweden and
possibly Japan, before heading back to Oxford in October.
</P>
<P>
   Mason admitted that he's a bit nervous about returning to
school. In addition to his courses, he'll be finishing his second
novel, which is about Oxford students ``who play terrible mind
games.''
</P>
<P>
   For Crowell, who's also completing her second book, tailoring
feminism to a younger generation is the chief concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feminism is not speaking to young women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Crowell will enter a graduate program in women's
studies at Towson University in Towson, Md. At the moment, she's
working on her second novel, about a 25-year-old woman who burns
out while getting her doctorate and then travels to Iceland to find
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Peres da Costa, whose novel was inspired by the
isolation she felt when her father moved to India, said she wants
to fill what she sees as ``a void in passion for the written
word.''
</P>
<P>
   She was savvy enough to pursue a first publishing contract in
the States _ she didn't want to be pegged as a local Australian
author.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Peres da Costa, who just moved here to start a
Fulbright-financed program in creative writing at Sarah Lawrence
College in Westchester County, admitted she is ndive at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my editor if she would write a permission slip so that
I could miss a couple of days from school,'' she said. ``She
thought it was so cute. She e-mailed all of her friends in the
office.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Anne D'Innocenzio is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5647 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-WRITERS-OF-GEN-Y-NYTS     08-31 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITERS-OF-GEN-Y-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JUNIOR LITERATI  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE B&AMP;W SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
