<P>
   But while the material is definitely mature, the inspiration
behind it may not be. Jong-Fast, for instance, turns to Nintendo's
``Gameboy'' to get her creative juices flowing. Rice likes jumping
up and down on his mini trampoline at his parents' house in New
Orleans' Garden District, where his first novel takes place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing it in my bedroom, but the plaster started falling
down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The five are also finding their own voices in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started writing because I wanted to feel like a grown-up,''
said Jong-Fast. ``In my family, you couldn't sit at the kitchen
table unless you were a writer.''''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jong-Fast said she's overwhelmed by her success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I would go on to a lackluster existence,''
she said. ``I saw myself just living on the Upper East Side,
wasting away and shopping at Eileen Fisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she got six figures, including a two-book deal in
England with Hodder &AMP; Stoughton.
</P>
<P>
   Jong-Fast has already written a few magazine articles about her
battle with an eating disorder and she sees herself as mentor for
the ``lost 17-year-old.'' Her novel, ``Girl,'' is about the social
pressures facing a 19-year-old New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a place where everyone was perfect all the
time,'' said Jong-Fast, who went to the Riverdale Country School
and grew up in a townhouse on the Upper East Side. ``If you were
fat, or if you had bad hair or if you had last season's coat, the
question was: `What was going to happen to you?'''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, whose novel examines how a group of high school friends
reacts to one character's emerging homosexuality, hopes to become
part of a pack of young literary gay writers who appeal to a
mainstream audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay fiction is a little too insular,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   His next book will be set on a Northeastern college campus,
inspired by his two semesters at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he's been able to strike a ``perfect balance''
between his mom's ``lush prose'' and the ``succinct style'' of his
dad, poet Stan Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom is into the supernatural,'' Rice said. ``My novel is
more seedy, more morally corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Rice, Mason said he doesn't want to be identified with a
particular genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each work is my own enterprise,'' said the writer, who is
getting ready to promote his first novel in Norway, Sweden and
possibly Japan, before heading back to Oxford in October.
</P>
<P>
   Mason admitted that he's a bit nervous about returning to
school. In addition to his courses, he'll be finishing his second
novel, which is about Oxford students ``who play terrible mind
games.''
</P>
<P>
   For Crowell, who's also completing her second book, tailoring
feminism to a younger generation is the chief concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feminism is not speaking to young women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Crowell will enter a graduate program in women's
studies at Towson University in Towson, Md. At the moment, she's
working on her second novel, about a 25-year-old woman who burns
out while getting her doctorate and then travels to Iceland to find
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Peres da Costa, whose novel was inspired by the
isolation she felt when her father moved to India, said she wants
to fill what she sees as ``a void in passion for the written
word.''
</P>
<P>
   She was savvy enough to pursue a first publishing contract in
the States _ she didn't want to be pegged as a local Australian
author.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Peres da Costa, who just moved here to start a
Fulbright-financed program in creative writing at Sarah Lawrence
College in Westchester County, admitted she is ndive at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my editor if she would write a permission slip so that
I could miss a couple of days from school,'' she said. ``She
thought it was so cute. She e-mailed all of her friends in the
office.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Anne D'Innocenzio is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
