<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-STOKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOKES INCHES TOWARD GAINING ACCEPTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ J.J. Stokes claimed there was no
significance to his disappearance shortly after last season. After
all, he leaves the country every off season. A trip to Brazil was
another simple weeklong getaway.
</P>
<P>
   But as Stokes vanished into the cosmic paradise that is Rio de
Janeiro, soaking in the sunshine and street celebrations, at some
point he had to wonder about his future. Stokes was entering free
agency, a period when professional football players discover what
they're worth, and he understood he might never play for the San
Francisco 49ers again.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes hadn't matured into the mesmerizing talent so many people
expected him to be, and the team faced a salary cap burden that
would make even Donald Trump sweat. What else was there to know?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know where my career would begin again,''
Stokes said. ``Wherever it was, I just wanted to go and see what I
could do, get out there and get a chance to play. I was thinking
about getting a new start.''
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing was, while Stokes was looking for something new,
few teams were interested in offering him that. He wound up back
with the 49ers, with a five-year, $16.9 million contract and the
understanding this is where he likely will finish his career. Which
brings up the important question: What kind of career will it be?
</P>
<P>
   Stokes has been swimming upstream since he entered the National
Football League as the 49ers' top pick in the 1995 draft. They,
along with the rest of the football world, tagged him as the
successor to wide receiver Jerry Rice. But that label has since
been snatched away by rising star Terrell Owens, leaving Stokes
with his first opportunity to play under a different microscope.
</P>
<P>
   After four years of disappointing people because of who he
wasn't, Stokes might finally be assessed for who he is. Said Stokes
of the Rice label: ``That's always been a way for other people to
measure me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like there has always been a lot of pressure on him
because everybody felt like he was going to be the next Jerry Rice
and he didn't want to be that,'' Rice said. ``He just wanted to be
J.J. Stokes. Now he's J.J. Stokes. He's making plays, he's happy
and he's only going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stokes works out, people notice. You see the massive hands,
the 6-foot-4-inch, 217-pound frame warding off defenders for passes
like a power forward handling weaker souls in the paint. You think
what most have probably always thought about Stokes _ this guy
could be something special. It is both compliment and curse.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes' career began with problems. Teammates questioned his
work habits. A wrist injury and a broken hand limited him to 56
receptions during his first two years in the league. But then he
flashed his potential as a starting receiver in 1997 and followed
that campaign with 63 receptions last year, eight for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key with J.J.'s success really is that he's stayed
healthy,'' said coach Steve Mariucci of the 49ers. ``There was
always a reason, setback, something to explain why he didn't
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there always have been flaws. Stokes dropped a potential
touchdown pass in a regular-season loss to the Green Bay Packers,
then exploded at a interviewer afterward. He didn't have Owens'
flare for the ``SportsCenter'' highlight moment. The ups and downs
add up to a career he hadn't expected when he came into the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't anticipate any injuries,'' Stokes said. ``I
got off to a slow start with that. But I thought I would have a
Super Bowl ring by now, a Pro Bowl nomination. I felt like I
would've done it all by now if you had asked me back then.''
</P>
<P>
   That desire to do it all made Stokes believe that leaving was
worth his while. The three-receiver system employed by the 49ers
was highly productive, but if Stokes wanted to be an 80-catch,
1,000-yard receiver, he would have no better chance to find a place
where that could happen than this past offseason.
</P>
<P>
   But come February, Stokes was humbled. The Pittsburgh Steelers
invited him for a visit and did little else. The Carolina Panthers
offered a decent deal. After that, Stokes' phone was ringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both teams were playing waiting games,'' Stokes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell they were heavily into their football, but they
sat around. My agent came back and said here's the situation at
both spots. I just made my decision from there. They were good
offers. It just wasn't worth me leaving after that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He could've gone elsewhere, but he will be productive here
because he has Steve Young, Jerry Rice and Terrell Owens around
him,'' said Larry Kirksey, the receivers coach for the 49ers. ``If
he went somewhere else he could get double-teamed and not get the
opportunities he'll get here. He knows that in this offense, he'll
get his chances.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the 49ers saved Stokes. He could have been the next
Alvin Harper for all anybody knows. This season could offer him a
break, a shot at acceptance, something he has never had with the
49ers. For Stokes, that could be comparable to paradise.
</P>
</TEXT>
