<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-BIEKERT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS' LINEBACKER IS ALL BUSINESS ON THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. _ Greg Biekert is a linebacker for the Oakland
Raiders. That's a big responsibility. It's almost expected that
Raiders linebackers will be either slightly wacky or totally
unhinged. Craziness used to be part of the job description.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that tradition and that history,'' Biekert said.
``I've just never been a flashy guy, a guy who likes to celebrate
after plays. I want to just take a business-type approach on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   It gets worse. Biekert plays middle linebacker. This is _ or
once was _ the glamour position on defense. Many of the men who
played it became famous. Dick Butkus. Sam Huff. Mike Singletary.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Biekert?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the linebacker for the Oakland Raiders. If the only people
who know I'm doing well are the guys on this team, then that's fine
with me. I could care less about any national recognition,''
Biekert said.
</P>
<P>
   In one way at least, Biekert is a throwback to an earlier,
tougher, era in this sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's the only middle linebacker in all of football
who stayed on the field for every single defensive play (last
season),'' coach Jon Gruden said. ``He's a complete football player
and a great leader. He's the heart and soul of our defensive
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Some guys allow this job to become their life. They walk the
middle linebacker walk and talk the middle linebacker talk.
</P>
<P>
   Biekert has made an effort to separate his job from the rest of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to be a middle linebacker when you're not on
the field,'' he said. ``And that's kinda the way I am. I'm not real
outspoken and talkative. You'd be in jail in five minutes if you
took an on-field attitude off the field. You have to, as best you
can, separate the two.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once Biekert suits up, he is a ferocious competitor. It is not
wise to irritate him.
</P>
<P>
   Biekert was a seventh-round draft choice out of Colorado in
1993. He spent his rookie season as a reserve linebacker and
special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, he became the Raiders' starting middle
linebacker. And in practice one day, he was in a grumpy mood. The
team had lost its previous game, and Biekert is not a gracious
loser.
</P>
<P>
   So this was not a good time to annoy him. Only no one warned
defensive end Scott Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The former No. 1 pick decided to mess with Biekert. The
linebacker told his teammate to stop. Davis persisted. Biekert told
him again. But the warnings went unheeded. So the linebacker lost
his patience. He whirled and knocked out Davis with one punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got that side,'' Biekert said, laughing. ``I don't
like to lose. I don't like really annoying things. They tend to get
on my nerves fairly quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Humiliated at being cold-cocked by a guy about 50 pounds
lighter, Davis left the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back three weeks later,'' Biekert said. ``But he spent
the majority of the year not playing. Then he stopped after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders had to be just a tiny bit irritated, too. They'd
invested a lot of money in Davis, and Biekert had literally knocked
him out of the game. Since Biekert had not yet established himself
as an irreplaceable part of the team's defense, losing his temper
could have cost him big time. He admits he was concerned about his
job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my second year, and I really didn't know what was
going to happen,'' he said. ``But I think it gained a little
respect for me from the other players, knowing that here's someone
who's not going to take anything from other guys. And that's what I
try to do on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   And his approach works. He was the Raiders' leading tackler in
1994 and has led them in that category twice since, including last
season when he finished with a career-high 146 tackles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
