<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOND MEMORIES ARE GOOD FOR BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The person I've thought about most in recent
days is somebody I met only once, six years ago, a nameless but
certainly not faceless shoeshine boy who never shined my shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The boy has a name, of course, but I don't know it. Getting your
shoes shined doesn't qualify as a deep personal relationship,
especially when the person doing the shining never exactly does any
shining. But the mental picture of Shoeshine Boy keeps popping up
because we met in Turkey, a place struggling to recover from the
devastation of an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Simple mathematics tells me that he is likely among the tens of
millions who survived rather than the tens of thousands who died,
but I'll never know. The only thing I really do know is that he is
at least as immortal as my memory.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Cathy, and I were about to enter the Grand Bazaar in
Istanbul when we were approached by Shoeshine Boy, who couldn't
have been more than 8 or 9, looking every bit the young
entrepreneur. As we wandered along the bazaar's outer shops, he
asked me again and again and again if I wanted a shine, and I told
him again and again and again: ``No!'' I thought I had a good
excuse: I was wearing tennis shoes at the time.
</P>
<P>
   As he kept coming back, my ``no'' kept losing its exclamation
points. Besides, Cathy is an elementary-school teacher, and
Shoeshine Boy was too much like one of those kids you just can't
stay mad at. Unlike the shopkeepers, his charm made up for his
pushiness.
</P>
<P>
   We still remember Turkish places like the Blue Mosque and
Topkapi and Ephesus. Those were only sites we saw in Turkey;
Shoeshine Boy WAS Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Once when we were in Paris, someone at our hotel put one of our
suitcases in the wrong taxi. The bag was headed to the airport and
so were we, but it had a 15-minute head start.
</P>
<P>
   As our driver tracked down the bag, another driver _ whose cab
had the errant suitcase _ waited at the airport for a good 15
minutes to help us explain to the airlines what had happened so we
could retrieve the bag. So much for rude Parisians.
</P>
<P>
   We went to a restaurant in the San Francisco area once and the
waiter suggested we try its signature dessert, saying he wouldn't
charge us if we didn't like it. We did. We have returned many
times, often having the dessert.
</P>
<P>
   A friend went to a coffeehouse, then realized that the change he
had in his pocket wasn't enough to pay for his drink. The barista
reached into the tip jar and grabbed enough change to make up the
difference. My friend is now a regular there, and a good tipper.
</P>
<P>
   None of these stories is exactly shocking, yet a lot of
employers still don't appreciate how much skill is involved in any
job _ if it is done well. You don't need a college degree to shine
shoes or drive a cab or serve coffee, but you need a lot of skills
if you want to do the job well.
</P>
<P>
   Waiters are often the difference between whether customers
return to a restaurant or eat elsewhere. Even a fast-food
restaurant with a slow-footed staff will lose customers.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of small businesses can be blind to this. They have a
great store or service or restaurant, but they try to run it on
such a shoestring that they can attract only mediocre employees.
Then the business fails and they have no idea what hit them.
</P>
<P>
   Large companies make the same mistake in customer service,
especially as they rely more on electronic commerce. All customer
service people do is take calls, right? Sure. And all waiters do is
bring you food.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried four Internet service providers in my life: my
current one, another that wasn't quite as good, and two others that
fit into that consumer category known as When Hell Freezes Over.
They are forever banished from my Rolodex because of sloppy
customer service.
</P>
<P>
   With one, I e-mailed a simple question. The company replied with
15 pages of boilerplate technical support, none of which came close
to answering that simple question.
</P>
<P>
   The other freeze-dried provider wouldn't let you cancel your
subscription by e-mail, and callers to customer service always
seemed to have to wait in the telephone queue for at least 25
minutes, no matter what time of day you called. Even if the service
sounds wonderful in the future, the company will never have the
chance to waste 25 minutes of my life again.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather spend it getting my tennis shoes shined.
</P>
<P>
   When Shoeshine Boy visited us for what seemed like the 1,000th
rejection, Cathy asked if she could take his picture. He picked up
his stand and posed for her.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, I gave him his dollar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
