<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-FISHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHING PRESIDENTS: FISH STORIES FROM GEORGE WASHINGTON TO BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES J. LEWIS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's difficult to visualize President Clinton with a fishing
rod. The gregarious, somatic president is not known to seek
solitude (and its invitation to introspection) or to become
enraptured by natural beauty; his recreation and renewal come from
the high-fives fellowship of Vernon Jordan and other male golf
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Of the presidents since FDR, Clinton has been the least frequent
user of Camp David _ the official presidential retreat in the
Catoctin Mountains of northern Maryland, with nearby streams
stocked with trout and bass.
</P>
<P>
   For many other presidents, fishing has provided a quick
refreshment from official duties. For George Bush, to pick a recent
example, fishing ``totally, totally clears your mind. ... It's not
just catching the fish; it's the background, the environment, the
beauty of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiences of presidents with lures, flies and bait is the
topic of an intriguing book, ``Fishing with the Presidents,'' by
Bill Mares. ($14.95, Stackpole Books.) The book's charming
collection of editorial cartoons and photographs supplement the
author's witty style to produce a history of presidential angling
that fishing fans and presidential history buffs will enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing has never been a partisan spot, according to Mares.
Democrats Grover Cleveland and Jimmy Carter loved to fly fish and
Republicans Calvin Coolidge and Bush were happy with bait.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington relied on commercial fishing for his personal
economy to supplement the crops. Mount Vernon wasn't just a
plantation _ it also was a fishery center for Washington's harvest
of the Potomac River, where seine nets collected shad and herring.
The slave fishermen were rewarded with a pint of rum a day and the
catch was sold as far away as the West Indies and Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Down through the years, presidential candidates found ways to be
photographed with fishing poles in their hands as a way of
conveying their wholesome common touch. Herbert Hoover summed it
up: ``Lots of people committed crimes during the year who would not
have done so if they had been fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover, a dedicated fisherman who habitually wore a jacket and
tie in his outings, wryly commented that ``no political aspirant
can qualify for election unless he demonstrates he is a fisherman,
there being 25 million persons who pay annually for a license to
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover built his own private fishing camp on the Rapidan River
in the foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains of Virginia. He
ultimately deeded the property to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Humorist Will Rogers summed up the 1932 presidential election in
fishing terms. ``This campaign will be settled on fish,'' Rogers
wrote. ``Do you want a deep-sea fisherman (FDR) in the White House
_ flounders and cod _ or a big trout and perch man (Hoover)?''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1990, following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, Bush
insisted on keeping his scheduled fishing vacation at
Kennebunkport, Maine, despite criticism that he should be back in
Washington to manage Operation Desert Shield. Bush ignored the news
photographers who captured him fishing daily. He later said he was
trying to avoid scaring the American public by ``creating a crisis
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Mares, a Burlington, Vt.-based writer with eight earlier books
to his credit, occasionally over-analyzes his topic. He provides
separate chapters devoted to ``Fishing and Swearing'' (six pages),
fishing and lying and fishing and Cabinets. The author's 18 pages
of footnotes testify to his scholarship on a sporting theme. Mares
reports that Dwight Eisenhower went fly fishing more than 40 times
but played almost 800 rounds of golf during his eight years in
office.
</P>
<P>
   After a suitable drumroll, Mares announces that his favorite
fishing president is ... Grover Cleveland. Among the reasons Mares
selects him is that Cleveland was a Democrat, proof that while
fishing may be a non-partisan activity, writing about it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, who even went fishing on his honeymoon in Western
Maryland, was a ``psychologist of fishing,'' according to Mares. He
had something to say about every fishing circumstance: getting
skunked, lying, pretensions, bad manners, patience.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his first term, Cleveland and some friends from Albany
hired four experienced guides for a combination fishing and hunting
trip on Saranac Lake in the Adirondack woods of New York. The
president left behind his entourage of aides and Secret Service
agents and it took a two-day hike through the woods for a reporter
to find them.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland later bought a cottage near Buzzards Bay, Mass.,
picking the spot because there were bluefish and sea bass in the
bay and trout in nearby streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``With warmth and wit, Cleveland summed up all that is good and
true in fishing,'' Mares concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland denounced fishing pretensions of those who would
substitute equipment for skill or prefer flies over bait; he
defended the black bass over the trout and salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland also made a fisherman's lies respectable with his
one-liner, ``Our maxim is: In the essentials, truthfulness, in the
non-essentials, reciprocal latitude.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
