<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-TRANSMISSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE AGE OF INTERNET, GROUP MARKS MILESTONE IN RADIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cellular phones, television, pagers and the
Internet were unimagined wonders 100 years ago when San Franciscans
in a basement by the Pacific shore waited for a mysterious-looking
gadget to print a message on a spool of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the device began beeping and barking. It printed a
series of dots and dashes on the paper.
</P>
<P>
   When translated from Morse code into English, the message, from
a ship nine miles at sea, read: ``Sherman is sighted.'' The Sherman
was a troop carrier bringing American soldiers back from the
Philippines, where they had served during the Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began, on Aug. 23, 1899, what radio historians say was the
first practical use of radio in America.
</P>
<P>
   It was the opening act of a century when wireless
electromagnetic waves would begin to seriously threaten paper and
print as the leading communications medium, and when invisible
signals moving at the speed of light would enable humans to listen
to symphony orchestras on distant continents, to watch astronauts
walk on the Moon and to phone anyone anywhere between the North and
South poles.
</P>
<P>
   Radio buffs, with help from agencies such as the Coast Guard and
National Park Service, on Saturday commemorated the 100th
anniversary of the ``Sherman is sighted'' transmission.
</P>
<P>
   In 1899, the Sherman message ``wasn't a big deal _ just a couple
of words (sent) by a ship,'' said Steve Kushman, president of the
California Historical Radio Society. ``But it opened the floodgates
for a whole century of radio and communications technology.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, radio was mostly a laboratory curiosity. It was
invented and tested in experimental forms in the 1890s by
researchers such as Guglielmo Marconi in Italy and Oliver Lodge in
Britain, but by 1899 the age of routine long-distance signaling and
mass broadcasting was still far off.
</P>
<P>
   As National Park Service official Steve Haller observed, the
United States was just beginning to flex its muscles as an
international power, as dramatized by its actions in the
Spanish-American War. The war was merited ``to conquer a new empire
for Uncle Sam,'' he quoted one San Francisco newspaper as stating.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Coast Guard Capt. Charles Williams stood by as a
radio receiver picked up a dot-and-dash repeat of the 1899 message
_ ``Sherman is here'' _ transmitted from a Coast Guard vessel. The
message was sent by Chief Warrant Officer Matt Skahill aboard the
Point Broward, five miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Then, unconsciously demonstrating how radically the world has
changed since 1899, Williams responded to a message on his pager by
pulling a cellular telephone from his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Lee, a San Francisco lawyer who is general counsel to the
historical society, observed: ``I imagine that a century from now,
people will be commemorating the Net and the World Wide Web just as
we're commemorating radio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
