<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-VIEQUES-0901-     08-31 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-VIEQUES-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: TINY VIEQUES FIGHTS FOR ITS PRISTINE LIFE, BUT WHAT IF
THE NAVY DOES LEAVE?
 &HT;    With Photo mug of Williams.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Out the window of a bumpy, cramped
commuter plane, this small island off Puerto Rico's eastern coast
sparkles like a Caribbean gem, verdant green hills rising from a
white ribbon of beach.
</P>
<P>
   San Juan's riot of all things American _ Burger King, Outback,
7-Eleven and Pizza Hut on every corner, at least outside the
historic district _ disappears with the prop wash. Through the
windshield, a landscape from a slower, simpler time looms on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Not a condominium or casino in sight, just quaint single-lane
roads winding through lush tropical greenery. Small farms and
modest homes dot the uplands, a line of jagged hills that mark the
island's spine. Taxi drivers beep their horns as they approach
sharp curves, warning on-coming drivers not to hog the narrow road.
</P>
<P>
   In the sleepy coastal village of Esperanza, leather-skinned
fishermen sit beneath a shade tree, swapping tales of the big ones
that got away. A row of dusty, open-air bars beckons the small
tourist crowd, offering tropical drinks, cold beers and barstool
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   But Vieques' fetching appearance belies its status as a
battleground. For decades, U.S. Navy pilots have practiced war on
the island's northern tip, dropping tons of munitions on a deserted
zone that in places resembles a moonscape.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders _ whose grandfathers saw their land condemned by the
Navy and were forced to move with just a pittance in compensation _
want the Navy out. They want their island back, and they want the
military to clean up the bomb damage and pay to help them bring
their economy into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Protestors occupying the bombing range for the past three months
vow they won't leave until the Navy relents.
</P>
<P>
   If they prevail, the island will be free of the constant
bombardment that has cracked the walls of houses and shaken
residents. No more dust from bomb craters will darken the sky
overhead; no more wayward bombs will threaten residents or harm the
fishing grounds just offshore.
</P>
<P>
   But what will Vieques' future hold without the Navy?
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that the sugarcane plantations that once thrived
on the 22,000 acres taken over by the military will return. It
isn't even clear whether the original owners of the land would get
their property back. More likely the government would take
possession, perhaps preserving some of the land as parks and
opening other areas _ including several pristine beaches _ to
development.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders and the tourists drawn to Vieques because it is so
undeveloped seem split on what they want the future to bring.
</P>
<P>
   Many natives have lived in the United States, but returned to
Vieques because the slow, simple life kept a hold on them they
couldn't shake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Brooklyn for 13 years, but I came back because this
is my birth island,'' said Jose Anibal Guerra, a 54-year-old
fisherman. ``I decided Vieques is peaceful and nice, not like
Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, having seen the bright lights and opportunities of the
mainland, they realize what they have given up by coming home:
modern conveniences, big-money jobs, opportunities for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, many hope the tourism industry that has brought
prosperity to their neighbors on Puerto Rico's main island might do
the same for Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many of the tourists drawn to Vieques because it is so
laid-back shudder at the thought of high-rise, mega-developments
replacing the quaint guesthouses, unspoiled vistas and easy-going
pace that gives the place its charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here from the Virgin Islands because the crime and
attitude there just wasn't very pleasant anymore,'' said one
American owner of a Vieques guesthouse, who didn't want his name
used. ``The same thing will happen here. Now it's this sleepy,
forgotten place, but it will change. It's a Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Vieques will find a happy middle ground. Perhaps Puerto
Rican authorities will learn from some of the mistakes of San
Juan's crowded tourist districts, where poor zoning controls have
led to garish commercial strips with little appeal.
</P>
<P>
   For now _ with the Navy bombing halted because of the protests _
Vieques retains its lost-in-time feel, a secluded hideaway for
snorkelers, fishermen and tourists looking for deserted beaches
lapped by gentle waves.
</P>
<P>
   What the coming years will bring, nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in California, but I came back here,'' said Jorge
Adams, another Vieques fisherman who also works as a lifeguard. ``I
want my children to grow up here, where it's safer and they know
their Puerto Rican heritage. But they must have jobs if they are
going to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MEDICAL-EXAMINER-HNS &LR;      08-31 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-EXAMINER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH IS ALL IN A DAY'S WORK FOR MEDICAL EXAMINER'S STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Graham Cowley is haunted by his work.
</P>
<P>
   The faces of death spring up everywhere, from busy intersections
to ballpark bathrooms. The sights and smells of the job still send
him into dry heaves. The few thank you notes he gets are stained
with tears.
</P>
<P>
   Those who recognize Cowley in bookstores or bars almost never
want to shake his hand. They are more likely to turn away in a
flood of horrifying memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will never forget you _ they'll even remember your
face,'' Cowley said recently. ``You'll get a kid looking up at you
like you're the Big Bad Wolf, coming to take another one of their
loved ones away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowley is one of 13 investigators in the San Francisco medical
examiner's office. The portion of their job the public sees,
retrieving the dead, is actually the easy part.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators feed orphaned pets, track down long-lost
relatives and guide family members into the autopsy viewing room so
they can confirm the identity of a mangled loved one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have literally given last rites,'' said Cowley, who could be
mistaken for an Eric Clapton roadie with his English accent and
just-short-of-grizzled beard. ``The family's around; there's no
priest there. What are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Working two to a shift, Cowley and his colleagues keep track of
the 7,000 or so San Franciscans who die each year, investigating
between 1,500 and 2,000 of the most stomach-churning cases.
</P>
<P>
   They have hauled dead bodies out of every corner of the city,
returning to some hotels and apartment buildings more than once in
a year.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly job has a starting salary of around $49,000 per year.
Asked why they don't just up and quit, and the investigators rarely
give a smooth reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's hundreds of reasons, but I can't explain a single one
of them,'' said Charlie Newman, the administrator of the medical
examiner's office. ``You'd have to walk in their shoes to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The first call one recent morning turned out to be investigation
No. 917 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like protagonists in the Quentin Tarantino film ``Pulp
Fiction,'' Cowley and investigator Bill Tolliver pulled on their
black jackets and jumped into a white van, which can hold four
bodies on a two-tiered rack in back.
</P>
<P>
   With uniforms unchanged since at least the 1930s, the
investigator's attire is pure film noir. Black boots. Black pants.
Black belt. Thin black tie. White shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The only protection they wear are loose, wrist-high rubber
gloves. Even with the most decomposed bodies, the investigators
don't put anything under their noses to dull the senses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only do that in the movies,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   As Cowley and Tolliver approached the destination _ a flophouse
hotel on the boundary of the Mission District and Upper Market _
they nod solemnly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here before,'' said Tolliver, 61, the senior
investigator. ``I've been here a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the building is a middle-aged man with thinning
long hair in a ponytail and a sleepy look. He met Tolliver and
Cowley at the entrance, then led them up three flights to two
uniformed police officers.
</P>
<P>
   There was no need for introductions.
</P>
<P>
   The body was across the room, slumped forward on a chair facing
a window with torn curtains. The 40-year-old's arms and legs was
frozen into rigor. His face, wedged between his knees, was nearly
black from the post-mortem flow of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Near his right boot was a pencil-thin syringe; the plunger was
fully depressed.
</P>
<P>
   There are no open-and-shut cases, so Cowley and Tolliver stepped
into the room with caution, making quick detailed notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at what it isn't, not what it is,'' Cowley said.
``Process of elimination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I start every case as a homicide and work down from there,''
Tolliver said.
</P>
<P>
   He took notes: The door was locked, and the key was in the man's
pocket, so it was unlikely anyone killed him and fled.
</P>
<P>
   The spider web of red lines on his body, called the ligature,
was consistent with the way he was found, so he probably wasn't
moved.
</P>
<P>
   A small sink holds a bottle of vodka, two liters of soda and a
few cups of fat-free yogurt. All were recently purchased and full,
indicating he probably didn't commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The body remained rigid in a sitting position, even as the
investigators lifted the armpits and set it gently on the ground.
Cowley worked the muscles in the arms and legs like a physical
therapist, limbering the joints enough to stretch it into the body
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a shower this morning. What's the point?'' Cowley said.
</P>
<P>
   The body weighed more than 250 pounds, and there were stairs to
negotiate, but the investigators considered themselves lucky: there
was a clear path to the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually walked in rooms that are so deep with garbage
that I have to bend down so I don't hit my head on the ceiling,''
Cowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowley and Tolliver zipped the body bag and secured the corpse
to a gurney with cloth straps, covering it with two sheets.
</P>
<P>
   There was a crowd outside, staring and whispering. A mother
grabbed a young girl's wrist and yanked her away as the men lug the
body off the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   After placing the corpse in the van, Cowley pulled out some
anti-bacterial lotion, scrubbed it high on his wrists and passed
the bottle to Tolliver. He'll wash his hands three more times in
the next hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important question for me: Did he have family?''
chief investigator Alan Pringle said when the two investigators
returned to the office. ``We want to get to family as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators recognize the importance of the few moments they
spend breaking the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I say the wrong word, if I have the wrong inclination with
a phrase, they are going to remember it for the rest of their
lives,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get a John Doe, it's all we want to do to get them
identified and let the family know,'' investigator Chuck Cecil
said. ``Because someone, somewhere loved that person.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phone number on a small blue scrap of paper belongs to
the man's father in New York. Tolliver rested his arm against a
desk and braced himself as he told the elderly man that his son
died of a ``possible drug overdose.''
</P>
<P>
   Tolliver has done this hundreds of times, but the words still
come out slowly, and are chosen carefully. Cowley and another young
investigator stepped to the other side of the room and gave
Tolliver some space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is terrible news, and I'm sorry to be the bearer
of this news. ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
