<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-COLTART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTART FLAGGED DOWN A SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ He had a passion for golf, which anyone could see.
He had a flag in his golf bag, hidden from view.
</P>
<P>
   After Andrew Coltart put the finishing touches on a round of 67
to win his match on a cold, raw October day at The Old Course four
years ago, he thought again about the &UR;  &LR; flag. Not quite yet, he
whispered to himself as he stood to the side of the 18th green at
St. Andrews. His countrymen were all around him, celebrating what
would be Scotland's first Dunhill Cup in 11 years, but it was not
quite official.
</P>
<P>
   At least it wasn't until Sam Torrance safely negotiated two
putts for par. And then . . . Coltart had his hands inside the bag.
He pulled out the flag of Scotland, ``draped it on my shoulders,''
and kept it there for quite some time as he celebrated a victory
that validated all the faith he had in himself and all the pride he
had in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to end the celebrating and get on with the
next golf challenge, Coltart did so without the flag. He kept the
passion, however. That's with him always.
</P>
<P>
   It was with him at the NEC Invitational, though it is mixed with
a healthy dose of pride. And why not? Last Sunday, the European
Ryder Cup team was completed when Mark James named his captain's
picks. One was Jesper Parnevik. (itals)Tell us something we didn't
know.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The other was Andrew Coltart. (itals)Tell us that again,
slowly.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said the captain, Coltart, with one career victory, was
his second pick. There would be a seventh rookie on the European
Ryder Cup team, a fact that sent reporters off in a rush to find
out not if, but how much, these lads were shaking in their
Foot-joys. Coltart has been the easiest target here, an unlikely
captain's pick who no doubt would be more nervous than a skydiver
whose chute doesn't open.
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true,'' said the 29-year-old Coltart. ``When
you get the chance to play something that is a dream there is no
point in being scared about it. You just can't wait to get out
there and peg it up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coltart understands the attraction to his story and he has been
impeccably polite all week at the NEC Invitational. He had, after
all, finished 12th in the Ryder Cup standings and the team already
had six rookies to challenge what is a very strong group of
Americans; surely, James would turn to veteran Bernhard Langer,
14th in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Even Coltart concedes he had not expected the nod, which is why
he headed to the airport in Munich. He was about to board a
connecting flight in London when James tracked him down. ``I was
surprised because I had slipped to 12th,'' said Coltart. ``If I had
finished 11th, I wouldn't have been surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not share the sentiment that a veteran such as Langer
(or perhaps Nick Faldo) should have been picked. ``They haven't
played up to their expectations this year. Nick hasn't played well
for the last couple of years.'' It is Sweden's Robert Karlsson he
feels for. Karlsson had finished 11th in the standings, knocked out
of the Top 10 by Ireland's Padriag Harrington at the BMW.
</P>
<P>
   But don't interpret this surprise as a lack of confidence. To
the contrary, Coltart believes he belongs. ``I thought it was
fantastic to be picked. I'm honored. I worked hard for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been under an awful lot of pressure, because I was always
the one sort of at the bottom (of the standings). I was the one
everyone was sort of able to have a pop at. But even when I dropped
out, I continued to play solid all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it counted most, he was at his best. A final-round 66
at the BMW vaulted him from 19th place to tied for fifth. It earned
enough money to nail down 12th in the standings. It made James take
notice. And it sent reporters his way with the same questions: Are
you afraid? Do you feel too much pressure?
</P>
<P>
   You'll excuse Coltart if he doesn't see this as that big a deal.
(itals)``Why would you be scared about something you've wanted all
your life to be doing?''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was 4 when he started playing golf in the land that claims
the sport as its own. His great uncle helped found Thornhill, the
club at which he first learned to play. His grandfather was a
scratch. His father carried a 1-handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's a scratch watcher now,'' said Andrew Chandler,
laughing. He explains that Robert Coltart is a fixture at European
events, and his interest in his son's career is as loyal as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler played the European Tour from 1974-89, but now he runs
a management company and included in his stable of golfers are
three members of the European Ryder Cup team _ Lee Westwood, Darren
Clarke, and Coltart. The former two need no introduction when they
enter the golf stage; the latter one should be taken seriously,
said Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know how badly he wanted to make the team. He has
represented his country in everything possible _ Scottish Boys,
Scottish Youths, Great Britain &AMP; Ireland team, Eisenhower Cup,
Walker Cup, Dunhill Cup, World Cup. Now the Ryder Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Coltart was a junior golf champion and through the years his
growth in the game has been followed closely by countrymen who
cherish the sport. But Europeans are more forgiving with their
youth, said Chandler, as opposed to Americans who hold them to
higher expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home,'' said Chandler, ``being a good junior doesn't mean
you go all the way. There are an awful lot who don't.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Coltart turned pro at 21 and proceeded to struggle, he
didn't feel a nation's wrath. The patience was paid off, as Coltart
was seventh in the Order of Merit in 1996, ninth last year when he
earned his first victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I felt pressure, it wasn't because of anyone else. It was
because of myself. I thought I was a good junior and I felt seeing
as how I was at the stage, perhaps I could make it onto the next
stage. But I put pressure on myself. There was never pressure from
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even from the people who mattered most to him _ his parents.
</P>
<P>
   His father was self-employed and his mother worked in a
geriatric hospital. ``Dad was closing the shop to run me all over
Britain to play in boys events and things like that. They
sacrificed a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Laurae, is married to Westwood, and it makes for
great laughs and mixups. ``Thanks for getting it right. Everyone
thinks I'm married to his sister,'' said Coltart, ``but there are
lot of wind-ups, you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a relationship that solidifies an intangible that the
Europeans bring to Ryder Cup competition _ one that the Americans
sorely lack. Camaraderie. They are friends, travel mates, and
conscious of one another's personal lives. Coltart's wife, Emma, is
pregnant with their first child (due date: Sept.13), yet something
else that will draw the team closer. Coltart's joy is their joy.
</P>
<P>
   So the Europeans are underdogs again. But aren't they always?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an attitude that we don't even think about being
rookies,'' said Coltart, ``because at the end of the day it is 18
holes of golf which every man on that team is capable of playing at
the highest level. I would say they are the favorites, but I
wouldn't say they are the overwhelming favorites.''
</P>
<P>
   Coltart is on target, said American Tom Lehman, who was paired
in the Irish Open a few years ago with the young Scot. ``I thought
it was a good pick,'' said Lehman. ``Andrew is a good player, a
very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has a pretty good grasp of history, which one would
expect of a Scot. Even if said history was just two years ago.
Weren't there five rookies on the European team at Valderrama, he
was reminded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' said Coltart, a wide smile breaking through. ``So
what's the big deal?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
