<HEADER>
A5750 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-31 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKEN RECORDS WARPED 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A game of 20 Questions with baseball's talking record book:
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your most misunderstood single-season record?
</P>
<P>
   A. That's easy. Mark McGwire's 70 home runs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How about your most overrated record?
</P>
<P>
   A. Hmmm. Probably McGwire's 70 homers in '98. Besides ``The
Blair Witch Project,'' it's the most overrated event I've witnessed
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What record has puzzled you most?
</P>
<P>
   A. I know what human has puzzled me most. You. What's your
point? Look, I'm baffled that true baseball historians consider the
record held by McGwire sacred. This year he will lease the record
to Sammy Sosa, who already has 54 homers. Sosa will sublease to
someone else in a few years. Big deal. Next question.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So you're bitter?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm more disappointed than bitter. Baseball may be a timeless
game, but all of its records are not. All I ask is that people put
my contents in context.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you mean?
</P>
<P>
   A. I mean you should have seen this day coming as early as '67,
supposedly the Dead Ball Era.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Um, Mr. Book? I wasn't born then.
</P>
<P>
   A. No excuse. Read more, kid. In '67, Tigers pitchers Denny
McLain and Earl Wilson allowed 69 homers between them. That was one
more than the four worst home run pitchers allowed _ combined _ in
'27.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Significance of '27?
</P>
<P>
   A. Babe Ruth hit 60 homers. Lou Gehrig was second in the
American League with 47. Tell me how many the third-place guy had.
</P>
<P>
   Q. 41?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nope. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you saying anyone can hit homers today?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not at all, son. They were hard to hit in '27, when the worst
pitcher gave up 18 homers. By '96, when two AL pitchers allowed 40
and one NL guy gave up 37, the long ball had changed. Hitting one
out still wasn't easy, but home run artistry became a more
accessible exercise. My God, son, even Brady Anderson popped 50
that year.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You don't like McGwire and Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   A. That's not the issue. What I'm trying to tell you is that I
pushed this record out of my exclusive Mount Rushmore section many
years ago. It is a nice accomplishment, but its touchstone has
diminished. Last year, six pitchers gave up 34 homers or more.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Did you ever love homers?
</P>
<P>
   A. I cherished them in '27, when Americans liked big home run
hitters, big bands, and a New England president, Calvin Coolidge,
who spoke in small sentences. (Coolidge's entire dialogue during a
game in '27: ``What time is it?'')
</P>
<P>
   Q. Were you intrigued by homers in '61?
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure. Roger Maris and Mickey Mantle in the Bronx. A
20-year-old Bob Dylan hanging out in the Village. Great era.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Hey, I know this is a baseball chat. But real quick: What's
your favorite Dylan CD?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Blonde on Blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Yo, what about ``Time Out of Mind''?
</P>
<P>
   A. Stick to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You didn't support an asterisk next to Maris's 61?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nah. If you're going to give an asterisk to Roger, you also
have to give one to the Babe. He played his entire career before
integration. People in the majors called Josh Gibson the black Babe
Ruth; people in the Negro Leagues called Ruth the white Gibson. Who
knows what would have happened if there had been one inclusive
league? So enough of this asterisk madness.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When did the home run lose its value?
</P>
<P>
   A. It was a gradual decline. It used to be that 25-homer guys
were special. Now a guy hits 25 and people say, ``So?'' Or maybe it
was the constant ``This is going to be the year'' chatter. I didn't
hear people saying that about Joltin' Joe's 56-game hitting streak.
They don't say that about Bob Gibson's 1.12 earned run average,
Grover Alexander's 16 shoutouts, or Ted's .406.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Respectfully, sir, I think you are generalizing. Can you give
an example?
</P>
<P>
   A. You work for the Globe, right? Only three Augusts ago, one of
your reporters, a man nicknamed Sides _ Larry Nostradamus Whiteside
_ wrote the following about McGwire: ``He will cross the threshold
that separates the above-average slugger from the
honest-to-goodness baseball legend. Don't bet against him.'' And
then McGwire said this to Sides: ``Until somebody gets to 50 home
runs in September, (chasing Maris) is not a legitimate question.''
</P>
<P>
   We had it last season. We have it now. No surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who is to blame for this home run obsession?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know many magic tricks, but try to follow me on this
one. Go to a nearby mirror and you'll see what's wrong with your
game.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Me?
</P>
<P>
   A. You and people like you. You have refused to see the game's
dramatic changes. You become excited when baseballs leave parks at
video-game frequency. You talk about awful pitching and awful
umpires. You talk about tightly wound baseballs. You frown at
batters who hog the plate as if they were your spouse at bedtime,
hogging all the pillows and blankets. But then you celebrate a home
run explosion?
</P>
<P>
   You have bought the propaganda. Baseball pulled a ``Wag The
Dog'' on you, telling you that homers are supreme when they are
truly Depression and Free Love measurements of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   You, newsboy, are a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What can I do to change?
</P>
<P>
   A. Simply mark Sosa's new record _ 71? _ on one of my pages. And
stop overstating the significance of home runs. You should have
done that years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
