<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5751 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-31 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOTAL STOCK MARKET GAINS ON DIVERSIFICATION WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you say you own an index fund, people automatically assume
you mean a Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fund.
</P>
<P>
   But these days another type of index fund is gaining popularity
with investors. It's called a total stock market index fund and it
provides just what the name implies: exposure to the entire
American stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In July such funds attracted nearly $1 billion in new money,
roughly half the amount that flowed into S&AMP;P 500 index funds,
according to Financial Research Corp. of Boston. Last July
total-market index funds attracted $401 million; in July 1997 they
received only $68 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, much of the money flowing into the
total-market funds is going to the Vanguard Group, king of the
index funds. Gus Sauter is happy to see it. ``We've been promoting
these funds for a long time, but for most of that time our words
were falling on deaf ears,'' says Sauter, a managing director at
Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Sauter isn't complaining about the $90 billion Vanguard has in
its S&AMP;P 500 fund. But the fund, popular as it is, essentially
represents an investment in large-company stocks. Those stocks have
done spectacularly over the last five years, which explains why the
500 funds have become all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   To purists like Sauter, however, indexing means something
broader. It is based on the philosophy that since you can't
possibly know what kind of stocks are going to do well tomorrow it
makes sense to own all kinds of stocks _ big, mid-sized, and small.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a total-market fund you don't have to make any
decisions,'' says Kristen Culp, who runs T. Rowe Price's version of
the fund. ``You don't have to make a bet on style, market
capitalization or a portfolio manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Total-market funds are based on the Wilshire 5000 _ a universe
that actually has 7,200 stocks in it. Go figure. The Wilshire list
includes all the stocks that are in the S&AMP;P 500 plus all those that
aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Because it isn't practical to own so many names, the typical
total stock market fund buys only a representative sampling of the
7,200 stocks. T. Rowe Price owns 1,100 stocks; Vanguard owns 3,100.
Both funds closely mimic the performance of the index. Like all
index funds, the total-market funds are low- cost and
tax-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   What explains why the funds are catching on? In a word,
diversification. By moving deeper into the market, investors spread
their bets around and in theory at least, reduce the risks they
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reducing risk is what investing is all about,'' says William
Dougherty of Kanon Bloch Carre, a consultant and money manager.
Last December Dougherty moved some of his money into total-market
funds because he was concerned about the growing concentration in
the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P index has 500 stocks, but its performance has been
driven by a small number of giant stocks such as Microsoft, General
Electric, and Cisco Systems. Those stocks have carried the 500
index to great heights, but should they reverse course, worries
Dougherty, they would exert a powerful pull on the way down.
</P>
<P>
   Total-market funds would provide some protection in the event
the big caps fall, but not as much as you might think. The S&AMP;P 500
stocks account for 77 percent of the market capitalization of the
Wilshire 5000. The same big stocks that dominate the S&AMP;P dominate
the Wilshire.
</P>
<P>
   With a market value of $470 billion, Microsoft throws its weight
around wherever it goes. The little stocks, on the other hand, are
great in number but modest in value. The smallest 3,000 stocks in
the Wilshire universe account for less than 1 percent of the
group's market value.
</P>
<P>
   The total-market funds have another drawback: they haven't done
as well as S&AMP;P 500 funds lately. They are trailing the S&AMP;P modestly
this year, as they have every year since 1993. Over the past 10
years the S&AMP;P index has returned an average of 17.38 percent a
year, compared to 16.36 percent for the Wilshire.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to a growing number of investors, the total-market funds
are a logical choice. ``These funds should help you smooth out the
peaks and valleys,'' says Sauter of Vanguard. For traditionalists
who still believe in the old-fashioned virtues of diversification,
that sense of security is a powerful selling point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
