<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' OTHER ALAMO PREPARES TO CELEBRATE AN ANNIVERSARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two official Alamos in Texas. There is the one that's
in the heart of San Antonio, with the traffic congestion and street
noise that fill most major downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the one in Bracketville, 150 miles away on the
Southwest Texas prairie where longhorns lie in sparse shade,
rattlesnakes curl up under rocks, and cactuses spring from hard-pan
soil.
</P>
<P>
   It is quiet there. The way it should be at a Spanish mission.
Also, it was there that John Wayne, dressed like Davy Crockett,
whopped the advancing troops of Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna over
the head with the butt of his muzzleloader.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder people get the authenticity of the two Alamos
confused.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's is real; Bracketville's is realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne filmed his ``Alamo'' in Bracketville 40 years ago, and on
Labor Day, Alamo Village will celebrate that anniversary with lots
of country music, poetry and talk of the Alamo heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Five authors will be on hand to discuss the Alamo. The authors
and their books are: Wally Chariton, ``Exploring American
Legends''; Alan Huffines, ``Blood And Noble Men''; Steve Hardin,
``Texian Iliad''; George Nelson, ``The Alamo _ An Illustrated
History''; and Kevin Young, ``To the Tyrants Never Yield.''
</P>
<P>
   Alamo Village is the tourist park that has grown up along with
the Alamo near Bracketville. Visitors can walk the streets of the
movie set, eat in the same cantina they've seen on the large screen
and, of course, buy a few souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   If there happens to be a film being shot, the visitors get to
watch that, too. Alamo Village has a policy that insists it always
be open to visitors. It is never a closed movie set.
</P>
<P>
   James T. ``Happy'' Shahan built the movie set on his ranch
according to Wayne's specifications, but it took years for Shahan
to convince Wayne that it was the right place to film his Alamo
saga.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as the story goes, Shahan told Wayne that the Daughters
of the Republic of Texas would boycott his movie if it were filmed
anywhere but Texas. Wayne took the threat seriously.
</P>
<P>
   It was Shahan who also declared that the set was always open. It
was open during filming of ``The Alamo.'' It stayed open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to open it to tourists,'' said Shahan's widow,
Virginia. ``In one week, we had our fence cut three times by people
wanting to see where John Wayne filmed `The Alamo.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Alamo'' sets took two years to build. It took more than 1
1/4 million adobe bricks to construct the full-scale mission and
the town of San Antonio de Bexar. The set was the largest and most
complete in the world up to that time, with a cost of more than
$1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo Village gates will open at 9 a.m. on Labor Day. Aside
from the musical entertainment, there will be a Western horse race
open to everyone with a horse (no stud horses, though).
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $7 plus tax for adults and $3.50 for children 6-11,
and children under 5 get in free.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call Alamo Village, (830) 563-2580.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
