<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LEGOLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGOLAND, A MODEL THEME PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ ``Look at the plane!'' a father standing near
us exclaims, pointing out a black dot in the blue southern
California sky to his young daughter. ``Is it real, or is it
LEGOS?''
</P>
<P>
   You never know. Not here anyway, not at LEGOLAND California,
where we wouldn't be surprised if the pizza we were eating for
lunch turned out to be made from the plastic stud-and-tube bricks.
The Denmark-based LEGO Group says there are about 30 million LEGOS
in its 128-acre theme park that opened in March, which is just one
example of the trivia that continually washes over us here.
Question: What's involved in making a detailed Lego model of Grand
Central Station? Answer: 600,000 bricks, four model makers, and six
months.
</P>
<P>
   LEGOLAND California is the third LEGO park, the first two being
in Billund, Denmark, and Windsor, Great Britain. (A fourth is
planned for a 2002 opening, most likely in Germany.) It is the
latest addition to the southern California ``family attraction''
loop that includes Disneyland, Knott's Berry Farm, the San Diego
Zoo, and Sea World. You may recall that during the early 1990s,
then-Massachusetts governor William Weld tried to pitch a plot of
land in Mansfield and Norton as the site for this first US
LEGOLAND. But LEGO executives were too smart for him: They knew
about New England's weather.
</P>
<P>
   Here, 97 percent of LEGOLAND is outdoors, and the park is open
year-round. Fifty percent larger than Disneyland and perched atop
rolling hills that were formerly tomato fields, it is aimed at
2-to-12-year-olds _ not to mention their bleary-eyed and
camcorder-toting parents. It cost $130 million to build and
features some 40 rides and attractions. But from the moment we
entered its portals and walked past a 23-foot-tall LEGO-built
tyrannosaurus rex, we learned it's really about the 5,000 or so
models that are made of those 30 million acrylnitrile butadiene
styrene bricks. That's plastic to you and me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The model of the US Capitol is made from 1,641,000 bricks,
weighs 717 pounds, and took 1,200 hours to build!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``LEGOS are so-o-o-o boring,'' laments a teenage girl walking in
front of us, and it's true that anyone between the ages of 13 and
19 will find this place a tad subdued. Its six major themed areas
are colorful but not flashy. There's no neon, no loud music. Our
12-year-old son discovers he's too old for many activities, even
when motoring a small blue electric car through Driver's School
with other stoplight-running children. (``My dignity is being
tested,'' he says.) Still, he's happy enough peddling around a tall
ridge in a goofy three-passenger Sky Cycle, rolling along in a
small and low-key roller coaster called The Dragon, or working his
way through an elaborate wood and plastic climbing structure known
as The Hideaways. And he particularly likes the LEGO stuff he can
do with his hands, such as building and testing a race car and
using a desktop computer to program and operate a small robot.
(``My dignity is restored.'')
</P>
<P>
   But, like his parents _ who have spent more money on LEGOS than
they probably will on his college education _ Ethan is fascinated
by the staff-created LEGO models. OK, the San Diego Zoo, located 34
miles down the freeway, has a pair of pandas. But are they made of
acrylnitrile butadiene styrene?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bust of Albert Einstein is made of 1,120,000 bricks and is
15 1/2 feet high! It was built in Denmark and had to be transported
to California in sections because it was too big to fit through the
doors of the building in which it was contructed!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The heart and soul of LEGOLAND _ this one and the other two _ is
Miniland. The first LEGOLAND opened in Billund in 1968 because LEGO
realized that folks wanted to see LEGO models. Today that park
primarily displays European buildings made of about 45 million
bricks. The Miniland here in California is constructed of about 20
million bricks and is strictly a US phenomenon that features
painstakingly-constructed models of New York City; Washington,
D.C.; New Orleans; the California coast; and even the very same New
England that was eschewed as a LEGOLAND site. It is incredibly
detailed, down to the limos waiting outside Mann's Chinese Theatre
in Hollywood, the cop chasing a burglar across the roof of a Los
Angeles manse, and the break dancers slithering on a Manhattan
sidewalk. Built in Denmark and England before being shipped here,
it took three years and about 100 designers and builders to
construct, is controlled by 12 computers, and uses 175 miles of
underground electrical wire.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a great promoter of LEGOS, so much so that you wonder
how in the world the LEGO Group managed to lose nearly $40 million
last year, its worst annual loss ever.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan likes Miniland so much that he asks to return after dark
so he can see it when its lights came on. ``I think I've discovered
what I want to do when I grow up,'' he announces as he watches the
Manhattan skyline twinkle in 1-20 scale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Bridge is made of 75,000 bricks and has 100
lights! It is made of a special shade of orange brick to match the
original bridge!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making LEGO models is just what 34-year-old Henrik Lykke has
been doing for eight years, although he never did it in Denmark as
a child and is an automobile spray painter by training. (``A Danish
kid without Legos? Impossible!'' chirps his fellow builder, Darren
Ward, who's from England.) We meet Lykke backstage at the Model
Shop, a building where LEGOLAND visitors can watch new models being
produced. Surrounded by hundreds of plastic boxes containing many
of the 6,500 bricks available to them, the five model makers
currently working at LEGOLAND California _ not to be confused with
the four ``animatronics'' people who build the electronics and
animate many new models _ are creating a 16-foot-long octopus that
will grace a water ride that is under construction. Like many LEGO
models, it was built first in miniature. Modelers then constructed
it in half-size before starting the full-size figure, a process
called ``doubling up.'' They use a liquid that slightly softens
individual bricks and allows them to be tightly fused.
</P>
<P>
   Lykke is one of two builders who designed and constructed the US
Capitol here, a feat that took about seven months. ``Because the
real building is so large, ours is 1-60 scale, not 1-20,'' he says.
He explains that he works from photos, drawings, and sometimes even
original blueprints. But there are no computer renderings involved.
Indeed, Lykke often doesn't even follow a photograph or drawing,
especially when he's concocting, say, a fish or a fox. ``It would
be like Picasso starting with a photo or a computer printout,'' he
says. ``Sometimes it's easier to just paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance of existing models is part of the job, too. ``We get
birds pecking on them all the time,'' Lykke explains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new red octopus will be made of 300,000 bricks weighing
about 600 pounds! It would take one person about six months to
build!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEGOLAND has all the accoutrements you'd expect to find at any
theme park. A family of four should plan to spend $100 or so for
meals that go beyond fast food but have often lost their freshness
by the end of the day. LEGO gear of all sorts can be had, too, from
75-cent pencils to $85 windbreakers. And, of course, LEGO building
kits are for sale at every turn. After all, LEGOLAND does nothing
if not further promote the well-known name of a company that began
in the 1930s making handmade wooden toys and now sells its
ubiquitous bricks _ billions of which are made in Enfield, Conn. _
in 138 countries. (LEGO, incidentally, combines the two Danish
words, ``leg godt'' for play well.) ``A new park every three years
around the world,'' proclaims the company.
</P>
<P>
   We've spent nine hours at LEGOLAND California, ending our long
day with a Coast Cruise through the park's S-shaped lagoon. As our
32-passenger boat is about to glide beneath a small bridge, our
captain, whose name is Chris, makes a startling announcement. ``The
bridge is made of zero LEGO bricks,'' he says. ``That's zero LEGO
bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't believe him for a minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5758 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-SUTTON-BOS &LR;      08-31 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-SUTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP CULMINATES SUTTON COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Hal Sutton stood in the background alongside
the clubhouse veranda at The Country Club Monday and listened to
his fellow US Ryder Cuppers share their impressions of the course
with the media _ its blind spots, its nooks and crannies, its
crystalline condition.
</P>
<P>
   When the time came for him to assess his practice round in
preparation for the matches against Europe Sept. 24-26, Sutton
stepped to the podium and said, ``I'll let go what they said, with
one exception. I think this place is dripping with history.''
</P>
<P>
   He just as easily could have been offering a self-analysis.
There was a time not long ago when Sutton fairly oozed history.
</P>
<P>
   He was considered a has-been.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Shreveport, La., oil company owners burst upon the
PGA Tour scene fresh from winning the 1980 US Amateur and
established himself as one of the game's most formidable young
stars. In his first six full years on the Tour, he won seven events
_ including the 1983 Tournament Players Championship and PGA
Championship at the age of 25 _ and qualified for the Ryder Cup in
1985 and '87.
</P>
<P>
   Success became routine; a platinum future seemed a given. And
then he vanished, if not from the scene, at least from the
leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage disintegrated; his attention was diverted. He
became more concerned about his hobby _ riding and selling cutting
horses _ than about making cuts. Still, his downfall was so
precipitous that it defied logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to speculate on what's responsible other than lack of
focus, I don't really have any idea,'' he said. ``I was interested
in other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf seemingly was forgotten, and it returned the favor. Sutton
did not win for the next eight years and only once in the next 11.
In 1992, he rang up exactly $39,2345 in earnings _ the equivalent
of a mediocre week for a true contender _ and he bottomed out after
the 1993 season, when his 10-year TPC champion's exemption expired.
The following year, he was reduced to using his one-time exemption
as one of the top 50 career money earners to gain automatic
entrance into tournaments and avoid the humiliation of returning to
the PGA Tour Qualifying School to regain his card.
</P>
<P>
   But on the precipice, he found redemption. He had remarried,
happily; he had children. And he dearly wanted them to know Hal
Sutton the golfer as something other than a historical footnote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a precious little family back at the house,'' he
said, ``and I didn't want my little girls not to know what Daddy
could do. So I tried to rejuvenate.''
</P>
<P>
   There was more to this rededication than whimsy. Sutton's talent
hadn't deserted him, merely his commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down, I thought I could still get it back,'' he said. ``I
thought I still had some game down inside. I knew I had the desire
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Desire translated into dollars as Sutton started his climb back
up the money list. He capitalized on his free pass in 1994 to win
$540,162, 29th among the leaders, and thus qualified for legitimate
exempt status for 1995. That year, he revisited a place that had
disappeared from his itinerary _ the winner's circle _ as he
captured the B.C. Open.
</P>
<P>
   After two middling seasons, which would have been considered
exemplary by the standards of his lost decade, Sutton hit the
jackpot last year. He won both the Texas Open and the prestigious
Tour Championship, raking in $1,838,740.
</P>
<P>
   That virtually cemented his status as a reborn Ryder Cupper, but
just to be sure, Sutton has remained on the upswing this year.
Though he hasn't won, he has racked up 11 top 10 finishes, cashing
checks worth $1,456,510.89.
</P>
<P>
   At 41, he is back near the top, and his appreciation is
magnified because of his extended stay in golf's netherworld.
</P>
<P>
   His Ryder Cup berth was just about secured before he teed off in
the final qualifying event, the PGA Championship two weeks ago at
Medinah, Ill. Still, when he stepped off the 18th green after
completing his fourth round, tying for 26th in the tournament and
easily clinching his Ryder return, Sutton seemed duly humbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really good,'' he said. ``I didn't know if I'd ever
make another Ryder Cup team. It's important because it's one of the
criteria y'all use to judge whether someone is back.''
</P>
<P>
   So there he was Monday, officially back, savoring the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on this Ryder Cup team is exciting for me,'' said
Sutton, ``because it's been 12 years since I've made one.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been so long, in fact, that he might not recognize the
competition now. Thanks largely to the unwilling contributions of
Sutton and his 1985 and '87 teammates _ both of whom lost the Cup
to Europe, the latter for the first time on US soil _ the Ryder has
been transformed from a biennial exhibition of American superiority
to a truly competitive event and a commercial goliath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been viewing it from the sofa in my living room,'' said
Sutton. ``I'm going to have a different prespective than I had, but
from everything I can tell, there's a large difference in the
magnitude of the Ryder Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton greatly prefers this view to that of the past dozen
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to be glad,'' he said, ``to be a part of this
next little history.''
</P>
<P>
   History, he knows, is much nicer when you're dealing with it in
the present tense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
