<HEADLINE>
SIGNS POINT TO SOLID CAREER FOR ROOKIE WOODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It has been 23 years since Pete Brock went
through this, but he's especially aware of center Damien Woody's
presence on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   Brock, an entrepreneur who also follows the Patriots for Boston
radio station WBCN, was the 12th pick overall in the 1976 NFL draft
out of Colorado. The Patriots took him seven spots behind Hall of
Famer Mike Haynes and nine spots ahead of Tim Fox in what turned
out to be a bonanza first round. (They received the extra picks as
a result of trading Jim Plunkett to San Francisco.)
</P>
<P>
   Brock never made a Pro Bowl, but he played 12 years of steady,
hard-nosed football on one of the best offensive lines the Patriots
ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Woody, the 17th overall pick this year out of Boston College,
has been thrown into the fire, with competition only from
second-year center Jason Andersen, but Brock was able to break in
gradually and learn from veteran Bill Lenkaitis. Red Miller, then
the offensive line coach, had Brock play every line position before
he eventually took over for Lenkaitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red wanted me to know what everybody's job was on the
offensive line,'' said Brock. ``He felt I'd be better prepared to
make the calls on the line if I understood what everyone's role
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock remembers one drive against the Chicago Bears on which he
played all six line positions, including tight end.
</P>
<P>
   That is something Woody will never experience. The Patriots want
him to be their center for some time. After three exhibition games,
he appears to be headed in that direction. Woody was one of the few
positives in a 45-14 thrashing at the hands of the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are really coming together now,'' said Woody. ``I think
I'm playing pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   What impressed the coaching staff was Woody's ability to keep up
with a very active Tampa Bay defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a lot of movement things, stunting and stuff that
caused us to freeze a little bit,'' said Woody. ``We couldn't come
off the ball like we wanted because all of the angling they were
doing. But I feel a lot of progress in every game I've played. Just
getting the reps and playing in game situations has really helped
to build my confidence up.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line coach Dante Scarnecchia doesn't speak to the
media about his players, but Brock is qualified to assess Woody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks to me to be a great athlete,'' said Brock. ``He has
great feet and tremendous strength. The one thing I've noticed
about him, and most young players, is they don't have a lot of
technique. He tends to rely a lot on his athletic ability and
strength. The technique and the fundamentals will come with it, and
the quicker he learns that the better off he'll be.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times he'll get out of position because of his lack of
technique, but his athleticism allows him to get back into position
very quickly. Trouble is, in this league, you're going to meet Dana
Stubblefields, Brad Culpeppers, and Warren Sapps week in and week
out. They'll be as athletic and strong as you are, and technique is
what will make or break him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock noticed that, against Tampa Bay, Woody ``got some good
push when he needed to really shore it up front, when he needed to
keep the continuity of the pocket together. You could see he could
drop anchor and play that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody got off to a rough start in camp, missing a couple of
workouts that angered the coaching staff and made them wonder about
his work ethic. Those concerns are quickly subsiding.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 picks are constantly under a microscope. He plays a
position that few fans watch intently, but when an opponent bowls
him over, he'll be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel (the pressure) easing right now,'' said Woody. ``When I
first came in they were hard on me _ not to say they're not hard on
me now _ but I'm getting used to the system and things are coming a
lot easier then they were in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock said the toughest part of the position is the mental part.
There's no doubt in his mind that Woody can handle that, and he
called his physical presence ``astounding.'' But Brock remembers
very well all of the calls he used to make, all the blitz pickups.
He remembers getting to the point where he'd call decoys just to
get the opposition thinking one way so he could do the opposite.
One thing he doesn't understand is offensive linemen like Woody
pointing to their opponents at the line of scrimmage, almost
tipping off the blocking scheme. These are things that Woody will
learn in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
