<HEADLINE>
USOC'S SCHULTZ WILL RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United States Olympic Committee executive director Dick Schultz
will step down next year, since the committee's proposed overhaul
would transform his job dramatically. A report from a public-sector
task force and an independent consulting firm, which was announced
Monday, recommended that Schultz's duties be changed to those of a
corporate-style president/CEO who would serve 3-5 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to commit that kind of time,'' said the
69-year-old Schultz, who will stay on until a successor is named,
which would not be until after the USOC board formally approves the
restructuring next spring. ``We're probably looking at 5-6 months
minimum, but hopefully it will be quicker than that.'' Schultz then
would focus on fund-raising, which has lagged since the Salt Lake
payoff scandal broke last December.
</P>
<P>
   Though Schultz reportedly has been at odds with USOC president
Bill Hybl and some board members over his management style, Hybl
had denied earlier reports that Schultz might be pressured out.
``The decision was Dick's,'' Hybl said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summertime blues &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been a hellish summer for the Cubans. Eleven of their
athletes defected at the Pan American Games in Winnipeg, where high
jump hero Javier Sotomayor had his gold medal stripped for doping.
Then their boxers walked out of last week's world championships in
Houston after welterweight Juan Hernandez got robbed of a
gold-medal victory over a Russian. Though the international
federation reversed the decision and banned four of the five judges
for at least four years (and possibly life), the Cubans kept
walking with the six medals (only two gold) they'd already won.
Meanwhile, the Cuban boxing president and eternal coach Alcides
Sagarra, who charged that a ``refereeing mafia'' sabotaged the
Cubans, were both suspended. ``It bothers them that we have the
best team in the world,'' said Sagarra.
</P>
<P>
   Or do they? Fact is, the Cubans had been losing decisions all
week, two of them to the hated Yanquis (light flyweight Brian
Viloria and light heavy Michael Simms). And Alexis Rubalcaba, their
monstrous superheavy, was outboxed by an Italian and didn't even
make the medal round. Beneficiaries of the walkout were the
Romanians, who topped the medal table, and the Americans, who ended
up with a record four golds after last time not advancing anyone
past the second round.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change of direction &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next year's World Figure Skating Championships won't be going
down under after all. The International Skating Union summarily
yanked them from Brisbane last week because it couldn't cut a deal
with Australian TV to serve as world broadcast feeder. So the event
will be held in Nice (yes, the Riviera) at the end of March . . .
Scratch South Florida from the US bidders for the 2007 Pan American
Games, reportedly for lack of government and community support. So
the USOC will choose between San Antonio and Raleigh-Durham, N.C.,
in October. No American city has played host to the Pan Ams since
Indianapolis in 1987 . . . That Sept. 15 deadline for the NHL to
say go or no-go for the 2002 Winter Games, already extended from
last winter, has been pushed into mid-November. Though the
International Ice Hockey Federation wanted the issue settled before
its Florida congress next month, the NHL and its players haven't
agreed on anything yet. Though most of the owners favor playing in
the Games (or at least don't oppose it) and would be willing to
break up the season for a dozen days, the idea of finishing the
playoffs at the end of June leaves them cold . . . When the men's
four failed to even make the semifinals at last week's World Rowing
Championships in St. Catharines, Ontario, it threw US Rowing's
Olympic trials schedule for next year into a jumble. Sweep coach
Mike Teti had hoped to pick both his four and eight as late as
possible (i.e. August) before the Games. Now he might have to do it
as early as April, so the boat can have time to jell before the
special Olympic qualifying regatta at Lucerne in July. ``We put
ourselves in this position,'' shrugged Teti. ``Now we'll have to
fight our way out of it.'' In all, five US boats will have to
qualify because they did so poorly at St. Kit's _ the men's pair,
four, and quad and the women's single and double. The berths that
were earned at worlds don't necessarily go to the people who earned
them, but to their country. Next year's trials victors get them . .
. Jenny Thompson of Dover, N.H., won six gold medals (three
individual and three relay), at last week's Pan Pacific swim meet,
broke Mary T. Meagher's 18-year-old record in the 100 butterfly,
and didn't even get named female swimmer of the meet. South
Africa's Penny Heyns, who set world records in both breaststrokes,
did. Thompson, who has performed brilliantly since she failed to
qualify in an individual event for the last Olympics, could be the
Mark Spitz/Matt Biondi of the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from personal interviews, the US Olympic Committee,
sports federations, and wire services was used to prepare this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
