<SLUG> BC-POP-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRAMAX FINDS `LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL' IN ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in the delightful 1996 film, ``Big Night,'' a thriving
restaurateur explains to his struggling competitor his key to
success. Both are owners of Italian restaurants, both trying to
curry favor with the pedestrian palates of 1950s New Jersey. While
one wants to offer every delectable dish of his homeland, the other
knows such efforts are a waste during these bland, unadventurous
I-Like-Ike years. So he tells his rival that no matter how absurd
or lowbrow it might seem, you've got to give the people what they
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy works all day, he don't want to look at his plate and
ask, `What the (expletive) is this?' '' he says. ``He wants to look
at his plate, see a steak, and say, `I like steak!' ''
</P>
<P>
   That scene came to mind last week after Miramax released an
English-dubbed version of its Oscar-winning film, ``Life is
Beautiful.'' Released in its original Italian last year, ``Life is
Beautiful'' earned $57 million, and won three Academy Awards.
Roberto Benigni directed, wrote, and starred in the comic drama as
a father trying to shield his young son from the horrors of the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, only about 13 percent of American moviegoers saw the film,
and Miramax believes it's because the film was in Italian with
English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   See, a guy works all day, he don't want to go to movies he has
to read and ask, ``What the (expletive) is this?'' He wants to look
at the screen, hear English, and say, ``I like English!''
</P>
<P>
   We Americans are a funny lot, bless our little xenophobic
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer is the biggest sport on the planet, but baseball is
America's pasttime. The rest of the world operates on the metric
system, while we're still measuring our lives in inches, pounds,
and miles. We're suddenly loco for Latin pop, so long as it's more
pop than Latin, and sung in English; Iceland's Bjork just plain
frightens us, and we don't know what to make of Brit comedian Eddie
Izzard, who is funnier than Jim Carrey, Chris Tucker, and Adam
Sandler combined.
</P>
<P>
   And we've always had problems with foreign films _ from the
films of Italy's Federico Fellini and Germany's Rainer Werner
Fassbinder, to the more recent works of Spain's Pedro Aldomovar.
There's often an ``If I wanted to read, I would have stayed home''
mentality when it comes to foreign films. Many folks _ and you know
who you are _ grimace and groan the minute they realize a film has
subtitles, if they bother to go at all. And that's a shame because
some of the best films of recent years, including Brazil's
``Central Station,'' Germany's ``Run Lola Run,'' and Mexico's
``Like Water for Chocolate'' are all foreign product.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that dubbing has progressed since the unintentionally
campy words-first, lip-movement-later days of Japan's old
``Godzilla'' films, perhaps this is the best way to get American
filmmakers to forgo the meatballs and spaghetti for the seafood
risotto. As Martin Grove, CNN's movie analyst, said last week,
``Those who do like (subtitled films) are such a small percentage
of the audience that you can't make a lot of money from that. But
dubbed in English, the movie will play just like any other movie.''
Benigni supervised all the dubbing, and had his own part dubbed by
an American actor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can an argument be made that Miramax is just being greedy?
Oh sure _ ``Life is Beautiful'' is North America's highest-grossing
foreign-language film ever, but never let it be said that studio
honcho Harvey Weinstein would turn his back on potential dollar
signs. (By the way, someone please remind Harvey that a dubbed
version does not make the film again eligible for Oscar
consideration.) Yet, Miramax is simply doing what most other
countries have been doing for decades. Overseas, Leonardo DiCaprio
rescues Kate Winslet in Italian, Will Smith saves the world in
French, and Jar Jar Binks is just as annoying in Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   More important, though, despite what dispute some might have
with dubbing, it presents an opportunity for subtitle-shy Americans
to see films they might have otherwise avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only someone could dub Adam Sandler films for those of
us over 14 years old.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Rene Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5766 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUDIO-PERFORMER-BOS &LR;      08-31 1744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-PERFORMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARGOLYES STAYS AT THE TOP OF HER VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day two years ago, actress Miriam Margolyes returned home
from work and found a letter on her kitchen table that had been
delivered by limousine from Buckingham Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to think,'' said Margolyes from her London
home by telephone last week, sounding as if she seldom fails to
know what to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a four-page handwritten fan letter from Prince
Charles,'' she says. ``He wrote to thank me for the recording I
made for the Cover-to-Cover (audio book) of Dickens's `Oliver
Twist,' unabridged. The letter was a paean of praise, and he told
me he loved listening to tapes of books when he is driving, and how
he found my reading very affecting. I was very touched. The funny
thing is that in Britain I had recorded a book called `The Queen
and I,' a satirical book about the queen being forced to move into
a housing project, and in it I played every member of the royal
family, including him. I was rather nervous that he would be
insulted, but it doesn't seem to have affected his opinion of my
work. I was invited to his birthday party at Hampton Court Palace,
and it was a very proud moment for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolyes's recording of ``Oliver Twist'' was issued earlier
this year in America, and it recently won the ``Audie'' award for
the best performance of a book by a female reader. Indeed, her
reading is just about the most astonishing display of sustained
vocal virtuosity this listener has ever heard _ the only possible
comparison is to the female p'ansori singers of Korean epic. Her
energy is unflagging over an 18-hour span of 12 cassettes, and she
finds a different timbre, accent, and rhythm for every character,
changing instantaneously during the dialogue. Her reading crowds
the mind with personalities, drama, and powerful emotions.
Margolyes admits that during the eight days of recording sessions,
she had to stop and pull herself together as she read the climactic
scene between Nancy and Rose Maylie on the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in tears,'' she says, ``and I couldn't go on. When I'm
recording an audio book, I throw myself into it; I am not acting
less because it's for the ear alone. In fact, it's quite the
opposite _ everything has got to be in the voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolyes boasts one of the most remarkable voices in her
profession today. ``I like it when I can sometimes surprise people
with a different voice,'' she admits quietly, and she will do it
repeatedly even during a short phone conversation. She can say,
``You're not wrong about that, sweetheart,'' and sound just like
Humphrey Bogart.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' she says, ``the voice is a way into a character.
Other actors may start from the shoes or the walk. I love listening
to people talk, and I particularly like combination accents _ a
Jewish Scots accent, for example.'' As she speaks, Margolyes falls
into one. ``Maybe that is a voice from my grandparents, who were
Russian, Polish, and German. I grew up in Oxford, in an academic
environment; my father was a doctor. But nothing was more valuable
to me in my work than listening to the voices of European Jews and
rejoicing in that heritage. I've just been to a Jewish genealogical
conference in New York, which was very thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Likes American roles &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Margolyes started off in the theater nearly 40 years ago, but
her onstage appearances are infrequent these days because she has
become so active in movies and television. ``In the theater they
tend to think I should play English roles, but I like doing
American stuff. I live in Santa Monica now, and most of the time I
play Americans in the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   American audiences probably know Margolyes best for her
supporting roles in Baz Luhrmann's ``Romeo and Juliet'' with
Leonardo DiCaprio and in the film of Edith Wharton's ``The Age of
Innocence.'' In Britain, she won an award for best supporting
actress for her performance in ``Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Her film roles certainly have been diverse. In addition to her
work in highbrow movies like ``Little Dorrit,'' ``Immortal
Beloved,'' and ``Orpheus Descending,'' she also appeared in ``Cold
Comfort Farm,'' ``Ed and His Dead Mother,'' and ``James and the
Giant Peach.'' One of her many voices is featured on the soundtrack
of ``Babe,'' and another appears as the matchmaker on the
soundtrack to Disney's ``Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, Margolyes also starred in her own short-lived
television sitcom, ``Frannie's Turn.'' ``I played a Staten Island
housewife trying to educate her husband into being a new man. I had
a very good time, not least because I made rather a lot of money in
a very short time!'' In England, Margolyes is a beloved household
figure because of her presence on a long-running series of British
Telecom television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Her newest film, just finished, is an Arnold Schwarzenegger epic
that will open at Thanksgiving. ``I am one of the baddies, and I
get to pick him up and hurl him against the wall. I must say he was
very sportsmanlike about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolyes says she has had no formal training in acting. ``It's
a gift, which I enjoy. At the beginning, I had a very traditional
career. It all started when I was a student back in the '60s at
Cambridge (University). I did a lot of comedies back then, and I
was in a group called the Footlights with people like John Cleese.
Then I went into repertory theater, and I played lots of different
things, and took on a new part every two weeks. Since I went into
television and the movies, I don't do theater as much as I would
like, although I enjoyed doing `The Killing of Sister George'
recently and Mrs. Hardcastle in a revival of `She Stoops to
Conquer.' I was also in the original production of `Cloud 9.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in Williamstown (Mass.) for two summers, in Moliere's
`The Learned Ladies' with Kate Burton, and I had the most fun in
the world, and I came back to do my one-woman show, `Charles
Dickens' Women.' I would love to return to Williamstown because the
spirit is so wonderful there _ it's summer camp for actors.
Tomorrow I'm off to the Theater Royal in York, where I'm going to
play Madame Ranevskaya in `The Cherry Orchard.' I find the prospect
very frightening, because I've never played Chekhov before,
although I've wanted to all my life. Gradually I got too old for
most of his parts. But you're never too old for Ranevskaya!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preserving the classics &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Margolyes hasn't recorded many audio books, but she appears on a
recording of Oscar Wilde's ``Lady Windermere's Fan'' and she reads
``A Christmas Carol'' by Dickens for Cover-to-Cover. ``I keep
hoping I'll be asked to do more because I love it so much. I
particularly love Edith Wharton; I did a reading from `Summer' at
the Mount in Lenox a week ago in preparation for the play and the
opera, and to support the restoration fund for her old home. I know
there's already a recording of `The Age of Innocence,' but it was
not recorded by me _ which was a grave oversight on someone's part.
I don't even really care about the money, I love doing it so much _
this is a way the classics can still be within reach of so many
people. So much crap gets recorded, the good stuff should be
recorded, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of audio books, for Margolyes, is the appeal of
storytelling. ``I strongly believe,'' she says, ``there is a need
in all of us to have a story told, a primal need. When you hear the
words `Once upon a time,' your whole being thrills to the
expectation. People often aren't interested in the idea of audio
books, until they hear one, and then they really love it. Nobody is
telling stories anymore, and this basic human need is something
that's been forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolyes says that she doesn't make any special adjustments
when she performs for the microphone. ``You are creating a world
and the people in it. You have to have a flexible voice and an
imagination _ when I sit down to record, I'm doing all the
movements and facial expressions I would do if I were acting
standing up. I don't make any concessions to the microphone. I put
my whole heart and soul and body _ which is rather large _ into it,
and I think you have to. The mike is really someone's ear, and what
you're doing is speaking directly to someone, just one person.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dickens a favorite &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dickens has been a particular favorite of Margolyes's since
childhood. `` `Oliver Twist' was the first novel by Dickens that I
read. It creates a world into which you are pushed, and it envelops
you _ a process I find delightful. You can't rehearse a reading
that lasts that long. You just read the book, and if you make a
mistake, you go over it again. But you do have to have in your head
a very clear picture of the characters, and Dickens is a godsend to
a reader, because he writes very sharply defined characters. It
isn't difficult to do the characters. What is hard is the strong
energy line you have to have to get through the long sentences. You
need a good breath and you need to know how to control it. The
voice is made by the breath; breath is the material from which the
voice is made.''
</P>
<P>
   Margolyes says her one-woman show tells the story of Dickens's
life and of the women in it, using the women he portrayed in his
books. ``Most of them were based on actual people,'' she says. ``I
picked 11 episodes, and between the scenes, I talk directly to the
audience. In the second half, I concentrate on the desperately sad
story of the breakup of his marriage. When a one-person show works,
it's thrilling. But doing one is a very dangerous exercise. The
audience is sequestered with just one person, and they get very
scared _ you have to reassure them that it's going to be all right.
This one-woman show is very precious to me because Dickens is, and
because it offers one of my relatively rare opportunities to be
onstage again. Yes, of course, I would love to perform the piece in
Boston, but the problem is that doing theater doesn't pay very
much, and the repertory theaters want you to commit a year in
advance. I can't afford to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``An actress's greatest asset,'' Margolyes adds, pausing lightly
and just long enough to make the exact effect she intends, ``is her
availability.'' In her voice, over the telephone, you can clearly
hear the twinkle in her eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
