<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DIANA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHER SAYS DIANA'S MENTAL STATE WAS IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DIANA IN SEARCH OF HERSELF 
Portrait of a Troubled Princess 
By Sally Bedell Smith 
Times Books, 451 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One irony attending the car crash that killed Diana, princess of
Wales, at age 36 two years ago is that the driver, Henri Paul, had
traces of Prozac in his system, an antidepressant that may have
impaired his judgment. Diana, who was drug-free that night,
probably should have been on Prozac; had she been on it, she might
never have been dating a spoiled, paranoid lunkhead like Dodi
Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   A reach? Not if one is to believe biographer Sally Bedell Smith,
who has previously chronicled the lives of CBS founder William S.
Paley and diplomat-courtesan Pamela Churchill Harriman. This time
Smith sets out to explore what she calls ``the interplay of Diana's
character and temperament,'' in a book that is at once morbidly
fascinating and profoundly sad.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing upon thick files of newspaper clippings and nearly 150
interviews with Diana's intimates _ including members of Britain's
tabloid press corps, whom the princess alternately seduced and
abandoned, depending on her agenda _ Smith marshals evidence to
suggest that Diana suffered from a serious, and largely untreated,
mental illness. It was an illness, suggests Smith, that affected
everything from Diana's choice in men (discreet, subservient,
career-enhancing) to her choice in therapists (new age types who
mostly told her what she wanted to hear), imprisoning her in a kind
of lethal, albeit gilded, cage.
</P>
<P>
   The illness was borderline personality disorder, so named
because its symptoms fall between neurosis (milder) and psychosis
(more severe). Among its common symptoms are chronic depression,
low self-esteem, violent mood swings, emotional dependency, fear of
abandonment, eating disorders, and self-mutilation. One underlying
cause of the disorder is thought to be the early and traumatic loss
of a parent.
</P>
<P>
   As documented by Smith, Diana, whose parents nastily divorced
when she was 6, and whom even close friends seldom regarded as an
intellectual overachiever, suffered from all these ills long before
her failed marriage to Prince Charles in 1980. An older sister
waged war with anorexia. Diana's mother all but disappeared from
Diana's life after the divorce. Other close relatives battled
depression and suicidal tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Diana, meanwhile, went from obscurity to celebrity virtually
overnight and was soon crowned the world's most glamorous woman.
It's hard to conceive of a more stress-inducing situation for a
woman in her teens, much less one about to marry the world's most
eligible (and emotionally clueless) bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   Juxtapose that diagnosis with much of what was said about the
princess before and after her death. To the British press she was
``Divine Di'' or ``Disaffected Di,'' not ``Dysfunctional Di.'' Her
struggles with bulimia and depression were duly noted, even
publicly discussed by Diana herself after her separation from
Charles. So were her battles with the royal family over who
controlled her life.
</P>
<P>
   Diana's commitment to various causes _ nearly 120 at one point _
was also praised by her eulogists, yet the causes themselves were
seldom selected for purely altruistic reasons, notes Smith. Many
were later discarded with brutal impersonality. Friends and lovers
got the same treatment: hour upon hour of teary phone calls
followed by icy silences and crossed-out invitations. Her one great
consistency may have been as a mother, and for that the world holds
out hope for her two sons. But the dominating image is of Diana the
cunning eavesdropper, the jealous envelope-steamer, the habitual
liar and media manipulator who served as her own worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Charles, for his part, was cast in one of two roles: as an
uncaring, unfaithful twit, or as a hapless victim of his wife's
obsession with celebrity. Neither was close to the complete truth,
according to Smith, who did not interview Charles for this book but
who did gain access to his private correspondence, much of it
concerning Diana. What seems true is that, notwithstanding
Charles's efforts to get his wife the proper psychiatric care, the
royal family in general regards mental illness about as seriously
as it does a nagging head cold. Diana was indulged _ or ostracized
_ when she should have been treated not as a problem but as a
patient. Charles may come across sympathetically in Smith's
narrative, but there are few heroes to be found here.
</P>
<P>
   In another epoch, Diana's troubled psyche might have landed her
in exile. Or worse, the Tower of London. We live in more
enlightened times, fortunately. Reading Smith's biography, however,
one wonders how far we've really come. Given the odds against her,
Princess Diana's life seems less a candle in the wind than an
accident waiting to happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
