<SLUG> BC-CHILD-COOKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TABLES ARE TURNED AT FAMILY MEALTIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The mornings when her mother is getting ready for her
job as an assistant teacher in a preschool, 11-year-old Salena
Abu-Eid prepares breakfast for herself and her 6-year-old brother,
Samir. She'll make eggs and toast and orange juice and, sometimes,
bacon, all of which, she says, is ``really fun'' because it's
``doing someone a favor and I enjoy making my mom happy and proud
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine DeFlorio, 45, a registered nurse, takes a break from
cooking every Tuesday, when her husband, a glass blower, works
late. Her daughter and step-daughter, Emily Kenfield and Barbara
DeFlorio, both 12, microwave supper for themselves and their
6-year-old brother, William. ``The other nights we have a family
night,'' says DeFlorio. ``That particular night we watch `Nova.' We
all make our own way.''
</P>
<P>
   This is mealtime '99, and kids are cooking _ or, at least,
heating and eating. Call it the convergence of time crunch and
convenience. In an era of microwave magic, dual-earner homes, and
single-parent families, surveys show an increasing number of
children and teenagers fixing meals not only for themselves but
also for their families. People spend less time these days eating
together, and, when they do, mom _ or dad _ has often come home at
the last minute so more and more young people are pitching in.
</P>
<P>
   Among children ages 9 to 17, almost half regularly prepare meals
for themselves, up from 15 percent in 1988, according to the
Connecticut-based Yankelovich Partners. More than a quarter
regularly prepare meals for their families, up from 8 percent in
1988. The Illinois-based Teenage Research Unlimited finds that
two-thirds of teens ages 12-19 spent time fixing one or more meals
in the week surveyed, up from half in 1991. For almost half in this
year's poll, the meal prepared was dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a consistently growing phenomenon since we started doing
this research in 1988,'' says Yankelovich managing partner J.
Walker Smith. ``Family structures are increasingly diverse,
requiring kids to take more responsibility. The shortage of time
people feel in their lives requires them to look around for help.
All of that is facilitated by the fact that food manufacturers have
made food ever easier to prepare. The other thing to be said is
that kids nowadays feel themselves to be more independent operators
than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Families may be spending half of their food dollar in
restaurants or on take-out, says Linda Cullen, vice president of
consumer knowledge at the Minneapolis-based Pillsbury Co., but
they're still making 95 percent of their meals at home, which
leaves plenty of time for kids in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we find is kids are doing this `quick fuel' stuff, things
that are ready to eat,'' Cullen says. ``They're participating in
meal preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jude Jean Baptiste, 11, finds quick fuel in the macaroni and
cheese or pancakes he likes to make himself when he's hungry.
Marianne Maguire, 13, helps out the nights her mother, Joanne, an
accountant, works in a bank's 24-hour international unit. If her
mom leaves a meatloaf for the family baking in the oven, Marianne
fixes mashed potatoes from a box and vegetables from a can. Jeremy
Marcus, 17, is on his own for dinner once or twice a week, so he
reheats leftovers or microwaves a frozen pizza or makes macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Marcus's mother, Barbara, co-owner of Parents in a
Pinch, tried to enlist more help in the kitchen from her son and
her husband. They each cooked dinner two nights a week and she took
the other three nights. The experiment fizzled, however, after a
few months of pasta and sauce from a jar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded pretty fair so I went along with it,'' Jeremy says.
``I didn't love it. I'm very busy at night. Homework and stuff. I
didn't want to spend the time, and I'd much rather eat my mother's
cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the culinary capabilities of adults varies, so does the
kitchen prowess of children and teens. For Lynn Fredericks, author
of the newly published ``Cooking Time is Family Time,'' the kitchen
is a perfect place for multi-tasking with a purpose: Get help
preparing meals, stay in touch with your children, and build a
sense of family teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meal today should not be the mother or the father being
the slave,'' she says. ``I love the idea that kids prep for the
meal _ chop the vegetables or get out the ingredients _ and then
when mom or dad comes home they've made it easier. They can
assemble the meal more quickly and together. Kids love being part
of the process. They feel this great sense of responsibility and
accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Polimer, 16, has been helping his mother, Jane, in the
kitchen ever since he was a young boy, cutting vegetables beside
her, learning how to curl his fingers the way he saw TV chefs chop.
Now he cooks three or four times a week, often from his mother's
recipes that he's memorized. When Jane Polimer is not home, it's
Ben who cooks dinner for himself and his dad.
</P>
<P>
   He grills himself a hot dog for lunch or barbecues pork chops
rubbed with spices for his family, or makes his signature
three-bean chili with sauteed onion and garlic, ground beef and soy
burger, chili powder and cumin, and chopped tomatoes from a can.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can actually see what goes in and see the final product
and say I made it,'' Ben says. ``Instead of just throwing something
in the microwave you can actually make something that looks and
tastes pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Martell, 11, has been watching her grandmother cook for
as long as she can remember. She rolls meatballs with ``Nana'' and
helps bake. She looks through cookbooks and watches cooking shows
on television and dreams of becoming a chef. Often, before her
mother, Kathleen, comes home from her job as a municipal clerk,
Ashley makes a salad. She chops tomatoes and cucumbers and tosses
them with the pre-cut, pre-washed lettuce her mom buys to make the
task easier for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes home from a hard day at work,'' Ashley says, ``and I
just feel bad sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she helps her mother prepare the rest of dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a single parent, so she's a big help,'' says Kathleen
Martell, 39. ``It's a time where it's teaching her responsibility
for later life. And it's quality time, you know. Just that we're
together like that, mother and daughter. We can talk about the day
while we're doing this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people are also finding their way around the food aisles.
Teen Research finds 52 percent of teens help with the family
grocery shopping, up from 39 percent in 1995. Yankelovich finds 22
percent of youths ages 9-17 shop for groceries, up from 8 percent
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making brand decisions for products that aren't
necessarily teen specific,'' says Teen Research vice president
Michael Wood. ``Mom makes a list. She writes down mayonnaise. She
doesn't write Hellman's. Do they go with what Mom usually buys? Do
they go with what they see in the store? What they see in their
friends' homes?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the main trip, teens are not doing that,''
says Pillsbury's Cullen. ``They're helping with a lot of fill-ins.
They are becoming more involved.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marianne Maguire, the 13-year-old, accompanies her mother
to the supermarket, she'll hit one aisle and her mom another.
``Sometimes,'' says Marianne, ``I can get stuff that I want. Stuff
she wouldn't usually buy, like Doritos.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Manon, 16, has taken over much of her family's grocery
shopping. The reason? She's been a vegan for almost a year and her
mother tired of reading labels to make sure food had no meat, egg,
or dairy ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   And once every week or two, Miriam cooks dinner, often a
stir-fry of tofu and vegetables, for her mother and, if she's home
from college, her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like cooking a lot,'' Miriam says. ``It's fun to
experiment with different things. It's satisfying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
