<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-WYOMNING-BOS &LR;      08-31 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WYOMNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTAMED WYOMING PACKS KAYAKING THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGER TETON NATIONAL FOREST, Wyo. _ Swollen by a late-spring
thaw, the Upper New Fork River roared past us as my companions
prepared to launch their kayaks on what they said would be the
first descent ever of the cascading waterway.
</P>
<P>
   They rated the run a Class 6, as challenging as they come, and
it was easy to see why. Water crashed through the narrow gaps in
the steep, rocky gorge with an awesome ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   When we came on a 12-foot waterfall 5 miles from the trail head,
it appeared to this nonkayaker virtually to rule out the attempt.
But a particularly tricky patch closer to the start of the descent,
farther up river, presented an even bigger challenge, a member of
the group told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's objectively more dangerous,'' said photographer Greg Von
Doersten. ``It's an undercut rock. They call it the squeeze box.
There's a snag (a stuck log) in front of it that makes it more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Four days in the untamed state of Wyoming gave this greenhorn a
pack of thrills. My encounter with extreme kayaking _ strictly as a
witness, to be sure _ was only the most dramatic of them. Besides
high adventure, I enjoyed beautiful scenery, a glimpse into the
history of the westward expansion, and a visit to an old-fashioned
cattle ranch.
</P>
<P>
   From Rock Springs, in the southwest corner of the state, I drove
with my hosts into the desert late one fine summer day. Our
directions sounded too cute to be useful: Make a right at the
Continental Divide and turn left on the Oregon Trail.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what we did. We went right at a sign marking
the imaginary line separating the eastern and western slopes of the
Rocky Mountains. Following a dirt road, with the snow-capped Wind
River Range ahead, we then made a left at a marker for the Oregon
Trail. The pioneers, pointing toward 7,550-foot South Pass over the
Rockies a few miles west, had trudged through a century and a half
before on their way west.
</P>
<P>
   With the sun sinking in the western sky, we arrived at a
one-room cabin where Mary Hay, a rare woman in a mostly male field,
has her ranch. Her 1,000 head of cows and calves graze freely on
400 square miles of public and private land during the summer. In
the fall, she and a few hired hands mount their horses to drive the
herd 50 miles south to a winter feeding station.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 percent of the nation's beef is still raised on public
land, according to Hay, and pressure is growing to end the practice
because of concerns about overgrazing. If cattle drives fade away,
so too will a big part of the romance of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Hay's cabin, which recently got telephone service but
still lacks electricity, the scene was idyllic. The Sweetwater
River flowed lazily by, snow-covered mountains loomed on the
horizon, and a herd of sheep, apparently escaped from another
ranch, grazed nearby. Two sage chickens, similar to pheasants, took
flight with a swoosh. As we drove back to Rock Springs after
dinner, with darkness creeping in, an antelope with twin fawns
close behind darted away off the edge of the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming markets itself as ``like no place on earth,'' and the
slogan seems apt. Its population of 480,000, the nation's smallest,
occupies a vast area. Sweetwater County, the home of Rock Springs,
is larger than all of Massachusetts. Driving across the bottom of
Wyoming on Interstate 80 takes you through high desert that is
eerily desolate and beautiful, if less dramatic than the Colorado
mountain resorts like Breckenridge and Steamboat Springs I had
passed through on my way.
</P>
<P>
   One day on a less traveled, two-lane road, with hardly a car in
view as I drove down a long hill, the horizon seemed to dip in
front of me. It seemed that if the landscape were to tilt just a
bit further I might slide off the edge of the earth. I could almost
imagine I were the last creature alive.
</P>
<P>
   I did not get as far north as Jackson Hole and Yellowstone
National Park. Some in Wyoming would say that was just as well,
since those well-known destinations, with their dramatic and
compelling attractions, draw much heavier crowds. The glitzy scene
in Jackson Hole, with its ever higher real estate prices, is not
the image of their solitary state most prized by Wyoming residents.
</P>
<P>
   My generous hosts in Rock Springs, John and Katharine Collins,
made possible my visit to Mary Hay's ranch and enabled me to
witness the hair-raising white-water river run undertaken by their
son Dave and his buddies, all professional kayakers. That descent
was successful, by the way, even if one kayaker had to right his
boat quickly after rolling over in churning waters, and Dave's
kayak crashed into a rock and he sprained an ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Personal contacts are not needed to enjoy the sky and the
mountains, or the national parks and wilderness areas. Approaching
the Wind River Range from the south takes you through Pinedale,
population 1,181, where there are motels and outfitters to serve
people heading into the mountains. Cabins, campgrounds, and dude
ranches are available closer in.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Colorado, with 56 peaks over 14,000 feet, Wyoming is
altitudinally challenged. Its highest mountain, 13,804-foot Gannett
Peak, can't match Colorado for elevation.
</P>
<P>
   But Gannett, 30 miles north of Pinedale in the Bridger Teton
National Forest, puts Wyoming in the thick of things when it comes
to bragging rights. Colorado's tallest, 14,433-foot Mount Elbert,
can be scaled with a relatively undemanding six-hour hike. To
conquer Gannett, Dave Collins told me, you start by backpacking
through 15 miles of wilderness. After camping, you still have to
climb 6,000 vertical feet, mostly over glacier, the next day.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer my adventures light. Like the day I hiked around the
lower Green River Lake. Beautiful mountain views alternated with
shimmering lake vistas. But even this tame outing carried a hint of
danger. A sign said I was entering a grizzly bear area and
``special rules apply.'' Had the need arisen, I was ready with my
own, maybe not-so-special rule: Run like hell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
