<HEADLINE>
BROKER `DEALS' NOT ALWAYS DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet may not always be the place to go for good deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discount buyer, beware'' _ that's the rousing cry from the
August issue of Consumer Reports Travel Letter on finding a great
buy on a hotel room on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel brokers, the increasingly popular discount outlets for
finding lodging, aren't consistently producing the bargains on the
Internet they're advertising or promoting, said Consumer Reports.
In a survey of room rates, the newsletter called brokers and hotels
directly to obtain more than 100 room quotes. They discovered that
nearly one out of three ``discount'' quotes were as much as 40
percent higher than the price quoted from the hotel's reservation
office.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers that fared well included 1-800-USA-Hotels, which
matched, exceeded, or improved on hotel rates. Central Reservation
Service offered savings or matched a hotel's quotes, while Quikbook
was the only one of the five surveyed that yielded savings in
virtually every case.
</P>
<P>
   The travel letter noted that unwary consumers could also get hit
with cancellation and booking fees, and should know that hotels
dictate the rates. They are at liberty to swiftly lower rates for
certain nights, and often make these changes without notification
to brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter advises travelers to avoid brokers that charge
fees, to check out a hotel's accommodations and offerings before
booking, ask about local taxes and surcharges, double-check
availability with a hotel to be sure a broker's ``nothing
available'' words are legitimate, find out if you need to pay in
advance or at checkout, and ask about cancellation fees.
</P>
<P>
   Every month Consumer Reports Travel Letter is filled with
information, from finding good deals to surveys such as the hotel
report. Subscriptions are $39 for one year; single copies of back
issues are $5. To subscribe, call 800-234-1970.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Two for one
</P>
<P>
   British Airways is offering two free economy class tickets to
just about anywhere in the world with the purchase of a round-trip
Club World business-class ticket. The offer is for new members of
Executive Club USA (British Airways' frequent-flyer program) in
exchange for sharing their opinions of the Club World experience. A
Club World ticket must be purchased between now and Dec. 15, and
upon completion of the survey, travelers will receive the
economy-class tickets good for travel between Jan. 15 and Dec. 15,
2000. Reward travel includes domestic US flights on British
Airways' partner carriers. For more information, call 888-698-4290.
</P>
<P>
   go
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
New World Festival
</P>
<P>
   The New World Festival, held for the last seven years in
Randolph, Vt., on Labor Day, celebrates village life as much as it
does the spirited Celtic and French-American music and dance that
are the musical focus. Seven years ago, Randolph was hit with three
fires in its downtown. The festival became part of a remarkable
rebirth for the downtown, which is listed on the National Register
of Historic Sites. There will be music, food and drink, crafts, and
a lot more. The festival runs from noon to 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   The seventh annual Boston Antique &AMP; Classic Boat Festival will
be held Sept. 4-5 at the Boston Waterboat Marina at Long Wharf. The
boats range from classic sailboats to powerboats and hand-powered
craft, dating from the 1890s to the 1930s. A parade of boats will
be held Sept. 5 beginning at 2:15 p.m. For information, call
617-422-1703.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some ballroom dance lessons? Then head for Purity
Spring Resort in New Hampshire for its dance lesson weekends on
Sept. 10-12 and Oct. 22-24. For information on this and other Mount
Washington Valley activities, call 877-948-6867.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire International Tattoo and Highland Games is
coming to Loon Mountain Sept. 16-19. The third annual tattoo _ with
lots of heart-pounding exhilaration _ will be held Sept. 16 and 17
with performances beginning at 8 p.m. Featured this year will be a
pipe and drum band from Scotland, along with bands from Canada and
the United States. The Highland Games _ which have become the
largest Scottish event in the Northeast, featuring music, dance,
food, and athletics _ will be held Sept. 17-19. For information on
tickets for the games, tattoo, or lodging (last year all area
accommodations were sold out for the event) call 800-358-7268 or
visit www.nhscot.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Stay cool
</P>
<P>
   The first exhibition to explore the transformative power of air
conditioning, ``Stay Cool! Air Conditioning in America,'' is on
view through Jan. 2 at the National Building Museum in Washington.
Through photos, artifacts, television commercials, and interactive
displays, the exhibit will explore the history of ``air
conditioning,'' beginning with pioneering experiments in the late
1800s. Manufacturers at the turn of the century were learning that
by filtering air and stabilizing temperature, mechanical systems
improved the environment for products . . . and people.
</P>
</TEXT>
