<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRACK-STERILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDICTS GIVE UP FERTILITY FOR $200 EACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Signaling an expansion into New England, three New Hampshire
women have participated in a controversial California-based
cash-for-sterlization program for drug-addicted women which has
already set up shop in California and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Children Requiring a Caring Kommunity, also known as CRACK,
attempts to curb the births of impaired or damaged babies by
offering female addicts $200 cash if they are willing to have a
tubal ligation, or submit to long-term contraceptives such as
Norplant.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Harris, the founder of CRACK, said her nonprofit program
is the key to ending the cycle of drug-addicted women bearing
damaged children they are not able to care for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe birth control is a solution to the problem of
drug-addicted babies,'' said Harris. The controversy over her
method, she said, misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to make it an issue about women'' while ignoring
the thousands of children born with emotional and physical problems
stemming from their mother's drug use, Harris said. The battle over
reproductive rights, she added, ``has already been fought at the
cost of billions of dollars. Nobody seems to be doing anything
about the children.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics contend CRACK is a thinly veiled way of coercing
women they see as unfit to give up their personal right to bear
children. And they note that some of her funding has come from
high-profile social conservatives, including radio psychiatrist Dr.
Laura Schlessinger.
</P>
<P>
   George Annas, chairman of health law at Boston University School
of Public Health, said the program echoes a dark period in American
history when the government passed laws to sterilize mentally ill
patients, sometimes forcibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state of California was doing this then people would be
beside themselves,'' Annas said. ``But because a private nonprofit
organization is doing this, then it doesn't seem quite as scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see Harris' large number of supporters as a reflection of
the nation's desperate effort to punish or at least stem, by
whatever means available, the number of pregnant women who use
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, the medical community estimates that 1 percent of the
children born in the country are exposed to cocaine. At least 21
states have used specific court cases to try and punish women for
using drugs while pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly every case, those efforts have failed, but South
Carolina is a notable exception. In 1997, the state's Supreme Court
ruled that a woman who uses drugs while pregnant is guilty of child
abuse under state law.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to starting CRACK, Harris tried, but failed, to get the
California Legislature to pass a law that would send a woman to
prison for bearing a cocaine or drug-addicted child.
</P>
<P>
   A Stanton, Calif., resident, Harris' crusade began after she
adopted four children from the same crack-addicted mother a decade
ago. She was touched by the chance to nurture the children who had
already been through so much but was angered that the mother was
allowed to continue having children.
</P>
<P>
   After losing a yearlong battle that would make it illegal to
give birth to a drug-addicted baby, she started a program that paid
women to choose birth control instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money has always enticed people to do things,'' said Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, women call in, then make an appointment to
have the birth control or sterilization procedure. For most women,
the procedure is covered by either health insurance or Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   CRACK participants must present a doctor's letter confirming
they've had the procedure before they can receive the cash.
Sterilization and long-term birth control are the only options for
participating women; Harris said CRACK won't pay for birth-control
pills.
</P>
<P>
   Since the program begin nearly two years ago in Anaheim, Calif.,
Harris said, 61 women have participated. Of that number, 41 opted
for tubal ligation. Those women in the program, she added, have had
a total of 400 pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who is white, has been criticized for setting up large,
eye-popping billboards advertising the program in minority
neighborhoods in St. Paul, Chicago and Florida. She has said that
the publicity makes the donations go up _ but so does the criticism
from women's rights groups and social libertarians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have to say we have some concerns about it,'' said Pam
Nourse, spokeswoman for the Planned Parenthood League of
Massachusetts. ``We certainly stand for a woman's right to chose
her own course of reproductive future but when offering a financial
inducement it crosses that line of being a little coercive, and
that is something that we do have many concerns about.''
</P>
<P>
   Annas said critics say the campaign raises an ethical conflict:
women are being enticed by a short-term reward and blinded by the
longer-term effects of sterilization or even Norplants which can be
surgically removed.
</P>
<P>
   But since her program began, Harris said, she has received
hundreds of calls and e-mails from people interested in starting
their own local programs, such as a group of nurses from Rhode
Island, or drug-addicted women who want to participate.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lakes Region of New Hampshire, a mother of four joined
the program and was paid $200 for a tubal ligation, Harris said.
But she also got an extra $50 for referring other women to the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the referral fee as a form of advertisement since drug
addicts know other drug addicts,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Though she has already opened a chapter in Chicago and plans to
open one in Seattle and Florida, Harris said she has no immediate
plans to further expand the campaign into Massachusetts and the
rest of New England _ unless enough people request it.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no shortage of callers or donors, she said. The
campaign has received $150,000, from liberals as well as
conservatives, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Brianne Fitzgerald, a Boston substance abuse treatment nurse,
said that Harris' campaign has problems, but should be examined
with an open mind.
</P>
<P>
   Communities as well as the health and criminal justice systems
should come together and investigate whether alternative measures
such as CRACK can replace foster care and social service programs,
which can't seem to curb the rising problem of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crack is a very very bad drug,'' said Fitzgerald. ``Women
addicted to crack are almost incapable of taking care of anything
but the need to smoke crack.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she questions if dangling $200 before an addicted woman
induces a mother rather than allows her to chose her own fate.
``There are no easy answers,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
