<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5785 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TROUBLED-INN-BOS &LR;      08-31 1542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROUBLED-INN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOURMANDS OUT IN THE COLD AS INN OWNERS, CHEF SPAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD CHATHAM, N.Y. _ Among the hundreds of upscale inns in the
hills of Western Massachusetts and New York, the Old Chatham
Sheepherding Company Inn glimmered.
</P>
<P>
   There was harmony at the four-year-old inn, guests like to say,
and there was success, including raves about the inn's ambiance.
Chef Melissa Kelly, who was named best chef in the Northeast last
year by the prestigious James Beard Foundation, appeared in
magazines from Food &AMP; Wine to Conde Nast Traveler. Martha Stewart
came to learn how to make sheep cheese, and Europeans began booking
rooms when the inn gained membership in the luxury hotel
association Relais &AMP; Chateaux.
</P>
<P>
   For wealthy New Yorkers and Bostonians for whom even a
$550-per-night suite rate mattered less than the satisfaction of
having a meal that could be considered the finest in the country,
the Old Chatham Sheepherding Company Inn was a treat to reserve
months in advance, a name to drop at important dinner parties, and
a secret to share with trusted friends and business colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a week ago, at the height of the summer season, the
inn closed.
</P>
<P>
   Owners Tom and Nancy Clark issued a brief press release
apologizing to staff and guests, some of whom had waited four
months for a dinner reservation. While the farm will continue
making cheese and yogurt to sell to upscale groceries, the future
of the 14-room inn is unknown. Tables are set in the dining room,
cobalt-blue goblets glistening on white table clothes. Neutrogena
soaps rest in claw-footed bathtubs, awaiting guests who may never
check in.
</P>
<P>
   A simmering battle for control of the kitchen between the Clarks
and the chef and her fiance, pastry chef Price Kushner, apparently
reached crisis in a dispute over a cook's resignation last week.
Kelly had given notice in July that she and Kushner would be
leaving in mid-September to open their own restaurant. Both parties
give different accounts of whether Kelly quit or the restaurant was
closed by the Clarks. Regardless, Kelly and Kushner's departure was
hastened.
</P>
<P>
   Among stunned residents of Old Chatham, where the inn's
international reputation was a source of local pride, the
relationship between the two couples immediately became a source of
gossip and confusion. In the growing world of luxury-dining
enthusiasts, there were only questions: Will the Clarks ever be
able to reclaim their inn's reputation? Will Kelly and Kushner's
new restaurant in Maine supplant the Old Chatham Inn as a
destination?
</P>
<P>
   Some would-be gourmands are disappointed, others are angry, and
all are perplexed. Owning and managing a country inn is everyman's
dream, many locals and visitors say. The Clarks had no money
worries. The couple had just finished two new guest rooms last
spring. People magazine had a feature planned.
</P>
<P>
   So why couldn't the Clarks and Kelly put aside their differences
for the larger purpose of creating the finest food and inn in the
region?
</P>
<P>
   Neither couple would speak about the final dispute that ruptured
their relationship, but both used mournful tones when speaking of
the inn.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Clark said she ``put her heart and soul into'' making the
OldChatham Inn the finest in the country and was ``devasated.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Kelly declared: ``It was a magical time, and we had a
lot of good ingredients. But it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   But to those who are most familiar with the world of
ultra-expensive bed-and-breakfasts, a market that has grown almost
at the pace of the stock market, the demise of the Chatham is less
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason may lie in the increasingly stressful job of
managing and maintaining a top luxury inn, say analysts and those
in the industry. Sophisticated guests expect top-notch service,
decor and food like never before. If an attraction like Kelly is
missing from a stellar inn, many say there is only one way to go:
down. Close when your reputation is still intact, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are only as good as the last meal you served or the last
guest that stayed; your reputation is on the line every night,''
said Laurence Bongiorno, owner of the White Barn Inn in
Kennebunkport, one of only 40 Relais &AMP; Chateaux members in the
United States. ``People come to a luxury inn, and they expect to be
pampered. It's the small details that get noticed. It takes great
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The Old Chatham Inn's success may also have been tied too
closely to Kelly. Kelly's meals became the inn's signature, some
industry analysts say. When she left, the inn was bound to lose a
piece of prestige, those analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems they built the concept around an individual,'' said
Thomas Wright, vice president of culinary education and former dean
of the school of culinary arts at Johnson &AMP; Wales University in
Rhode Island. ``But there are ways to ensure your ability to
outlive a chef.''
</P>
<P>
   It was never Tom and Nancy Clark's plan to open an inn. After
making a fortune with his Greenwich, Conn., investment firm, Tom
Clark wanted to start a sheep farm, a throwback to his childhood
when he took care of a few sheep on his grandfather's farm near
Poughkeepsie, N.Y. The couple bought the farm of John S. Williams,
a well-known Shaker collector, and began sheepherding operations,
now the largest sheep dairy farm in the country, with some 1,000
animals.
</P>
<P>
   A trustee at Cornell University, Tom Clark commissioned students
there to conduct a study of whether a luxury inn would be viable in
Old Chatham, a rural town some 15 miles from the Massachusetts
border filled with second homeowners from New York. The answer was
yes.
</P>
<P>
   An interior decorator, Nancy Clark scoured upstate New York
antique shops for furnishings. Rooms were decorated with
watercolors she had painted and whimsical touches like a red
clawfoot bathtub. Meanwhile, the Clarks found Kelly, who had
graduated at the top of her class from the Culinary Institute of
America and worked with some of the best-known chefs in the
Northeast. The farm prospered; 94 staff members took care of the
farm and 14 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was perfect,'' exulted Gayle Angsto of Newton, who stayed
at the inn last year and who was visiting friends in the area last
week. ``No matter what you wanted, it was there. I remember feeling
so cozy; they really made an effort. And the food was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Every night, the menu would read like a page from Gourmet
magazine: foie gras with a fig compote, venison prosciutto,
farm-fresh Camembert. The suites were luxuriosly elegant, with an
accent of Shaker simplicity. Next to four-poster beds, quarried
stone fireplaces reached to cathedral ceilings. Outside, verandas
overlooked sheep-grazing hills. Families could rent a renovated
farmhouse for $800 a night.
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of international luxury dining, the restaurant
kept its prices down. Dinner with wine cost about $110 to $150 for
two _ reasonable enough for some in the surrounding area to enjoy a
birthday or anniversary celebration there. Everyone in Old Chatham
_ a village comprising little more than a general store and Post
Office _ knew someone who worked at the inn. Now, most know someone
who is out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really put Columbia County on the map,'' said Stephen
Kinglsey of Hudson Michael Realty. He has mentioned the inn and
restaurant in New York Times ads he placed to sell nearby property.
``It's definitely a setback for the area,'' Kingsley said. ``People
came from all over for that restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   But success came at a price. Tensions grew between Kelly and the
Clarks, many say. Kelly, a co-manager of the property, didn't want
interference in her kitchen. But the Clarks wanted their say.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Kelly and Kushner announced they would leave at the
end of the year to open their own restaurant. Tension continued to
mount, and Kelly and Kushner told the Clarks in July they would be
leaving at the end of August. They later agreed to stay until Sept.
15. And then came the quarrel over the cook.
</P>
<P>
   The Clarks say they were interviewing other chefs. But after the
fight, ``the decision to close the inn was made quickly,'' Nancy
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   With Kelly gone, ``getting the inn to that point again will take
a lot of work and effort, and we are not sure we want to do that
again,'' Nancy Clark said. ``Even though you hire managers, this
job consumes you 28 hours a day, nine days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Clarks don't have immediate plans for the inn and
have not ruled out reopening or living on the property. Tom Clark
said there are no plans to sell or lease the inn. Earlier this
week, staff members washed down walls and cleaned curtains to
preserve the guest rooms and property.
</P>
<P>
   Behind their worry was a curious pride: For its brief life, the
Old Chatham Sheepherding Inn had succeeded in doing something well
_ producing a world-class meal and setting for a parade of
discerning gourmands _ and the thrill of that accomplishment seemed
reason enough to hold one's chin high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all sad,'' said Kathy Eil, at the Old Chatham Country
Store. ``But if you gotta go, why not go out on top like Michael
Jordan?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
