<HEADLINE>
Y2K CELEBRATIONS: BIG, LITTLE AND NO BUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To some, Jan. 1, 2000, is the start of the False Millennium.
That's because 2000 is really the final year of this millennium.
(When you count to 2,000, you don't stop at 1,999, do you?) That
technicality, however, isn't going to stop people from whooping it
up this Dec. 31, and there are plenty of activities to choose from.
Some of them cost nothing, some a little, and some a lot. Here's a
tiny sampling:
</P>
<P>
   --Let's start at the top. A 16-day ultra-deluxe journey will
culminate in a New Year's Eve black-tie celebration atop the world
in the Himalayas. Also included are three nights in a private
bungalow in Pokhara Village overlooking the foothills of the
Annapurna Range; first- and business-class flights; luxury suites,
including two nights in Katmandu; a hot-air balloon or airplane
flight over Mount Everest; and a full-day desert safari in Dubai.
The trips will take place Dec. 26-Jan. 9 or Dec. 28-Jan. 11. Only
10 couples can go, and the price is $26,000 per person, double
occupancy. For information, call World Travel Consultants at
800-432-7436 or e-mail wtcinc(at)juno.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Philadelphia plans a 24-hour celebration beginning at 7 a.m.,
Dec. 31. Each hour, one of 24 clocks inside the Pennsylvania
Convention Center, representing time zones around the world, will
strike midnight. Confetti will float to the ground, and music and
fanfare will feature a country in that time zone, where the
calendar is actually turning to 2000. For more information, call
the Philadelphia Visitors Center at 800-537-7676 or 215-636-1666,
or, on the Web, visit http://millennium.philadelphia.org/.
</P>
<P>
   --The Stonehedge Inn, a European-style country manor in
Tyngsborough, plans a three-day extravaganza beginning Dec. 31,
when guests will toast the millennium with Crystal Champagne,
Methusaleh Bottle Number 1,078, 1990 vintage. (There are only 2,000
bottles of this bubbly in the world.) Throughout, there will be
lavish dinners and buffets _ and sleigh rides, too. Prices begin at
$4,250, double occupancy, including tax and tips. For more
information, call Crystal McKiel at 978-649-4400. For more
information about the inn, visit www.stonehedgeinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Boston's original First Night will be a three-day festival,
Dec. 31-Jan. 2. More than 3 million people are expected to join in.
Among attractions: large-scale arts projects, dance, music,
parades, parties, and fireworks. For information on First Night
hotel packages, ranging from budget to luxury, call the Greater
Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at 888-SEE-BOSTON.
</P>
<P>
   --And then there's Times Square, where one thing is certain: Ed
Woodyard of Westchester County, N.Y., isn't going to miss seeing
the famed ball fall to usher in 2000. Woodyard booked a suite at
the New York Marriott Marquis, with a view overlooking the square,
16 years ago. That's two years before the hotel was completed. The
Marriott people were so impressed that they're picking up his tab. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Y2K: According to one survey, 43 percent of those
who have made no travel plans for New Year's 2000 agree with this
choice on the survey: ``The millennium means nothing to me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Four states begin and end with the same letter. Name
them. (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: A West Virginia valley that is considered the oldest
geological formation in North America has a river running through
it, making that the continent's oldest river. Its name: New River.
(With thanks to info(at)daytips.com via Mike Schuster of
Foxborough.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Don't confuse your travel agent with God.'' _ Kenneth
R. Morgan, an American writer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Triple treat: When the Portofino Bay Hotel opens in Orlando, Fla.,
next month, it will offer three unique services. The 750-room Loews
hotel, part of the Universal Studios Escape complex, will have
curbside check-in, making a stop at the front desk unnecessary. It
will also have Smart Rooms, which adjust the temperature to the
most comfortable setting, automatically report room malfunctions,
monitor whether a minibar needs replenishing, and alert
housekeeping when the room is vacant. The hotel will have butler
service in 26 of the rooms and suites. &QL; 
 &QL; 
On the menu: The Sea Street Deli at the famed Raffles Hotel in
Singapore offers such treats as Bacon Your Pardon; Lox, Stock &AMP;
Bagel; and Live and Let Liver. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In Devon, Conn., it's unlawful to walk backward
after sunset. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Traveling the Web: Bella-Online, a new site that calls itself ``the
voice of women on the Web,'' has a travel and leisure section with
topics geared to women and their families, including student,
sport, and adventure travel. Check it out at www.bellaonline.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ghosts, ghosts everywhere: The ``Ghosts &AMP; Graveyards'' trolley tour
described last week isn't the only way to view the weirder side of
Boston. ``The Boston Spirits Walking Tour,'' led by ghost hunter
and storyteller Jim McCabe, visits the city's most infamous
locations. Who knows _ during this 90-minute tour you may even meet
such spirited fellows as Harvey Parker, founder of the Parker House
hotel, still seeing to guests' needs a century after his death.
Participants meet at 7:30 on selected evenings at the Boston Common
Information Center. For the schedule, more information, or
reservations, call 781-235-7149. The cost is $12 for adults and $9
for children under 12 or people in groups of 10 or more. Bus tours
for 10 or more are also conducted to Salem and Marblehead, and
Concord and Groton. The Web site is at
http://members.aol.com/nehaunts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Alabama, Alaska, Arizona, and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
