<HEADLINE>
NEW LIFE FOR SAN FRANCISCO'S SOUTH OF MARKET SECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUIS A. DIIORIO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Foul lines and faultlines, new hotels and
restaurants, and a four-story, 350,000-square-foot entertainment
complex with 15 movie screens are helping turn the once drab
flatlands of SoMa (South of Market Street) into one of California's
hottest properties.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered the other side of town, SoMa and the China Basin
area are filling in a hurry . . . so much so that investors and
entrepreneurs have started looking to the neighboring Potrero
Hills. Cases in point: The Potrero Brewing Co., which opened in
May, took over the space formerly occupied by a Hellman's
Mayonnaise factory and transformed it into a three-level brewpub at
535 Florida St. (near Mariposa). And the ``Double Play,'' opened in
1909 as a watering hole at 2401 16th Street (at Bryant), has been
renovated, reopened, and expanded. Gigi Fiorucci's three-room
restaurant/ bar, kitty-corner from where Seals Stadium once stood
and where Joe DiMaggio began his professional baseball career, is
crammed with sports memorabilia and serves a hearty breakfast and
an Italian menu for lunch. No dinners, but the bar is open till 8
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, long before Bay Area Rapid Transit and the
Moscone Center, when if you headed south of Market and toured the
Anchor Steam Brewery or found the Esprit outlet, you had a great
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' according to one hotel employee, ``there's just so much
to see and do here we find tourists staying more than the usual
week.'' And from our room at the Hotel Argent on Third Street, we
could only marvel at what has been accomplished in the last 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscone Center, built in '81 for major conventions, trade
shows, and fairs, was the catalyst. And now, thanks to the removal
of the Embarcadero Freeway, the waterfront area south of Market
also has taken on new life. Rows of stately palms have been
planted; there's been a boom in restaurant and apartment
development; and Pacific Bell Park, the soon-to-be $319 million
home of the San Francisco Giants at Third and King streets, has
become a reality. A mere pipe dream a few years ago, construction
of the privately financed, 13-acre, 41,000-seat stadium is well
underway and according to Giants spokeswoman Traci Slaughter, it
will be ready in time for the April, 2000 opener.
</P>
<P>
   PacBell Park, if you can imagine it, is but a 15-minute walk
down Third from Market Street. It also can be reached by new Muni
(the city's trolley lines) service, buses, BART, and by ferry from
Marin, Oakland, and Vallejo. A marina is nearby and a CalTrain
depot is a block away.
</P>
<P>
   The park's main entrance will be on King Street where the Giants
will erect a nine-foot statue of Willie Mays making that famous
over-the-shoulder catch of Vic Wertz's fly ball to deep centerfield
at the Polo Grounds in the 1954 Giants-Cleveland World Series.
</P>
<P>
   And with a not-too-high right-field fence at 307 feet down the
line, ``Golden Gate Retrievers'' _ so they tell us with a
not-so-straight face _ will be diving into the bay during the
``Seventh-Inning Fetch'' for home run balls!
</P>
<P>
   (The park's mailing address: Pacific Bell Park, 1 Willie Mays
Plaza, San Francisco, CA 94107.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rooftop happenings &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The development of the stadium is changing the feel of this part
of San Francisco, from the Moscone Center to the bay at China
Basin. New businesses are moving in and businesses that were here
are expanding.
</P>
<P>
   One city official describes it as ``a renaissance in an area
that for years languished as a declining port and warehouse
district in the shadow of double-decker freeways.'' The 1989
earthquake eventually changed the face of the city, clearing
freeways and opening the neighborhood for what will be the nation's
newest vintage ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Yerba Buena, a burgeoning 87-acre urban renewal neighborhood two
blocks south of Market Street, has become home to the Rooftop at
Yerba Buena Gardens, the Esplanade, Yerba Buena Center for the
Arts, the Moscone Center, and the Museum of Modern Art, which
features more than 15,000 works of 20th-century art. In 2000, both
the Jewish and Mexican museums will be opened in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Rooftop, opened last October by the San Francisco
Development Agency as an urban destination for young people and
their families, cleverly covers the top of the Moscone Center along
Fourth, Howard, and Folsom streets. Among its attractions are a new
children's center opened with its flagship attraction, Zeum, a $56
million high-tech arts and production facility for children. The
rooftop also is home to a 12-lane bowling alley and a huge
child-care center with a two-acre interactive play and learning
garden, while its entrance houses a restored 1903 carousel from the
city's former amusement park, Playland-at-the-Beach. And much to my
pleasure, atop the Moscone Center is a 200 x 85 foot ice skating
rink at 750 Folsom St. between Third and Fourth streets. With
towering windows overlooking the San Francisco skyline, it's like
skating outdoors. There are skating schools, youth and adult
Faultline Hockey Leagues, Brian Boitano's youth skate program, a
senior program, pick-up hockey games, hockey workshops, power
skating lessons, and figure skating. It's a marvelous inner-city
facility and open to all. Call 415-777-3727 for additional
information.
</P>
<P>
   Metreon, a Sony Entertainment Center across from the skating
center and carousel, was opened June 16 at Fourth and Mission
streets. It includes 15 state-of-the-art movie theaters, eight
restaurants, the flagship Discovery Channel store: ``Destination
San Francisco,'' and the city's first Sony-IMAX theater with 2-D
and 3-D capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   It took 28 workers using ropes to lift the one-piece IMAX
screen. It weighs 600 pounds, is 80 feet tall and 100 feet wide,
and to project a clear image on the screen, movies must be made on
film three times the size of conventional movie film. ``Everest''
will be one of the first films shown there.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth floor of the Metreon is devoted to the imaginative
world of Maurice Sendak, award-winning author and artist of the
classic children's book ``Where the Wild Things Are.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Down by the Boulevard &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem with eating out in this city is that there are too
many good restaurants to choose from. On our most recent visit we
lunched at Boulevard where the ambience, food, and service were
incredible. It's our new favorite south of Market.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the Ferry Plaza at One Mission (at Steuart), Chef
Nancy Oakes and designer Pat Kuleto have turned the rundown 1889
French-style Audiffred Building into one of the waterfront's
hottest draws. Tables in the back provide a great view of the
harbor and Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its eclectic menu, Boulevard's is noted for its
desserts. Pastry chef Heather Ho, a Boston University hotel and
food administration graduate, boasts: ``No doggie bags with my
desserts.''
</P>
<P>
   Spared from the 1906 earthquake and fire by a quick-thinking
saloonkeeper, Boulevard offers lunch and a bistro menu Monday
through Friday; dinner is served nightly. As for the tale of the
saloonkeeper: Firefighters were about to dynamite the Audiffred to
halt the spread of fire _ until he promised them two quarts of
whiskey apiece and a cart full of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Recently added to the list of new restaurants south of Market
are Momo's at 760 Second St., serving new American fare across from
Pacific Bell Ballpark; Dadio's, at 300 Brannan at Second Street
(South Park), a fairly new hip, happening hangout; and Entros, at
270 Brannan, a bar &AMP; grill-arcade combo that offers food along with
unique mind-challenging games.
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning to get out of the city for a day or two, take
in Donna and Giovanni Scala's ``Bistro Don Giovanni'' on Highway 29
in Napa. With Tuscan ambience, mouth-watering food and a view
overrlooking the vineyards, it remains one step from heaven (call
707-224-3300). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Need a room? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the continued blossoming of SoMa, business and leisure
travelers need not look too hard for a room. At Third and Howard
streets in the burgeoning culture and commerce zone, the New
York-based Starwood Hotels &AMP; Resorts Worldwide Inc. has opened the
31-story, 423-room W San Francisco Hotel across the street from the
Moscone Convention Center, and next door to the city's Convention &AMP;
Visitors Bureau and Museum of Modern Art. The hotel features rooms
with an emphasis on style and comfort, and ``XYZ,'' an upscale
split-level restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bill Kimpton is at it again. When the sweater-wearing
hotel magnate opened the 236-room Serrano Hotel in the theater
district at 405 Taylor at O'Farrell streets, it was his 15th hotel
in the city. Number 16 will be the secluded 198-room Palomar at
Fourth and Market streets. To be opened Sept. 1, the Palomar will
be on floors 5-9 in the restored and refurbished 1907 landmark
Pacific Place building.
</P>
<P>
   SoMa really hit the jackpot when Four Seasons broke ground at
Market between Third and Fourth streets for its $300 million,
280-room hotel and tower. In addition to 142 luxury condominiums, a
fitness and spa facility and retail and restaurant space are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Argent Hotel (formerly the Meridien and the ANA) has been
taken on by Destinations Hotels &AMP; Resorts. . . . And if you're
interested in latest trends, how about microbrewed root beer!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The latest ``The San Francisco Book'' can be purchased ($3 for
postage and handling) by calling 415-391-2000 or by writing to the
San Francisco Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, PO Box 429097, San
Francisco, CA 94142-9097. You also can send your request by e-mail
to vic1(at)sfcvb.org_
</P>
