<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FISHING-CONFLICT-ART-     08-31 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-CONFLICT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHERMEN BRIDLE AS RETRICTIONS GET TOUGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATHAM, Mass. -- Five years after the collapse of New England's
famed Georges Bank fishing ground, tough fishing restrictions are
beginning to restore the cod and other fish that had been pushed to
near eradication. But even as the fish stage a comeback, scientists
are calling for tighter limits. A new report by federal and state
biologists suggests that fishing for most of the region's major
groundfish may need to be cut further to speed their recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Every new restriction, every new rule, say frustrated fishermen,
is another blow to a dying way of life. Already, fishing
communities from New Bedford to Rockland, Maine, have lost tens of
millions of dollars in fishing income and hundreds of fishing
industry jobs, with more losses expected the longer the limits are
in force.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the end more poignant than among the cod fishermen,
whose quarry brought Europeans to Cape Cod in the first place. From
the halcyon days of the 1980s, when the cod catch was five times
larger than today, cod fishermen have seen 6,000 square miles of
ocean closed to them, and catch limits so low in the Gulf of Maine
that it might as well be closed, too.
</P>
<P>
   But the new rules reached everyone, from the Maine lobsterman to
the New Bedford scalloper. At times, meetings of the New England
Fishery Management Council, which makes the rules, descended into
catcalls and near-fistfights as rough-handed fishermen squared off
against the economists and biologists who had the difficult job of
trying to count the remaining fish and figure out how to save them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, fishermen yielded to limits on what gear they could
use, which fish they could catch, where they could go, and how
often they could go there.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble, say regulators, is that fish from the flounder to
the cod were so severely depleted that it will take years to reach
a population that can sustain fishing over the long haul. That
means catching perhaps 20 percent of the available fish each year,
instead of the 60 to 80 percent a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't sitting well with the likes of Bruce Kaminski.
</P>
<P>
   Working his trade some 40 miles southeast of Chatham one day
recently, Kaminski gave a look of disgust as he removed one cod
after another from his hooks and tossed them back into the ocean,
dazed or even dead, and likely to be eaten by the swarm of blue
sharks chasing his boat, Never Enough.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of lean times in the Great South Channel,
Kaminski and other cod fishermen say they are having their best
summer season in a decade, but a new 2,000-pound catch limit is
forcing them to dump part of their haul. On this trip, Kaminski set
fewer lines than usual, and he still gave away 100 pounds of gutted
cod that exceeded the limit rather than throwing them overboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is stupid,'' said Kaminski, 43, a stocky, ponytailed man
who has been fishing for 21 years. ``We're just killing fish and
throwing them back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As things do improve, you want to make the case persuasively
to invest in conservation the next five to six years rather than
catching the fish today,'' said Teri Frady, spokeswoman for the
National Marine Fisheries Service in Woods Hole. ``The challenge is
going to be staying the course.''
</P>
<P>
   However, what makes sense on land can look different at sea,
where fishermen often shake their heads in disbelief at the rules
and spend a healthy amount of creative energy trying to get around
them. They particularly despise rules that seem wasteful, such as
the new cod limit. Kaminski's trade organization, the Cape Cod Hook
Fisherman's Association, would rather see fishing grounds
temporarily closed than face limits on the daily catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most bizarre way to come to work I've known in 20
years,'' said Kaminski, standing over the gasping codfish he has
just pulled from the water. He makes no secret that he will
illegally give his surplus fish to other fishermen rather than let
his catch ``feed the sharks.''
</P>
<P>
   Up and down the coast, there are signs of the fishing crisis,
from fishermen learning to be computer programmers in Gloucester to
the scores of groundfishing boats that remain tied up in
picturesque villages, to the dozens of boats that fishermen sold to
the federal government under a program to reduce fishing pressure.
</P>
<P>
   And, though the collapse was years in the making _ the result of
too many fishermen using too much gear to catch fish _ many date
the crisis to August 1994 when the New England Fishery Management
Council announced plans to close some of the hardest-hit fishing
areas. Since that time, the 17-member panel has, with few
exceptions, steadily tightened the limits.
</P>
<P>
   But about 1,700 fishing boats are still catching groundfish,
according to the National Marine Fisheries Service, and these
people, generally the best or most aggressive of the lot, do not
give uy. Kaminski, one of about 20 Cape fishermen who rely
on baited hooks rather than nets, was offered $169,000 from the
federal government for his 40-foot boat _ and he refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I want to make my money any other way,'' said
Kaminski as he steamed through the fog of Chatham's Stage Harbor at
5 a.m., the start of a 17-hour day. His crewman, Mike Woods, 33,
feels the same way: He was all set to run a charter boat for
tourists this year, but he came back to Kaminski's boat instead.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen such as these have weathered hard times, with younger
ones such as Woods dreaming of buying their own boat. Many are
drawn by family or ethnic tradition, but Kaminski and Woods are
first-generation fishermen drawn to the work itself.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Kaminski and Woods were able to fish pretty much as
they pleased as long as they stuck to their little patch of the
ocean in the Great South Channel. As hook fishermen, who are both
less numerous and less damaging to the sea floor than fishermen who
drag nets on the bottom, Woods and Kaminski were among the last
holdouts from heavy regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But that only made it more frustrating when the Fishery
Management Council decided to limit the cod catch. The pair had
recently started having big days when they caught 3,000 pounds of
fish or more, a haul that can bring up to $4,500 for a day's work.
When the 2,000-pound cod limit took effect Aug. 15, they had to
stow some of their gear, and be careful not to catch too many fish.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, though, the cod came in too fast, lured to the
squid dangling from thousands of hooks on Kaminski's long lines.
The deck was quickly covered with dying cod and diluted blood as
Kaminski used a sharp gaff hook to pull in the catch and Woods
gutted each cod with two knife strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, by releasing hooked fish and giving away the gutted
ones, the Never Enough came home with 2,007 pounds of cod and both
fishermen made money. But, they said, this is probably just the
beginning of cutbacks in the cod catch that could force Kaminski to
lay off Woods, the father of two young children, or tie up the boat
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't done screwing with us. This is just the
beginning,'' said Kaminski.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the New England Fishery Management Council has made no
decision on what to do next, and it released a report earlier this
month that highlighted improvements in fish populations over the
last five years, such as a 45 percent increase in Georges Bank cod
and the complete recovery of witch flounder. Some fish, it said,
could even be fished more heavily.
</P>
<P>
   But the same report, compiled by a group of federal and state
biologists called the Northern Demersal Working Group, showed that
New England fishing is up to a decade from full recovery as six of
the 11 main groundfishing stocks remain at less than 50 percent of
recovery levels. Scientists are particularly concerned about cod
because they are producing so few young fish to replace those that
are caught and they are not sure why.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at it as a set of stocks rather than as
individual stocks, then additional restrictions are necessary,''
said Phil Haring, a fishery analyst with the New England Fishery
Management Council. The Northern Demersal Working Group report
suggested that fishing for eight of the 11 groundfish stocks may
need more restrictions to meet the conservation goals in the
federal Sustainable Fisheries Act.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the once-mighty Atlantic cod is dropping from
American menus. Americans eat 40 percent less cod today than they
did in 1990, according to the National Fisheries Institute,
dropping to sixth most popular seafood behind three species _
shrimp, salmon, and catfish _ that are largely raised in fish
farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we persist with strict conservation measures, (cod) stocks
should continue to increase, and consumption will likely follow,''
said Richard Gutting Jr., vice president of the Fisheries
Institute, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   That is small comfort to Kaminski and Woods, who, like many
fishermen, are convinced that the biologists do not go to sea
enough. ``The fish are back big time and I don't think they realize
it,'' said Kaminski. ``It's a shame because . . . they don't need
to do all this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
