<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMUM WAGE ISSUE RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They disagree on several major issues, but on one
thing Vice President Al Gore and his Democratic rival former Sen.
Bill Bradley are in accord. They both say the federal government is
too stingy in putting a floor under the nation's lowest wages.
</P>
<P>
   Courting organized labor, Bradley recently endorsed an increase
in the minimum wage, a perennially popular Democratic issue. By
doing so he echoed a theme Gore long ago incorporated in his own
basic stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in fact, is so far ahead of Bradley on this and other
labor-friendly issues that he is the heavy favorite for the
Democratic nomination among AFL-CIO members. Gore already has
several labor endorsements; Bradley has none.
</P>
<P>
   The federal minimum wage that employers must pay kitchen help,
waiters, salespeople, janitors and other workers at the bottom of
the economic ladder is currently $5.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   When the floor was established by the Fair Labor Standards Act
of 1938, it was set at 25 cents an hour. But in those days, 25
cents would buy five cups of coffee, five hot dogs or five rides on
the New York subway. Members of Congress were paid $10,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the standard has not kept up with inflation. Various
proposals pending in Congress would raise it to $6.15 an hour over
three years or boost it a dollar an hour in annual increments for
several years or provide annual increases up to 4 percent depending
on inflation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton favors the $6.15 pay hike, as does much of the
Democratic Congressional leadership. Labor unions, in a burst of
renewed political energy, are campaigning for it with the slogan
``America needs a raise.'' Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., tried to
attach it to a liability measure favored by the Republicans before
the August Senate recess, but he was procedurally outmaneuvered.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, concerned about the potential impact on
labor-intensive small businesses, have traditionally opposed
minimum wage legislation. In 1996, the last time the wage was
increased, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, vowed to
fight it ``with every fiber in my being.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey lost that battle and may well go down this time too. But
based on past experience, the GOP leadership will manage to pass
plenty of favors for business to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage issue will come up for a vote this fall. More
than two dozen moderate House Republicans, nervous about losing
their narrow majority in the 2000 elections, are inclined to go
along because it could benefit GOP incumbents in swing districts.
The moderates' votes could be enough to pass the legislation in a
House with just 11 more Republicans than Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans, less worried about losing control, may yet
block it. But it is more likely they will bend it to their own
ends. Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., is planning a competing
bill, misleadingly called a ``workers' protection package,'' that
would offer other labor law changes favoring business.
</P>
<P>
   A similar dual-track strategy worked in 1996, when Congress
raised the minimum wage from $4.25 to $5.15 but included in the
legislation $21 billion in tax breaks for business. Workers got
pennies; employers got the pot at the end of the rainbow. Everyone
was briefly happy, but they might as well have been eating Chinese
food. They were all hungry again soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage fight is more symbolic than substantive. But it
does focus national attention on the huge salary gap between
business executives and their lowest-paid employees. And it tends
to push up the wages of those just above that level to keep pay
scales proportionally distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Once again we will hear the familiar debate over whether a
minimum wage increase will hurt small-business profits, force labor
cutbacks and drive up the unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   After the minimum wage was increased in 1996, however, job
growth appeared unaffected. The current unemployment rate of 4.3
percent is the lowest in almost three decades.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by the liberal Economic Policy Institute,
the 1996 increase raised the wages of almost 10 million workers,
about 71 percent of whom were adults and 58 percent of whom were
women. Approximately half worked full-time.
</P>
<P>
   A contradictory survey by the pro-business Employment Policies
Institute, however, contends that only 44 percent worked full-time.
It reports that 37.6 percent affected were young people still
living with parents, who presumably could be tapped for additional
income.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are not drastically far apart, but they demonstrate
that it is easy to selectively highlight those statistics that
support the points you wish to make.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the minimum wage is not a living wage. It must be
supplemented by other federal programs, handouts from relatives,
investments or a second job if the worker's family is not to
starve. But it is politically naive to pretend that a raise
wouldn't send a friendly message for the coming election year.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
