<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USAGE FACTS FROM A FICTION WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Angela Thirkell Society, North American Branch, met in
Boston this weekend, so what better time to introduce word-loving
readers to this usage-conscious English novelist?
</P>
<P>
   Not that Thirkell is only for word mavens. Her gentle comedies,
written in the 1930s, '40s, and '50s, will appeal to many readers _
say, those who have dug down to the third tier of Trollope and are
finding ``Sir Harry Hotspur of Humblethwaite'' more a chore than a
diversion. (Thirkell is a conscious though modest borrower from
Trollope, setting most of her novels in the 20th-century version of
his fictional Barsetshire County.)
</P>
<P>
   But Thirkell deploys an attentive ear, as well as a sharp eye,
in her pictures of midcentury's shifting mores, and anyone who ever
tsk-tsked over ``12 items or less'' at the supermarket checkout
will find her a kindred soul. Her pet peeve is surely the
pronunciation con-TROV-er-sy, a barbarism she blames on
ill-educated BBC announcers (and one still common on BBC radio).
More than one book has a violent aside on the cultural decline that
would allow such an excrescence.
</P>
<P>
   Thirkell isn't merely a scold, though. Her characters comment on
usage the same way they discuss other conventions _ why the maid
shouldn't knock at the sitting-room door, say. So in ``Wild
Strawberries'' (1934), we learn that a well-bred girl (for so she
would be described) considers the toast ``Cheers'' _ at least on
the lips of her rival _ a ``schoolgirl exclamation.'' A desultory
suitor is alarmed when a woman proposes ``an intelligent discussion
of our present relationship'': the use of relationship for a
romantic involvement is new enough to be noteworthy, and the man
thinks (as his fellows have thought ever since) that ``the word
relationship had a sinister sound.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Private Enterprise'' (1947) the bugaboo is hullo, which,
Thirkell complains, ``is rapidly becoming the Basic English for all
greetings, morning, noon or night.'' A child's nurse tries to beat
it back: ``Say how do you do nicely,'' she urges her young charge.
On the other hand, turfing _ now hospital slang for dumping an
undesirable patient on some other department _ was old news even in
1947, it seems. A character describes the British Museum's
``turfing that delightful couple (a sculpture) out of the Etruscan
room,'' and further research reveals that turfing dates at least to
1888.
</P>
<P>
   Thirkell swings with the times _ there are no flies on her, as
her Mr. Wickham would say _ apologizing all the while for the
locutions she's forced to adopt, like ``the Barchester premiere (as
these things are called) of `Mayflower Madness.' ''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so she's not H.W. Fowler. On the other hand, most usage
books have no romance, and they often fail to explain the social
context of their rules. Fiction can teach things that usage guides
can't, and Thirkell, even half a century later, is a master of the
novelistic language lesson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Missing' in action
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If a plane or an 18-year-old went missing, asks Paula Gillen,
``aren't they just missing?'' Paul Freeland of Hingham has been
wondering about the phrase too: ``Is it correct? Is it a new
coinage? Where does it come from?''
</P>
<P>
   It comes from England, fairly recently _ a 1944 citation was the
earliest I could find in the OED. And go missing seems not to have
been treated as slang: It appears in a list of similar (and utterly
standard) constructions with go, such as ``suppose he goes lame''
and ``Her cheeks went scarlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Go missing has been catching on gradually, probably by way of
the BBC, which brought us ``at the end of the day'' and the current
``people on the ground'' (the ones who really know what's
happening, as opposed to the official sources). It appeared in the
Globe sparsely in the '80s, a bit more frequently in the '90s _
though the record is 11 citations in a year.
</P>
<P>
   It's an import you're free to adopt or shun, but it's more
accurate than got lost when the speaker doesn't know whether the
missing plane (or woman) is truly lost or merely out of reach. And
it offers a zippier, more focused alternative to disappeared, a
verb that works with everything from rainbows to hamsters to
headaches. Now that we've got it, some of us would miss go missing
if it went missing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Word appears every other week through summer. Write Jan
Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CARTOONIST-PRICE-ART-     08-31 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTOONIST-PRICE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILARY PRICE DRAWS HUMOR FROM MUNDANE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER BONFANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHAMPTON, Mass. _ As Hilary Price tells it, she acquired
Doxy, a 6-year-old mix of husky and pit bull, in a rather peculiar
way. Her old roommate's boyfriend's ex-girlfriend was looking for a
new home for her dog, and would Price know of a good home? Price
took Doxy in.
</P>
<P>
   Much about Price's life lends itself to funky little stories,
and some end up in the 29-year-old's nationally syndicated comic
strip, ``Rhymes With Orange.'' (Incidentally, orange, as Price is
quick to point out, does not dominate her life. She has red hair,
she drives a red Jeep Wrangler, and she has red lenses on her
sunglasses. The strip's title is merely a little bit of whimsy on
her part. And except for door hinge and the scientific term
sporange, few words easily rhyme with orange.)
</P>
<P>
   A native of Weston, Price earned a bachelor's degree in English
literature from Stanford University. At 25, she became the youngest
woman ever to have a syndicated cartoon strip. Today she is in her
fifth year of a 10-year contract with King Features Syndicate,
based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strip represents a perspective not normally seen on the
comics page, of a woman in her 20s and friends of a similar ilk,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rhymes with Orange,'' which runs daily in more than 100
newspapers nationwide, including The Boston Globe, avoids
pie-in-the-face comedy in its thought-provoking wit. Price artfully
frolics with topics such as dogs' psyches and human relationships,
and finds humor in more mundane issues such as technology and
business. Most of all, she focuses on the ``tiny little details of
everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   Price found her niche without design. ``I never expected to be a
cartoonist. It didn't fit into the plans,'' she says, which in
college were to work in academia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked art class. I drew on the side of my notebook and sent
notes to my friends, like jokes about the class,'' she recalls. ``I
always doodled, but I was never a fine artist. I'm fair to average
when it comes to drawing teacups and still lifes. I see myself more
as a writer than an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Price grew up in Weston reading ``Far Side'' and ``Bloom
County'' comics. She attended Concord Academy, which she describes
as ``funky, fun . . . not buttoned up.''
</P>
<P>
   After high school, ``I catapulted myself across the country for
some unknown reason,'' Price says. She graduated from Stanford in
1992, then settled down in San Francisco, where she lived in the
Mission district for five years. She freelanced as a copywriter at
an advertising agency. ``I wanted to try another avenue for
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   During that time, she published a weekend cartoon called
``Price'' in the San Francisco Chronicle, which inspired her to try
for syndication.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, she decided to return to Massachusetts. ``I really
wanted to move back to New England,'' she says, adding that the
West Coast was a ``great lesson for me. I learned that there are
funny, cool, smart, and active people everywhere, and I can meet
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Price settled down in the central Massachusetts town of
Northampton. She works in the hamlet of Florence, sharing her
office with a painter and a graphic designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work environment is different. It's a pretty funky
office,'' she says of the old brush factory that was converted into
office space and is full of artists.
</P>
<P>
   The strip allows her a flexible schedule. ``Creating a structure
will always be a challenge,'' says Price. ``I'm not the 
get-into-work-at-9-have-a-grilled-cheese-at-noon-and-then-back-to-wo
rk type. I'm much more of a meanderer and late sleeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, however, she works Monday through Friday from about
10 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   She begins her workday by reading all the comics in an
assortment of newspapers. She also regularly checks out the
cartoons in The New Yorker magazine by her hero, Roz Chast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Female cartoonists that are out there making it are few and
far between,'' says Price, calling Chast an inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time to create a cartoon, Price turns to any of the 11
notebooks she has filled with ideas. Daily cartoons must be
submitted to the syndicate a month in advance, and the deadline for
Sunday cartoons is five weeks ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the business section of a newspaper yields a wealth of
ideas, because ``they use funny words . . . and talk about the
Internet,'' she says. ``I generally don't get inspiration from
other people writing funny stuff, but from serious stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also Doxy and her family, whom Price describes as
``fertile ground.'' Her mother owns an ``environmentally friendly''
gift shop in Weston and her father is retired and lives in
Brookline. Price has an older brother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the strips that come easy. They keep their funniness,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Price draws the strip on tracing paper, outlines it in ink,
writes the script, and then scans it into her computer. When the
cartoons are completed, she sends them via computer to a branch of
King Features Syndicate in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not writing or drawing, she says, ``I want to
entertain and be entertained.'' To relax, she plays soccer, runs,
and does inline skating.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Andrews McMeel published a collection of the
first two years of her work in a book. Within the next year,
``Rhymes With Orange'' will be expanded into a line of greeting
cards.
</P>
<P>
   All of which, to use a favorite word of Price's, is pretty
funky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put pressure on myself or strive to be funky. If it
comes, it's by accident,'' she says. ``I'm not a perpetrator of the
funk.'' Just someone who captures it on paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
