   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POLLUTE _ BEIJING _ Authorities on Tuesday revealed a
sooty secret long suspected by residents of this heavily polluted
capital: that for vital state occasions, the Beijing government can
switch off the smog. Beijing officials promised to use that power
to the hilt next month ``to insure a successful celebration'' of
the 50th anniversary of the communist takeover of China on October
1, state media reported. (Albright, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-VIEQUES _ VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Out the window of a
bumpy, cramped commuter plane, this small island off Puerto Rico's
eastern coast sparkles like a Caribbean gem, verdant green hills
rising from a sandy ribbon of beach. San Juan's riot of all things
American _ Burger King, Outback, 7-Eleven and Pizza Hut on every
corner, at least outside the historic district _ disappears with
the prop wash. Through the windshield, a landscape from a slower,
simpler time looms on the horizon. But Vieques' fetching appearance
belies its status as a battleground. For decades, Navy pilots have
practiced war on the island's northern tip, dropping tons of
munitions on a deserted zone that in places resembles a moonscape.
(Williams, Cox News Service). WITH MUG.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GOP-WEEKEND _ Conservatives hold a Renaissance-like gathering
called the Weekend in Colorado, beginning with opening address
Friday by former House Speaker Newt Gingrich. Also on the agenda
are Wayne LaPierre of the NRA on a panel on caring for the inner
city and Rep. Bob Barr getting an award along with other House
managers in the president's impeachment trial. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NEWT-ANALYSIS _ ATLANTA _ Newt Gingrich's political future was
cloudy at best after his resignation as House speaker and
congressman. Now it seems all but over. News of his impending
divorce _ his second _ and allegations of a lengthy affair with a
33-year-old congressional aide have rendered him unelectable to any
post substantial enough to hold his interest. News of his affair
has also exposed Gingrich to charges of hypocrisy, not to mention a
substantial bit of snickering. (Bookman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   QACHARLOTTE _ A federal judge is expected to rule any day now on
whether Charlotte-Mecklenburg schools can continue to use busing to
try to avoid resegregation of schools. The man on the hot seat is
Superintendent Eric Smith. He reflects on the future in a Q&AMP;A.
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-CRASH _ A big rig crashes into a metro Atlanta bridge
and bursts into flames. The morning rush-hour accident nearly shut
the city down. Commuters stuck in cars, businesses without
employees to answer phones. How Atlanta coped _ and didn't _ during
the standstill. (Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BROADBAND _ WASHINGTON _ A huge and hot war is shaping up over
high-speed Internet access and who will give it to us. The size of
this market is staggering, and the telephone companies are fighting
the cable companies tooth and nail over who will have the
advantage. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
