<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN ARE INDEED SUBJECT TO STRESS WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people of the United States have an enormous number of
rights. The harvest of countless protests, marches and sit-ins has
included a crop of documents explaining the rights of our citizens
and the limitations of our government.
</P>
<P>
   In 1791, the Bill of Rights was added to the United States
Constitution. In the tradition of England's Magna Carta of 1215, it
granted us a basic list of privileges including the right to bear
arms and the right to a speedy trial.
</P>
<P>
   Another significant piece of legislation for this country was
the 19th Amendment, passed in 1920, which finally assured that all
citizens, male and female, have the right to vote. More recently,
the Civil Rights Act of 1964, though often construed as legislation
specifically for minorities, actually is a law protecting the
rights of all.
</P>
<P>
   I revisited these landmark developments in the history of our
great nation in an effort to find another unalienable right that I
need to exercise. I have yet to find it documented anywhere, but I
didn't find the right to breathe, either, during my research.
Therefore, I have concluded that like inhaling and exhaling, it is
simply such a fundamental part of survival that we don't even need
to write it down. I am referring to the right to change my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was a time in my life when I was steadfast and
unmoving about my ideas. Even when confronted with overwhelming
evidence to the contrary, I chose to stand my shaky ground and
endure the plummet into the chasm of ignorance that resulted when
my most recent theory split at the seams. Now, having miraculously
survived an embarrassing number of academic earthquakes, I have
finally learned an excellent survival technique. This won't be a
news flash to anyone but the young and the stubborn, but we
actually do have the right to change our minds. It's OK to be
wrong. It happens. Just hang a right and move along.
</P>
<P>
   What am I changing my mind about today?
</P>
<P>
   Kids and stress.
</P>
<P>
   In reflecting on my childhood through the myopic glasses of
middle age, I tend to focus on the good times, the happy times and
the funny times. Yes, I recall a number of harrowing moments, but
they pale in comparison to the laughter and gaiety that seemed to
be the order of the day. Consequently, I have been one of those
people who found the idea that children can be stressed out
incomprehensible. My usual response to the subject has been, ``What
do they have to be stressed about? They get food, clothing and
shelter for free. They don't have to work hard. They do a little
homework and play a lot. So what's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the suicide rate among teens is at an all-time high.
Teen pregnancy and drug use continue to remain at alarming levels.
And kids are joining gangs because they want ``a real family.''
Clearly there is a problem, whether we adults can identify with it
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Judsen Culbreth, the editor of a parenting magazine, explains
that even the act of returning to school can be stressful. She
suggests that adults try to imagine going to a new job every year,
with new policies, new expectations and new co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   That's what returning to school is like for our children. That
really is stressful.
</P>
<P>
   So the moral of this story is simply that we need to be
sensitive not only to the physical state, but also the emotional
state of our children. A stressed-out mind puts up roadblocks on
the information superhighway. I guess an inflexible mind does the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing my mental map, it appears that taking a right at
this roadblock will actually lead me and my family to a better
place.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if it doesn't, I can always change my mind.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
