<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDENCE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
 
RHODE ISLANDERS TEAM UP ON '70s TEEN COMEDY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
OUR RATING: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rhode Island is a small place, so it's not too
surprising that its two most prominent filmmaking entities _ the
gross-out joke-loving Farrelly brothers and street drama specialist
Michael Corrente _ would bump into one another.
</P>
<P>
   But as you might expect, Ocean State solidarity isn't quite
enough to bring two highly diverse creative temperaments into
harmony. ``Outside Providence,'' the alliance between the director
of ``American Buffalo'' and the guys who made ``There's Something
About Mary,'' keeps careening between uninspired slob comedy,
working-class sentimentality and a sporadically intelligent but
stubbornly half-baked coming-of-age story. It's a movie about,
among other things, solidarity among Rhode Islanders, but it seems
to be in a constant fight with itself.
</P>
<P>
   Scripted by Bobby and Peter Farrelly and director Corrente, the
film is based on a novel Peter wrote before ``Dumb and Dumber'' and
``Mary'' made him and Bobby something like Hollywood's reigning
artists of bad-boy humor. Oddly enough, Corrente comes from the
meaner districts of Pawtucket that ``Outside's'' hero, mid-'70s
teen-ager Tim Dunphy (Shawn Hatosy), calls home. The more
comfortably raised Farrelly built his book around the few poor
classmates he observed at his tony New England prep school.
</P>
<P>
   Tim lives with his crude/loving/undemonstrative widowed dad
(Alec Baldwin, pretty good until he goes overboard with the
everyman mannerisms), a wheelchair-dependent little brother (good
for a few of the Farrellys' awful handicapped gags) and _ though
Dad won't let it in the house _ a three-legged German shepherd with
an eye patch.
</P>
<P>
   Tim's a good if wayward sort who mainly hangs out with his
dope-smoking buddies until he rear-ends a police cruiser one
bong-befogged night. A friend of Dad's pulls strings to get Tim
enrolled in a fancy prep school; he hates the idea of leaving his
lifelong loser pals for senior year, but it sure beats jail.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Tim soon makes friends with a bunch of dope-smoking
winners at the Ivy League factory, and even attracts the attention
of the cutest, brightest girl on campus, Jane Weston (Amy Smart,
last seen in ``Varsity Blues''). Improbable as this may seem,
Hatosy's portrayal of a lower-class lunk is charming enough to make
the rich girl's interest credible; he's adorably awkward like most
teen-age boys, but he has more than enough street cool to
compensate.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the moment-to-moment behavior in ``Outside
Providence,'' in fact, will ring warmly true for anyone who grew up
in the '70s. Even the film's innocence is convincing; Tim's
Pawtucket posse brag brutishly about minor romantic exploits, but
this film hardly sports the sexual obsessiveness most contemporary
youth comedies wallow in. Indeed, we never even see the physical
side of Tim and Jane's relationship; the emphasis is, refreshingly,
on their emotional growth and joy in each other's company.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the absence of rampant horniness here is
compensated for by compulsive drug-taking. Not inauthentic for the
period, these kids' idiotic pursuit of getting high regardless of
the risk (what passes for a plot revolves around a vengeful dean's
efforts to bust as many dopeheads as he can) is nevertheless
unbelievable, especially when key characters have the chance to
logically outgrow their partying ways but refuse to do so out of
some hokey, rebellious impulse.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, other serious matters are brought up _ such as how Dad
and his poker buddies cope with the revelation that one of them
might be gay _ only to be unexplored and laughed away half an hour
down the line. For these and many similar disappointments,
``Outside Providence,'' admirable as its desire to be a teen comedy
with a lot on its mind is, flunks out more than it passes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Outside Providence'' (R; drug use, nguage). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Shawn Hatosy, Alec Baldwin, Amy Smart, George Wendt. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Michael Corrente. Written by
Corrente, Peter Farrelly and Bobby Farrelly, based on Peter's
novel. Produced by Corrente, the Farrellys and Randy Finch. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 35 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
