   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Sept. 1
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Dili, East Timor) _ The anti-independence thugs
who have terrorized East Timor for months reasserted themselves on
Tuesday, one day after an extraordinarily peaceful referendum in
which officials said 98.6 percent of eligible voters had cast their
ballots. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   with map.
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM-ARABS (Jerusalem) _ An Israeli official indicated that
a policy of expelling Arabs from residency in Jerusalem would stop,
but then a prominent professor who has long lived there was told he
is no longer a resident but a tourist. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LAUNDER (Undated) _ Developments in the Russian bank and
money laundering investigation. By Thomas L. O`Brien.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-POLITICS (Caracas) _ As the political crisis
continues, the president of the state oil company is replaced. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ The war in Dagestan is on again. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul) _ Northwest Turkey experiences an
aftershock with injuries and at least one death. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-ANNIVERSARY (London) _ Remembrances and conflict on the
anniversary of her death. Diana is suddenly a forgotten figure in
her own land, though those who showed up complained at the lack of
a permanent memorial. A foreign journal, by Warren Hoge. (1200
words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCONNELL-FUNDRRAISING (Washington) _ Feature on the fight
between Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and a campaign reform group
led by business and academic figures. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   KEYES-PROFILE (Greenville, S.C.) _ Alan L. Keyes, the
arch-conservative radio talk show host, is the invisible man in the
Republican primary for president. He gets few cameras at his
events. Political analysts tend to forget him in their
prognostications. Polls show him receiving one percent of the vote,
or less. And when the Log Cabin Republicans, a homosexual group,
issued a news release last week attacking religious conservatives
for intolerance, Keyes didn't even merit a mention. But to his
small yet devoted cadre of followers, Keyes a former Reagan
administration diplomat with a Harvard Ph.D., has something his
fellow arch conservatives lack: mesmerizing oratorical skills
twinned with a messianic vision. By James Dao. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-TEACHERS (Detroit) _ This city's schoolteachers went on
strike Tuesday, canceling the first day of fall classes and dealing
another blow to the effort to revive Detroit's underperforming
schools. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SHOOTING (New York) _ Folo on the fatal shooting by
police of a mentally disturbed man in Brooklyn: the mayor, after
meeting Hasidic leaders, calls the shooting ``unfortunate'' but
defends police actions. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS (Undated) _ Developments at the four-day conference on
AIDS in Atlanta. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-ECON (Paris) _ Total Fina's hostile bid for Elf Aquitaine
and a three-way bank brawl have been the latest illustration of how
much French business has changed. In the last two years, France has
moved to shake up and slim down its corporate world. As a result,
France has become a darling of foreign investors more thoroughly
and quickly than many would have thought possible. The Paris bourse
has surged by 50 percent over the last two years. Growth prospects
are brighter than in a long time. And there is little sign that the
corporate reshuffling will let up soon. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ A small group of analysts,
skeptical of the fuzzy financials of Internet retailers, have
devised a simple method for evaluating growth. They take the two
numbers that Internet retailers love to trumpet _ total revenue for
a quarter and total customer base _ and divide one by the other.
The results are eyebrow raising. They go straight down. Internet
companies argue that there is a gaping methodological flaw in this
formula, namely that the customer base number is cumulative. By
Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR (Undated) _ The dollar falls below 110 yen for the first
time since January. No intervention by central banks is seen. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2:00 p.m., stocks are lower. The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 83 points, the S&AMP;P 500 was down
10 points, the Nasdaq composite index was down 24 points. The
30-year bond was yielding 6.00 percent. In Europe, stocks were
lower, with London down 1.49 percent and Frankfurt down 1.52
percent. In Japan, the Nikkei closed down 2.69 percent, and Hong
Kong's Hang Seng index closed down 1.50 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-CISCO (Undated) _ IBM agrees to supply Cisco Systems with
network technology, components and computer services in a five-year
deal valued at $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   KAUFMAN-WARNING (Los Angeles) _ Home builder Kaufman &AMP; Broad
Home Corp. says that unauthorized mortgage loan trading by an
employee of its mortgage subsidiary would reduce its third-quarter
earnings by 24 cents a share. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   CARREFOUR-PROMODES (London) _ Looking at the impact of the
Carrefour-Promodes merger on other European retailers, whose shares
surged for a second day today on speculation that more such deals
are to come. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
