</P>
<P>
   BAD-TABLES (New York) _ On the list of atmospheric irritants to
the dining experience, the bad table is right up there with the
rude waiter and ear-splitting noise levels _ and often accompanied
by them. With more restaurants opening than at anytime in recent
history _ 50 this fall alone _ and more money behind them for space
and design, bad tables should have been wiped out, like smallpox.
But Tim Zagat estimates that his office gets 30 complaints a day on
the subject. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   RAW-FISH (Undated) _ Sushi and sashimi opened the door to raw
fish; salmon tartares and tuna carpaccios took it beyond Japanese
restaurants and onto mainstream tables everywhere. Now ceviche has
expanded the world of flavors and textures created in fish when no
cooking is involved. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
