<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CHILL-FACTOR-LADN &LR;      08-31 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILL-FACTOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION MELTS AWAY IN `CHILL FACTOR' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's ``Speed'' in an ice-cream truck. It's ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' crossed with ``Breakdown.'' It's
rude, crude and eminently forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Chill Factor,'' a derivative, workmanlike buddy movie
that may find an audience with undiscriminating action fans upset
over the summer's paucity of explosions. But hard-core genre
enthusiasts will likely leave this movie disappointed, because for
all of its explosions, throat-slittings and off-camera
decapitations, ``Chill Factor'' delivers precious few thrills.
``Shrill Factor'' would have been a more apt title.
</P>
<P>
   The action, such as it is, begins on a tiny South Pacific island
where the U.S. government is conducting some perilous chemical
weapons research. An unfortunate accident occurs, causing one too
many ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' face peels for the servicemen
patrolling the area. Their commander _ not the scientist in charge
_ takes the fall and packs his bags for 10 years at Leavenworth.
</P>
<P>
   When his sentence is up, Maj. Andrew Brynner (Peter Firth)
decides to get his revenge, steal the deadly chemical substance and
sell it (on eBay we presume) to the highest bidder. Helping him is
a multicultural band of mercenaries, including an African-American,
a Latino and a blonde in tight leather pants.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in their way are an aimless drifter named Tim (Skeet
Ulrich) and an ice-cream delivery man, Arlo (Cuba Gooding Jr.), who
intercept the lethal goo. Their mission: Get it back to the
government and keep it cold. If the substance rises above 50
degrees (and the filmmakers conveniently provide the storage device
with a digital temperature readout), there will horrible death,
decay and cable outages within a 100-square-mile area.
</P>
<P>
   Ridley Scott protege Hugh Johnson doesn't do as much with the
premise as he could in his debut as a feature director. The film
veers between slack action and broad schtick, scoring occasionally
with a cheap laugh or decent chase sequence. More often than not,
though, the shifting tone results in a movie that doesn't quite
work as a thriller _ or a ``Midnight Run'' buddy comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding Jr. clowns broadly, but he needs a better joke writer.
And the movie's serious moments are pure corn. (Maj. Brynner to Tim
and Arlo: ``So the average citizens have decided to risk their
lives for country. I almost remember what that feels like.'')
</P>
<P>
   It would also be easier to buy into the movie's ``chill''
concept if they kept the chemical substance away from fire and
direct sunlight. The ensuing loss of tension, not to mention brain
cells, is palpable. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Chill Factor'' (R; violence and language). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Skeet Ulrich, Cuba Gooding Jr., Peter Firth, David
Paymer. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Hugh Johnson. Screenplay by Drew
Gitlin and Mike Cheda. Released by Warner Bros. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 42 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;   &UR; 2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
