<SLUG> BC-DREAMCAST-ACCESSORIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCESSORIES YOU'LL WANT TO CONSIDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; What should you get to go with the basic $199
machine?
</P>
<P>
   To start with, you have to get the virtual memory unit as well,
for another $20. Its presence will transform sports games, allowing
two people playing each other to secretly pick their plays on the
VMU's separate tiny screen.
</P>
<P>
   As well, with titles such as Sonic Adventure, it will download
mini-games and characters you can play independently, and most
usefully, stores high scores, characters and game progress. At
least one VMU is a must-have, adding a great deal to the
playability of many games.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple-player games (the machine has jacks for four
controllers) will require multiple controllers, and multiple VMUs
(you can actually fit two VMUs in a single controller, or a VMU and
the separate $19.95 Jump Pack for ``rumble'' functions), but you
can probably hold off a bit on that purchase, say for Christmas,
unless you're just itching to bash your buddies in a fighting or
sports game.
</P>
<P>
   Prices will vary on the extra controllers because Sega and
numerous accessory makers such as Interact (at www.interact.com)
are already making a variety of inexpensive alternatives, as well
as some unusual accessories such as keyboards, light guns and
driving wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of keyboards, if you're serious about using the
Dreamcast as an Internet machine for e-mail and the like, you'll
want to get a keyboard. Sega's custom keyboard will cost just $20,
a bargain for the annoyances it obliterates. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
