   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
The Kansas City Star offers the following for use Wednesday, Sept.
1, 1999:
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSH: WASHINGTON _ The political question of the moment is, did
Texas Gov. George W. Bush ever use drugs and if he did, should he
say so. But another question may be, shouldn't some of the others
who are wading into the debate about the Republican presidential
frontrunner's past keep quiet for fear of sounding hypocritical?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OZLAND: DeSOTO, Kan. _ Developers for the World of Oz theme park
will give away 2,800 acres of the Sunflower plant site, or almost a
third, to Johnson County Parks, Kansas University, Kansas State
University, De Soto and De Soto schools. The park land, about 1,700
acres, is less than originally sought. By Grace Hobson.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CROWD: KANSAS CITY _ Over pasta and pizza, Al Kohlman, Klaus
Frank and Arthur Abt talk about the restaurant business, Kansas
City's need for mass transit and the dent in Frank's car. Kohlman
serves another slice of pizza, and Frank marvels at the busy car
wash across the street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's casual talk, the kind they have every Friday over lunch.
The amiable conversation springs from a friendship that has endured
50 or 60 years, a friendship forged in much different times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These men, all Jews, escaped Nazi persecution in World War II.
Along the way, they lost loved ones _ fathers, grandmothers,
cousins _ but in America, they found new ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They found ``the Crowd,'' a group of 11 Jewish immigrant
families that adapted to Kansas City together. Over the years, even
after they started their own families and careers, the Crowd has
stayed together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a substitute family,'' Klaus Frank says. By James
Hart.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MILLER: MILLER COUNTY, Mo. _ Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon
today will seek the ouster of Miller County Sheriff Tom Russell.
The county's new jail has been the subject of federal and state
investigations over allegations that jailers had sex with female
inmates, allowed sex between male and female inmates and allowed
alcohol into the jail. By Will Sentell. 25. Map. (Miller County is
near Lake of the Ozarks.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WANT: KANSAS CITY _ Convicted killer Alan Echols evaded the law
for eight years before his capture last week, but a Jackson County
man wanted for murder has avoided the law for almost two decades.
Yellowing police reports tell of the tale of Richard G. Bocklage,
his 10-foot Burmese python and a bizarre letter that foreshawdows a
murder. Jackson County probably has fewer than a dozen outstanding
warrants for murder, investigators say. But Bocklage's case is the
oldest one that prosecutors could take to a jury. Bocklage is
accused of killing his former girlfriend, who was doctor. Joe
Lambe. 25. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   w/ SHARON01: Jackson County's oldest active murder warrant is
probably also the most notorious _ a pretty brunette called ``La
Pistolera.'' Sharon Kinne was charged with killing three people
before her 25th birthday, but the Independence woman once called
herself ``just an ordinary girl.'' She's been on the run for nearly
40 years. Joe Lambe 10. Photos, list of others wanted for murder.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER-COLUMN: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Odd lots from a bulging
column portfolio. Column by Jerry Heaster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROV-MOVIE REVIEW: ``Outside Providence.'' Three stars. Tale of
blue-collar kid shipped off to prep school instead of jail. By
Robert Butler.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS-SPORTS: BOSTON _ Game coverage. Kansas City at Boston,
6:05 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WIGHT-SPORTS: He once was the biggest player ever for the
Wichita State basketball team. Now at 7-1 and 460 pounds, Paul
Wight, a.k.a. ``The Big Show,'' is one of the biggest stars in
professional wrestling. By Jason King. With photos. &QL; 
 &QL;
