<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5942 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-MUSIC-DIXIE-REVIEW-HN     08-31 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DIXIE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICKS STILL RULING THE ROOST WITH `FLY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Fly,'' due in stores this week, finds the Dixie Chicks walking
the line between their independent Texas instincts and the country
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks, the freshest act to emerge in country music in the
last two years, honed their bluegrass-inflected sound on the Texas
club circuit in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Maines' lead vocals combine a rock edge with deep
country roots and an unmistakable Texas twang, while the
instrumental abilities of fiddler Martie Seidel and banjoist Emily
Robison give the group a sound distinct from the Nashville assembly
line.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been 6 million sales _ the most ever for a
country duo or group _ of the Chicks' debut album, ``Wide Open
Spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly'' was co-produced by Blake Chancey and Paul Worley, the
same team responsible for ``Wide Open Spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   After writing only one song on their debut (the hit ballad ``You
Were Mine''), the group members have song credits on five of the 13
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The first single, ``Ready to Run,'' was co-written by Seidel and
Marcus Hummon. The song opens with Irish air played on the fiddle
by Seidel, then opens up into the spirited tale of a woman intent
on asserting her independence.
</P>
<P>
   Seidel and Hummon also collaborated on ``Cowboy Take Me Away,''
which builds from a folkish guitar part reminiscent of Lyle
Lovett's ``If I Had a Boat.'' Robison and Seidel contribute soaring
harmonies behind Maines' lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye Earl'' is a Thelma-and-Louise tale of two women who
conspire to murder an abusive husband and get away with it. Maines
delivers the lyrics with a rollicking good humor that should play
well to the Chicks' core of young women fans.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not until the middle of the program that the album
really takes off and flies. ``Hello Mr. Heartache'' is Buck
Owens-style Bakersfield honky-tonk. Maines' father, Lloyd Maines,
plays all the pedal steel guitar parts on the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Waste Your Heart,'' co-written by Robison and Maines, is
pure-country ballad sung from the unapologetic point of view of a
woman leaving a relationship. (The song mirrors events in Maines'
life; she was divorced last year.)
</P>
<P>
   This is followed by ``Sin Wagon,'' in which a woman looks
forward to doing a little ``mattress dancing'' following a wild
night on the town. Seidel, Robison and acoustic guitarist Bryan
Sutton contribute hot solos combining rock energy with bluegrass
instrumentation.
</P>
<P>
   Maines also co-wrote ``Without You,'' which somewhat less
effectively features a string orchestra. And ``Some Days You Gotta
Dance'' is as close as the album comes to smiley-face Nashville
filler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hole in My Head'' is twanging hillbilly rock, with Mike
Henderson on heavy-stringed lead guitar. Although Maines comes
across as soft and sweet when the song calls for it, she can also
punch out the lines with as much raw aggression as any female
singer in country music.
</P>
<P>
   The album closer, ``Let It Fly,'' was written by Austin, Texas,
songwriter Patty Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly'' is not the album to change the world, or even change the
rules in Nashville. But it demonstrates that the Dixie Chicks have
what it takes to keep on cluckin' for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars out of a possible 4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
