<HEADER>
A5959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      08-31 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF RESTAURANTS, WINES, AND THE PRICES THEY CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wow, $380 for a Batard-Montrachet,'' I remarked to
the wine steward at a New York restaurant as I surveyed the wine
list. ``A lot of money for a bottle of white Burgundy. It must be a
tough sell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``It will be gone in a couple of days.
Now, that little California riesling for $18, our least expensive
wine, that's hard to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Was that because his customers did not like California riesling,
I asked. ``No,'' he said. ``They hate, absolutely hate, buying the
cheapest wine on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of a wine list is indeed an awfully lonely place,
overlooked by many if not most diners. For many people, choosing
any wine from a lengthy list is an unnerving experience: so many
names, so many prices, so little time. The people with you become a
critical audience; the server becomes every teacher who ever waited
for an answer you didn't have. One can feel the pressure to
overreact, to stab blindly at something costing far more than you
planned to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough to appear ignorant; at least you won't look like a
tightwad, too. And so that little riesling or Macon blanc or
obscure Bordeaux languishes alone and unwanted. Or does it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not here,'' one restaurateur told me. ``If no one will touch
the lowest-priced wine, I wait a few months, then raise the price
and move it up a few places on the list. Then it will sell _ no
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Another restaurant owner told me this was an old ploy. ``And it
works,'' he said. Neither man wanted to be identified, but others
were more open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lowest-priced wines are usually from obscure
appellations,'' said Daniel Johnnes, the wine director at
Montrachet, a popular New York restaurant. ``People don't buy these
wines because they are unfamiliar with them, so we talk about them.
Just giving them a wine list to look at won't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he noted that the restaurant has a Sancerre that
costs $34. It also has a Quincy, which is very similar, for $22,
``but you have to talk about it to get people to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Hersom, the wine director at Le Cirque 2000, regularly
sells rare Bordeaux for $2,000 a bottle and more, but is fully
aware of the problem of the low-priced wine that no one wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone paying $90 per person for dinner, a $60 bottle of
wine may be no problem,'' he said. ``But we have customers to whom
we recommend the lowest-priced wines _ and they buy them. It could
be a special celebration, a party of eight. They're better off with
three our four inexpensive wines, especially if there are people in
the group who don't drink wine.''
</P>
<P>
   At a restaurant like Le Cirque 2000, inexpensive is a relative
term, but Hersom said that some 80 wines are less than $40, with
the lowest another of those ubiquitous California rieslings, this
one from Fetzer Vineyards, at $18.
</P>
<P>
   At the Water Club, the manager, Bruno-Noel St.-Andre, said he
never has any problem selling his least expensive wine. ``It's a
Beaujolais-Villages at $25,'' he said, ``and very popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaujolais benefits from its popularity. Indeed, the name is
almost a brand. People buy it because they know and like it,
regardless of the price. Unfortunately, many restaurants have
realized this and now charge outrageous prices for Beaujolais.
</P>
<P>
   At the Union Square Cafe, the owner, Danny Meyer, will
occasionally sell his least expensive wines by the glass if they
don't sell quickly enough by the bottle. A wine that sells for $18
a bottle translates into $5 a glass. ``That would be our least
expensive glass,'' Meyer said ``but we have no trouble selling it
that way. ``
</P>
<P>
   Union Square Cafe's wine list is divided into categories
determined by taste and style rather than by origin. ``Our cheapest
price is $18,'' Meyer said, ``but each category has one. We
confront people about their built-in fears. We make things easier
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's worth keeping in mind that where wine is concerned, price
is often more a reflection of demand than of quality. Most
restaurants that are serious about wine have a few gems that are
moderately priced because no one asks for them. And no one asks for
them because they are unknown. At I Trulli, the owner, Nicola
Marzovilla, and his wine director, Charles Scicolone, use
subterfuge to introduce their customers to their least expensive
wines. They put those wines in the tasting programs at their wine
bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will sell three tastes for a flat price,'' Marzovilla said.
``Afterwards, we may tell the customer that No. 2 or No. 3 was the
least expensive wine in the house. After that, he'll order it by
the bottle because he likes it, not because it's cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of I Trulli's wines come from the Puglia region and are
virtually unknown here. People avoid them because they have never
heard of them, not because they are inexpensive, Marzovilla said,
``but Charles Scicolone knows how to reassure them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always getting people to buy a less expensive wine,''
Marzovilla said, paying his colleague a grudging compliment. ``He's
the best down-seller in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
