<HEADER>
A5962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      08-31 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD-ROASTED TROUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This is the seventh of eight columns by Waldy Malouf, the chef and
an owner of Beacon in Manhattan. His collaborator on these columns
is Melissa Clark.) 
(jt) 
 c .1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I started experimenting with the wood-burning oven at
Beacon, I found that the combination of high heat and wood smoke
worked extremely well with fish, especially trout. Trout is a
relatively fatty fish, which allows it to take on the taste of the
smoke while the flesh stays juicy, despite the intensity of the
fire. The fire crisps the skin, which gives the soft fish a little
bit of crunch. It's a terrific cooking method.
</P>
<P>
   Its only flaw is that most people, like me, don't have
wood-burning ovens at home. But the recipe for wild roasted trout
below was easy to adapt to a charcoal grill.
</P>
<P>
   Using firewood, or even wood chips, and indirect heat, anyone
can turn an ordinary kettle grill into a near approximation of a
wood-burning oven.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer real wood charcoal, but any kind will do, so long as
you use plenty of it. If you are using a log, add it right away,
after lighting the charcoal. Then let the fire burn for about an
hour (depending on the size of the log) until the wood is
practically reduced to ashes and the coals are beginning to die
down.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using wood chips, soak a good-size handful of them in
water while the charcoal lights. About 10 minutes before you are
ready to cook (the charcoal should be gray all over), add the
soaked chips.
</P>
<P>
   The fish has to cook over indirect heat, so remove the grilling
rack and push the coals and wood over to one half of the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Then cover the grill, close the vents and let it get really hot
inside, like heating an oven.
</P>
<P>
   When the fish is placed inside, on the half of the grill without
coals underneath, it will actually be roasting, rather than
grilling.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce for the trout is also its marinade, which makes this
dish extremely easy once the fire is lighted. A simple chervil
vinaigrette, seasoned with shallots and Champagne vinegar, lends a
subtle herby-onion flavor to the trout.
</P>
<P>
   Because the sauce is made in a blender, you don't have to chop
any of the ingredients finely; just throw them all in together.
</P>
<P>
   I like to blend the herbs with only half of the olive oil and
then stir in the other half by hand. This is purely for looks. The
sauce isn't fully emulsified, and so it breaks on the plate. The
effect is like a pale green pool surrounding dark islands of herbs.
Spooned over the fish, it is so striking that no no other garnish
is needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOOD-ROASTED TROUT WITH CHERVIL VINAIGRETTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes, plus about 1{ hours preparing the grill
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped chervil
</P>
<P>
   } cup chopped flat leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons roughly chopped shallot
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Champagne or white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 boned trout, skin on, heads removed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Light grill, using plenty of charcoal. If using firewood, add
it, and let wood and charcoal burn for about an hour, or until most
of the firewood is burned up. If using wood chips, soak them at
least 20 minutes; then, add to the coals after they are completely
gray. Let chips burn for 10 minutes. Move charcoal and wood to one
side of grill for indirect grilling.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, prepare vinaigrette. In a blender, puree chervil,
parsley, shallot, lemon juice and vinegar with { cup olive oil.
Transfer mixture to a small bowl, and stir in remaining oil, 1
teaspoon salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Sprinkle inside of trout with remaining salt and pepper to
taste. Spoon about half of the vinaigrette on trout, inside and
out. Rub vinaigrette into fish. Cover trout, and refrigerate for 15
to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Spray one side of a 15-inch-square piece of foil with cooking
spray. Cover the side of grill that has no charcoal underneath with
the foil, sprayed side up. Place fish on foil, and cover grill.
Check fish after 10 minutes. (It does not have to be turned.) It's
done when flesh is opaque and skin is crisp. Serve immediately,
with remaining vinaigrette as sauce. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1605EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
