<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORTH A TRY, GAZPACHO OR NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I like gazpacho, but the ultimate minimalist technique _
pureeing a few tomatoes, a red pepper, some onion, oil and vinegar
in a blender _ is not the best. This yields a pulverized salad that
I find coarse, its raw flavor strong and entirely too lingering.
The vinegar, which adds necessary acidity, is also overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried many solutions to this problem over the years, most
of them actually traditional _ roasting the vegetables first to
reduce the raw taste; adding almonds, cucumbers or even grapes to
lighten the flavor; letting the soup sit overnight so the flavors
can meld. None really did the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Then a friend suggested I abandon tradition (although you never
know when something you ``invent'' is in fact an old preparation)
and combine tomatoes with another fruit: cantaloupe. At first, I
was disappointed; the melon added essential sweetness but had an
unappealing graininess. Cooking, at least a little bit, would
surely help.
</P>
<P>
   I peeled and seeded the tomatoes, then quickly sauteed them and
the flesh of the melon in olive oil. I substituted lemon juice for
vinegar and added basil to produce the mildest, most delicious,
creamiest gazpacho I've ever tasted. With its bright orange color,
it was also among the most beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Was it really ``gazpacho''? I don't know. Some references say
gazpacho is any cold soup with vinegar; others say it is simply a
cold soup; still others say it has to have stale bread as a
thickener. All that matters is that this is one great soup.
</P>
<P>
   The tomatoes take an extra step because the skins are bitter and
the seeds are impossible to puree. To prepare them, core them by
cutting a small cone out of the stem end; then make a small ``x''
in the skin of the opposite end. Get a bowl of ice water ready, and
then plunge the tomatoes into boiling water for 10 or 15 seconds;
quickly remove them, and plunge them into the ice water. Peel with
a paring knife, cut in half through the equator and scoop out the
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   The tomatoes and melon have to cook in separate skillets so they
sit in one layer and cook quickly without steaming, which would
make them mushy.
</P>
<P>
   This gazpacho has one disadvantage: it has to be prepared in
advance so it can cool. Using ice cubes in place of some of the
water in this recipe will speed that up. If you are really in a
hurry, pour the soup into a wide bowl, place it in an even wider
bowl filled with ice water and stir until it chills.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOMATO-MELON GAZPACHO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus time to cool
</P>
<P>
   4 tomatoes, about 1{ pounds
</P>
<P>
   1 3-pound cantaloupe
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   10 leaves basil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Juice of a lemon.
</P>
<P>
   1. Core, peel and seed tomatoes; cut flesh into 1-inch chunks.
Seed melon, and remove flesh from rind; cut into chunks. Place a
tablespoon of olive oil in each of two 10- or 12-inch skillets and
turn heat under both to high. Add melon to one and tomatoes to the
other, and cook, stirring, until they become juicy, no longer than
2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a blender or food processor, puree melon with tomatoes, 1{
cups water and basil, along with some salt and pepper. Stir in
remaining olive oil. Chill, add lemon juice to taste and adjust
seasoning. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
