<HEADLINE>
ANTI-SEMITIC GRAFFITI FOUND ON JEWISH CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SARAH YANG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Employees arriving at work at a San Francisco
Jewish center on Monday were confronted with a swastika and the
words, ``Adolf Hitler was here,'' the second of two apparent
anti-Semitic crimes in the region within hours.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, a Molotov cocktail was thrown at the San Jose
home of a judge. Two 17-year-old boys and a 19-year-old man were
booked for investigation of committing a hate crime, terrorism and
arson, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects apparently thought Santa Clara County Superior
Court Judge Jack Komar was Jewish, although he is Catholic. Neither
the judge nor his wife was harmed.
</P>
<P>
   The graffiti at the Jewish Family and Children's Services
center, which was written in what appeared to be black magic marker
on a support beam in front of the building, was being investigated
as a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   Officers noted that the graffiti still smelled of marker fluid
when they arrived at the center shortly after 10 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Zahler, director of Emigre Services, an office of the
center, called the police shortly after the graffiti was noticed at
about 9:30 a.m. She said the desecration could have occurred any
time over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that makes you concerned,'' Zahler said. The
graffiti was painted over after the police arrived, and before it
could be seen by many of the elderly people and recent immigrants
served at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Zahler said the incident was the first time there had been a
problem at the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no leading up to this,'' she said. ``We're hoping
it's an isolated incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Both incidents were the latest in a string of anti-Semitic
events throughout the country that have put Jewish leaders on
alert.
</P>
<P>
   Security was heightened at many Jewish community centers and
schools after the shooting earlier this month at a Jewish center in
suburban Los Angeles, and the June arson attacks against synagogues
in the Sacramento area.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have their antennas up at this point,'' said Jessica
Ravitz, associate director of the Anti-Defamation League in San
Francisco. ``In the past, people would receive flyers or
threatening phone calls and just hit delete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0182 </DOCNO>
