emotionally disturbed Hasidic man a day after protests roiled the
Brooklyn neighborhood, Borough Park, where the Monday shooting took
place. Jewish leaders in neighborhood are split in their reaction
to the shooting, with critics saying the police did not need to use
deadly force. Other developments. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARCH (New York) _ A federal judge ruled Tuesday that Khallid
Abdul Muhammad, the self-professed successor to Malcolm X, may hold
a youth rally in Harlem, saying city officials had no right to use
the content of Muhammad's inflammatory speeches as a basis for
denying him a rally permit. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-PRISONERS (Undated) _ The prevalence of AIDS among
prisoners in the United States is five times that of the population
at large, and the rates of other sexually transmitted diseases
among inmates are very high, scientists said in reporting the first
comprehensive study of these diseases in correctional facilities at
a meeting in Atlanta on Tuesday. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR (Undated) _ The American dollar, which dropped again
Tuesday against the Japanese yen and the new euro, has begun a
moderate slide that could continue for the rest of the year as
economies in Asia and Europe rebound while the United States, under
the drag of higher interest rates, slows down. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PAVAROTTI-TAXES (Paris) _ Luciano Pavarotti has paid an
undisclosed sum to a German court to settle a tax evasion case
arising from a lucrative world tour by the so-called Three Tenors
in 1996, the prosecutor's office in Mannheim, Germany, has
announced. Placido Domingo reached a similar settlement last week.
By Alan Riding.
</P>
