<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5988 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DIXIECHICKS-TEX     08-31 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIXIECHICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICKS-REVIEW) 
A LOOK AT THE WHIRLWIND RISE OF THE DALLAS TRIO THE DIXIE CHICKS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by DIXIE CHICKS-OTHER, DIXIE CHICKS-DAD, DIXIE(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emily Robison was a long way from home on the Lilith Fair tour
when she turned 27 a few days ago, and looking forward to
celebrating her birthday in a quiet, boring Detroit hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   And then she got a surprise: Her hubby, country
singer/songwriter Charlie Robison, to whom she's been married a few
months, flew in to spend a little quality time with her.
</P>
<P>
   So now, instead of just hanging out with fellow Dixie Chicks
Natalie Maines and Martie Seidel and crew members Sunday night in
Cleveland, she and Charlie prepared to hit the town and go to a
nice restaurant _ two attractive, successful people in the bloom of
their personal and professional lives.
</P>
<P>
   A romance novelist with a jones for Patsy Cline and Tammy
Wynette couldn't have written it any better: To be a Dixie Chick
these days is to constantly be given happy surprises, unexpected
gifts _ to find that life is just a little better than you'd
thought it was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year or so, that's meant two Grammys (including best
country album for ``Wide Open Spaces'' and best country vocal
performance by a duo or group for ``There's Your Trouble''),
playing on both George Strait's stadium tour and Lilith Fair (what
other group can claim that?) and, at present, watching as more than
6 million copies of ``Spaces'' walked out of the stores.
</P>
<P>
   The CD has sold better than any release by any country group,
ever, and is still in the national top 30 of the ``pop charts''
after 79 weeks. This would be astounding for anybody, but even more
so when we remember that not all that long ago the Dixie Chicks
were a cute (maybe too cute) Dallas novelty act, a-pickin' and
a-grinnin' and a-wearin' vintage cowgirl outfits, guaranteed to be
playing a bar or a wedding near you.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they are the sweet but tart country/bluegrass/pop trio,
role models of empowerment and self-expression for thousands of
young women who have spawned a series of blatant imitations
(SheDaisy, stand up! Redmon &AMP; Vale, take a bow!) while popping up
in the pages of Elle and in ads for Candie's shoes. This November,
they'll appear _ as sisters from Louisiana _ on an episode of
``King of the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Emily Robison is 27 and happy _ giddy, almost, when talking
about all things Chicks-related from her Cleveland hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING THE DISC: The main topic at hand is ``Fly,'' the
much-anticipated follow-up to ``Spaces.'' The new disc came out
Tuesday and is sure to be one of the most talked-about country
releases of the fall, if not the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we felt more confident this time, obviously, and this
one was easier,'' she says. ``And what really helped was setting
aside four or five months to do it and not try to do it when
touring.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Fly'' was cut this past spring after a round of
writing retreats in which the trio would snag a day or two at a
remote cabin, something that Seidel has credited in past interviews
with making the writing easier.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that five of the 13 songs were written by the
Chicks _ either together or with outside writers Marcus Hummon,
Stephony Smith and Eric Silver. Then Seidel and co-producer Blake
Chancey picked the best material from outside writers.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Griffin contributed the closing ``Let Him Fly,'' Matraca
Berg and Annie Roboff penned ``If I Fall You're Going Down With
Me,'' and Buddy Miller and Jim Lauderdale came up with the peppy,
rockish ``Hole in My Head.'' But some of the CD's best songs, such
as the party anthem ``Sin Wagon,'' were written or co-written by
the Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between ``Fly'' and ``Spaces'' is that the
former, Robison says, is more consciously about their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more true emotions on this CD, and the emotions fit
our lives and what we're going through,'' she says. ``And all three
of us were going through such different things. I was planning a
wedding, Natalie was getting a divorce and Martie was keeping her
marriage going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parts of `Wide Open Spaces' were autobiographical, but this
album really is more us. It was subconscious _ we didn't reflect on
the songs and what they said as a whole until the CD was done.''
</P>
<P>
   And while there is a wide range of subjects and situations in
the ``Fly'' songs, there is still that independent streak.
``Goodbye Earl'' is about two longtime friends who kill an abusive
spouse after he defies a restraining order, and both ``Sin Wagon''
and ``Some Days You Gotta Dance'' are about not worrying about
boyfriends or long-term relationships and just going out for a good
ol' night on the town. Hence the CD's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't name the CD until it was nearly done,'' Robison
says. ``We told the label we were going to name it `Sin Wagon' just
to scare them _ we had no intention of doing that. But as we
reflected on it, there are a lot of songs that have references to
flying and leaving and `don't tie this bird's wings' and stuff. We
thought it was universal and that it made a good statement.''
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT A CANDLE: But if both men and women can apply the messages
of the songs to their lives, Robison is well aware that she and her
bandmates are role models for young women walking gingerly through
the minefield of romance and independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people just feel we're honest,'' she says. ``A lot of
the Nashville stuff is so sterile and PC. Especially the young kids
_ I hope they react to things they think are real and honest. ...
We want to influence girls to pick up instruments and do things
that are more male-dominated. A catch phrase like `chicks rule' is
great, but it's just a catch phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, though, the Chicks do rule: They're perched on their
own little branch of country music, a singular entity that
satisfies the tastes of longtime country fans as well as youngsters
who maybe got into the music in the past few years and also listen
to female singers such as Jewel and Sarah McLachlan.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, though, is that they're still fans of other
performers _ and they've been sharing the Lilith Fair stage with
some of them. Happy though she is throughout the interview, Robison
sounds positively rapturous when talking about the night before,
backstage in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't fathom that Sheryl Crow is familiar with your
music,'' she says. ``It's just too cool to look up to someone so
much and have them respect what you do. Last night, they all gave
me a birthday cake, and Sheryl Crow sang `Happy Birthday' to me!''
</P>
<P>
   And the happy surprises just keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
