<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO TIP? FLIP OVER THE CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way John Schreadley tells it, the idea came to him one
morning when he and his wife were having breakfast at a chain
restaurant. When the bill came, Schreadley, a paramedic in Tampa,
Fla., pulled a tipping chart he had bought out of his pocket. When
he looked down and saw both the check and tip card in his hand, a
light bulb went on. Why not, he asked himself, combine the two?
</P>
<P>
   With the help of his wife, Mitzi, who owns a commercial printing
company, he came up with a tipping chart, which he calls Computip,
that can be printed on the backs of restaurant checks, both flat
ones and tape rolls. It has calculations for 15 percent, 17 percent
and 20 percent tips for up to $100. After waiting 19 months for a
patent, he is test marketing it in the Tampa area.
</P>
<P>
   While New York City diners for years have had a built-in rough
guide for calculating a tip _ doubling the 8.25 percent sales tax
shown on the bill gives a 16.5 percent tip, which is in the ball
park _ Schreadley is hoping the Computip will make it a bit easier
to calculate tips. He wanted, he said, ``to bring some sort of
standardization to this ballgame, to remove some of the negative
issues _ the embarrassment and the fear and the anxiety _ of
tipping.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was careful to let diners know the guide is just a guide.
The top of each chart reads: ``For your convenience you may
consider referring to the chart below. It is designed solely for
assisting you in quickly calculating a tip and is in no way meant
to influence your usual method of tipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Schreadley knows tipping is a sensitive issue, with some
restaurants in recent years trying to add a standard tip percentage
to checks and others including tip calculations at the bottom of
the check, to encourage better tips for waiters and kitchen help.
But these techniques are often disliked by dinerc, who feel they
are being forced into leaving a larger tip than they want.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lynn, an associate professor of consumer behavior and
marketing at the Cornell Hotel School, said a guide like Computip
might be a good idea, as it gives diners assistance while making it
appear that they have as much choice as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Schreadley chose to print his chart on the back of
checks. ``The feedback is that people are offended by having it on
the front of the check,'' he said, ``but my feeling is that having
it on the back is a little more subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   So subtle in fact that restaurateurs who use it should worry
more that diners might not notice it, rather than be offended by
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
