<HEADER>
A5999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NIXON-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     08-31 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RICHARD NIXON, THE CONGRESS YEARS': TAKING EARLY NIXON OUT OF THE
DOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
(Publication notes at end) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The posthumous rehabilitation of Richard Nixon continues apace
with ``The Contender'' by Irwin F. Gellman, a professor of American
history at Chapman University in Southern California, not far from
Nixon's hometown, Whittier. Specifically, Gellman takes on the
widespread idea that Nixon owed his early rise to national
prominence to a unscrupulousness and dishonesty, the most important
element of which was his practice of associating his opponents with
communism and subversion.
</P>
<P>
   Gellman's focuses on Nixon's early years as a public figure,
from his first congressional race, in 1946, to his vice
presidential nomination in 1952. It was from those very beginnings,
Gellman argues, that Nixon's reputation became irrevocably stained
with powerfully negative myths, most important, that calculated
red-baiting of his opponents was the key to his early electoral
success. The truth, in Gellman's view, is very different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixonphobia turned into a cult, and its visceral hatred cannot
be overemphasized,'' Gellman writes near the end of his narrative
of the early Nixon career. ``Every major charge brought against him
during his congressional years'' is ``not sustained by facts.'' In
reality, Gellman concludes, Nixon was a ``hard-working, promising
young star'' of Republican politics who played to win; and he did
win, not by engineering dirty tricks but, in Gellman's view, by
outthinking his opponents and better measuring the drift of
post-World War II American life than they did.
</P>
<P>
   Gellman's book will not convince everybody, but it is the solid,
heavily documented sort of work that will have to be taken into
account by serious people as the debate about Nixon continues.
</P>
<P>
   It is a full-scale political biography of Nixon during his early
career in politics. It is not a biography that adds a conspicuous
store of new material to what has been presented by other writers
over the years, from Garry Wills to Stephen E. Ambrose to Henry A.
Kissinger. But in directing our attention to what he portrays as
the anti-Nixon myth and its endurance, Gellman effectively joins
the argument. At some point in almost every chapter he itemizes a
few of the major allegations that have acquired the force of truth;
then he tries to refute them.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect of this is persuasive enough to cause some
reflection on the entrenchment of images in American political
life, how a certain view of a figure, enhanced by an unquestioning
acceptance of the putative facts of that figure's life, gains a
kind of etched-in-stone validity. But some of Gellman's refutations
are more persuasive than others. His detailed chapters on Nixon's
defeat of the Democratic candidate, Jerry Voorhis, for Congress in
1946 addresses accusations that that Nixon was the handpicked
choice of a cabal of monied conservative interests in Southern
California, and that he underhandedly and falsely charged Voorhis
with gaining endorsements from the political action committee of
the Congress of Labor Organizations, which at that time was viewed
as Communist-affiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Gellman shows that the California committee that approached the
young Nixon to run for election in the state's 12th Congressional
District was not a bunch of professional dirty-tricksters but an
ordinary, non-nefarious group of Republican activists. They were,
in Gellman's description, doing nothing more than what many other
groups of interested citizens, Democratic and Republican, have done
for decades. As for the famous CIO-political action committee
connection, Gellman shows that Voorhis did receive such
endorsements, endorsements that the candidate himself found
troubling and had sought to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   An impressive element of Gellman's thorough research is that he
is able to pinpoint when certain anti-Nixon myths were born and how
they have been repeated over the decades. In the Voorhis case, they
began with a 1952 article in The New Republic by Ernest Brashear,
an unsuccessful candidate for the California State Assembly. Among
other things, Brashear wrote of legions of Nixon supporters' making
anonymous phone calls to voters accusing Voorhis of being a
Communist. Gellman finds no evidence that any such dirty trick took
place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even some of the material that Gellman presents makes the
red-baiting charge seem more serious. Certainly, a significant
element in Nixon's 1950 senatorial campaign against the liberal
Democrat Helen Gahagan Douglas was to portray her not as a
Communist but as soft on Communism.
</P>
<P>
   The ``pink sheet,'' a significant artifact of Nixon's campaign,
involved the sort of suggestion that was at the heart of the
guilt-by-association technique used in that troubled time in
American history. The pink sheet demonstrated that Douglas'
congressional votes coincided almost exactly with those of the New
York congressman Vito Marcantonio, described in turn as ``the
notorious Communist Party-liner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gellman does not go into a deep analysis of the political
semiotics of the pink sheet. He simply states that it was ``mild by
comparison to later (or, for that matter, earlier) standards of
negative campaigning.'' The author's deeper argument, as he
examines other elements of Nixon's career _ especially his roles in
the sensational Whittaker Chambers-Alger Hiss affair and the on the
House Committee on Un-American Activities _ is that Nixon sincerely
believed that Communist subversion was a major threat to American
security.
</P>
<P>
   Gellman's attention is on the political career itself, and he
does not expend much effort demonstrating that Nixon was right or
wrong. His argument is that whatever the validity of Nixon's
beliefs, there was nothing underhanded or demagogic about the way
he expressed them.
</P>
<P>
   The real ``damage to governance of this period,'' Gellman
contends in what seems at best an overly simplistic statement,
``was the steadfast, rigid refusal of Truman and his advisers to
recognize that the United States had to address the question of
Communist espionage rather than just dismissing it as partisan
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, revelations from newly opened files in Moscow and
Washington like the so-called Venona papers, transcripts of some
3,000 communications between the Soviet Union and its agents in the
United States, have given support to Nixon's belief in the
existence of subversive forces. But Truman, even according to some
of the material that Gellman presents, was less rigidly unaware
than the author suggests.
</P>
<P>
   One can argue with Gellman, in other words. But his overall
vision of Nixon cannot be neglected as historians continue to
assess the man who was probably the most interesting president of
recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `The Contender: Richard Nixon, The Congress Years 1946-1952.'
</P>
<P>
   By Irwin F. Gelman.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 590 pages. The Free Press. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
