u e BC-CHILL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-31 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHILL FACTOR': ELVIS' TEMPERATURE IS RISING, AND THEY'RE ALL SHOOK
UP  
(PRODUCTION NOTES AT END)
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would action-adventure screenwriters do without Elvis
Presley as a reference point? To their credit, the writers of the
comically tinged thriller ``Chill Factor'' have at least had the
wit to dream up a variation or two on the cliche ``Elvis has left
the building.'' In the movie's opening scene, as a deadly chemical
defoliant (code name Elvis) is about to be tested on a remote
Pacific island, a technician announces, ``Elvis is approaching the
stage.'' Later in the film, we have ``Elvis on ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it gets its engines going, ``Chill Factor,'' directed by
Hugh Johnson, is a mechanically efficient chase-by-numbers movie in
which two young men pursued by terrorists transport Elvis across
the Montana high country in a rattling stolen ice-cream delivery
truck. Leading the list of hazards is the fact that if the
temperature of Elvis' container rises above 50 degrees (hence
``Elvis on ice''), they and possibly hundreds of thousands of
others in the region will meet excruciating deaths as their flesh
is chemically stripped away from their bones. (The opening scene in
which a test of Elvis goes awry offers a brief but grisly preview.)
</P>
<P>
   Driving the truck is Arlo (Cuba Gooding Jr.), a goofy ice cream
delivery man who happened to be in the wrong place at the wrong
time. Guiding him at gunpoint is Tim Mason (Skeet Ulrich), a young
fishing buddy of the guilt-stricken scientist (David Paymer) who
invented the top-secret Elvis and who informs Tim of its lethal
potency moments before dying from gunshot wounds. That information
goads Tim into heroic action: Elvis must be transported to a nearby
military base at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Long's murderer is his former boss, Capt. Andrew Brynner
(Peter Firth), an angry Vietnam veteran who went crazy in a
military prison after taking the rap for the hushed-up Pacific
island accident, in which 18 soldiers died. Now Brynner and a group
of commandos who resemble refugees from a James Bond movie hope to
sell Elvis on the international market to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   As the truck careens and clatters over the mountain passes of
Montana, Arlo and Tim face the predictable hair-raising situations.
The truck gets stuck and nearly tumbles from a narrow winding road.
Ultimately they have a collision with a car transporting a boat,
which the pair hijack and use as a downhill toboggan through the
forest, over a precipice and into a river whose icy waters keep
Elvis pacified. The final confrontation takes place in a tunnel
with the terrorists, the police and Elvis' custodians converging
just as Elvis' temperature rises above 49 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chill Factor'' has no aspirations to be anything but what it
is: a live action-adventure cartoon stuffed with macho banter,
decorated with weaponry and charged with enough cliffhangers to
stir up some adrenaline. For Gooding, the movie is quite a comedown
from the heights of ``Jerry Maguire.'' His scared-witless ice-cream
delivery man belongs to the same category of wisecracking
noncharacters as LL Cool J's indestructible, scared-witless chef in
``Deep Blue Sea.'' Ulrich's future as an action-adventure star
looks dim. He's too bland, too earnest, too normal to compete in a
field that requires actors to look and behave like flesh-and-blood
action-adventure toys.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``Chill Factor'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has scenes of violence and some
strong language.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Hugh Johnson; written by Drew Gitlin and Mike Cheda;
director of photography, David Gribble; edited by Pamela Power;
music by Hans Zimmer and John Powell; production designer, Jeremy
Conway; produced by James G. Robinson; released by Morgan
Creek/Warner Brothers. Running time: 110 minutes. This film is
rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Cuba Gooding Jr. (Arlo), Skeet Ulrich (Tim Mason), Peter
Firth (Capt. Andrew Brynner), David Paymer (Dr. Richard Long),
Hudson Leick (Vaughn), Kevin J. O'Connor (Telstar) and Daniel Hugh
Kelly (Col. Leo Vitelli).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
