<HEADER>
A6019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-GARLIC-ART-3TAKES-NYT     08-31 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARLIC-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOVE THAT BITES BACK: VARIETIES OF GARLIC IN SWEET AND PUNGENT
GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON CORNERS, N.Y. _ The overhead door of the big shed at La
Terre Garlic Farm was open as my car crunched over the gravel
driveway on one of those perfect cloudless summer mornings in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, I could see a long table set with a white cloth where
Ruth Nosonowitz was puttering under rows and rows of newly
harvested garlic, the bulbs hanging by their yellowing leaves, dirt
still clinging to their roots.
</P>
<P>
   The table had been set with a cutting board, a sharp knife, a
bottle of olive oil, chunks of baguette, bottled water, a large
bunch of parsley and several varieties of new garlic. Nearby, Mrs.
Nosonowitz had ready pesto, garlic soup and garlic puree.
</P>
<P>
   This was a tasting I was both eagerly anticipating and mildly
dreading.
</P>
<P>
   I had come for a garlic refresher course. I knew garlic came in
white and purple and something called elephant, which is actually
not garlic but a member of the leek family.
</P>
<P>
   I knew that some types had hard large cloves and were easy to
peel, that others had tiny cloves that were almost impossible to
peel. But I had no idea that garlic came in 200 varieties, with
some subtle and some not so subtle differences.
</P>
<P>
   I considered garlic generic _ whatever the grocery store had was
good enough, even though it might well be bitter because of its
age. I had no idea that it had lost whatever subtleties it might
have had when it was newly harvested. I certainly had no idea that
once I tasted fresh garlic, I would never want to use any other
kind.
</P>
<P>
   I was about to learn what those who frequent farmers' markets or
grow their own already know: some garlic is mellow, some pungent,
some sweet, some astringent and some have a bite that lasts and
lasts.
</P>
<P>
   I was anticipating the tasting because I love garlic; I was
anxious because I was sure the dreaded garlic breath would be with
me for the next two days. But that was why Mrs. Nosonowitz had set
out that bunch of parsley; chewing a few sprigs after each sample
of the several varieties she grows saved me. And that is one of the
few rules of garlic that applies to all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nosonowitz and her husband, David, an endodontist in nearby
Pleasant Valley, have been growing garlic for seven years. This
year, they planted 110,000 bulbs, by tucking a clove of each into
the soil.
</P>
<P>
   All of their garlic is organic, as is the rocambole variety
grown by Keith Stewart at Keith's Farm in Greenville, in western
Orange County, that he sells at the Union Square Greenmarket in
Manhattan. ``It's frightening what they spray on garlic,'' Mrs.
Nosonowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the peak of the garlic season. Growers in the Northeast
have harvested their crop and have either just finished curing it,
or will soon. They hang the garlic by its leaves for several weeks
under controlled temperatures and humidity, with fans blowing to
dry it. After the garlic is trimmed and cleaned, it is sorted
according to size and variety, and placed in string bags, which are
hung from the same rafters. From July to November, cured garlic is
at its best.
</P>
<P>
   If this local garlic is stored properly _ in a cool dry place in
a string bag or garlic keeper _ it will last until February and be
better than anything the supermarket has to offer, which is
commercially grown garlic that has come from thousands of miles
away. Almost 90 percent of the garlic sold in the United States
comes from California.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest differences between local and California
garlic is the basic variety: the former is hardneck, which sends up
a central stalk and is more tolerant of colder climates;
California's is softneck, which has a very small central stem.
</P>
<P>
   Chester Aaron, who grows 87 kinds of garlic in Sonoma County,
Calif., and is the author of ``The Great Garlic Book'' (Ten Speed
Press, 1997), is partial to hardneck garlic. He said commercial
farmers prefer the softneck because it is easier to grow, produces
greater yields, is less labor intensive and lasts longer. But most
softneck garlic has smaller cloves that are more difficult to peel
and, many insist, tastes harsher. (It may just be that it is older
when it gets here.)
</P>
<P>
   Hardneck garlic, Aaron said, ``has a span of tastes that is far
wider than softneck. Whenever I do a tasting I will put out both,
and people's response is always that the hardneck is far
superior.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences were certainly clear when Mrs. Nosonowitz sat me
down to taste her products, freshly minced and offered on a spoon.
She started me off with her favorite, Prussian White, also known as
Music. It was pungent, with a pleasing aftertaste. Then, we moved
on to Italian rocambole, one of the most popular garlics, somewhat
gentler than the Prussian but still pungent.
</P>
<P>
   German White was quite strong, with heat that hit at the back of
the throat; Marino was quite mild; German Red, which Mrs.
Nosonowitz said is always the strongest, was obviously different
this year because it was quite mild. Spanish Roja was strong, with
a bite on the tip of the tongue and a long garlic aftertaste. No.
65, not a particularly romantic name, packed the biggest wallop, a
slightly delayed hit at the back of the throat.
</P>
<P>
   The Prussian and the German White are porcelains, with white
skins and little or no purple; the others are rocamboles, which are
tan to white, with varying amounts of purple.
</P>
<P>
   The elephant garlic was, as always, perfect for those who aren't
sure they really like garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Those were my tasting notes, though. Mrs. Nosonowitz's were the
same in only some instances. As with wine, the taste of garlic is
very personal.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I tried the chopped-up garlic that had been sitting for a
while. All of it was much gentler because its volatile oils begin
to dissipate once it is chopped, but the individual characteristics
remain. Spanish Roja, for example, was still more pungent than the
others.
</P>
<P>
   What struck me more than the various levels of bite or pungency
was the lack of bitterness that is so often part of the supermarket
bulb.
</P>
<P>
   After consuming plenty of water and bread, not to mention half a
bunch of parsley, we then moved on to the pesto, garlic puree and
garlic soup. The freshness of the flavors proved the difference
between supermarket garlic and the local kinds.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Alice Waters, who has been credited with reviving interest in
garlic in American cooking and does a garlic dinner at her
restaurant, Chez Panisse, on Bastille Day, summed up the appeal.
``The moment garlic is harvested, it's got an irresistible quality
about it,'' she said in a telephone interview. ``You can eat it raw
because it's very sweet and very pure. But as the year progresses,
we cook it more. Every day that garlic is drying, it's changing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, the first shoots of garlic, called scapes, appear
and develop seed pods on the tips of their very graceful stems. The
scapes are cut from the growing bulbs and used for the delicate
garlic flavor they impart. Some call them garlic scallions; others
think their texture is more like a blend of garlic and green beans.
Later in the season, young garlic, whose bulb looks like a swollen
spring onion, comes to farmers' markets. And sometime in July or
August, the harvest of the mature bulbs begins.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hoffman, the chef and owner of Savoy on Prince Street in
Manhattan, features whole bulbs at this time of year ``because it
is sweeter, creamier and has a smoother texture when it's
roasted,'' he said. ``I buy special garlic. It's local and has
incredible juice and life and has great full flavor, partly because
it's fresh. God knows how long California garlic has been stored.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Georges Vongerichten, the owner of Jean Georges, compares
garlic to ginger. ``There are so many different kinds,'' he said.
``When it's new it's very different.''
</P>
<P>
   Savoy, Jean Georges, Picholine and EQ buy La Terre's garlic
(800-909-2272 or 914-266-4320). What they look for are large firm
bulbs, and price is no object. A pound of garlic costs less than $3
in a supermarket, but La Terre's is $3.50 a pound plus shipping,
with a minimum order of $10. Stewart, at his stand at Union Square,
sells his for $1.25 a head ($6 to $8 a pound).
</P>
<P>
   He says the price to some shoppers may seem like garlic to a
vampire, but those who want the best-tasting heads, fresh and firm
with the largest, most easily peeled cloves, are hardly going to be
put off by price. Garlic is like corn and tomatoes: fresh and local
is always best.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. THREE SIDEBARS AND FOUR RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   APPEAR IN FOLLOWING TAKES)
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THE MOST FROM GARLIC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By MARIAN BURROS
</P>
<P>
   Even with fresh local garlic, there are ways to get more out of
a bulb. Here are a few tips.
</P>
<P>
   _ Choose garlic by weight and size; the heavier it is, the
fresher it is likely to be; large heads have bigger cloves that
take longer to dry out.
</P>
<P>
   _ The more garlic is cooked, the milder it gets: roasting
produces a mild, sweet, nutty flavor; boiling, a mild flavor;
sauteing, a moderately strong flavor with more bite than boiled but
less intensity than chopped raw.
</P>
<P>
   _ Garlic sauteed with onion will almost always burn. To avoid
this, add the garlic at the end.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fresh garlic does not burn as quickly as older garlic because
it has more moisture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use stronger garlic for roasting a chicken; for flans, use a
more delicate variety.
</P>
<P>
   _ The green germ that grows in the center of each clove does not
need to be removed in fresh garlic; but later it becomes bitter and
should be cut away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not store garlic in the refrigerator. Keep it in a cool,
dry place in a net bag or a garlic keeper so that air can
circulate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chop garlic at the very last minute; as soon as it is chopped,
it begins to change, to lose some of its characteristic pungency.
</P>
<P>
   To make chopping garlic easier, add a pinch of salt, which keeps
the garlic from sticking to the knife. The grains also help crush
the garlic.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST SIDEBAR ENDS HERE. TWO MORE SIDEBARS, AND FOUR RECIPES,
FOLLOW) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GROWING GARLIC IN THE GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   By RICHARD W. LANGER
</P>
<P>
   What separates great homegrown garlic from just good garlic is a
carefully tended garden, not too surprisingly. And garlic lovers
have just a few weeks to prepare for next year's crop, which should
be planted around the first day of autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Neophytes should know that a clove from an existing garlic bulb
is the seed for a new one: break the bulbs apart and insert the
individual cloves in the soil root end down, about two to three
inches deep and four to six inches apart. All things being equal,
the larger the clove you plant, the larger the bulb you will
harvest next July or August. But the garlic will demand that you
give it a care or two in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   The soil for garlic needs to be loose, easily crumbled and well
drained. If the soil is hard packed, clayey or gravelly, it will
not allow the bulb to expand as it grows. Small, soil-squished
bulbs sometimes develop a more intense flavor, but the effect is
usually disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Raised beds filled with rich soil supplemented with sand, bone
meal, ash and other sources of minerals give garlic an excellent
footing. But if you use raised beds or grow garlic in containers or
on a terrace, make sure the soil never dries out. Garlic likes soil
that is constantly moist, but never wet. Wet soil induces fungus
and blight.
</P>
<P>
   In November, mulch the garlic heavily to a depth of at least six
inches. Come spring, you can just pull the mulch aside and leave it
around the plants for moisture conservation and weed control. It
will break down and enrich the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic originated in central Asia, in a region of long cold
winters, damp cool springs and hot dry summers. Areas of the United
States with similar climates are good for garlic, especially the
Rocambole varieties, which are the closest to their wild cousins in
their growing preferences. Rocamboles and the Silverskin varieties
are more flavorsome than the Artichoke variety from California most
often found in the supermarket. The Artichoke is easy to grow (it
does not need as long a winter as other varieties), but why grow
what you can buy so cheaply?
</P>
<P>
   First-time garlic growers might consider two good-looking
varieties: the Porcelain (golden brown with purple streaks) or the
Purple Stripe. These two are a bit more drought tolerant and better
for those who go away for weeks at a time in the summer and let the
garden fend for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant garlic _ very mild tasting but botanically not a true
garlic at all, but rather a relative of the leek _ is usually
disease free and not bothered by insects, but is a little more
frost sensitive. With so many varieties to try, a garlic grower is
never bored.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest your garlic when the leaves have half yellowed. Lift,
don't pull, the bulbs out with a spading fork so as not to damage
the stems. If you bruise the crop, it will not store well.
</P>
<P>
   Let the bulbs lie and cure in a dry, cool shaded place. In two
to four weeks you can cut off the stem and not be overwhelmed by
the smell of garlic. Remove all but a quarter to a half inch of
root and an inch of stem. Store the bulbs as close to 50 or 55
degrees as possible in an area with good air circulation. Cardboard
egg cartons (but not plastic) work well as containers.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND SIDEBAR ENDS HERE. THIRD SIDEBAR AND FOUR RECIPES
</P>
