<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-DINING-COLD-NOODLES-A     08-31 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINING-COLD-NOODLES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN NOODLE DISHES TO BEAT THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN RAICHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chinese have the perfect antidote to a late-summer heat
wave: cold wheat noodles, served with a piquant sesame sauce. The
soothing noodles are ice, the sauce fire, in the form of chili
paste, ginger and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably as many versions of this traditional Sichuan
dish, called dan dan noodles, as there are individual cooks. But
the Chinese are hardly the only Asians to have discovered that hot
weather requires cool thinking. The Japanese and Koreans also beat
the heat with an array of flavorful cold noodle dishes that are
irresistibly refreshing, whether you sample them in a restaurant or
make them at home.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best cold soba noodles this side of Tokyo can be
found in SoHo, at Honmura An. In this cool, Zen-like space, with
its high ceilings and uncluttered decor, you can watch the
buckwheat noodles being kneaded, rolled out and cut by hand. The
flour is ground on the premises, so of course the soba is
exquisite. But what really shows off the noodles is a cool,
delicately flavored broth that plays the briny tang of bonito
flakes and soy sauce against the sweetness of sake and mirin, a
sweet rice wine.
</P>
<P>
   Cold soba comes two ways at Honmura An _ in broth in a bowl or
on a plate with the broth served separately as a dipping sauce.
Accompaniments range from simple (slivered nori seaweed or bonito
flakes) to elaborate (sticky nameko mushrooms or gooey pearls of
ikura, salmon roe). And almost always, there's a fiery wallop of
wasabi.
</P>
<P>
   Honmura An's owner, Koichi Kobari, said the true connoisseur
prefers to eat soba cold. ``Hot broth makes the noodles swell,'' he
said, ``so you can better appreciate the texture of the soba when
it's served cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Eating cold soba calls for a personal touch: you stir in chopped
scallions, slivered nori, wasabi and other flavorings to suit your
taste.
</P>
<P>
   One dish found everywhere in Seoul, South Korea, mool naeng
myun, raises noodle soup to the level of art. It features slender
buckwheat noodles in an icy beef broth with a kaleidoscopic
assortment of sliced beef, pickled cucumbers, hard cooked eggs,
Asian pear and radish. For the diner, the dish is a study in
contrasts: chewy beef, crunchy cucumbers, chilly broth and hot
Chinese mustard.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes here may require a trip to an Asian market, but
natural-food stores may carry some items, too. For an impromptu
meal, I sometimes take an everything-but-the-kitchen-sink approach
to the cold noodle, combining flavorings from several different
Asian cuisines. The noodle salad here contains fish sauce and basil
from Thailand and lemongrass and chili paste from Vietnam, with an
ecumenical sprinkling of peanuts and bean sprouts for crunch. I
can't think of a better dish for lunch or light supper when the
weather runs to Indian summer.
</P>
<P>
   COOL SOBA NOODLES WITH SWEET SOY BROTH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the broth:
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 tablespoon) instant dashi
</P>
<P>
   \ cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons mirin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sake
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the noodles:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces dried soba noodles
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons wasabi powder
</P>
<P>
   4 scallions, green part only, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 sheet nori seaweed, cut into matchstick slivers
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons dried bonito flakes (optional).
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine 4 cups water, dashi powder, soy sauce, mirin, sake
and sugar in bowl. Whisk until dashi and sugar dissolve; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring 4 quarts water to boil in large saucepan. Add soba
noodles, and cook until tender, about 6 minutes. Drain noodles in
colander, rinse with cold water until cool, and drain again.
</P>
<P>
   3. Combine wasabi powder and 1 tablespoon water in a small bowl,
and stir. Let stand about 6 minutes, until it becomes a thick
paste. Using your finger, form 4 small balls.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, divide noodles among 4 bowls, and ladle broth over
them. Arrange wasabi balls, scallion greens, nori and dried bonito
flakes (if using) on top of noodles. Using chopsticks, dissolve
wasabi balls into broth; do not eat whole. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   DAN DAN NOODLES
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces thin fresh Chinese wheat noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil, plus 3 tablespoons
</P>
<P>
   { cup sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 scallions, white part minced, green part thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   { cup smooth peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons Chinese chili paste or hot bean paste (or to
taste)
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cook noodles in 4 quarts rapidly boiling water until tender,
for 4 to 5 minutes. Drain in colander, rinse with cold water, and
drain again. In bowl, toss noodles with 1 teaspoon sesame oil.
Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   2. Lightly toast sesame seeds in dry skillet. In food processor,
place 5 tablespoons seeds, plus ginger, garlic, white scallions,
peanut butter, { cup water, soy sauce, vinegar, sugar, chili paste,
pepper and remaining oil. Process until smooth. Sauce should be
highly seasoned and pourable. Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   3. Divide noodles among 4 bowls, and pour sauce over them.
Sprinkle scallion greens and remaining sesame seeds on top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN NOODLE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the dressing:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk fresh lemongrass, trimmed and minced (about 2
tablespoons)
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   \ cup Thai fish sauce or soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Vietnamese or Thai chili paste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Chinese wheat or buckwheat noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced cooked shrimp or lobster (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups mung bean sprouts
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded Napa cabbage
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, cut into matchstick slivers
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, peeled, halved lengthwise, seeded and cut into
matchstick slivers
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh cilantro leaves, plus 4 whole sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh Thai or regular basil leaves, cut into slivers
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh mint leaves, cut into slivers
</P>
<P>
   2 jalapeno chilies or to taste, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped dry-roasted peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine dressing ingredients in bowl, and whisk until honey
dissolves. Adjust seasoning to taste. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cook noodles in boiling salted water until tender, about 5
minutes. Drain in colander, rinse with cold water until cool, and
drain. Place noodles in salad bowl; toss with oil.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir in shrimp or lobster (if using), bean sprouts, cabbage,
carrots, cucumber, cilantro leaves, basil, mint and half the
chilies. Stir in dressing. Divide noodles among 4 plates, sprinkle
with peanuts, and garnish with reserved chilies and cilantro
sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
