<HEADLINE>
WHERE ARE THE LOST CHICKS?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies DIXIE CHICKS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before ``Wide Open Spaces,'' bare midriffs, blond ambition and
the occasional cuss word onstage, the Dixie Chicks were four
cowgirls of differing ages, hair colors and musical direction,
united by fringe and pearl snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank heavens,'' they sang, ``for Dale Evans.''
</P>
<P>
   Where are they now, those lost Chicks with the bluegrass ballads
and eccentric cowgirl style?
</P>
<P>
   Robin Macy, the first of the original Chicks to get walking
papers, doesn't like to talk about the experience or give
interviews, friends say.
</P>
<P>
   She married guitarist Mark Bennett and is living in Kansas City,
where they have transformed an arboretum into a one-of-a-kind
house. The two of them still perform informally.
</P>
<P>
   After her departure from the Chicks, Macy participated in
several musical ventures in the mid-'90s, notably the Domestic
Science Club with Sara Hickman, an eclectic/folk trio that released
a critically praised album.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Lynch, the bubbly brunette with the stand-up bass, married
Weatherford, Texas, cattleman Mac Tull after she was eased out of
the lineup. Now, she presides over a three-teen-ager household: her
daughter, Asia, 18 in September; and Tull's children, Meriwether,
16, and Christopher, 13.
</P>
<P>
   She first met Tull, a family friend, when she was 16, and he
would go out to her father's ranch in Dell City _ to take her
sister out.
</P>
<P>
   ``She sort of bequeathed him to me,'' Lynch said, laughing. ``I
ran into Mac again in '96 at an open house at Eagle Audio, and we
both said, `There you are.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch manages to keep busy in her post-Chick life, which has led
her full circle to the real Dale Evans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite thing I'm most excited about is the Cowgirl Hall
of Fame, and the groundbreaking this year,'' she said. ``It's such
a uniquely American museum, and Fort Worth was really on top of
things to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch is on the capital campaign committee, ``my
out-of-the-house deal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the music business, ``I'm still dreamin' about it,''
Lynch said. ``But it takes so much energy, and the blessing and
luck of it is, it takes chemistry. And you don't just go out and
find that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch tries to keep up with all current and former Chicks, band
members, agents and others, and spurns offers of solo gigs.
Someday, she says, she might put a band together and do something
low-key.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an `us' girl, not a `me' girl,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite it all, relations are cordial with the current Chick
lineup, Lynch said: ``Martie and Emmy keep up with me more than
ever now.''
</P>
<P>
   She often comments on the early Chicks for media and television.
Her worst nightmare? Bad pix of the early Chicks that keep
surfacing, from TV to tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we had our cute days,'' she pined, ``but they always
run something ancient and heinous.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
