<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIXIECHICKS-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACHING FOR THE SKY: CHICKS `FLY' TO NEW HEIGHTS WITH SECOND
EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies DIXIE CHICKS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone obviously forgot to tell the Dixie Chicks about the
dreaded sophomore slump, in which a band puts out a great first CD
and then a miserable-by-comparison second.
</P>
<P>
   Released Tuesday, ``Fly,'' the follow-up to the trio's
6-million-sold-and-counting 1997 debut, ``Wide Open Spaces,'' is
fairly amazing on two fronts: One, that it's just so darned good,
and two, that it was made under so much pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not kid ourselves _ amid all the shows, all the interviews
and all the travel, making a weak follow-up would have been, well,
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't happen: This 13-song CD is the equal of the first and
maybe, just maybe, better. No kidding. ``Fly'' is the real deal, a
batch of sometimes bitingly funny, wickedly sexy or heartbreakingly
sad songs about love lost and found, raising a little hell _ see
the hilarious ``Sin Wagon'' _ and, on ``Goodbye Earl,'' making an
abusive ex disappear. Permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Empowerment-country is all the rage these days, but lead
vocalist Natalie Maines, fiddle player Martie Seidel and banjoist
Emily Robison have a lock on it, a knack for looking at young women
in various situations and making each one believable.
</P>
<P>
   You believe Maines whether she's looking at the joy of found
love on ``Cowboy Take Me Away,'' having a simple good ol' time on
``Some Days You Gotta Dance,'' staying away from a bad boy on the
Buddy Miller/Jim Lauderdale-penned ``Hole in My Head,'' or finding
the courage to let go of a relationship that just isn't going to
work, as on the quiet closer, Patty Griffin's ``Let Him Fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the perspective, these songs ring true, and the Chicks
and their studio buds (including steel guitarist and Natalie's
daddy, Lloyd Maines, and excellent organ players Steve Nathan and
Matt Rollings) rip through them like music's going to be made
illegal tomorrow. Blistering instrumental trade-offs are the rule
here but are most impressive on ``Cowboy'' and the breakneck ``Sin
Wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   And the harmonies? As was expected, fab.
</P>
<P>
   It's now apparent that ``Wide Open Spaces'' wasn't a fluke, and
that by balancing perspectives and story lines and singing like
barroom-savvy angels, this trio is going to be one of country's
finest for years to come. Perhaps two of the tunes here _ ``Without
You'' and ``Heartbreak Town'' _ are just OK, just good country
music. Otherwise, ``Fly'' takes off and doesn't look back.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Chicks
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly''
</P>
<P>
   Sony Music Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
