<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-PRINCE-EDWARD-2TAK     08-31 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRINCE-EDWARD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCE EDWARD, TAKING TEA AND MEETINGS, COMES TO HOLLYWOOD AS
PITCHMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood is a town that, for all the mumbo jumbo
about creativity, breeds a striking sameness _ in dress (Armani
casual), in automobiles (anything outrageously expensive), in
speech patterns (``Love ya!''), in ambition (multimillion-dollar
guaranteed contracts) and even in the frequency with which people
talk about seeking something different.
</P>
<P>
   But with the lords of the television industry in turmoil these
days, maybe it is time for the pattern to be broken by a
soft-spoken Englishman, one with almost no experience in American
media, a wardrobe filled with the sort of neckties people here
threw away after high school and a fondness for tales of kings and
queens rather than footloose 20-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   Just such a young man has come to America and in a relatively
short time has met with about every power in a town that often
takes more delight in the meetings rejected than the ones taken.
The young man's agent, the courtly Southerner Sam Haskell of the
William Morris Agency, said that for virtually the first time in
his career not a single person had turned down a meeting with the
overseas visitor, and some actually pleaded for invitations to dine
with him. In short order the visitor has lined up agreements to
develop movies or series with NBC, Showtime, CBS, Paramount and the
Fox Family Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Over breakfast the suddenly hot, newly anointed mini media baron
sat ramrod straight in a navy blazer that he never unbuttoned, pale
blue and yellow tie in a whimsical pussycat pattern and jaunty
brown suede loafers. As he nibbled on fruit and yogurt and sipped
tea (he had to instruct the waitress to let it brew, so unpracticed
was she in the art of preparing a cup in this latte-sipping burg),
he explained that, great ideas or not, his presence here was
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is where the money is,'' said the canny newcomer,
Edward Windsor, who spoke delightedly of ``our business'' with a
brio that showed only traces of the English reserve with which he
was famously raised. Windsor, who is 35 and recently married, has a
checkered business record and, as it happens, is the third son of
Britain's Queen Elizabeth II. He is a prince, but in a realm with
its own notion of royalty he insists on the name Edward Windsor, or
just Edward, and describes himself disarmingly as someone who
``just wants what anyone in this business wants.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that, here anyway, that means money, and
that if he struck it really big he could buy a castle, he replied
dryly, ``Or repair one.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is famous for being jaded and insular, but Windsor
described it as a breath of fresh air compared with the Britain he
knows, and it was clear that he left many executives here
starry-eyed. Since he started his television production company,
Ardent Productions, in 1993, his treatment in the British media has
generally ranged from skeptical to savage, largely because of the
heavy losses the company has accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hate anyone who succeeds,'' Windsor said early in the
meal, served in a private suite with a single security man in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a much greater openness and willingness to take us
for what we are here,'' he added. ``Over there there's more
baggage, if you understand that expression.''
</P>
<P>
   The ardor goes both ways. Hollywood people who have met Windsor
stumbled over their words in talking about their encounters, and
acknowledged that they leapt at project ideas partly because they
would be produced by a real Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Lindy DeKoven, an executive vice president for movies and
mini-series at NBC, recently agreed to develop a mini-series about
Windsor's grandmother, the Queen Mother, and said it was unlike any
other professional experience she had had, particularly the first
lunch. ``I didn't even expect a meeting,'' Ms. DeKoven said. ``I
really just said to Sam once, `If you're having one of your parties
with him, please invite me.' I didn't know this was a pitch meeting
until it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But that did not put her off. She said Windsor had been
talkative and was well informed about his family's background.
``It's not often that you have lunch with a producer who really
knows something about history,'' Ms. DeKoven said. ``I can't put my
finger on it and say why, but it was kind of awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeKoven insisted that she would never commit millions of
dollars to a project just because the producer was related to a
monarch, but she did concede that Windsor was certainly not a
veteran at television.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were curious to know how you sell projects and
everything,'' said Ms. DeKoven, referring to Windsor and his
development executive, Nigel McCrery. ``I was kind of surprised at
some of the things they were asking.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Windsor said he understood that inspiring awe is not enough; he
knows he must prove himself with his productions. So far he has
sold ideas, which may not make it to television screens unless the
quality satisfies the networks.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to produce documentaries, detective shows and
historical dramas, he said, but conceded that he was probably
destined to have his failures remembered more than his successes.
</P>
<P>
   He has had his share of misfires in Britain. ``It's a Royal
Knockout,'' which he produced in 1987, was a game show to raise
money for a charity. The show was generally considered an
embarrassment. He later produced ``Annie's Bar,'' a political
satire that ran for one episode and was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   He started Ardent in 1993 and had his first success with
``Edward on Edward,'' a documentary about his great-uncle, King
Edward VIII, who abdicated the throne in 1936 to marry an American
divorcee, Wallis Warfield Simpson. He was later involved in
``Castle Ghosts of England,'' which ran in the United States on the
Learning Channel, and ``Crown and Country,'' a series on the royal
family's influence over English history, which he narrated and
which ran on public television in the United States. He has started
developing another documentary, potentially for CBS, on the
paparazzi who have bedeviled members of the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   He feels obligated to produce occasional shows about the royal
family, he said, but is much more interested in doing more of the
sort of show ideas he sold recently to the Showtime cable channel.
One is a new movie version of the Mark Twain story ``The Prince and
the Pauper,'' appropriately enough the tale of a prince who trades
places with a look-alike commoner. He is developing two other
movies for Showtime that could involve budgets totaling more than
$10 million if they are completed.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Zakarin, an executive vice president at Showtime who is
developing the movie ideas with Windsor, said it had been a heady
experience. ``You do get jaded in this business,'' Zakarin said.
``You meet the Hollywood stars, but there is a curiosity as to how
these guys'' _ meaning British royalty _ ``are different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I tell my wife before I went to the first meeting that I
was meeting a prince?'' Zakarin asked. ``Sure I did.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was impressed that Windsor clearly intended to be
intimately involved in the productions and not just lend his name.
``He does what all real producers are supposed to do but often
don't,'' Zakarin said. ``He picks up the phone and calls the talent
and asks them to get involved in the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Windsor said he liked that part of the job best, mixing with
commoners in a common enterprise and feeling useful. ``I do enjoy
it because it's what the business is all about,'' he said. ``You
feel like you're part of the team. Our business demands that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
