<SLUG> BC-WORST-TABLES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN NICE PEOPLE GET BAD TABLES AT GOOD RESTAURANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eat out enough in this city, and chances are some
maitre d'hotel is going to stick you in Siberia. Once used for the
tourist-trap second floor at the old Russian Tea Room, the term
Siberia has become a metaphor for second-class seating.
</P>
<P>
   To the right of the door at Nobu. The frisbee-size table at the
entrance of Balthazar. Behind a column at Mercer Kitchen or Pop. In
any place's obvious bad-table zone: a drab tacked-on room, next to
a swinging kitchen door or the restrooms, within earshot of a
nerve-jangling service station.
</P>
<P>
   With more restaurants opening than at any time in recent history
_ some 50 this fall alone _ and more money behind them for space
and design, bad tables should have been wiped out, like smallpox.
But Tim Zagat, publisher of the restaurant guides, estimates that
his office sees 30 complaints a day on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Are there really so many bad tables at good restaurants? If
there are better tables open, why do paying customers so often get
the dogs? Most importantly, if a diner is dissed by a lousy
location, what is he or she supposed to do about it?
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Palmer, who owns Aureole, is the rare restaurateur to
acknowledge he had a Siberia problem. He had to: He noticed
comments in the reservation book like ``Don't put me upstairs.'' As
a result, the restaurant is redesigning its cramped, loud upper
level. The kitchen is up there, and a table that was right in front
of it has been taken out, with the three adjacent tables turned
into what Palmer called a ``cozy alcove.'' There will be more
fabric and carpeting to cut down on the noise.
</P>
<P>
   There is an element of subjectivity in all this. As Palmer
observed, ``Somebody's idea of a bad table is somebody else's idea
of a great table.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the bar, away from the bar. Banquette or center table. At
Cafe Boulud, some people request the little train-car nook facing
the bar and a service station. Can a tiny place like the Pearl
Oyster Bar be said to have a bad table? They're all equally bad, or
equally good, if you love oysters. At Ruby Foo's, the second floor
is the hot floor. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the main room at many traditional French restaurants,
like La Caravelle, diners have to go through a narrow section with
tables on either wall. Sometimes called the ``royale,'' this can be
considered the hot area both for people-watching and proximity to
the front desk, because the maitre d'hotel or captain can take
better care of you. Or it could be thought of as a traffic
nightmare, like living on a highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key things in life is not to be shy and sit there
feeling bad about yourself,'' Zagat said. Most of the time, they'll
move you, he continued. If not, he added, ask the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Gustafsson, the service director at Gotham Bar and Grill,
said that her restaurant's policy was, ``If somebody is not happy
with their table and we can move them, then we do.'' But as Ms.
Levine found, policy does not always translate into practice.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bastianich, a co-owner of Babbo, said he had reseated
customers up to three and four times.``We call it table hopping,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bastianich, like most restaurateurs, insisted, ``We have no bad
tables,'' but he agreed that ``the perception is that the place to
be is downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained his rationale for who gets seated where.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm working the door, you try to gauge people's
expectations and take advantage of that,'' he said. ``If you see
someone who's not going to care where they're sitting, you give
them a table that's more appropriate for them'' _ like businessmen,
he hastened to add, as opposed to a couple looking for a romantic
evening. Asked what category of customer would possibly want to sit
in the terrible triangle of kitchen-bathroom-bus station, he said,
``The last table is the last table.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateurs also say that their architects are now more
conscious of hiding service stations, kitchen entrances and the
like. Pia Prevost, a partner in CPS Design, a New York architecture
firm, has worked on several restaurants, including La Fourchette
and the new Southwest NY, scheduled to open next week in the World
Financial Center. ``I try to avoid any view into kitchen area,''
she said. ``The next point is bathrooms. If you sit at a table and
four feet away you can see the water closet, that is not very
nice.'' At La Fourchette, the kitchen is a level below the dining
room.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Nieporent took issue with the hypothesis that anyone seated
in the front right at Nobu is a nobody. ``You make the table, the
table doesn't make you,'' he said. ``The food's going to taste the
same whether you're sitting at one table or another.''
</P>
<P>
   At Nobu, he added, some diners start to protest when the hostess
leads them to the back of the restaurant, ``until they see a
celebrity.'' One glimpse of Robert De Niro and they wouldn't dream
of sitting anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming everyone's worst fears about the judgments made at
the front desk of a supertrendy hotel restaurant, Terrence
Wittmaack described his days as an assistant manager at Heartbeat,
Nieporent's restaurant in the W New York hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all unwritten,'' Wittmaack said (he left the restaurant
business a couple of months ago to become a contractor).
Unfashionably dressed hotel guests ``would be shoved up in the
front by the bar or put in the back so they wouldn't be seen,'' he
said. VIP's in T-shirts and ripped jeans would get the opposite
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to tell you there's not a single bad table in the
restaurant, but we know exactly where the bad tables are,'' he
said. Why assign someone a bad table when a good one is available?
The attitude, he said, was, ``We're going to pawn it off on you,
and if you accept it, great. Then it's like we kind of just
scored.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
