<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTSIDE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE': WHAT'S UP AT PREP SCHOOL? CULTURE SHOCK
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Outside Providence'' is about the circumstances that plunk Tim
Dunphy (Shawn Hatosy) into a Connecticut prep school classroom,
where he winds up answering ``Hamlet'' when asked to name his
favorite author. He also tries ``NASA'' when asked who launched the
New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dunph, as his friends call him, has not the faintest
desire to make good in this setting, his irreverence sets the tone
for Peter Farrelly's laid-back, raffishly funny 1988 novel and for
this eminently likable film version. ``Outside Providence'' doesn't
have time or piety for the usual coming-of-age hallmarks, and it
doesn't even bother to contrive much of an older-but-wiser happy
ending, unless you count the one supplied by fate.
</P>
<P>
   Farrelly, whose book was somewhat autobiographical (though he is
a doctor's son with a background significantly different from
Dunph's), went on to write and direct ``There's Something About
Mary'' with his brother, Bobby. That certainly qualifies as having
the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There once was a boy from Pawtucket. ...'' reads a road sign
featured in ads for ``Outside Providence,'' indicating that the
``There's Something About Mary'' sensibility is not far from hand.
Both its frat-house raunch and its improbable sweetness color this
account, circa 1974, of a boy from a blue-collar Rhode Island
background who is sent into culture shock by his bellicose father.
(Old Man Dunphy's nickname for his son is notably more coarse than
``Dunph.'')
</P>
<P>
   But ``Outside Providence'' also has an affectingly dramatic side
thanks to Michael Corrente (``Federal Hill''), another of Rhode
Island's finest, who wrote the film with the Farrellys and adds
some of his own experience to the mix. The part of the film that
details Dunph's fractious relationship with his father is
especially potent, thanks to a splendid performance from Alec
Baldwin in a far cry from his usual roles. Beneath that leading
man's exterior is a tough, versatile character actor who can
dominate a story from the sidelines, as the loudmouthed senior
Dunphy does here.
</P>
<P>
   Old Man Dunphy, who spends much of his time playing cards with
the group of like-minded bigots who are his cronies, has raised his
boys alone and has not been made more pleasant by that experience.
And since Dunph, while in Pawtucket, spends his time loafing and
smoking dope with his own no less dead-ended buddies, he inevitably
serves as a lightning rod for his father's angry outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   One day, a stoned fender-bender with a police car seals Dunph's
fate, and the father pulls strings to have him shipped off to
boarding school. Baldwin delivers a very funny evocation of the old
man's benighted side but also makes it plausible that a loving
parent is buried beneath all that bluster.
</P>
<P>
   When Dunph, played with disarming naturalness by Hatosy, arrives
at the school carrying his belongings in a trash bag, it looks as
if we're headed for another sociological skirmish among spoiled
schoolboys and less privileged ones. But one of the most likable
things about ``Outside Providence'' is its way of shrugging this
off, letting Dunph make friends easily, and just sending up the
place's prim atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The movie becomes sidesplitting, more than a few times, when
Dunph's worlds collide: The dean (George Martin) intercepts a
pricelessly lethal letter from Dunph's Pawtucket pal, Drugs Delaney
(Jon Abrahams), who clearly deserves his nickname. Just the dean's
reading this letter aloud, stone-faced, is enough to bring down the
house.
</P>
<P>
   The film, with a ``Rushmore''-like mix of sharply funny
observations and been-there-done-that knowingness, offers an
irresistible sketchbook filled with prep school memories. They
range from Dunph's first love (Amy Smart) to his nerdy roommate
(Jack Ferver) to the eternal dormitory nemesis (Tim Crowe) just
waiting to catch the students misbehaving.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film includes the masturbation gag that has become
the authorial stamp of the Farrellys, it weaves a surprising amount
of wisdom and tenderness into all these antics. Only one
well-meaning extra flourish, in which Old Man Dunphy's gay-baiting
friends (in a group including George Wendt) get their comeuppance,
seems out of sync with a time period that is otherwise flawlessly
captured, Drugs Delaney and all. That effect is enhanced by a
soundtrack full of best-loved radio hits of the early 70's. An
overabundance of familiar songs usually feels like a desperate
measure; this time, it's a jukebox to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside Providence'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes colorful
profanity, frequent drug use and sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Corrente; written by Peter Farrelly,
Corrente and Bobby Farrelly, based on the novel by Peter Farrelly;
director of photography, Richard Crudo; edited by Kate Sanford;
music by Sheldon Mirowitz; production designer, Chad Detwiller;
produced by Peter Farrelly, Corrente, Bobby Farrelly and Randy
Finch; released by Miramax Films. Running time: 95 minutes. This
film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Shawn Hatosy (Tim Dunphy), Jon Abrahams (Drugs Delaney),
Jack Ferver (Irving Waltham), Amy Smart (Jane Weston), George Wendt
(Joey), Alec Baldwin (Old Man Dunphy), George Martin (Dean Mort)
and Tim Crowe (Funderburk).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
