<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-SCHOOL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE LAUNCHES NEW ANTIDRUG CAMPAIGN TO REACH KIDS IN CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With nearly 60 million youngsters returning to
school, the White House on Tuesday unveiled seven new anti-drug
campaigns aimed at reaching children in the classroom, on the
playing field, at home and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're straight with them, kids do listen; so we need to
give our children every opportunity to hear the facts on drugs, and
that means surrounding them with information,'' Barry McCaffrey,
director of the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy,
said at news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said the new campaigns are designed to go beyond
traditional advertising, such as radio and televisions commercials,
to reach children at all times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids spend a majority of their waking hours in school; so why
not use that to help get them the message about drugs,'' McCaffrey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns consist of:
</P>
<P>
   _ A documentary film about a cross-country trip by six high
school students who talked in different places with other
teen-agers, telling them about their own bad experiences with drugs
and alcohol. The film will be shown in 13 cities and distributed to
schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   _ A program to increase the number of reports in high school and
middle school newspapers that show harmful consequences of drug
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   _ The stepped-up use of anti-drug banners at sporting events and
rallies at high schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ The distribution of guides to teachers containing tips on how
to educate students of different ages about drugs.
</P>
<P>
   _ A program by cable TV companies around the country to give
schools, teachers and parents free access to more than 500 hours of
commercial-free educational programming on drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   _ An interactive Web site created by America Online in its Kids
Only channel where youngsters can learn about drugs, alcohol and
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   _ A special Spider-Man comic book series that teaches children
about drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey cited a recent study showing that drug abuse among
12-to-17-year-olds was down 13 percent in 1998 from its 1997 level.
That proves antidrug advertising has begun to change the way young
people look at illegal narcotics and alcohol, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has taken some time, but I believe we have turned the
corner on drug use in this country,'' McCaffrey added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russell Thompson, a 17-year-old student from Richmond, Va., and
one the six high schoolers featured in the antidrug documentary,
said students want information about drugs but don't want their
teachers and parents to preach to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids know the truth about drugs, they're usually smart
enough to realize how bad they are and that using them is a waste
of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Judi Kosterman, a former Seattle high school principal who works
for the Office of National Drug Control Policy, said television,
radio and magazine ads aren't enough to stop teen drug use. She
said the campaign must also involve teachers and coaches because
they, along with students' peers and parents, have the most
influence on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids need to hear the message about drugs not just from the TV
but from the people they see everyday in school because those are
the people they know and trust,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
