<HEADLINE>
A CAMP FOR CHILDREN OF GAY PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVADA CITY, Calif. _ Ten-year-old twins Alison and Jason are
accustomed to the two-mom concept. They've been living in a lesbian
household since they were born. But the world is still unaccustomed
to the idea, so Alison, who like other children in this story asked
that her last name not be used, gets questions from children at
school. ``They say, `How can you be born if you don't have a
dad?'''
</P>
<P>
   To which she responds, ``My mom got sperm from the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' she says, ``they ask, `What's sperm?'''
</P>
<P>
   For one week each summer, Alison and Jason and 28 other children
don't have to explain anything to anyone _ why they have two
mothers or two fathers or two mothers and one father.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Lavender Hill in the Sierra foothills outside Nevada
City _ the only camp in the United States exclusively for children
of gay, lesbian or bisexual parents _ they can be just plain
children.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, Abi, now 16 and a counselor-in-training, has gone
with her two sisters to Lavender Hill from Willits, which she
describes as ``not the most gay-friendly town.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp is the first place she referred to her mother's partner as
her ``other mother'' instead of her ``friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit camp, for children ages 7 to 14, is run by Chris
Van Stone, a children's therapist; Cindy Romero, a former special
education teacher turned real estate agent; and Catherine Brenegan,
a marriage, family and child counselor. Van Stone and Romero are
partners and live in Guerneville. Brenegan is from Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the counselors at this summer's camp were Sonoma State
University students. The counselors are either gay or from a gay
household.
</P>
<P>
   In this way everybody relates to the same lifestyle _ ``no one
has to watch their pronouns,'' said Mary Blanchette, mother of a
camper.
</P>
<P>
   The latest salvo in the battle over gay rights is a California
measure on the March 2000 ballot calling for a ban on same-sex
marriages. It is likely to spur further debate over gays' and
lesbians' becoming parents.
</P>
<P>
   Although state law already defines marriage as between a man and
a woman, the Definition of Marriage proposition was written when it
appeared that Hawaii would recognize gay marriages and force other
states to extend the recognition. Hawaii ended up voting against
same-sex marriage, and so far 30 states have adopted such bans.
</P>
<P>
   A California poll this June showed that voters are split almost
in half over both gay marriage and parenting. Nearly 60 percent of
voters said they think lesbians and gay men can be just as good at
parenting as heterosexuals, but 55 percent oppose same-sex
marriage. The poll, commissioned by the San Francisco-based
Horizons Foundation, which opposes the same-sex marriage ban
initiative, was matched by a Field Poll in April showing the same
level of support and opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But public opinion polls don't matter inside Camp Lavender Hill
nearly as much as lanyard making and who has the gummi worms.
</P>
<P>
   Kavita, 11, from Cambridge, Mass., said her favorite activity at
Lavender Hill was mini-Olympics day. Two years ago Kavita went to a
traditional camp in New Hampshire. When another camper told
everyone in their cabin that Kavita's mother is a lesbian, Kavita
was teased; she told her mother she didn't want to go back.
</P>
<P>
   Kavita is adopted, a native of India, and has two mothers. It's
the last detail that causes her the most discomfort, even though
she says, ``I don't feel I'm different just because my family is
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Stone, who started the camp in 1992, wanted ``a place for
kids to feel part of a community, where there are no secrets, where
they can talk openly and not hold back at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmanuel, a 9-year-old from Stockton, like some of the other
children tells of being taunted. ``Sometimes people at school call
me a faggot and I walk away.'' He liked being where people
understand that you can have two fathers. Otherwise, he said,
``Some people think it's bad, because it's more regular to have a
mom and dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the rainbow flag and the lavender triangles on some
of the art work, there is nothing obvious to set this camp apart
from any other.
</P>
<P>
   As a group the campers seem more mature than many children their
age. Counselor-in-training Abi explained, ``You jump into maturity
because it's a very mature issue. At age 8 you're dealing with
being a minority.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp director Romero said, ``We don't sit everyone down and say,
`Now, let's all talk about the family.' We let them initiate
discussions. Most of it happens unscheduled in the cabins.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case late one afternoon in the big girls' cabin,
for girls aged 12 to 14. As the group showered, dressed and got
ready for dinner the talk turned to home.
</P>
<P>
   One girl said her father has started bringing his lover to her
basketball games, but it is OK. Another said she tells people at
school that her mother's partner is her aunt. One girl, who's been
coming to the camp since it opened, said, ``It meant a lot at first
to be assured you're OK, but now I'm used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't as cavalier. Peering into a mirror with an eyelash
curler in hand, a 13-year-old said, ``I wish I didn't have to deal
with it. I want to be homecoming queen. I don't want to be beaten
up. But I don't want to change my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizebeth DePrimo, 20, was the only counselor this summer who is
heterosexual, but she grew up in a gay family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the kids like me to be here,'' because they can
relate, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Until she was 5, she lived with her mother and father. Then her
mother left home and moved in with another woman. When DePrimo was
12, she moved in with her mother and her girlfriend and the
girlfriend's son.
</P>
<P>
   DePrimo's background is typical of a lot of the campers but not
all, says Van Stone. ``At first we got lots of kids that came from
marriages before a parent became lesbian or gay. Now, more are
coming from lesbian and gay families that started that way.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 8 million to 13 million children are being raised
by gay or lesbian parents nationwide, according to the National
Center for Lesbian Rights in San Francisco. Van Stone refers to ``a
baby boom'' among same-sex couples, of which she and Romero are
part. The two Guerneville women became mothers of twins this March.
Van Stone carried the babies, but the eggs were harvested from
Romero, a process they started a year before the birth.
</P>
<P>
   The biological father and sperm donor is Paul Brombige, a friend
and colleague at Romero's real estate office. Brombige and his
partner, Jeff Morford, were present at the births. All four are
helping to raise the babies.
</P>
<P>
   The twins, who accompanied their mothers to camp this summer,
were a novelty to the older campers, but the method of their
conception wouldn't have raised an eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   Camilla, a 10-year-old with glittery purple nails from
Williamsburg, Va., explained that her biological father, whom she
calls Bucky, is ``my unbiological mom's brother. My mom was
injected with his sperm.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanchette, whose daughter attends the camp, said, ``I
understand that everyone needs to live in the real world, and these
children do for 51 weeks of the year. But for one week they get to
be with other children just like them. For one week, they are the
dominant culture.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TATE-EXHIBIT-NYT &LR;      08-31 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TATE-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIGHT LOOK AT THE WORLD IN `NEW ART' AT THE TATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Helped along by the hype, gimmickry and raw talent
normally associated with British pop music, the current boom in
British contemporary art could hardly have gone unnoticed abroad.
In 1996, ``Life/Live,'' a show at the Modern Art Museum of the City
of Paris, introduced young British artists to France. Then, after
drawing huge crowds to the Royal Academy in 1997, ``Sensation,''
the iconic exhibition of this generation, traveled first to Berlin
and will soon open at the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   However, if many Britons believe that artistic creativity starts
in London and ends in Glasgow these days, it is simply because they
have not been exposed to non-British contemporary art of late. Now,
the Tate Gallery is making amends with ``Abracadabra: International
Contemporary Art,'' a show running through Sept. 26 that brings
together work from nine countries by 15 artists ranging in age from
29 to 45. To judge by the crowds visiting the exhibition, it is
news that contemporary art also exists abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, three artists from France and Belgium, two from
the United States and Britain and one each from Italy, Brazil,
Japan, Spain and Germany are variously presenting sculpture,
photography, video, installations, drawings and even painting. As
for the problem of organizing such an eclectic group,
``Abracadabra'' has found a daring solution by displaying the work
in a single large space, in the process creating something of the
feel of a fun palace.
</P>
<P>
   The light mood in turn underlines one difference between this
international group and the British artists collected by Charles
Saatchi and presented in ``Sensation.'' Much of young British art,
whether Damien Hirst's dissected animals, Jake and Dinos Chapman's
disturbing mannequins or Richard Billingham's photographs of his
working-class family, suggests almost existentialist malaise. In
contrast, ``Abracadabra'' is often mischievous and, above all,
humorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The London art scene has American bias, but this show leans
towards Continental Europe,'' wrote Mark Sladen in The Independent
on Sunday, noting that the show's main organizer, Catherine
Grenier, is a curator at the Georges Pompidou Center in Paris.
``The London galleries love painting and sculpture, but this show
offers more transitory media and participatory works. And London's
trendier artists tend to go for big themes and big statements,
whereas this show is characterized by an oblique, whimsical
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Entrenched critics of contemporary art, of course, have not been
won over. ``Though the Tate apparently resents it, comparison with
`Sensation,' the Saatchi circus at the Royal Academy two years ago,
is inevitable,'' wrote Brian Sewell, the drum-beating art critic of
London's Evening Standard, ``for `Abracadabra' is imbued with the
same overwhelming sense of the tacky, the tawdry and the pointless,
the urge to shock for no good reason, the whim to tickle fancy with
the childish and the frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Maurizio Cattelan's ``Twentieth Century
(Novecento),'' a dead horse with leather harness that hangs from
the ceiling of the Tate's lobby, is reminiscent of Hirst's defunct
animals. And predictably, it has provoked protest from Britain's
legions of horse lovers (Hirst is perhaps lucky that shark and cow
lovers are less vociferous).
</P>
<P>
   But in the show's main space, there are no echoes of
``Sensation.'' Cattelan's ``Stadium,'' a table-soccer game with
positions for two full 11-member teams, invites participation,
while his ``Bidibidobidiboo,'' a taxidermic squirrel sitting
slumped over a tiny table, with a miniature pistol suggesting a
suicide, is more Dada than depressing.
</P>
<P>
   Narrative is present in many of the works. Belgium's Patrick
Corillon, for instance, often recounts the life of a fictional poet
and composer, Oskar Serti. ``At the Station'' has Serti awaiting
his friend, Catherine de Selys, on a railroad platform, with each
portrayed full length on opposite sides of a large wooden board,
their faces cut out as in seaside photo booths. ``Oskar Serti's
House'' comprises five doors leading to dark spaces where visitors
can sit and listen to episodes of Serti's life.
</P>
<P>
   France's Pierrick Sorin focuses on his own life in many of his
droll videos. In ``Awakenings,'' he appears briefly and sleepily on
successive mornings as he mumbles excuses about going to bed too
late and drinking too much to be able to work. The exhibition
catalog explains that it is about ``the human desire for
rejuvenation and renewal,'' but the piece is simply funny because
it is familiar. In another work, ``I Have Kept My Slippers on So
That I Can Go to the Bakery,'' six television monitors show
different images of books tumbling on Sorin's head. His homage to
slapstick cinema is undisguised.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's Eric Duyckaerts plays with the absurd in his ``Two
Thumbed Hand'' series in which, through drawings, sculptures and
video, he solemnly argues the benefits of an evolutionary mutation
that results in a symmetrical hand, with two thumbs and four
fingers. In ``How to Draw a Square,'' he appears in a video as a
lecturer who hides the simple in obscure language and, in the words
of the catalog, ``deconstructs and reconstructs the didactic
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Two British artists, Paul Noble and Emma Kay, neither present in
``Sensation,'' offer new twists to conventional narrative. Noble's
``Doley'' series includes a comic strip peopled by geometric shapes
representing social outcasts struggling to make ends meet. In ``The
Bible from Memory'' and ``Worldview,'' Ms. Kay reduces the Bible
and the history of the world to one sheet of small print text that
forces the vagaries of memory to provide the connections.
</P>
<P>
   The show also includes works by the Americans Katy Schimert and
Keith Edmier, Brazil's Vik Muniz and Spain's Fernando
Sanchez-Castillo, but the work that has awakened most interest is
Momoyo Torimitsu's ``Miyata Jiro,'' a crawling robot that resembles
a life-size Japanese businessman who drags himself along the ground
with a look of steadfast determination. He is, Ms. Torimitsu notes
dryly, ``a soldier of the Japanese corporate empire who invades
foreign economies for the motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying videos show the robot performing on Wall Street,
with Ms. Torimitsu walking beside him dressed as a nurse and
occasionally tending to him with a screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   In a catalog essay, Ms. Grenier said that what many of these
works have in common is a new theatrical sense of reality that
enables them to connect art and life. ``The central place is
occupied not by art, subject or society, but by humanity,'' she
writes. ``Man is thus looked at with a gaze that is neither
narcissistic nor ideological, neither soppily benevolent nor
sadistically cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   The result turns out to be something unusual for contemporary
art: visitors walk out of the show feeling good about the world.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
