<HEADER>
A6117 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-JANISJOPLIN-RESURGENC     08-31 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANISJOPLIN-RESURGENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEARL' JAM: THESE DAYS, EVERYBODY LOVES JANIS JOPLIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long before the end, in July 1970, Janis Joplin and her Full
Tilt Boogie band plays on a multiband caravan traveling through
Canada. July 4, 1970, finds them in Calgary, and during the show
she introduces ``Little Girl Blue,'' a song she first heard from
Nina Simone. Joplin has been living a hard life for years, she's
tired and lonely and probably on heroin, which will kill her three
months later.
</P>
<P>
   But for the four minutes of ``Blue,'' Janis Joplin is a blues
singer nonpareil. ``Sit there, count your fingers,'' she coos
softly, her voice dripping sorrow. ``What else, what else can you
do? Honey, I know how you feel/I know you feel that you're
through.''
</P>
<P>
   The song is directed at a lonely young woman, but there's no
question that ``Pearl'' (as she was often known) is singing it to
herself, soothing the pain that was a constant part of her journey
from a teen oddball in Port Arthur, Texas, to a folkie oddball in
Austin, Texas, to the psychedelic era's foremost female vocalist,
who was found dead in a Hollywood hotel room at age 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue'' had originally been released on the ``I Got Dem Ol'
Kozmic Blues Again Mama!'' LP, but this version, which is found on
the new ``Box of Pearls: The Janis Joplin Collection'' boxed set,
is the keeper, a perfect blues tune from a woman who had long tired
of living them but couldn't find her way out.
</P>
<P>
   And these days, more people are listening to the music she made
than at any time since the flurry of commercial success that came
after her death on Oct. 4, 1970. The LP she was working on,
``Pearl,'' topped the national charts for nine weeks in early 1971,
and ``Mercedes Benz'' and ``Me and Bobby McGee'' became radio
staples.
</P>
<P>
   Set for release next Tuesday, the ``Box of Pearls'' boxed set is
the latest testament to the revived interest in Joplin. Featuring
remastered versions of all four of her studio records _ with
previously unreleased tracks _ and a five-song CD of previously
unheard material, ``Pearls'' is the definitive Joplin.
</P>
<P>
   There have been books about Joplin, and this summer, even a
two-act musical, ``Love, Janis,'' that is due to hit Broadway soon.
Featuring much of Joplin's most famous music, the narrative also is
in Joplin's own words, drawn from letters she wrote home to her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Rock fans have never stopped listening to Joplin: ``Piece of My
Heart,'' ``Mercedes Benz,'' ``Down on Me'' and ``Me and Bobby
McGee,'' have become classic-rock staples, songs that personify our
vision of her as a pioneer and casualty, whose star blazed briefly
and brightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistically, 40 percent of the people that buy Janis' CDs
are 25 and younger,'' said Mark Feldman, senior director for
marketing for Sony Legacy, which is releasing ``Box of Pearls.''
``It feels like a Janis renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the interest in Joplin is tied to the resurgence of
female rockers in recent years, particularly women who lead bands.
Among them and their bands: Sarah McLachlan, Hole, No Doubt, The
Corrs, Liz Phair, Texas, The Cardigans and The Cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the massive success this year of blueswoman Susan
Tedeschi, whose sometimes Joplinesque vocals have made her one of
the most successful youngsters on the blues scene.
</P>
<P>
   Women leading bands was rare when Joplin hit the San Francisco
music scene in the mid-'60s. At the time, the most successful
female acts were coming out of Motown and were shaped by music
executives and dance instructors. A female pop musician was
supposed to be beautiful first and compliant to what her male
managers wanted her to sing and wear.
</P>
<P>
   Joplin, however, was full of contradictions. A carefree spirit
shaping the San Francisco rock scene, she also wrote sentimental,
touching letters to her folks in Texas. Her songs are often about
needing one good man, as she once put it, but she also enjoyed
relationships with women.
</P>
<P>
   Although never conventionally pretty, she exuded a rough
sexiness and a raw, earthy toughness. And even though she could
out-drink and out-sing almost anyone, she also craved being alone
in her little nest, away from the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is why Joplin is appreciated by a younger
generation of female rockers. In ``Scars of Sweet Paradise,'' Alice
Eckols, a Joplin biographer, writes that Joplin was constantly
scared of being found out as an ``imposter, a talentless girl whose
powerful voice fooled people into thinking she could sing.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to longtime associate Sam Andrew, Joplin also had
boundless reserves of good humor and self-reliance. And she really
did ``lead'' Big Brother and the Holding Company and the Full Tilt
Boogie band.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very much a band leader,'' said Andrew, who wrote
``Combination of the Two,'' the leadoff track from ``Cheap
Thrills,'' the million-selling 1968 album by Big Brother and the
Holding Company. ``She wanted to make sure things were organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew notes that even though Joplin was lonely and drank too
much, she was also a joy to be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a lot more fun than she's given credit for,'' he said.
``She was real bright and real fast and very articulate. She was a
party on wheels, but not wild like Sid Vicious or Led Zeppelin. She
wasn't a victim; she was very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
