<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6119 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV07-     08-31 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV07-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING HOPE FOR THE FUTURE, ONE NOTE AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sept. 7) 
 (smw) By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pivotal moment in one of my all-time favorite movies is when
``Harold and Maude'' meet at a funeral. It foreshadows many of the
themes of the movie: Even a long life is short, embrace it fully;
no possession is truly yours; big issues are good and well, but
they too shall pass.
</P>
<P>
   Funerals, admittedly, make better theatrical devices, but to
renew my hopes for our species, I'll take a piano recital any day.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about all those kids in their best pants and
frilly dresses, so solemnly and nervously fingering out melodies.
</P>
<P>
   And not just when it's my kid.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I'm relieved when his piece is over and played well, since
we've heard it 693 times by then and really could do without ever
hearing it again.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole scene _ families sitting together, listening
politely as 23 kids do their best to fill an auditorium or church
hall with song _ warms my cockles.
</P>
<P>
   From the youngsters whose legs dangle from the wooden bench to
teen prodigies whose hands are a blur, piano recitals are proof of
so many reassuring things.
</P>
<P>
   They prove that practice pays off, even if it's done while
grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   They prove that even tiny fingers have memories, that Chopin and
Bach are still alive and kicking, that notes are just black dots on
a lined page until someone's heart gets mixed up with them.
</P>
<P>
   And they prove that a good number of families have decided they
have nothing better to do on a Saturday afternoon than gather to
watch children play their recital pieces, even though movie
theaters beckon and water parks are filled and malls are open.
</P>
<P>
   I remember my son's first recital, in the back room of a music
store in Tampa, Fla. He was 5 and had just finished learning his
``twinkles,'' every child's first Mozart. As he walked up to the
stage holding my hand he leaned up and whispered, ``You think I'm
going to make a mistake, but I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right; I did think that. And he was right again; he
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, his recital pieces have become both harder
to master and easier to listen to. Oh, he's had his false starts
and stumbles, even with a piece he's practiced to perfection. But
for the most part, he does himself and his parents proud.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every minute of his nightly practice is a minute he'd
rather be doing 500 different things.
</P>
<P>
   So I make him extravagant promises about piano: That it will get
easier and easier. That when he's 17 and playing synthesizer in a
band, he will be able to have any prom date he wants.
</P>
<P>
   That in a few years he can take drums or trumpet or sax or
guitar lessons and I will gladly pay ... as long as he still takes
piano lessons, too. I'm sure a good number of these promises are
true.
</P>
<P>
   He still gripes, but he practices. And about twice a year, his
father and I sit in pews or folding chairs, holding a program with
the now familiar tunes like, ``Horse Sense,'' ``Lightly Row,'' and
``The Busy Bee,'' and get our fix of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Try it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a kid on the bench, I don't think anyone will mind
if you crash a piano recital.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus writes this column for the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group. She has master's and specialist degrees
in marriage and family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
