<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BASEBALL-MEMORABILIA-     08-31 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-MEMORABILIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BASEBALL TREASURES MONEY CAN'T BUY AT THE SOTHEBY'S AUCTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, September 5)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(dw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nearly 80,000 items of baseball memorabilia _ from the
gorgeously historic to the madly esoteric _ that filled the
comfortable home of Barry Halper in Livingston, N.J., have mostly
been packed up and shipped out. About 20 percent of his collection
was sent to the Baseball Hall of Fame, where a wing named for this
collector non pareil has been built. Most of the rest of the
collection will be sold at a weeklong auction at Sotheby's in
Manhattan, beginning on Sept. 23, which, according to Sotheby's,
has a chance to break the house record of $34.4 million set by the
sale of the Jackie Kennedy Onassis estate.
</P>
<P>
   But in Halper's home, some things remain the same. He was unable
to part with some items of value, for sentimental reasons. He was
also unable to part with some items of perhaps little economic
value, for the same heart-plucking reasons. He has held on to books
and photographs signed ``To my friend, Barry Halper'' from the
likes of Joe DiMaggio and George Brett, a lock of Babe Ruth's hair,
a rubber glove once used by a doctor to examine Mickey Mantle, to
name a few.
</P>
<P>
   In Halper's spacious den, which is sectioned off into four
rooms, are empty glass cases and barren areas on the walls. No
longer can one peer into the window in one part of the wood
paneling and see, with a flick of a switch, 1,053 baseball uniforms
come rolling past on a dry cleaner's carousel. Many of the uniforms
are signed; they include those worn by Cap Anson for the 1888
Chicago White Stockings, Jim Thorpe for the 1918 New York Giants
and Jackie Robinson when he played for Kansas City of the Negro
leagues in 1946; others belonged to Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Willie
Mays and Pete Rose. (About the only things left on the carousel are
a few of Halper's seldom worn suits and some dresses that belong to
his wife, Sharon.)
</P>
<P>
   Gone from his home, as well as from warehouses where the rest of
his collection was kept, are the baseball treasures he compiled
over a half century. Halper, now 60, began his quest when he was 8
years old and continued it through his years as a partner in the
family's wholesale paper business, now defunct, in New Jersey. He
went about collecting with a determination, a passion, sometimes
with an obsession. The list of what he has got rid of is
staggering. Gone are the myriad baseball gloves and shoes and caps
and bats. One bat, for example, bore the signature of Earl Averill,
the Hall of Fame outfielder, who signed it for Halper a month
before his death. Gone, too, are the mountains of signed baseballs
and photographs and rarest of baseball cards and letters and
contracts and trophies. Alas, gone as well is the first issue of
Playboy Magazine, published in 1953, with Marilyn Monroe on the
cover and in the centerfold. Halper asked her husband, Joe
DiMaggio, to autograph the cover. He agreed but only on the
condition that Halper not show it in DiMaggio's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was going through my collection,'' Halper recalled, ``I
said to my wife and sons, Steven and Jason, `I'll have to keep this
contract of Babe Ruth's from the Red Sox in 1918, and I have to
keep this ball and that bat ... ' And they said, `If you're going
to keep all those things, you might as well start a new
collection,' and so I let most of it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Halper had suffered a stroke a few years ago _ he has recovered
almost fully _ and decided that it could create financial chaos for
his family if he left the collection as it was. ``And I didn't want
a fire sale,'' he said. So he went about looking for a home for it,
and wound up with the current arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Robbins, a spokesman for Sotheby's, conservatively
estimated that the sale would yield $10 million. ``I would hardly
be surprised, however, if it surpassed our record auction,'' he
said, referring to the Onassis sale. Another indication of the
worth of the Halper collection was a $42 million appraisal from an
insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Still hanging on the wall in Halper's basement, however, is a
framed letter from 1932 that reads: ``In all my years in baseball I
have received many requests of autographs, balls, bats, equipment,
but you are the first person to ask for some of my hair. Therefore
I feel I am obligated to comply with such a request at least once.
You will find enclosed an envelope containing some of my hair. I
don't know what you're going to do with it, but I hope you enjoy
it. Good luck with your collection. Sincerely, Babe Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the frame is a lock of the Babe's hair, dark brown with a
few strands of gray. A note beside it reads, ``I guarantee that the
enclosed hair is my own, Babe Ruth.'' The note was addressed not to
Barry Halper but to Matthew Ward, a memorabilia collector from
Ruth's time with whom Halper would have obviously identified.
</P>
<P>
   Halper, whose hair remains as thick and dark as Ruth's and whose
stocky build, in sport jacket and tie, is a scaled-down version of
the old slugger's, walked around his den, stopping at various
places to point out to a visitor what wasn't there and explaining
why he had kept what he had. As he did so, one could sense the
bitter-sweet feeling he had about parting with much of his
collection. (While understanding of her husband's obsession, Sharon
Halper was not reluctant to see the collection go. ``She's not much
of a baseball fan,'' Halper said. ``Besides, I think all the mildew
in the house was getting to her.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``What I kept are some items that I felt personally about,''
Halper said. Many of the objects he kept are associated with the
Yankees. He owns 2 percent of the team, enough to enable him to sit
in the box of the principal owner, George Steinbrenner, when
attending games. (One thing he held on to is a felt yarmulke with
the red-white-and-blue Yankee logo sewn into it. A letter
accompanying it describes it as a gift to Halper from
Steinbrenner.)
</P>
<P>
   From a shelf in the office of his den he pulled off a silver
nail-file case bearing the initials ``GHR,'' for ``George Herman
Ruth.'' ``I rub this for good luck when I'm watching Yankee
games,'' he said. ``Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't.'' He
also has the Babe's tweezers, hand mirror, shoe brush, hair brush
and glass tooth-brush case, all monogrammed.
</P>
<P>
   In a glass case nearby, he has a handful of baseball bats
autographed to him, including one from some 30 years ago that
reads: ``To Barry _ the No. 1 collector from the No. 1 home run
king. Best always, Roger Maris.''
</P>
<P>
   Halper pointed out an empty spot in the case where the Averill
bat once stood. He recalled how he had acquired it: He had been
attending the 1983 All-Star game in Chicago on the 50th anniversary
of the first major-league all-star game, in which Averill had
played. ``I saw him in the hotel lobby after the game,'' Halper
said, ``and he was looking very sickly. He said he'd sign the bat
tomorrow. I thought that if he made it to tomorrow it would be a
miracle. I just about begged him to do it now, and we went to his
room, where he signed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next morning I came down to the lobby, and there's a big
commotion. Averill was leaving the hotel in an ambulance, and died
shortly after. I don't want to be callous, but I did get lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
