<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BASEBALL-MEMORABILIA-     08-31 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-MEMORABILIA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: did get lucky.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On another shelf Halper has also kept high school yearbooks of
famous players (a 1963 yearbook from Scottsdale, Ariz., includes a
senior named Jim Palmer, star baseball and basketball player, as
well a junior varsity basketball player listed as ``Danny Quail,''
who later became vice president and who himself had at least one
moment of shaky spelling).
</P>
<P>
   A framed cover of a record album on a wall is titled ``My
Favorite Hits, Mickey Mantle.'' It is inscribed with Mantle's own
peculiar brand of spelling, ``To Barry _ You should here me sing!
Mickey Mantle.''
</P>
<P>
   Halper, pausing to look at the album cover, smiled. He had
become friends with Mantle, as well as with DiMaggio and other ball
players. Many came to his home not only to look at his remarkable
collection but also to eat at the table of Sharon Halper, who is
known for her Italian dishes. (Her shrimp fra diavolo over linguini
was a particular favorite of DiMaggio's.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey had a great sense of humor, sometimes a bizarre one,''
said Halper. ``I was in Dallas shortly before he died, and he was
holding a news conference to discuss his liver cancer. He saw me
and hollered, `Hey, Barry, do you want to buy my liver?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey knew that I had Ty Cobb's dentures,'' Halper added,
with a laugh. ``Maybe he was trying to be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Halper wasn't interested in Mantle's liver, but he did covet the
scalpel used in the liver-transplant operation. The surgeon said he
could not be sure which one he had used, but Mantle had another
idea. A few weeks later Halper received a Federal Express package,
and when he opened it he found a plastic glove, with a note: ``This
is the glove from my hemmorid exam. Mickey Mantle.''
</P>
<P>
   Halper framed the glove in a glass butterfly case but discreetly
tucked it in a drawer. ``What should I do?'' asked Halper. ``Throw
it away?''
</P>
<P>
   Hanging from a peg in Halper's den office, meanwhile, is another
glove, but this one an actual baseball glove, which also bears
Mantle's name. In the Sotheby catalog for the Halper collection, a
glove worn by Mickey Mantle, ``circa 1960,'' is listed at $10,000
to $20,000. And what is this one worth?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' Halper said. ``It's my glove. It just happens to be
a Mantle model. But it's from the days I played softball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
