<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 1, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, winds near 50 mph and 10 to 15 foot waves battered
portions of the North Carolina Outer Banks as Hurricane Dennis
ceased its eastward drift and stalled 100 miles east of Cape
Hatteras. Wednesday, the clockwise circulation around high pressure
over the Northeast should cause Dennis to move slowly westward,
bringing the threat for windswept heavy showers to eastern North
Carolina. In a weakened form, the hurricane is expected to drift
near the southern Middle Atlantic Coast on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Subsiding air currents associated with the Northeast high will
promote abundant sunshine from the central Great Lakes to New
England. After a cool start, temperatures will rapidly rebound,
reaching the low 80s by midday. An exception will be along the
Northeast Seaboard where onshore breezes bring cool ocean air
inland.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of showers and thunderstorms will erupt over eastern
Texas and Louisiana today as a weak low pressure system interacts
with humid air emerging from the Gulf of Mexico. Farther north,
increasingly humid breezes from the south intercepting a cold front
will set the stage for a few potent thunderstorms across the
eastern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the front, unseasonably chilly air will spread into the
Northern Rockies with the risk for a few snow showers in the higher
mountain peaks of western Montana. Offshore breezes will bring
sunshine and milder weather to the Northwest Coast while sunny and
hot conditions cover the Southwest deserts.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Changes
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hurricane Dennis was a changed storm. An infusion of
cool, dry air from the continent caused the hurricane to begin to
lose some of the characteristics of a tropical cyclone and take on
the appearance of middle latitude storm. The tall thunderstorms
surrounding its center, the heat engine of a hurricane, collapsed.
The strong winds that once hugged close to its core spread out over
a large area and weakened. The storm's eye became a cloud-filled
swirl. Disturbances that share features of both tropical and middle
latitude cyclones are sometimes called sub-tropical storms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
