<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6148 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     08-31 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   CDs vs. Money Market For the Short Haul 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: I soon will receive a lump-sum inheritance. After paying off the
mortgage, I will have approximately $100,000 to invest. I would
like to park that money safely for up to three months, by which
time I hope to find an investment counselor. Should I choose a CD
or a money-market account or something else?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Either a CD or money-market bank account _ fully covered by
federal deposit insurance _ will do for a short period of time.
Such accounts currently are paying interest of about 5 percent
annually, which translates to $1,250 on a $100,000 deposit if you
maintain your account for three months. Shop around for the best
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that a CD will pay more interest than a money-market
account at the same institution because with a CD, you won't have
the freedom to withdraw your funds without penalty until the three
months are up. There are no such penalties with a money-market
account.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting part of your question is your throwaway
line about ``paying off the mortgage.'' You ought to consult your
investment counselor first. If your mortgage interest rate is lower
than the estimated return on stocks, mutual funds or whatever other
investments your counselor recommends, it might be best to keep the
mortgage and invest more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also, don't forget that paying off the mortgage would deprive
you of a significant tax deduction _ the amount of interest
included in your monthly mortgage payments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Q: My husband is going to retire soon, and we are planning to
move to a smaller home. We heard about Proposition 90, which is
supposed to keep our property taxes low when we change homes. How
does this work, and in which counties does it apply?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: Actually, there are two propositions that protect certain
Californians ages 55 and older _ as well as disabled homeowners of
any age _ from an increase in property taxes when they change
homes. One is Proposition 60; the other is Proposition 90.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 60 permits these homeowners to transfer the current
assessed value of &UR;  &LR; the homes they sell to the homes they buy if
both homes are in the same county and if the new home costs no more
than the sale price of the old home.
</P>
<P>
   This can be a huge benefit for taxpayers who have lived in their
present homes a long time. Thanks to another Proposition _ No.13 _
many people are paying taxes of only a few hundred dollars annually
on $300,000 houses they bought 20 years ago, while their neighbors
who moved in last year are paying $3,000 or so.
</P>
<P>
   The tax authorities of all 58 California counties legally are
required to honor Proposition 60, says Kristine Cazadd, senior
staff attorney with the state Board of Equalization.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 90 covers moves from one California county to
another, but the coverage is less sweeping. The ground rules are
the same as with Proposition 60 _ but only if the county where the
new home is located has authorized the use of the old tax base.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, not many counties have done so, and some of those
that did initially have withdrawn their authorization. The current
list of those that authorize transfers of tax bases numbers only 10
counties: Alameda, Kern, Los Angeles, Modoc, Monterey, Orange, San
Diego, San Mateo, Santa Clara and Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: Is it true that I can delay withdrawal of money from my
traditional Individual Retirement Account if I continue working
beyond age 701/2? That seems only fair because, after all, it is a
retirement account and I won't be retired.
</P>
<P>
   A: &LR;   &LR;  A: Your logic is flawless, but man does not live by logic
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Calderaro, technical coordinator with the Internal Revenue
Service, says you must begin taking withdrawals from your IRA no
later than April 1 of the year following the year in which you
reach age 701/2. ``It's a must,'' he remarks. ``There is no way of
getting around it. It's like Social Security. At age 701/2, you
start drawing it whether you want it or don't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation would be different with a Roth IRA. No matter how
old you get, you never are required to withdraw funds from a Roth _
and you can continue making contributions beyond age 701/2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
