<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6158 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SUN-CANCER-TEX     08-31 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-CANCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE KNOW THE SUN IS BAD FOR US, BUT WE'RE STILL DOING A SLOW BURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ultraviolet ray shoots out from the sun and travels 93
million miles through space, hurtling toward Earth in an
eight-minute mission to attack and destroy those who fail to
protect their skin.
</P>
<P>
   The ray is thwarted thrice by its targets who, at the last
second, put up an umbrella, put on a hat and apply sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   The third time's the charm. The determined ray lands on the back
of an unsuspecting lad who has just taken off his shirt. A warning
label flashes across the television screen at the end of this
public service announcement: ``Exposure to the sun's UV rays can
damage your skin.''
</P>
<P>
   As August melts into September, the public service announcement
serves as a timely reminder: Just because summer is ending doesn't
mean the sun isn't going to get you. And keep getting you. The PSA
is part of The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's
five-year ``Choose Your Cover'' campaign, an effort co-sponsored by
the American Cancer Society Skin Protection Federation that urges
Americans to ``Slip! Slop! Slap! Wrap!'' and, whatever you do,
``Protect the skin you're in.''
</P>
<P>
   The federation is a coalition of nonprofit organizations,
government agencies and corporations working together to inform
people how to protect themselves from the sun: Slip on a shirt,
slop on sun screen, slap on a hat and wrap on sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple, but here's the concern: Although overall cancer
rates are dropping, the number of skin cancer cases continues to
climb. Melanoma and basal and squamous cell carcinomas now occur
more frequently than all other cancers combined in the United
States and are increasing, with approximately 1 million new cases
annually _ 80 percent of them linked to the sun's burning rays.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 44,200 Americans are expected to learn that they have
malignant melanoma, the most deadly form of skin cancer. That's up
6 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in skin cancer appears to be related to increases
in voluntary sun exposure. We're apparently asking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Skin cancer experts say huge increases in weekend and childhood
exposure to the sun's rays have made a big difference. Blasts of
blistering exposure, especially in crucial early years of life, are
taking a lot of the blame for the increase.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? What we've heard before, but obviously need to
hear again: Protect your skin. The Department of Health and Human
Services estimates that about one-third of adults take measures to
protect their skin from the sun's UV rays.
</P>
<P>
   Three new polls show there is a lot we either don't know about
skin cancer prevention or foolishly choose to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   For example, although health professionals agree that children
under 6 months should not be exposed to the sun's harmful rays at
all, more than 70 percent of people polled for Discovery Health
Media say they believe infants can be protected with sunscreen, and
62 percent think, wrongly, that light-colored clothing offers the
greatest protection from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a typical dry, white cotton T-shirt offers only about
an SPF level of 8 to 10, as does an SPF-15 sunscreen if applied
only sparingly. Closely woven, long-sleeved shirts provide the most
protection; wet T-shirts provide hardly any. Infants should never
be exposed directly to the sun, no matter how much sunscreen they
have on.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also shows that Americans don't understand sun
protection factors (SPF) found in sunscreens. More than half
believe incorrectly that sunscreen with an SPF of 30 offers twice
the protection of a sunscreen with SPF 15.
</P>
<P>
   In a second poll, conducted in behalf of Cancer Care Inc., the
majority of respondents (82 percent) said they have experienced a
serious sunburn that resulted in blistering or peeling, yet
slightly more than half (52 percent) said they rarely or never
apply sunscreen to their exposed skin when planning to spend more
than 15 minutes outside in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of those polled said they have never been to a
dermatologist to get their skin checked for abnormal moles. That
survey also found that men are much less likely than women to apply
sunscreen when they're outdoors, though more men are found to have
melanoma (and die from it) each year.
</P>
<P>
   The third poll, conducted earlier this summer for the Cancer
Society's Youth Sun Exposure and Skin Protection Study, found
almost three-quarters (72 percent) of youths ages 11 to 18 get
sunburned in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin Weinstock, chairman of the Cancer Society's Skin
Cancer Advisory Board, says the findings confirm that people do not
use sunscreen properly and do not take other measures to cover up
with hats and protective clothing. In other words, we seem to know
how to thwart those rays, we just don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Sun Protection 101
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we should be doing to protect ourselves against the
sun's rays:
</P>
<P>
   Apply a broad-spectrum sunscreen with an SPF of at least 15
liberally on any exposed skin at least 15 minutes before going
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Reapply sunscreen every two hours or more often when swimming or
perspiring.
</P>
<P>
   Wear wrap-around sunglasses to protect the eyes and the delicate
skin around them.
</P>
<P>
   Plan outdoor activities to avoid the midday sun, whenever
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Slip on a shirt, slop on sunscreen, slap on a hat and wrap on
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   To find out how much you know about sun protection, take the
Sun-Sense Quiz online at www.discoveryhealth.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
