<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6160 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-POISON-PLANT02-COX     08-31 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POISON-PLANT02-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Avoid trouble in the garden by knowing which plants are toxic
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 2
</P>
<P>
   By Danny C. Flanders
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kids _ and some adults _ eat the darndest things.
</P>
<P>
   That philodendron leaf on the floor looks kind of like the
spinach Mom was trying to get Johnny to eat the night before; and
those plump red berries covering the holly bush outdoors could pass
for the raspberries Suzy likes on her cereal.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the type of plant and the amount ingested, symptoms
of poisoning can range from stomach upset to organ damage and even
heart failure, according to officials at the Georgia Poison Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``For about 80 to 90 percent of the cases, it results in
nothing, just watching for symptoms,'' said Dr. Gaylord Lopez,
director of the emergency information service at Hughes Spalding
Children's Hospital. The remainder of the cases are referred to
area emergency rooms for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The key to avoiding poisoning is knowing which plants are toxic.
Even plants thought to be nontoxic can cause an upset stomach when
eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Most problems stem from the foliage of houseplants or the
berries of outdoor plants, said Paul Thomas, a floriculture
specialist for the University of Georgia Extension Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We average about one call a week, though in the spring it
picks up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the calls are seasonal, especially during the holidays,
when children, attracted to the colorful plants, ingest mistletoe,
Jerusalem cherries and poinsettias. The latter, while not
poisonous, can cause an upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Both the poison center and the Extension Service begin by
identifying the plant in order to advise the caller on how to
react. ``Without being able to identify the plant, we can't give
them any advice,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   If Extension staff members have some description of the plant,
they consult the ``Southeastern Poisonous Plant Guide'' and contact
the poison center to determine if there have been other reports of
problems with the plant. ``If we see it's a dandelion or a
poinsettia, we can tell them it's not poisonous,'' Thomas said.
``But if it's something like nightshade, castor bean or oleander,
those are pretty serious, and we refer them to the center.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, staffed around the clock by physicians, pharmacists
and nurses, advises callers to make sure no part of the plant
remains in the victim's mouth. ``We're not botanists, but parents
are pretty good about knowing what's growing in their yards or
inside their homes,'' Lopez said. ``Then we try to figure out how
much they ate and the symptoms they're having.''
</P>
<P>
   Most indoor plants are nontoxic, but three of the most common
ones _ philodendron, dieffenbachia and peace lily _ cause problems
for children. When chewed, their leaves release microscopic
crystals that become embedded in the lips and tongue. If ingested,
they can cause pain, swelling and breathing difficulty, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Most calls about outdoor plants occur in summer, when children
spend more time outside. Most often they result from berries the
child has eaten from plants such as pokeberry, lantana and
pyracantha, but the foliage of ornamentals such as caladiums and
elephant's-ears also holds varying levels of toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious cases, referred to emergency rooms, are ones in
which the person has ingested wild mushrooms and, to a lesser
extent, castor beans, which can cause heart problems, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that most often the kids don't get into that
much of it,'' he said. ``And just because they've gotten into a
toxic plant, it doesn't mean they will experience toxic effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the center gets few calls about poison ivy, poison
oak and sumac, the saps of which can irritate skin with a burning
and itching rash.
</P>
<P>
   And while cows are concerns for veterinarians, most dogs and
cats don't eat enough toxic plants to experience symptoms, Thomas
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just so many varying degrees of poisoning,'' he
said. ``Some plants can only irritate your mouth or cause an
allergic reaction. Some make you sick to your stomach. But others
are very deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Poison Center
</P>
<P>
   404-616-9000 or 1-800-282-5846.
</P>
<P>
   S A F E T Y T I P S
</P>
<P>
   To help prevent plant poisonings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Know the names of plants growing inside your home and in your
yard. If you need help identifying the plant, take a piece of it to
a nursery, florist or county Extension Office.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Label plants so you can later identify any that have been
eaten.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep houseplants, seeds and bulbs out of the reach of children
and pets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't eat wild plants or mushrooms. (Cooking them does not
make them safe.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Destroy mushrooms growing in your yard.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep children and pets away from lawns newly sprayed with
garden chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Teach children never to put any part of a plant in their
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If any part of a plant is ingested, remove as much of it from
the mouth as possible and call the poison center. Don't wait for a
victim to become ill.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid touching poison ivy, poison oak or sumac by wearing
gardening gloves. If you do come in contact with those plants, wash
the area with warm soapy water right away. Also wash any clothing
or gardening equipment you suspect may contain the plant's sap.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Post the phone number for the Georgia Poison Center (see box
on this page) near your telephone. The information service is free.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Poison Center
</P>
<P>
   P O I S O N O U S P L A N T S
</P>
<P>
   Both indoor and outdoor plants can be poisonous. Here are some
of the most common:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amaryllis
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  American ivy/Virginia creeper
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anemone
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Apricot (seeds and pits)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aralia
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Azalea, rhododendron
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Baneberry
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Belladonna/deadly nightshade
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birch
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bird of paradise
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bittersweet/woody nightshade
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bleeding heart/dicentra
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boxwood
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buckeye
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Burning bush
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Caladium
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Castor bean
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cedar
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cherry laurel
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chinaberry
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chrysanthemum
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clematis
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cyclamen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Daffodil
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dieffenbachia
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Elephant's-ear
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  English ivy
