<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX     08-31 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall won't be same without Celestine, woman for all seasons
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 2.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a touch of fall in the air,'' Celestine Sibley
was fond of saying and writing this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it didn't matter whether the touch turned into true cool
that meant the end of summer's sizzle. Or whether we only had a
brief respite before melting again. No, Celestine's touch had much
more to do with heart and senses than with mere thermometers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of life cannot be measured, quantified. So it is with
autumn's embrace. Each year, unpredictably, a moment comes and
takes us across an emotional threshold _ to autumn, a moment much
like one in which a stream of western sunshine bathes a stand of
bamboo in buttery splendor. When that happens, you know the change
has come, independent of shorter days, breathable air and crisper
nights.
</P>
<P>
   And you smile, as Celestine used to, eyes sparkling, a little
more pep in her step, a whole lot of gardening in her head. This is
the time of the autumn renewal. In the garden and in the gardener.
</P>
<P>
   When we found our fall touch, Celestine and I would launch into
planning our mind gardens, talking about what peach trees we were
going to plant, dwarf or full size, where the biggest mullein
stands grew, how lovely was joe-pye weed, whether to dig more
Christmas ferns out of the woods and plant them closer to the house
(Celestine always loved putting them in containers).
</P>
<P>
   Too, a touch of fall always put us in a chinaberry state of
mind. That's because, on one blue-sky day, we trekked to Newnan,
Ga., where a reader friend gave us several of the underappreciated
trees, along with a sumptuous lunch of soup and fried cracklin
bread. Knowing these sweet-blooming, fun-fruiting trees were rarely
seen in her north Fulton County and my southwest Atlanta, Celestine
and I would wonder at autumn whether our gifts would survive the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   We're all touched by fall but not necessarily at the same time,
not in the same way. Yes, calendars mark the season's start, but
that signifies not much. The real mark is individual, carved in the
soul.
</P>
<P>
   This year, I crossed that emotional threshold with more than a
week left in August, when the daytime temperatures still bubbled
past 90.
</P>
<P>
   Browned leaves drifting from stressed trees made me long for
drought-busting rains, but the sight also signaled time's passage
and progress toward cool and cold.
</P>
<P>
   My touch of fall awakened a desire to reclaim the heat-beaten
garden; I cut back the parched cinnamon-colored pigtails of several
Japanese painted ferns and in a week or so noticed renewed growth
sprouting green and fresh. I emptied about a dozen pots of
long-gone perennials, retiring the containers until fresh material
comes along. Soon. Too, I pruned off several pieris branches that
had roasted in the heat, renewing the plant and opening up space
around it.
</P>
<P>
   Experiencing a surge of renewal and a need to assert some
control of my space after giving it up for the summer, I swept the
brick walk down to only two layers of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   And, sensing an eventual chill that would make spicy food
especially enjoyable, I picked enough cayenne peppers (I got a good
crop for a change) to put up pepper sauce, shoving the bright red
and green pods into new bottles of vinegar and recapping them. In a
few months, I'll hungrily slosh that hot juice onto a plate of
collards or a bowl of black-eyed peas and savor the summer,
displacing memories of its searing pain.
</P>
<P>
   These pepper-sauced victuals will remind me of similar meals
enjoyed with Celestine, including the incomparable red beans and
rice that she and her family shared with Lyn and me when we enjoyed
a Sunday visit to Sweet Apple cabin a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That day steamed, but it was so mellow and fine, filled with
good cheer, cold brew and strolls through Celestine's garden and
chats about what we'd soon plant, what would grace our spaces the
next spring. It was all so free and easy, I could swear there was
something fallish going on.
</P>
<P>
   It was back in the 1970s, when I was a member of the
Constitution's editorial board, that I first heard Celestine sing
out with delighted hope from her office down the hall from mine,
``There's a touch of fall in the air!'' Pretty soon each year,
several of us joined her in reciting that restorative line. There's
a touch ...
</P>
<P>
   Even in later years, when she did not say it or write it, I
still thought it. And thought about her, her ever-renewing spirit,
quest for life's rich and varied offerings, her exquisite love for
words. Ohhh, the words.
</P>
<P>
   And, now, still less than a month after Celestine left us after
devoting some 58 of her 85 years to writing for this newspaper,
it's undeniably clear: There's more than a touch of loss in the
air. Fortunately, though, she left a skyful of zestful grace. For
all seasons.
</P>
<P>
   lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
