<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poisonous Plants of Georgia
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 2.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most calls to the Georgia Poison Center from parents whose
children have just eaten leaves or berries turn out fine in the
end. But Georgia does have its share of dangerous plants (although
any plant can make a child or pet sick if enough of it is eaten),
and it's a safe bet that knowing what's poisonous will put you
ahead of the game when it comes to protecting your family. That's
where our guide comes in. Here, we feature some of the most common
poisonous plants found in the Southeast, as well as a few of the
most common toxic houseplants. Some of the plants featured below
are more toxic to animals than humans; the severity of the symptoms
depends on the age and size of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Redroot pigweed
</P>
<P>
   (annual)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Amaranthus retroflexus
</P>
<P>
   Other names: None
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Leaves, roots and stems
</P>
<P>
   Milkweed
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Asclepias
</P>
<P>
   tuberosa
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Silkweed, butterfly weed, bloodflower
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Stems, leaves and roots
</P>
<P>
   Mexican poppy
</P>
<P>
   (annual or biennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Argemone
</P>
<P>
   mexicana
</P>
<P>
   Other name: Bluestem prickle poppy
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Seeds and leaves
</P>
<P>
   Deadly nightshade
</P>
<P>
   (annual)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Atropa belladonna
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Black nightshade, belladonna
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: All parts, especially berries
</P>
<P>
   Mustard
</P>
<P>
   (annual, biennial or perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Brassica
</P>
<P>
   Other name: Wild mustard
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: All parts, especially roots and seeds
</P>
<P>
   Angels' trumpets
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Brugmansia
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Datura, Indian apple, thorn apple, cornucopia
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: All parts, especially seeds and flowers
</P>
<P>
   Sweetshrub
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Calycanthus
</P>
<P>
   floridus
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Pineapple shrub, strawberry shrub, Carolina
allspice
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Seeds
</P>
<P>
   Common buttonbush
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Cephalanthus
</P>
<P>
   occidentalis
</P>
<P>
   Other name: Button willow
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Leaves
</P>
<P>
   Lamb's-quarters
</P>
<P>
   (annual)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Chenopodium album
</P>
<P>
   Other name: Goosefoot
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: All parts, especially older leaves
</P>
<P>
   Autumn sneezeweed
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Helenium
</P>
<P>
   autumnale
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Swamp sunflower, staggerwort
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: All parts, especially leaves, seeds
</P>
<P>
   St. John's wort
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Hypericum
</P>
<P>
   perforatum
</P>
<P>
   Other names: None
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Leaves
</P>
<P>
   Maleberry
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Lyonia ligustrina
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Male blueberry, cereca
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Leaves
</P>
<P>
   Perilla mint
</P>
<P>
   (annual)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Perilla frutescens
</P>
<P>
   Other names: None
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Leaves and stem
</P>
<P>
   Pokeweed
</P>
<P>
   (perennial )
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Phytolacca
</P>
<P>
   americana
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Pokeberry, pokeroot, inkberry
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: All parts, especially roots and seeds
</P>
<P>
   Castor bean
</P>
<P>
   (annual)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Ricinus communis
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Palma christi, koli, moy bean, mole bean
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: All parts, especially the seeds
</P>
<P>
   Poison ivy
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Toxicodendron radicans
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Three-leaved ivy, mercury
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Irritant oil found in all parts
</P>
<P>
   Poison sumac
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name:
</P>
<P>
   Toxicodendron vernix
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Swamp sumac, poison elder
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Irritants found in all parts
</P>
<P>
   Atamasco lily
</P>
<P>
   (perennial)
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Zephyranthes atamasco
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Fairy lily, rain lily
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Bulbs
</P>
<P>
   Houseplants
</P>
<P>
   Peace lily
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Spathiphyllum
</P>
<P>
   Other names: White anthurium
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: The whole plant is considered potentially toxic.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms: Burning sensation on the lips, tongue and mouth
</P>
<P>
   Dumb cane
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Dieffenbachia
</P>
<P>
   Other names: Mother-in-law's tongue, leopard lily
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Leaves
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms: Skin and eye irritation, blisters and swelling of the
mouth
</P>
<P>
   Philodendron
</P>
<P>
   Scientific name: Philodendron
</P>
<P>
   Other names: A variety of species
</P>
<P>
   Toxic part: Leaves and stems
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms: Upset stomach, dermatitis, burning sensation on the
lips, tongue and mouth
</P>
<P>
   For information and advice, call the Georgia Poison Center at
404-616-9000 or 1-800-282-5846.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Poisonous Plants of the Southeastern United States,''
Cooperative Extension Service, University of Georgia, Georgia
Poison Center
