<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINGDANCE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The swing's the thing at big metro Atlanta party
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``It's fun. It's energetic. It makes me smile. It
makes my body feel good. And I get to flirt and socialize with
everyone,'' says Kitty Wimbish, a Delta Air Lines flight attendant
who organizes a swing dance party every other month with Robert
White, a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it: swing dance in a nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   Rob and Kitty's Swing Dance, held in the First Existentialist
Congregation building in Atlanta and promoted mostly by word of
mouth, features a beautiful hardwood floor and a live band, Scott
Janna &AMP; Friends, that plays all kinds of dance music, from waltzes
to rhythm &AMP; blues.
</P>
<P>
   At Reunions, the lounge at the Atlanta Marriott Perimeter
Center, a DJ provides the music when the Atlanta Swing Dancers
Club, with about 340 members, takes over the floor on Friday and
Sunday nights. On Saturdays, the lounge becomes the hangout for
Shag Atlanta, which has about 470 dancin' fools.
</P>
<P>
   These and others like them are the dancers Elizabeth Benjamin
hopes to tap with ``A Natural Ball: An International Swing Dance
Extravaganza,'' at the Gwinnett Civic &AMP; Cultural Center(Ga.) this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, whose sister taught her to swing dance as a youngster
in Jacksonville, is a former production accountant for a film
company who founded the New York Swing Dance Society in 1993. She
now runs Everybody Dances Inc., which promotes and proselytizes
swing dance.
</P>
<P>
   Her company produces instructional swing dance videos and CDs of
swing music; organizes dances, competitions and festivals; and
provides Internet guides and other ways for swing dancers to
exchange information.
</P>
<P>
   Swing comes in all styles and degrees of athletic abandon. The
Lindy Hop, invented by ``Shorty'' Snowden in 1927 to celebrate
Charles Lindbergh's trans-Atlantic flight, takes lots of floor
space for its lifts and flings. West Coast swing, by contrast, is a
``slot dance.'' Dance floors became smaller as real estate prices
rose during the postwar building boom, so swing dancers learned to
move within a narrow rectangle.
</P>
<P>
   Every kind of swing goes on in the Atlanta area. Clubs meet
weekly or monthly in lounges and nightclubs; studios such as
Atlanta Dance World School &AMP; Club Ltd. and City Lights Dance Club
host dance parties where students can show off what they've learned
in class.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin thinks there's more than enough local talent to fill up
the Gwinnett center, which has 50,000 feet of floor space. And she
plans to lure the locals with some top-flight names, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frankie Manning, still spry at 85, the man who helped
popularize the Lindy Hop.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Count Basie Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Jivin' Lindy Hoppers from England.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Rhythm Hot Shots from Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Champion dance teams of all ages and swing styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so disappointed I can't go to the whole thing,'' said
Shelley Schumaker of Lawrenceville, Ga., ``but I'll get to
everything I can.''
</P>
<P>
   A resources and marketing coordinator for Gwinnett County Senior
Services, Schumaker took up dancing in October as ``a way to be
active, to learn a new skill, to meet people. And it helps me to
lose weight.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to acquire new steps, the day hours at the
Gwinnett center are packed with workshops on every kind of swing.
``If I'm going to give a party,'' Benjamin said, ``I want everyone
to come.''
</P>
<P>
   DANCE PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   A Natural Ball: An International Swing Dance Extravaganza
</P>
<P>
   Noon-midnight Friday; 8 a.m.-
</P>
<P>
   1 a.m. Saturday; 8:30 a.m.-
</P>
<P>
   1 a.m. Sunday. $135 weekend pass; $35 per evening dance; $95
one-day workshop pass plus evening dance; $75 one-day workshop
pass; $15 single workshop; $25 teenagers and senior citizens (per
evening dance). Gwinnett Civic &AMP; Cultural Center, 6400 Sugarloaf
Parkway, Duluth. 770-931-3568.
</P>
<P>
   WEB TAG: For more information or to order instructional videos
or CDs: www.everybodydances.com.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
