<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6165 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TRIAL-     08-31 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SELECTION BEGINS IN SECOND DRAGGING DEATH TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ Prosecutors spared the grisly details Tuesday as
jury selection began in the capital murder trial of Lawrence
Russell Brewer Jr., the second of three white men accused of
dragging a disabled black man to death in Jasper last year.
</P>
<P>
   The racially charged trial, which was moved to the Brazos County
Courthouse to avoid giving Brewer an easy appeals issue if he is
convicted, drew 161 potential jurors. Twenty of them, including
five black women, were excused for a variety of reasons, leaving a
jury pool that includes only 14 blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some evidence in this case that's a little bit rough.
It's a little bit tough,'' Jasper County District Attorney Guy
James Gray told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this case is also very fascinating and very interesting,''
he said, adding that jurors would learn about a subculture of
racists and criminals and would hear testimony about DNA evidence
that can be gleaned from tiny spots of blood or saliva from a
cigarette butt or a beer bottle from the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is just about as serious as a heart attack,'' Gray
added. ``And it belongs to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's 20-minute, low-key talk was in stark contrast to the
speech he gave on the first day of jury selection in last
February's trial of Brewer's former prison buddy and fellow white
supremacist John William ``Bill'' King, who was convicted and
sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, Gray shocked jurors, and even the victim's family,
by revealing that James Byrd Jr. was alive and conscious when he
was chained by his ankles to a pickup in the early morning hours of
June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old father of three was dragged more than two miles
down Huff Creek Road east of Jasper. He died when his head slammed
into a culvert, decapitating him. His mangled body lay a mile away,
in the middle of the road outside the gates to a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a different environment,'' Gray explained later,
after jurors were dismissed for the day. ``In Jasper, everyone
thought these were just drunks that went crazy. Now there's so much
out there and people know what happened that night. I thought it
was best not to say too much.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gray said the 12 jurors who ultimately decide this case will
find some of the evidence ``real, real traumatic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of pictures and they're bad. They affect
you,'' he said. ``You don't just walk away from this without being
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's defense lawyers, Doug Barlow and Layne Walker of
Beaumont, cautioned jurors to keep their focus when they hear the
evidence. ``Don't decide this case on some fascination over how the
evidence was collected,'' Barlow said.
</P>
<P>
   And Barlow asked jurors not to use their feelings against the
death penalty as an excuse to get out of jury duty. ``Just being
opposed to the death penalty doesn't prevent you from serving, but
we need people who are able to listen to the evidence and make a
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker reminded jurors that the indictment against his client is
not evidence of anything, and said, ``There is nothing in this
indictment that says Mr. Brewer is a racist. The sole issue is
whether he is guilty or not guilty of capital murder. Right now,
the evidence in this case is at zero.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked jurors to consider the case as seriously as they would
consider their most important personal affairs, and he gave as the
example purchasing a house.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, wearing dark green slacks, a blue shirt, tie and an
oversized cream-colored jacket over a bullet-proof vest and a stun
belt, sat at the defense table, swiveling in his chair and asking
his lawyer for mints. His girlfriend, Tammy Perritt of Como, sat in
the back of the courtroom. She declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Barlow said Brewer, 32, has been
``fairly distraught'' as the trial approaches. ``It's hard to be in
good spirits when you're charged with capital murder, but he's
doing as well as can be expected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the 20 jurors excused from duty Tuesday had
medical or child care conflicts, one black woman juror told the
judge that ``something similar'' had happened to her friend in
Mississippi. It was unclear whether she meant that her friend was
killed, and lawyers did not ask her to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining jurors were dismissed by early afternoon, after
filling out a three-page questionnaire, asking routine questions
about their education, work history, church and political
affiliations, and their views on the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a dozen jurors will return for individual questioning,
and lawyers said they hope to seat a jury of 12, plus two
alternates, in the next couple of weeks. Testimony is tentatively
set to begin Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Brewer would be sentenced to life in prison or
death by injection. A third defendant, 24-year-old Shawn Berry of
Jasper, will be tried later this fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three of Byrd's sisters and his nephew spoke briefly outside the
courthouse and said they have prepared themselves to relive the
horror of the King trial. Clara Taylor of Houston said starting
Brewer's trial is ``like the same nightmare over and over and over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   But her sister, Mary Verrett, also of Houston, said she hopes
this trial will be easier than the first because there will be
fewer surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least this time, we know what happened to James Jr.,'' she
said, ``so the information will not be as horrific as last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding hands with her sister, Betty Boatner of Jasper, Verrett
said family members now know more than they wanted to know about
Byrd's death. ``But we had to hear it,'' she said. ``Now we know
step by step, moment by moment, mile by mile and we know how he
suffered _ and how he fought.''
</P>
<P>
   Verrett said the family has received thousands of letters since
Byrd's murder, and continues to receive about 100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Many are from prisoners on death row who wrote to say that in
following the Byrd case, they realized for the first time the
impact that their crimes had on their victims' families. Other
people write to say that the case has made them re-examine their
own racist actions, however subtle they may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we can see that something good can come of this,'' Verrett
said. ``We try to answer every one of them.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
