<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for the
Wednesday, Sept. 1 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Warnken (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARCH (New York) _ A federal judge ruled Tuesday that Khallid
Abdul Muhammad, the self-professed successor to Malcolm X, may hold
a youth rally in Harlem, saying city officials had no right to use
the content of Muhammad's inflammatory speeches as a basis for
denying him a rally permit. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR (Undated) _ The American dollar, which dropped again
Tuesday against the Japanese yen and the new euro, has begun a
moderate slide that could continue for the rest of the year as
economies in Asia and Europe rebound while the United States, under
the drag of higher interest rates, slows down. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   LAUNDER-MANSION (Undated) _ Last September an opulent California
mansion once occupied by Hollywood star Eddie Murphy, with
41-rooms, five swimming pools and a barn-sized ballroom, was sold
for $6.75 million _ in cash _ to a company that turned out to be
controlled by the former Ukrainian prime minister, Pavlo Lazarenko,
who immediately ensconced his wife and children there. But
Lazarenko has not moved in just yet. He is in a U.S. detention
center fighting a Swiss extradition request on charges of looting
millions from his homeland. With the U.S. investigation of the
billions of dollars moving through the Bank of New York from
Russia, there is increased concern in the West that ill-gotten
gains from Russia or other parts of the Soviet Union are
infiltrating the United States and Europe. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SHOOTING (New York) _ Mayor Giuliani and Police
Commissioner Safir defend the fatal police shooting of an
emotionally disturbed Hasidic man a day after protests roiled the
Brooklyn neighborhood, Borough Park, where the Monday shooting took
place. Jewish leaders in neighborhood are split in their reaction
to the shooting, with critics saying the police did not need to use
deadly force. Other developments. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   MCCONNELL-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Sen. Mitch McConnell, one
of Congress's most ardent opponents of a bill that would overhaul
the campaign finance system, has aggressively urged 10 business
executives to resign from an organization that has endorsed a wide
array of reforms, including the banning of soft money. By Don Van
Natta.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DEBT (Tokyo) _ One of the striking paradoxes of Japan is
that this is a country with the greatest savers in the
industrialized world, and yet everywhere one looks there is debt.
Japanese savers are famous for their ability to salt away money for
the future, but as a nation, this country has some of the worst
accounts in the industrialized world, and its debt trajectory
increasingly looks like that of a third world country like
Tanzania. By Sheryl WuDunn and Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-UMPIRES-GARCIA (Undated) _ Rich Garcia has made judgments
and rulings for the last 25 years, as an umpire in the American
League, and on Tuesday, his career was hanging on the decision of a
federal judge in Philadelphia. ``I'm hopeful, but we're hanging on
a limb,'' said Garcia. The Players Association has rated Garcia,
57, as one of the best umpires in the game for his effort and
competency, but Garcia will be among 22 umpires losing their jobs
after Wednesday's games, barring a legal interception or an
unforeseen truce in the umpires' splintered labor war with Major
League Baseball. By Buster Olney.
</P>
