<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6194 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-WAGNER-ART-2TAK     08-31 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WAGNER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYREUTH, LIKE WAGNER, SURVIVES THE CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 5)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(dw) 
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYREUTH, Germany _ Does Bayreuth's cult of Wagner still matter?
Some mavens say no and stay away. Bayreuth, of course, is the poky
Bavarian backwater where, in 1876, Wagner introduced his mighty
cycle, ``Der Ring des Nibelungen,'' all four evenings and 17-odd
hours of it, before an audience of crowned heads, artists,
socialites and intellectuals. The revolutionary Festspielhaus he
built here, with its concealed orchestra pit and egalitarian
amphitheater-style seating, was meant as a sketch for a more
splendid theater of the future, yet it endured. The second season,
in 1882, brought the first performances of ``Parsifal,'' a mystic
ritual Wagner wished to reserve for his festival alone.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wagner's death the following year, the five other operas
in the canon (``Der Fliegende Hollaender,'' ``Tannhaeuser,''
``Lohengrin,'' ``Tristan und Isolde'' and ``Die Meistersinger von
Nuernberg'') have taken their places in Bayreuth's exclusive
repertory, in productions that always aspire to the definitive. The
festival's (never quite airtight) monopoly on ``Parsifal'' expired
along with the score's 30-year copyright, but for years to come,
Bayreuth continued to set the agenda for Wagnerian interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   In the first decades after World War II, timeless, ascetic,
psychologically profound stagings by the composer's grandson
Wieland Wagner revitalized the tradition. After Wieland's death, in
1966, other pioneering directors carried on. The last thunderclap
from Bayreuth's Green Hill sounded in 1976, with the unveiling of
the post-modern centennial ``Ring,'' directed by Patrice Chereau
and conducted by Pierre Boulez. Since then, wherever opera is
performed, the array of theatrical styles has exploded
exponentially. Iconoclasts from Arizona to Australia are forging
``Rings'' of their own, with or without regard to Bayreuth
precedent. If the festival no longer enjoys its old hegemony, that
is simply a measure of its success. These days, Wagner belongs to
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 80s and early 90s, professional visits brought me to
the festival here every second or third summer. Since 1993, for no
particular reason, I lost the habit. But even in my earliest
seasons, critics and cultural historians galore were looking on
Bayreuth with a jaundiced eye, complaining of interpretive
irrelevance, questionable casting, an inability to come to terms
with the nightmare of Wagner in the Third Reich. Not that the press
then or now has any impact on demand for tickets, which outstrips
supply by a factor of seven.
</P>
<P>
   But now the chorus of detraction is growing louder. In July, The
Economist prefaced the new Bayreuth season with a historical and
political analysis under the headline ``A Wagnerian Crisis of
Imagination.'' The magazine was not alone in blaming Richard
Wagner's grandson Wolfgang Wagner. Wolfgang, who turned 80 last
week, has been running the festival since its postwar opening in
1951, originally in tandem with his brother, Wieland. Wolfgang's
administrative talents, in stark contrast to his contributions as a
stage director, have never been in doubt. The trouble, as many now
see it, is that he stays on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolfgang has neither found the right moment to step down,''
The Economist put it, ``nor has he adequately prepared a
successor.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang had promised to name a new director in late July. When
the time came, he announced that he would be sticking around an
undetermined time longer. ``I know what I owe Bayreuth,'' he
explained in Der Spiegel, Germany's leading newsweekly. The German
economy is tottering. Government support is faltering. A cut of
more than a quarter of a million dollars is threatened. Michael
Naumann, the German Minister of Culture, makes light of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the waiting list for tickets to Bayreuth is as long
as for a handmade Lamborghini,'' he declares, irrelevantly, ``the
future of the festival is assured.'' Against such attacks, Wolfgang
says, he must defend Bayreuth as only he can.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several Wagners by blood are waiting in the wings,
none, alas, combining the executive track record and fresh artistic
agenda the job ideally requires. This summer, dueling Q-and-A's in
German news magazines, plus commentary from the pundits, made brisk
reading, especially the barbs that flew between Nike, Wieland's
bookish, sharp-tongued daughter, and Gudrun, Wolfgang's right hand
and second wife, both 50-something. Most festival regulars regard
Gudrun's future high in the Bayreuth hierarchy as a foregone
conclusion. A lofty post for Katharina, Gudrun's daughter by
Wolfgang, in her early 20s, likewise seems a distinct possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The polemics injected excitement into what would otherwise have
been a somewhat low-key year. The ``Ring'' of the 90s, admired for
James Levine's conducting but not for Alfred Kirchner's production,
has been retired. The ``Ring 2000,'' from the director Juergen
Flimm and the designer Erich Wonder, under the baton of Giuseppe
Sinopoli, is taking shape in secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from ``Tannhaeuser,'' the rest of the Bayreuth canon was
on view, with a new ``Lohengrin'' taking pride of place. Of all his
creations, Wagner deemed this romance of the maiden falsely accused
of murder and the white knight of her dreams who uselessly comes to
her rescue ``by far the saddest.'' In the hearts of the public, it
has also proved the favorite, so much so that Wolfgang has written
of the ``burden'' of its popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Lohengrin'' held a special appeal for me. Last spring, the
conductor Valery Gergiev, director of the Kirov Opera in St.
Petersburg, invited me onto the production team for a new
``Lohengrin.'' On a sabbatical from my usual occupation as a
writer, I spent most of June backstage at the Kirov, working on
everything from individual coaching and dramatic workshops with the
singers to staging and lighting design. Our premiere on July 1 was
the closing event of the White Nights festival. The next day, the
show was packed up for dates at the Ravenna Festival in Italy, and
in Baden-Baden, Germany, where we opened four days ahead of the new
``Lohengrin'' in Bayreuth. My curiosity, I trust, needs no
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Bayreuth's ``Lohengrin'' _ directed by Keith Warner, with sets
by Stefanos Lazaridis and costumes by Sue Blane _ was a wonder of
space-age hydraulics and engineering. In the first of many
drop-dead yet dramatically cogent effects, the King and his
warriors entered not from the wings but from the sky on a tray,
which hovered in midair across the full width of the stage like the
space station in ``Independence Day.''
</P>
<P>
   At the climax of the tragedy, more cryptically, a massive
platform representing the bridal chamber suddenly tipped, spilling
a cataract of water into a sinkhole, necessitating a pause in the
music surely longer than Wagner would have approved. (I have it on
the authority of Wolfgang Wagner that water, in this production,
represents the feminine principle. Armchair Jungians can take it
from there.) The blasted landscape on the stage floor resembled
some crater on the moon, dressed up with a chair here, a daybed
there. In a more abstract vein, mystifying cubes of varying
dimensions and materials had their symbolic parts to play. The king
and his army wore the clanking armor of the Age of Faith.
Otherwise, the wardrobe suggested the 19th century.
(MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
