<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WAGNER-$ADV05-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
 (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
 BEYREUTH, Germany: 19th century.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, the Kirov ``Lohengrin'' was by intention an
altogether more old-fashioned affair. The late Yevgeny Lysyk's
settings (realized by Tadey Ryndzak) looked torn from illuminations
of a medieval manuscript, dominated by the blue of lapis lazuli,
airily Gothic yet twisted into strange, dreamlike perspectives. The
jewel-studded costumes (also from Lysyk's designs, realized by
Oksana Zinchenko) were sumptuous to a fault, in a palette ranging
from snow white to blood red by way of rich ivory and deep gold,
with ethereal flowered coronets for the women.
</P>
<P>
   Yet deep down, the Bayreuth and the Kirov productions converged
with surprising frequency. At the crucial point when Lohengrin
tells his bride-to-be that she may never ask his name, the
triple-cast Kirov Lohengrin (the visiting Gosta Winbergh, Victor
Lutsuk or Leonid Lubavin) grabbed the double-cast Elsa (Tatyana
Pavlovskaya or Tatyana Borodina) by the chin, raising his free hand
as if to strike her. In Bayreuth, Roland Wagenfuehrer, not
otherwise long on ferocity in this unsettlingly hot-and-cold part,
held Melanie Diener and shook her like a rag doll: a picture as
unsettling as I hope ours was.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, both productions conceived the great duet of the
villains at the beginning of the second act, beneath its blistering
mutual recriminations and ice-cold conspiracy, as a depraved love
scene. In Bayreuth, Gabriele Schnaut's Ortrud, reclining on a
divan, drew Jean-Philippe Lafont's Telramund into her arms and
locked her legs around him. The Kirov's sopranos Larisa
Gogolevskaya and Makvala Kasrashvili worked their wiles on the
basses Edem Umerov and Victor Chernomorzev in more maternal
fashion, wife cradling husband's head in her lap, stroking his
hair, gently dripping into his ear her words' deadly poison.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the different stage pictures in the Bayreuth and
Kirov productions reflected genuine differences in intention. Minor
figures we did our best to particularize in St. Petersburg _ four
noblemen who conspire with Telramund, four pages who clear the way
for Elsa's procession to the church _ in Bayreuth sang unseen on a
stage plunged into pitch black. John Tomlinson, the King in
Bayreuth, played his part as a stentorian Lear, decaying from
authority to impotence and death at the final curtain: an
outside-the-box reading at the farthest possible remove from the
straight-ahead majesty of the Kirov's Mikhail Kit and Gennady
Bezzubenkov. Lohengrin himself _ an underwritten character, in my
opinion, mostly a blank onto which the beleaguered Elsa and her
antagonists project their fears and desires _ emerged in Bayreuth
as a hero against his will, in the grip of some churning anxiety or
neurosis the root of which was never revealed.
</P>
<P>
   But in the unusually painstaking treatment of the mute character
of Gottfried, the rightful heir of Brabant, the two productions
were again in striking accord. When the story begins, the boy is
missing and feared dead. Elsa, his sister, stands accused of his
murder, but Lohengrin clears her name through trial by combat.
Moments before the end of the opera, the boy's true fate is at last
revealed. In a plot to grab the duchy, the witch Ortrud has
transformed him into a swan: the very swan that guided Lohengrin
across the waters to Elsa in the first place. As his final act
before returning to his sacred retreat, the hero lifts the spell,
restoring Gottfried to a rank and title _ indeed a life _ no one is
left to protect. In the power vacuum of Brabant, the young duke's
prospects (pawn or lamb to the slaughter?) are bleak indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The symbol of the swan has not aged well. Realistic or stylized,
it morphs into instant kitsch. The bright haze that worked for a
while has worn to cliche. Yet the creature's presence must be
palpable. Lohengrin's farewell to the swan _ the first passage he
sings _ is among the most heartfelt moments of his part, surpassed
only by the page in which Lohengrin hands over his horn, sword and
ring to Elsa as keepsakes to hold in trust for her brother. The
savior's purity of compassion for the wronged, absent child strikes
a note of pathos quite distinct from that of his oddly contingent
affection for the sister.
</P>
<P>
   To motivate Lohengrin's intensity and tenderness, we at the
Kirov wanted the audience to see from the start the truth behind
the illusion. Lohengrin made his first entrance led by the hand of
a boy: Gottfried, lightly disguised in a short, feathered cape he
would shed at the moment of his release. At the same point in the
action, the Bayreuth audience saw Gottfried suspended high above
the stage, imprisoned in a glass cube, beating desperately against
the sides. The final tableau, in both productions, centered on the
child, barefoot and half-dressed at the Kirov, wrapped in the
King's cast-off scarlet in Bayreuth, in either case traumatized,
vulnerable and alone.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Bayreuth principals, Ms. Diener's vocally underpowered
yet mesmerizing Elsa led the field, her every gesture bold and
sudden, punctuating a stillness that was never inexpressive. In
Wagenfuehrer's sweet-toned Lohengrin, the lack of power proved a
greater liability. Opposite Ms. Schnaut's squally, hyperactive
Ortrud, Jean-Philippe Lafont's Telramund offered powerful singing
and insight that struck to the character's core. Antonio Pappano
conducted at an urgent pace, achieving rich color and sharp
dramatic detail.
</P>
<P>
   In other performances, Wolfgang Wagner's thoughtful but stolid
``Parsifal,'' erratically led by Sinopoli, boasted deluxe vocalism
from Violeta Urmana as the time-traveling Kundry and a touching
account of the title role from Poul Elming, especially convincing
in the potentially awkward scenes as a wild child of the forest.
Dieter Dorn's classic picture-book ``Fliegende Hollaender,''
unforgettable for the yellow house that levitates and slowly
pinwheels through the night sky, returned for one last summer,
still looking magical, though surely a shade less so for viewers,
like me, who had marveled at it before.
</P>
<P>
   Also on view for the last time was Heiner Mueller's spare
``Tristan und Isolde,'' which was new to me. In 1993, most critics
showered its unveiling with disdain. Staged in precisely calibrated
color fields by Wonder, inspired in part by the ritual theater of
Japan, in part by the endgames of Samuel Beckett, the production
has ripened to a masterpiece, every moment charged with precise,
impassioned meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, too, the performance was a triumph, with Waltraud
Meier incandescent as the tempestuous Irish princess and Siegfried
Jerusalem holding the course beyond all expectation as her
guilt-haunted lover. From the covered podium of the Festspielhaus,
unseen by the audience, Daniel Barenboim led a reading shattering
in its raw power yet equally remarkable for transparency, lyricism
and finesse.
</P>
<P>
   For artists as well as for audiences, the isolation and tunnel
vision of the festival add up to an experience not easily
duplicated elsewhere. Whatever the complaints against Bayreuth in
the present or anxieties for Bayreuth in the future, there is still
no better place for Wagnerites to check their bearings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
