<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS-HNS &LR;      08-31 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH REACHING OUT TO NON-HISPANIC CATHOLICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush's
proposed new partnership between government and charities has a
subtle message: He wants support from Catholics, one of the
nation's largest voting blocs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congregations and community groups must fight for children and
neighborhoods, creating what Pope John Paul II calls `a hospitable
society, a welcoming culture,''' Bush said as he unveiled his plan
in July in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Although far from having the Republican presidential nomination
sewed up, Bush's campaign staff already plans to win the general
election in part by targeting Hispanics, suburban women and the
nation's non-Hispanic Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that my message of hope and optimism is a message
(that) will appeal to people of faith,'' Bush said Tuesday while
campaigning at a Catholic school. ``I hope people understand that I
am serious that the compassion that exists in churches and
synagogues and mosques can change people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The defection of suburban women _ the so-called soccer moms _
from Texas Gov. Ann Richards in 1994 helped propel Bush into the
Governor's Mansion that year. And Bush's capture of about 40
percent of the Texas Hispanic vote in 1998 turned his re-election
victory into a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush aides say privately they also are reaching out
nationally to the non-Hispanic Catholics who once constituted the
core of the Reagan Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are likely to be 30 percent of the turnout in a national
election,'' said William B. Prendergast, author of a new book on
Catholic voting patterns and former research director for the
Republican National Committee. ``They also are strategically
located in states that are rich in electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Hispanic Catholics comprise large portions of the population
in Illinois, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
Catholics and other voters who traditionally voted Democratic
switched to the GOP column in the 1980s under the sway of Ronald
Reagan's patriotic appeals and became known as Reagan Democrats.
Total Catholic populations also are substantial in Texas, Florida
and California.
</P>
<P>
   While Reagan appealed to this group with a tough anti-communism
message in a Cold War world, Bush aides believe they can attract
Catholic voters with his ``compassionate conservative'' message.
</P>
<P>
   ``A president can speak without apology for the values that
defeat violence and help overcome poverty,'' Bush said while
outlining his faith-based initiatives in an Indianapolis speech.
``A president can speak for abstinence and accountability and the
power of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Portions of Bush's $8 billion plan _ new tax deductions and
credits for giving to charities, including those run by churches _
echo 1996 Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole's overture to
Catholic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan, like Dole's in 1996, appeal to an area of Catholic
social teaching that social problems should be solved first at the
local community or church level before government becomes involved.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's design on Catholic voters also appears to be shaping his
eventual potential quest for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge has been frequently mentioned for
Bush's second spot. And Bush, at an early campaign stop with Ridge,
said he would not rule out a running mate who favored abortion
rights, such as Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   But syndicated columnist Robert Novak recently reported that a
Bush adviser met privately with a prominent Roman Catholic
archbishop who said Ridge, especially because he is Catholic, would
be unacceptable to Catholics because of his views on abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he opposes abortion rights, even though he would not
fight as president to overturn Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court
decision legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, I am pro-life,'' Bush said Tuesday. ``I assume
there are some in the Catholic Church who will make their
determination based on that issue. I hope that convinces some
people to be for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Flynn, former Boston mayor and ambassador to the
Vatican, now heads the Catholic Alliance, a get-out-the vote
organization similar to the Christian Coalition. Flynn's goal is to
get the nation's 62 million Catholics to vote based on Catholic
issues, not partisan rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, both parties have been insensitive to the Catholic
vote,'' said Flynn, a longtime Democrat. ``The Catholic voter has
been ignored or taken for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said Catholics are ``pro-life, pro-family, pro-poor.'' He
said Democrats tend toward helping families and the poor while
ignoring Catholics on the abortion issue. He said Republicans tend
to be anti-abortion and for the family but generally turn their
backs on the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn in his weekly national radio addresses has been critical
both of Bush and Vice President Al Gore, the front-runner for the
Democratic presidential nomination, saying there is little
difference between the two.
</P>
<P>
   To win over Catholic voters, Flynn said, Bush is going to have
to show his compassionate conservative message is more than just
lip service on a few targeted programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about cliches. I'm talking about specifics,''
Flynn said. ``Who's in favor of health care for families ...Who's
in favor of a decent wage so people can support their families.
These are the blue-collar bread and butter issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan and President Carter almost evenly split the Catholic
vote in 1980, but Reagan's 1984 re-election set the record for the
largest Catholic vote received by a Republican, 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush won his 1988 presidential victory by capturing about
half of the Catholic vote. But Bush lost his re-election bid in
1992 with support from only 35 percent of the total Catholic vote.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast said that a lack of Catholic support for Democrats
was one of the causes of the Republican takeover of Congress in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   But Prendergast said Catholics also have shown themselves as
more of a swing vote rather than realigning to the Republican
Party. As much as 35 percent of the non-Hispanic Catholics tell
pollsters they are independent.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton won 53 percent of the Catholic vote in 1996,
Prendergast noted in his book, The Catholic Voter in American
Politics, but exit polls found the vote by non-Hispanic Catholics
dropped by more than a million votes from the 1992 election while
the turnout of Hispanic voters grew by 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won that vote largely by targeting Catholic voters with
political rhetoric that the White House dubbed M2E2: Medicaid,
Medicare, education and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast said Bush's compassionate conservative message could
be a Republican answer to that formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems in making a persuasive case to Catholic
voters is the perception that they (Republicans) are not
compassionate,'' Prendergast said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
