<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-BELLSOUTH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth's equipment deal with Lucent shows growth of wireless
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth has announced a $180 million deal with
Lucent Technologies for hardware, software and services needed to
expand the company's wireless network in Atlanta and southern
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year deal, an extension of a contract that expires
this year, is a reflection of increasing use of BellSouth's
wireless network in its two largest markets, said Kristie Madara,
spokeswoman for BellSouth Cellular. ``We are enhancing what we
have, adding capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has about 5.2 million wireless phone customers. The
company does not provide statistics for individual markets, but
demands on the network have been skyrocketing. For instance, the
company's customers in north Georgia (including Atlanta) now use
about 150 million minutes of wireless air time each month _ roughly
double the demand of only two years ago, according to Madara.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment for most of BellSouth's wireless network had been
provided by Hughes, an agreement that has been replaced with a
recent deal to buy from Ericsson. However, Lucent's portion is
substantial: One-third of BellSouth's system is represented by
north Georgia and south Florida, which includes Miami, Fort
Lauderdale, Boca Raton and West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of many carriers have complained in recent months that
some calls are dropped or blocked by crowding on the network. But
Madara said the expansion was not forced, since BellSouth's system
is not at capacity. ``Everyone is expanding their network. If you
are a wireless carrier, you are expanding your network because you
are looking at future growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Lucent products will come to BellSouth from outside
the region _ including the transmission equipment that is made in
Massachusetts. However, the fiber optics are coming from Lucent's
huge plant in Norcross, said Lucent spokesman Jim Messenger. The
company is providing various software, as well as transmission
equipment and some bigger optic lines that are increasingly
connected to cell sites. The fiber can carry far more information,
including digitized conversation, than copper lines. As wireless
phones are increasingly used to carry data _ especially from the
Internet _ the wireless carriers are looking for still more
capacity in the lines connecting cell sites to networks.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has more than 7,400 employees in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
