s e BC-LONDON-COMEDY-THEATER     08-31 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-COMEDY-THEATER$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRITISH PARABLE ABOUT LIFE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By MATT WOLF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Right Size _ or, as this two-man comedy team
prefers it, the right size _ is into more than typographical
anarchy. With nine original shows to date, these British performers
have acquired a sizable following since meeting at a clown school
in Paris a little more than 10 years ago. Absurdist drollery with a
sprinkling of Sartre and a dash of Beckett might describe their
most popular show so far: about being locked in a bathroom with a
stranger for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 8 that show, ``Do You Come Here Often?,'' will mark the
New York debut of Sean Foley, 34, and Hamish McColl, 37, when it
begins performances at Public School 122 in the East Village. The
work, which runs through Oct. 10, won an Olivier Award this year in
London for best entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one scatological gag in the entire thing,'' said
McColl, the more manic of the team and the one with longer hair.
``That's not to say that we didn't get them out of our system in
rehearsals.''
</P>
<P>
   A 75-minute mixture of sight gags, verbal groaners (``We need
nutrition'' elicits the reply, ``What's wrong with old trition?''),
and a healthy dose of the mock-portentous, ``Do You Come Here
Often?'' finds the comedy in confinement. The similarly bound (if
placeless) tramps of Beckett's ``Waiting for Godot'' never allowed
themselves this much diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Beckett's name has come up in describing the piece, as
have such disparate figures as Sartre, Ionesco, Abbott and
Costello, and the quintessentially British comic team of the late
Eric Morecambe and Ernie Wise. Americans, for their part, may think
first of Monty Python or, closer to home, of Bill Irwin and David
Shiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a lie to say we're not aware of that resonance as
we're doing the show,'' said McColl, responding to the Beckett
comparison. ``We put the characters in this situation because it
exposes their humanity extremely well. But we're not working from
an existentialist philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, why a locked bathroom? ``We were once stuck in an airport
toilet in the north of Norway,'' Foley said. ``The attendant had
finished the shift, so for 15 minutes we shouted very loudly.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the men moved away from their own material, appearing
to critical acclaim in `` Puntila and his Man Matti'' at the
Almeida Theater and then on the West End. McColl was the
hard-drinking landowner Puntila, with Foley as his comically
put-upon chauffeur, Matti, in a staging that folded mime, Bessie
Smith and an ode to the properties of herring into Brecht's 1948
parable.
</P>
<P>
   The production confirmed that the two are actors, not simply
sketch artists, which is why ``Do You Come Here Often?'' isn't the
exercise in lavatory humor it could have been (notwithstanding a
whimsical reference to ``papier de loo''), nor is it a foray into
audience participation _ for which, read humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joke's always on us, I think,'' said Foley, who, like
McColl, lives in north London. Directed and co-devised by Jozef
Houben in a variety of comic styles, ``Do You Come Here Often?''
asks what it would be like to spend years with another individual
who starts out a stranger but over time becomes companion and
adversary, even as both parties try to escape now and again. The
scenario resurrects an age-old archetype: companionship is a
defense, no matter how absurd the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   And what of that name, the Right Size? ``We thought it was such
a good title for us,'' McColl said. ``We weren't sure it made a lot
of sense, but we liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
