<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGNET01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bank software firm is on the money
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Magnet Communications is typical of an Advanced
Technology Development Center success.
</P>
<P>
   The company started in 1995 in the nascent field of Internet
banking for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last September, the company, which started in
Georgia Tech's ATDC, a state-funded incubator for high technology,
employed eight people. Steve Gordon, who was brought in as
president and chief executive, was No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company employs about 53 people. Last week, Magnet
closed its second round of venture capital, receiving a $9.5
million investment from a group of firms, including Cordova
Ventures and Live Oak Equity Partners near Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Magnet received $3.2 million of venture capital in September
from Minneapolis-based Coral Ventures, which also invested in the
recent round.
</P>
<P>
   Magnet Communications reported revenue less than $500,000 for
1998. Gordon said the company is on pace for about $5 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Dalton, a venture capitalist with Cordova Ventures, said
he tries to visit the ATDC once every three months. He said he
likes the Internet banking industry and the depth and strength of
Magnet's management.
</P>
<P>
   Magnet offers a group of 14 software products that let
businesses manage their money through the Internet. Magnet products
automate much of the software-based or pen-and-paper-based duties
of a company treasurer, Gordon said. Its customers include SunTrust
and First Union.
</P>
<P>
   This has been the year Internet banking has taken hold in the
public consciousness. In April, NetBank, a company near of Atlanta,
saw its share price climb 754 percent in the first four months of
this year. Shares of the Internet-only bank have since re-entered
the stratosphere _ up about 146 percent for the year _ but the
market activity made people aware of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based S1 and nFront, both of which write software that
banks use to offer their products online, also had big years. S1
announced plans to merge with Edify and FICS, two of its larger
competitors. NFront, which sells its products to small and
medium-sized banks, had an initial public offering of its stock in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Magnet Communications' business model is closer to nFront or S1
than to NetBank: Magnet's software for banks targets business
banking. S1 and nFront target individual banking customers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
