<HEADER>
A6214 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WALLST01-COX     08-31 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLST01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everyday stock investors showing little sign of panic
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Y2K arrived on Wall Street in August, with debt
markets flooded with offerings by companies unwilling to chance a
year-end computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   On Main Street, however, the much ballyhooed prospect that
computers might fail on Jan. 1, 2000, apparently is being viewed by
individual investors as a yawner.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers, investment advisers and mutual fund officials
agree that while the individual investor is interested in the
problem, and even becoming concerned enough to ask about it, there
is no evidence of panic.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the sentiment just 121 days before the world finds
out what happens when computers have to read dates ending in double
zero. The old ones can't, which created the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients have not made an issue out of it at this point,''
said Jack J. Calhoun Jr., vice president of Capital Directions, an
Atlanta investment counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, this is no different from any other
potential event that you have to endure because you have no way of
knowing how it will come out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When investors do ask about the issue, they get pretty much the
same advice, at least from mainstream advisers: Don't panic and
don't go to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advise clients not to take special precautions other than
the ones they normally take in today's market,'' said Robert M.
Balentine, chief executive of Balentine &AMP; Co., an Atlanta
investment counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, take a few extra dollars out of an ATM machine so as not to
be caught short of cash at the end of the year. But no, don't make
any wholesale portfolio changes.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, investors apparently are following that advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any specific investment decisions made in
anticipation of Y2K,'' said Balentine.
</P>
<P>
   If and when investors do decide to act, they'll have plenty of
information to go on. Amazon.com, the online book seller, lists 250
titles dealing with Y2K. A Y2K computer search brings up at least
800 Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, other financial institutions and professional
organizations have published brochures and articles designed to
inform investors of the nature of the problem and to reassure them
that it will not be ``the end of the world as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   But one mainstream analyst who comes close to a doom-and-gloom
attitude is Edward Yardeni, chief economist and strategist for
Deutsche Bank Securities. He has repeatedly forecast widespread
computer breakdowns that threaten to cause a worldwide recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we're hearing lots of good news doesn't mean that
everyone who's important to our economy will be ready,'' Yardeni
said in a published interview.
</P>
<P>
   If individual investors are not yet absorbed by Y2K, it may be
because they are distracted by a stock market that has already
suffered a moderate midyear correction and two Federal Reserve
interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, people are wondering if the market has already
topped out,'' said Victor Ugolyn, chief executive officer of the
Enterprise Group of mutual funds, based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the individual's concerns, they are likely to
be about interest rates, or whether there will be inflation, or a
turnaround in the price of oil. Y2K is there, but pretty far down
the list,'' said Ugolyn.
</P>
<P>
   That's not just a local phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Yankelovich Partners Inc., a research organization, conducted a
national survey for the Securities Industry Association in April
and May and found that only 6 percent of investors said they would
be likely to take money out of stocks before the year 2000 due to
concern about computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   J. Walker Smith, a vice president of Yankelovich Partners,
attributed that low level of concern to the amount of publicity the
problem has gotten in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels like, wherever the problem might be, it has
been addressed, especially in the last six to 12 months,'' said
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, people are getting a little tired of hearing
about it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith blames the doom-and-gloom tenor of some scenarios on
``consultants who can't sell their services unless they create a
demand, and they have been very skillful in stirring up hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that 2000 marks the end of a millennium, with its
biblical allusions to Armageddon, contributes to the Y2K issue, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial advisers are concerned that gullible investors may be
taken in by various defensive schemes, some of which border on the
survivalist agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is money to be made by playing on people's fears,'' said
Calhoun. ``In the recession of the early '90s, the doomsday
scenarios recommended that people put their money in gold. That was
the worst strategy they could have adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun and other advisers urge investors not to do anything
drastic with their assets. Their advice is mostly common sense in
nature: Keep good records of holdings and transactions and stick to
a long-range strategy unless there is some compelling reason to
change.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of issues that individuals are likely to
become more concerned about as the year wears on, the advisers
agree.
</P>
<P>
   What won't change is the predicament that everybody is in
because of the unique nature of the problem. There are no
precedents for guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in unknown territory,'' said Atlanta investment adviser
Lewis J. Walker, chief executive of Walker Capital Management and
national president of the Institute of Certified Investment
Management Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an adviser, I can't look back and say, `We went through
this back in '72 and '73, and did this and that.' At the same time,
this is not something that is catching us by surprise. The
uncertainty is there, but it's not the same as something coming at
us out of the blue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
