<HEADER>
A6226 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-DAD-DIFFICULTPHASE-TE     08-31 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAD-DIFFICULTPHASE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING THROUGH A `DIFFICULT' PHASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labels are a destructive, hurtful byproduct of our very mean,
mean-person, meanie society. I know. I endured many before
fatherhood: e.g., ``baldie,'' ``flirt'' and ``hack.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a caring father, I have to endure another unfair label:
``difficult.'' It's so wrongly applied to me. Herewith, I make my
case that I am not difficult, merely ``concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   I wrote a few weeks ago about my daughter's impending maturation
into kindergartenhood. I warned readers that I was having trouble
imagining that my sweet angel of purity _ hereinafter, ``Maddison''
_ was ready to leave the nest, primarily because state laws forbade
me from standing at the classroom door all day in an attempt to
ensure Maddison's every whim was served.
</P>
<P>
   Since many of you have asked, I will first tell you that my
daughter has adjusted to kindergarten fine. Swell. Loved it. Has a
friend named Kia. She's infatuated with some boy who eats whatever
comes out of his nose. Wants to get to school early so she can
swing while belting out ``Deep in the Hundred-Acre Wood.'' Normal
kid stuff.
</P>
<P>
   I, however, have been labled ``difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   It began on Day 1 at 0800 hours. The kindergartners filed into
class, parents in tow, and took their seats. They immediately began
coloring with school-issued Crayolas. There were, as I recall,
eight in the box. I always provided my precious ball of bubbly
perfection (i.e., Maddison) with 24 crayons at home, but, you know
... public schools. Whatareya gonna do?
</P>
<P>
   The teacher _ whom I'm still running background checks on; full
report in weeks to come _ told the children that they could, if
they so desired, write their first names on the sheet of paper they
were drawing//coloring on.
</P>
<P>
   This was no problem. My daughter, after many years of day care,
not only has many separation issues that will be probed in therapy
someday but also knows how to write her name very well. I stood
proudly as she wrote it out in, I believe, Violet. Some parents,
overly concerned with ``competition'' between tots, panicked
because their munchkins were so behind Maddison. You could see them
huddle around their tot, frantically blurting out in stage
whispers, ``DEEE ... AYYY ... ARRR ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``And now,'' the teacher said, ``you can write your last name.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddison looked up at Mommy and Daddy with confusion. She had
never practiced this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last name!'' I bellowed uncontrollably, then turned to my
wife. ``What kind of psychotic taxpayer-funded last-name-writing
boot camp are they running here?'' Then I noticed that Kia, across
from my poor bewildered baby, whipped out her last name. This was
serious. My daughter was ... ``behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher noticed my wild eyes and red face. She squinted. I
could read her mind: ``difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wife, please make a note,'' I said. ``Tonight, two pots of
coffee, a Big Chief tablet and six solid hours of last-name
calisthenics.''
</P>
<P>
   I think it was Day 4 that sealed it.
</P>
<P>
   All seemed to go well at first. Swinging at 0730. The line-up
bell at 0750. But the teacher was late. The kids and parents waited
in the hall. We were told something about ``car trouble,'' but that
the kids would be ``fine.'' They could wait in another teacher's
classroom until their teacher arrived. The parents kissed their
munchkins and left for work. All 'cept one. That would be me. Dr.
Difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, can I help you?'' asked a pleasant person from the school
office who had been sent to deal with this person standing in the
hallway at 0820. ``Nope,'' I said, ``juuuuust waitin' on teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Office person's eye's narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, sir, I can relay a message ...?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you are, sir. What can I tell the teacher?''
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. I gave in. I figured I'd now been labeled ``difficult.''
But the next level is ``psychotic,'' and we don't want to go there,
so ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted her to know that Maddison doesn't like peanuts
in her M&AMP;M's. So if someone could be assigned to remove them before
snack, you know, that'd be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I decided on the way to work, and based on reports from
the PTA meeting, I don't think I won the ``difficult vs.
concerned'' debate.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
