<SLUG> BC-COCAINE-TEACHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON TEACHER ARRESTED AFTER COCAINE FOUND IN SCHOOL BATHROOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A special education teacher was arrested Tuesday on
drug charges after cocaine was found in a room the teacher had just
vacated, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Yvonne Dailing, 38, a teacher at Jefferson Elementary
School, was charged Tuesday with possession of a controlled
substance, said Carmen Abascal Gomez, a spokeswoman for the Houston
Independent School District.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said that around 12:15 p.m. CST Monday, workers at the
school noticed that Dailing was behaving erratically.
</P>
<P>
   ``She met with the school nurse and then asked if she could use
the principal's restroom, which she did,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   After Dailing left the restroom, the school principal, Ann
Zamarripa, went into the restroom and noticed there was a bag in
the room containing what appeared to be drugs, the spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said the principal called HISD police, who had the
substance tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be 5.5 grams of cocaine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   HISD police took the case to the Harris County District
Attorney's office, where the charges were filed in the 182nd
District Court. Bail was set at $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said Dailing was arrested about 3 a.m. Tuesday at her
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Dailing, who instructs children on different grade levels, will
remain on the district's payroll, but she will be relieved of
teaching duties pending the outcome of the case, Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also said Dailing was given a drug test and, if the results
are positive, the teacher will be terminated.
</P>
<P>
   HISD teachers are not drug tested before employment, Gomez said.
However, she said teachers are tested randomly or at the request of
a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   HISD officials said drug offenses among teachers are so rare
that they don't keep statistics on drug-related firings.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Federation of Teachers President Gayle Fallon concurred
that few teachers have ever been charged with drug possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not common,'' she said. ``It's tragic, but it's not
common.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A review of Houston Chronicle stories showed only two drug
arrests of HISD teachers in the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some parents outside the school in north Houston
expressed surprise about the arrest, while others said they did not
know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Pilar Sifuentes, standing outside the school Tuesday waiting for
her two children, said she was not bothered by the arrest. ``They
don't even have any contact with her,'' Sifuentes said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Guagarer said she was shocked to learn of the allegations.
``They should check out all the teachers before they let them in
the school,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another parent, who did not want to be identified, said she was
concerned about the arrest but added that such incidents can happen
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good school. Drugs are every where in this
country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
