<HEADER>
A6246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO-0901-COX     08-31 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-0901-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FREEH 'WOULD SUPPORT' OUTSIDE WACO INVESTIGATOR
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI would ``welcome and cooperate with'' an
outside investigation of its handling of the 1993 siege at the
Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, an agency spokesman said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While not specifically recommending that Attorney General Janet
Reno call in an independent investigator, bureau director Louis
Freeh has made it clear during regular conversations with Reno that
the bureau would not object to such a move, said FBI spokesman Tron
(CQ) Brekke.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of talk is going around that the FBI can't investigate
ourselves,'' Brekke said. ``I think we would be very comfortable
with any outside investigator or staff of investigators that the
attorney general might choose.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau, a division of Reno's Justice Department, has been
under fire for more than a week because of its disclosure last week
that ``pyrotechnic'' canisters containing a riot control substance
were used on April 19, 1993, the day the religious cult's Mt.
Carmel compound burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure, which contradicted assurances by Reno and FBI
officials for more than six years that no incendiary devices were
used by federal officials at Waco, touched off a new round of
congressional investigations and caused Reno to declare that she
was ``upset'' at having been misled by bureau officials.
</P>
<P>
   The House Government Reform Committee has issued subpoenas in
its own investigation of the use of what FBI officials have
described as ``a very limited number'' of the exploding canisters
on the final day of the extended Waco siege.
</P>
<P>
   The committee wants to see evidence gathered by Texas Rangers
following the fire in which cult leader David Koresh and 79 other
members of his apocalyptic sect died, according to a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the Government Reform
Committee, has said he will hold hearings on the matter in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Rangers' evidence, Burton has said he wants
to know what role members of the U.S. Army's secret ``Delta Force''
anti-terrorism unit played in the Waco tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department and the FBI have acknowledged that three
or four active duty members of the military were at the Branch
Davidian standoff but only as observers and advisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the interest of avoiding a potential perception on the part
of the media and others of a conflict of interest, it might be in
the best interest of everybody concerned to have outside
investigators,'' said Brekke. ``We have 40 assistant directors here
and a staff that does this kind of investigation quite often, but
some people are saying the FBI can't investigate itself and any
findings would be tainted.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Reno was quoted by the Associated Press as
saying she had not made a decision Tuesday on how to investigate
the FBI's admission that some exploding canisters of ``CS,'' a
military riot control substance, were used at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials say the canisters were fired away from the
compound where Koresh and his followers holed up during the 51-day
siege and were used early on April 19, roughly six hours before the
Davidians' compounds burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Documents made public last week by the FBI and the Defense
Department indicate Reno questioned not only FBI officials, but
also commanders of the ``Delta Force'' and Defense Department
chemical weapons specialists, about the affects of the CS before
approving its use to force Davidians out of their compound.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was told the bureau had evidence children inside
the rambling wood-frame building were being abused and that the
extremely irritating substance would force members of the sect to
leave the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after an armored military vehicle began pumping CS dust
into the Davidian's building, the structure burst into flames. The
FBI has said the Davidians themselves set fire to the building.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
