<HEADER>
A6249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-KEYES-PROFILE-ART-2TA     08-31 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYES-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNORING THE ODDS, KEYES INSISTS HIS IS THE VOICE OF MORAL
VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: S.C., Iowa, N.H., Texas, Md.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ As he wanders the nation prophesying a
political apocalypse, Alan L. Keyes, the staunchly conservative
radio talk show host, is the invisible man in the Republican
primary for president.
</P>
<P>
   He gets few cameras at his events. Political analysts tend to
forget him in their prognostications. Polls show him receiving one
percent of the vote or less. And when the Log Cabin Republicans, a
homosexual group, issued a news release last week attacking
religious conservatives for intolerance, Keyes didn't even merit a
mention.
</P>
<P>
   But to his small yet devoted cadre of followers, Keyes is the
best kept secret of the campaign. To them, Keyes, a former Reagan
administration diplomat with a Harvard Ph.D., has something his
fellow conservatives lack: mesmerizing oratorical skills twinned
with a messianic vision.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the heart of the Keyes for President campaign.
With little money, name recognition, organization or governing
experience, Keyes is running on his powerful voice, breathlessly
wooing far-right voters with Boschian word pictures of schools that
are ``places of death,'' taxpayers who are ``enchained slaves'' and
children who have fallen into a ``howling moral void.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he is given little chance of winning _ he finished
seventh of nine candidates in the Iowa straw poll _ winning is not
what he promises his followers. What he offers is the chance to
feel morally correct on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusion I've reached is that no one is doing what I
believe needs to be done,'' Keyes said in a recent interview,
speaking of the moral issues. ``If I were satisfied that anyone
else was addressing it, I would not run.''
</P>
<P>
   His campaign chairman in South Carolina, Hal W. Stevenson, said,
``If you only care about your chances of winning, you don't back a
guy like Alan. You back him because you like what you hear. You'll
feel better when the election is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes did win the Alabama Republican straw poll last Saturday,
but other than Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, who finished second, he
was the only candidate who competed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time when several Republican candidates, including
the front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, are trying to downplay
divisive issues like abortion and gay rights, Keyes provides an
eloquently uncomfortable reminder that, to some dedicated
conservatives, ideological purity matters more than victory in
November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a struggle going on in the party,'' said
Keyes, 49, who also ran for president in 1996. ``It's a struggle
between the Money-is-God Republicans and the God-is-God
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Keyes aims the sharpest barbs at Bush, whom he
considers a tepid-tongued pragmatist. In Greenville, he mocked
Bush's slogan of ``compassionate conservatism,'' saying, ``You
don't prove you are compassionate by talking about it.'' He accused
Bush of exploiting moral issues, ``without being seriously
committed to facing the moral challenges.'' And he ridiculed the
Texan for saying he would not demand that all his nominees to the
federal bench share his opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it true we need leaders who will be vague in their response
to the most compelling moral issues we face as a people?'' Keyes,
who is black, asked the virtually all-white crowd in Greenville.
``No!'' many of them responded.
</P>
<P>
   Though his campaign has received little media attention, Keyes
has consistently drawn hundreds of people to his ``Renewing
America'' speeches in South Carolina, Iowa and New Hampshire.
Marietta Kaiser, 72, of Greenville, walked out a convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a breath of fresh air,'' she said following Keyes'
appearance here two weeks ago. ``We've heard the cliches of the
other candidates, and they just don't move the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   But his against-all-odds campaign has drawn questions from some
rivals and analysts, who suggest that he is using the race to draw
attention to his speaking-for-hire business and to gain listeners
for his radio program, which until recently was syndicated to about
75 stations in more than 43 states.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, Keyes gave about 20 paid speeches a year,
typically to corporations or college groups, charging between
$12,000 and $15,000 for each, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But the aides scoffed at the assertion that he profits from
running for office. They said that he suspended the radio show
during the campaign and has scaled back his paid speaking
engagements to about 15 this year. They added that most of his
speeches are given free to benefit pregnancy counseling centers and
anti-abortion groups.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics have asked whether Keyes is living off his
campaign account, as he did during his losing 1992 U.S. Senate race
in Maryland when he paid himself more than $8,000 a month from
campaign donations. Though the practice was legal, it prompted
criticism even from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes says he is not drawing a salary from his campaign fund,
which had raised $1.9 million as of June 30 and had $172,497 on
hand. But he argues that the practice is legitimate and that his
critics are ``wealthy oligarchs.''
</P>
<P>
   In private, Keyes cuts a different figure from the acid-tongued
talk show performer who has amazed even the most combative hosts
with his ability to shout them down. With his goatee and newly trim
build _ he has lost 70 pounds in two years _ he can come across as
a genial academic. An opera buff, he confesses to relaxing with
westerns and action films or ``Star Trek'' re-runs.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, the youngest of five children, is the son of a career
Army officer who moved the family repeatedly through Italy and the
United States. Raised a Roman Catholic, Keyes attended parochial
schools for much of his youth, though he graduated from a public
high school in San Antonio, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, he was already demonstrating his powerful
speaking skills, winning the American Legion's national oratorical
competition and getting elected president of the Legion's Boys
Nation, the first black to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Though his parents were die-hard Democrats who admired John F.
Kennedy, Keyes became a Republican while attending Cornell
University in the late 1960s, where he viewed Vietnam War
protesters as repugnantly anti-American. He transferred to Harvard,
where he earned a doctorate in government.
</P>
<P>
   While serving as a State Department official in India during the
Reagan administration, he met Jeane J. Kirkpatrick, who later
called him ``one of the most dramatically articulate people'' she
had ever met. After she became chief delegate to the United
Nations, Ms. Kirkpatrick made Keyes the ambassador to the U.N.
Economic and Social Council. Reagan later appointed him assistant
secretary of state for international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In India, Keyes also met his wife, Jocelyn Marcel Keyes, who is
Indian. They have three children and live in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Keyes' speeches are aural spectacles, part revivalist sermons,
part Oprah. With a microphone on his lapel, he wanders through the
audience, talking _ sometimes in a whisper, sometimes in a shout _
for an hour or more without notes, weaving incandescent images of
an America going to Hell in a high-speed handbasket.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that a collective loss of faith in God's authority has
caused a panoply of social ills, from the breakdown of
``marriage-based families'' to the Columbine shootings to failing
schools to ``immoral'' military interventions abroad, including in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Without God in their lives or their politics, Americans are
allowing an increasingly authoritarian central government to tax
and regulate them into submission, he says. Likening Americans to a
frog that sits calmly in a pot while the water gets hotter, he
argues that Americans are passively watching their freedoms erode.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're past medium rare and headed toward well done,'' he said
in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, he prescribes some strong medicine. He would
eliminate the income tax and finance the government on tariffs,
duties and excise taxes. He would end welfare and outlaw abortion.
He has even endorsed the public paddling of parents who abandon
their children.
</P>
<P>
   But in private conversation, Keyes reveals more nuanced views.
And that makes for some interesting paradoxes.
</P>
<P>
   Though he ridicules targeted tax cuts as ``marionette strings,''
he also endorses federally subsidized mortgages for families and
tax breaks for banks that invest in poor neighborhoods. And while
he warns that ``perpetual war'' is a means by which totalitarian
governments control their citizens, he is not an isolationist,
having strongly supported America's involvement in Vietnam,
Cambodia, Grenada and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   There are interesting nuances in Keyes' views on race as well.
He is an ardent opponent of affirmative action and other race-based
social programs. But he also speaks passionately about the need to
address urban poverty through private investment, and has often
lambasted the Republican Party for not recruiting more blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans vacillate between trying to buy off black
voters with programs, trying to out-Democrat the Democrats, and
just writing them off,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Keyes says, his revulsion for slavery has intensified
his conservatism, not weakened it. As a teenager, he voraciously
read books about slavery, weeping while he wondered why more slaves
did not revolt. Lincoln became his hero. Even his stump-speech
language _ ``We need to strike off our chains,'' is a favorite
phrase _ is drawn from the peculiar institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered, why didn't people resist to the point of
fighting and dying?'' he said. ``Why would human beings let
themselves be oppressed, when they could have said, `give me
liberty or give me death,' and gone out in a blaze of resistance?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6257 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MIT-ASPHYXIATE-BOS &LR;      08-31 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-ASPHYXIATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURE NITROUS OXIDE CUTS OFF ALL OXYGEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nitrous oxide, the colorless, sweet-tasting gas believed to have
been involved in the death early Tuesday morning of MIT student
Richard A. Guy, has been used for decades as both a legitimate form
of anesthesia and, not so legitimately, as a drug to induce
euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   When used properly to induce anesthesia, it is quite safe,
anesthesiologists say, because it is always given as a mixture with
oxygen. But if someone breathed 100 percent nitrous oxide, that
would mean he was getting no oxygen, which would be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Discovered in England in the late 1700s, nitrous oxide (not to
be confused with another gas, nitric oxide) was common in traveling
fairs, said Dr. Jeffrey Uppington, a Massachusetts General Hospital
anesthesiologist. After a few puffs, people would start ``cavorting
around,'' triggering the nickname, ``laughing gas.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid 1830s, an American dentist, Dr. Horace Wells, noticed
that during such gaiety, people seemed to experience no pain, the
first clue that the euphoria-inducing gas might be an analgesic as
well.
</P>
<P>
   To prove his hunch, Wells arranged for a public demonstration of
nitrous oxide at MGH in January 1845. But he apparently failed to
give enough because his patient yelped as Wells pulled his tooth.
</P>
<P>
   With cries of ``Humbug!'' medical students drove Wells from the
room. (A more successful demonstration of anesthesia _ with ether _
occurred the next year at MGH, prompting surgeon John Collins
Warren to proclaim then, ``Gentlemen, this is no humbug!'')
</P>
<P>
   Despite this awkward beginning, nitrous oxide was soon adopted
by surgeons and dentists because it worked quickly _ inducing a
rapid onset of anesthesia and wearing off fast, too.
</P>
<P>
   Today, nitrous oxide is used in virtually every operating room,
though it's still unclear precisely how it (or any general
anesthetic, for that matter) works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a common anesthetic agent. We use it all the time,'' said
Dr. David Feinstein, an anesthesiologist at Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But to prevent danger, anesthesiologists always use a mixture of
70 percent nitrous oxide to 30 percent oxygen. In fact, anesthesia
machines are calibrated to mix the two gases so that the patient
never breathes 100 percent nitrous oxide.
</P>
<P>
   The human body does not naturally make nitrous oxide, but it
does make the gas with which it is often confused, nitric oxide,
which causes blood vessels to dilate. Nitric oxide is often given
in intensive care units to patients suffering from pulmonary
hypertension; inhaled, it works quickly to dilate blood vessels in
the lungs, without reducing blood pressure elsewhere in the body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FRANCE-ECON-ART-2TAKE     08-31 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-ECON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE FRANCE RESHUFFLES, FLEXES MUSCLES ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 (smw) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When Thierry Desmarest joined the French oil company
Total as an exploration expert 19 years ago, most of Total's
shareholders were French _ including the French state, with 35
percent _ and most of its profit was made in France. Its far larger
domestic rival, Elf Aquitaine, was mainly a government fief run by
bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest, now the chairman at age 53, mused in a recent
conversation that it would be ``difficult to imagine'' Total
contemplating a merger with Elf back then.
</P>
<P>
   Today both companies are publicly owned, and about 65 percent of
Total's shareholders and 51 percent of Elf's are not French.
Earlier this year, Total took the brash step of merging with the
big Belgian group Petrofina to become Total Fina, and it is now
locked in a brawl to acquire Elf Aquitaine. If Desmarest succeeds,
and he is convinced he will by the end of the year, the combined
Elf and Total Fina will still be only half the size of new giants
taking shape, like the Mobil-Exxon combination, but it will dwarf
many European rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can change rapidly,'' Desmarest said, seated in his
office here with a view of Elf's black glass headquarters tower.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, France has moved to shake up and slim
down its corporate world more thoroughly and quickly than many had
thought possible. And in the process, it is simultaneously creating
a kind of fortress within Europe even as it reaches aggressively
beyond its borders into the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   France has gone through periods of wrenching restructuring in
the past. In the 1980s, heavy industries like steel and coal, as
well as financial services like insurance, were reorganized, and
tens of thousands of jobs were shed.
</P>
<P>
   But while those changes, aimed at overcoming a chronic bloat
that was smothering the economy, required France to go through a
decade of pain, there are tentative signs that the latest wave will
produce a much faster payoff.
</P>
<P>
   France has become a darling of foreign investors, and the Paris
bourse has surged by 50 percent in two years, against an average of
44 percent for the top 300 European companies.
</P>
<P>
   Growth prospects are brighter than in a long time. This year,
the economy is expected to grow 2.5 percent, and though that is
less than last year's 3.3 percent because of the downturn in
emerging markets, the government expects as much as 3 percent in
2000. Last year's growth produced a windfall of tax revenues, which
were $6 billion higher than anticipated in this year's first half,
prompting discussion of possible tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   There is even some relief on the job front. Though unemployment,
at 11.5 percent, remains stubbornly high, in this year's second
quarter private-sector jobs rose by 266,000, or nearly 2 percent,
over 1998. The feeling, however tenuous, that things are getting
better has helped transform the gloom that shrouded France in the
mid-1990s into a new consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   And there is little sign that the corporate reshuffling will let
up soon.
</P>
<P>
   In banking, an unsuccessful $37 billion hostile bid by Banque
Nationale de Paris for two domestic rivals, Societe Generale and
Paribas, ended with the takeover of Paribas, a strong investment
bank, by the far larger Banque Nationale, creating what will be the
third-largest bank in Europe after Deutsche Bank, the German
banking giant, and Switzerland's UBS. The takeover will reshape the
banking landscape in ways that could favor future consolidation
beyond France.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by the changes, French corporations are entering new
and inventive alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the big aluminum group Pechiney joined Alcan
of Canada and Alusuisse Lonza of Switzerland to form a behemoth to
challenge the pre-eminence of Alcoa.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the chemical giant Rhone-Poulenc agreed to a $23
billion merger of its drug activities with those of Hoechst in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   And as French companies reorganize, they are flexing their
muscles abroad. Americans were struck in recent months by the
struggle of two French giants, Vivendi and Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux,
for control of the growing American market for water services. In
March, Vivendi, once a stodgy utility called Generale des Eaux,
made the biggest French acquisition ever in the United States when
it paid almost $8 billion for the United States Filter Corp. Not to
be outdone, Lyonnaise des Eaux has spent more than $6 billion on
similar acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other way but to follow the rules of the game as
it's played now,'' said Eric Barthalon, chief economist at Paribas.
Change is much in evidence at Paribas itself after the takeover by
Banque Nationale. Yet Barthalon senses spirits rising.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when he returned to Paris after spending two years at
Paribas' offices in London, ``it was a nightmare,'' he recalled.
Paris was crushed by gloom, particularly among the young, who
thought there was little chance of upward mobility. Talented
graduates emigrated to Britain or the United States, finding work
in Silicon Valley or at London brokerage firms. ``This has pretty
much changed over the last two years,'' Barthalon said. ``Good
people don't have to go abroad for jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly, the shake-up is the work of a new type of French-bred
corporate raider. Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH-Moet
Hennessy Louis Vuitton, has consolidated the fashion and perfume
businesses. Earlier this year, the billionaire Francois Pinault
bought a large stake in Gucci, the Italian fashion group, in hopes
of creating a rival luxury goods conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   More often, graduates of the elite French training schools are
learning to play by the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Bebear, chairman of the big AXA insurance group, got a
degree from the Ecole Polytechnique. But with results below those
that would have qualified him for top government jobs, Bebear went
to work at a sleepy insurance company in Normandy. In the past, he
would never have made it to the top of French society. But Bebear,
now 63, had a strong sense of opportunity, picking up acquisitions
at opportune moments. The turning point in his career came in 1991,
when AXA paid $1 billion for a majority stake in the Equitable
Insurance Company. Today, AXA's share is worth 15 times that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bebear went further, acquiring Union des Assurances de
Paris, a big French insurer the government had sold off two years
earlier. But Bebear's real influence comes from AXA's role as one
of France's, and the world's, largest asset managers. AXA is the
biggest shareholder in Elf Aquitaine and owns substantial shares of
Banque Nationale and Paribas. ``He is a fabulous manager, but he
has a vision,'' said Elie Cohen, a leading French economist. He
added that Bebear, who is an avid big-game hunter, brings the same
instinct to his business decision-making. ``He knows that if you
have to kill, you have to kill immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Also driving consolidation is the government's push the last two
years to sell big shares of more than a score of huge enterprises,
including banks, industrial companies, and insurance. Though the
state still holds large stakes in companies like Renault, Air
France and France Telecom, the government of Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, despite its Socialist heritage, has sold assets worth more
than $30 billion to private shareholders. Many of these assets have
gone to British and American investment funds, which become
involved with the way the businesses are run, demanding good
returns on investment and sensible long-term strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Total was one of the pioneers. In 1991, the company listed its
shares on the New York Stock Exchange, starting a flood of
investment from institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   And the trend toward an international shareholder base
continues. The arrival of the euro is encouraging European
investors to diversify geographically. ``What strikes me much more
now,'' Desmarest said, ``is the arrival in the last year of new
shareholders from Germany, the Netherlands.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the private sector is getting back into shape,
over-manned government operations pose even greater challenges for
Jospin. Government spending, much of it on railways, postal service
and medical care, account for 54 percent of the economy, against 40
percent in Britain. More than 25 percent of the workers in France
are employed by government compared with 14 percent in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce unemployment, the government has resorted to an
immensely costly make-work program that created 174,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's immediate challenge, advisers say, is getting a handle
on pensions and health spending. With more than two years before
national elections, Jospin wants to start debate on reducing the
gap between government pensions, which reach as much as 85 percent
of final salary, and those in private business, where they are
about 50 percent. To cut medical costs, the government wants to
consolidate the public hospital system.
</P>
<P>
   Despite union resistance to changes in the traditional public
sector, labor leaders support Jospin in his bid to speed financial
and industrial privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Christophe Le Duigou of the executive board of the CGT, the
big labor federation that grew out of the Communist labor movement,
accepts the government's retreat from the business of running
businesses, arguing that the public sector had ``reached its limits
both industrially and financially.''
</P>
<P>
   And he acknowledges that the private sector is creating jobs,
even if many of them are considered temporary or part-time
employment. Last year, hours lost through private-sector strikes
were the fewest ever in postwar France. What his union now wants is
for the government to help by improving education and pouring more
state money into industrial research. Referring to a cellular phone
on his desk, Le Duigou asks, ``Why should this be made by Nokia or
Motorola _ not in France?''
</P>
<P>
   His union is conciliatory in part because Jospin delivered on a
pledge to enact legislation cutting the work week to 35 hours, from
39. The idea, based on a popular notion of the labor market as a
pie of fixed size, is that if the slices are cut smaller, there are
more slices for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Le Duigou acknowledges that the 35-hour week has not
automatically created jobs. Still, he says, the new law is
delivering benefits because it forces labor, business and the
government to sit together and discuss ways to ease the dislocation
caused by corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Business grudgingly swallowed the 35-hour week, negotiating in
exchange a union commitment to more flexibility. In exchange for
fewer hours, business won the right to more overtime, weekend and
night work, increasing the productivity of factories that operate
on high- and low-production cycles, and can now run nonstop in
periods of high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Total Fina is an example. The 35-hour week, Desmarest says,
means the company ``will try to achieve a level of productivity
gains to compensate'' for lost hours. Total Fina should benefit
from greater flexibility at its robot division, which supplies the
auto industry, with its seasonal and cyclical demand.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Desmarest added, he would have preferred a different
approach. ``At the end of the day,'' he said, ``I am not at all
convinced this will create jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
