<SLUG> BC-DIANA-ANNIVERSARY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO YEARS LATER, DIANA IS THE `FORGOTTEN' PRINCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The death of Diana, Princess of Wales, on Aug. 31,
1997, marked the beginning of an outpouring of grief and national
stock-taking that astonished no one more than the British
themselves. They awoke to find that they lived in a country whose
most famous lip was suddenly a trembling lower one.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two years later, Britons are struck by how quickly the
woman whose funeral drew the largest television audience in history
has come to be overlooked in her own land, how swiftly buttoned-up
royal reserve has returned and how few of the societal changes that
were so confidently forecast then have actually taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgotten'' was the one-word banner headline in the Mirror
deploring the neglect of Diana's memory. ``It is almost as if she
never existed,'' the paper complained. ``If we are not very
careful, there is a real danger that she will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   The tabloids kept her alive long after her death with adoring
biographical series, reminiscences from acquaintances no matter how
distant, and excerpts from instant books. But, significantly, The
Mirror is now the only newspaper rising to the defense of
enshrining her memory. Attitudes elsewhere in print were epitomized
by Anne McElvoy, a columnist for The Independent, who concluded,
``Diana is yesterday's princess.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Mallory Wober, a social scientist who has just completed a
book on the news media and the monarchy, said he was not surprised
at this year's diminished commemoration. ``When Diana died, we
allowed ourselves to go over the top for a bit, but now we have
gone back to normal,'' he said. ``We have discharged all the grief
at her death, which has thrown up all sorts of emotion _ including
embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a monument in Kensington Park have been shelved
without even a scaled-down tribute under active discussion, and the
exhibit about her life and death at her stately family home Althorp
House is no longer a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   The monarchy remains starchy, remote and secure despite the
abrupt readjustments it had to make in the week after Diana's death
to meet the expectations of the sorrowing British population who
thronged central London and demanded that the royal family get more
in touch.
</P>
<P>
   The heir to the throne, Prince Charles, appears in public with
Camilla Parker Bowles, the mistress whose permanent banishment from
his side was said to have been insured by the public canonization
of his dead young former wife.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll by the Sun in June, 59 percent of readers who
responded said that Charles should be free to marry Mrs. Parker
Bowles without having to renounce his right to the crown.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parker Bowles regularly sees Diana's sons, Prince William,
17, and Prince Harry, 14. The boys spent Tuesday, the second
anniversary of Diana's death, with their father in Balmoral, the
Scottish residence of Queen Elizabeth II, rather than with their
other ``blood relatives'' whom Diana's brother Earl Spencer
famously called their true guardians in his eulogy at Westminster
Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The queen decided there would be no special commemoration of
Diana's death, as there was last year when a special prayer service
was held in Crathie Church with Prime Minister Tony Blair and his
wife, Cherie, in attendance. The flag at Buckingham Palace, lowered
a year ago, flew at full staff Tuesday, and the state rooms of the
royal residence in London were open to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Diana, 36, died in Paris in the early hours of Aug. 31, 1997,
from injuries suffered when the chauffeur-driven car carrying her
and her millionaire admirer, Emad Mohammed ``Dodi'' Fayed, 41,
slammed into the wall of an underpass by the side of the Seine,
killing the two of them and the chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   A French judge's official report into the accident and its
causes is to be published shortly, and prosecutors have already
concluded that, contrary to claims in the immediate aftermath,
paparazzi photographers chasing the limousine were not responsible
for its losing control. The driver, Henri Paul, was found to have
three times the legal limit of alcohol in his body and to have been
traveling at excessive speed.
</P>
<P>
   Income to the Diana Memorial Fund has declined substantially,
but much of that is attributable to its announcement last summer
that in fairness to other charities it was no longer actively
seeking money. It is estimated to have attracted $150 million, much
of it in royalties from Sir Elton John's ``Candle in the Wind,''
memorably sung at the funeral, and from approved memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, the fund expects to have distributed
$40 million to charities favored by the princess, including groups
that support land-mine clearance and care for people maimed by the
devices.
</P>
<P>
   The committee to come up with a London monument, headed by
Gordon Brown, the chancellor of the Exchequer _ the second most
powerful person in the Blair government _ has been dormant since
its proposal for a three-acre memorial garden and fountain outside
her Kensington Palace home was squelched by neighborhood objections
over its size. The committee has not met since November.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a permanent London shrine was the principal
lament of people who placed flowers at the gates outside her former
home Tuesday. ``Where's Diana's memorial?'' one placard read.
``Remembered by the people and forgotten by the establishment,''
said another.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not so many people out here this year, and it's
going to get less and less, which is why we need a permanent
memorial, '' said Joyce Vanherring, 42, from Bracknell in
Berkshire.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors used the occasion to attack the former cavalry
officer James Hewitt, 40, Diana's onetime lover, whose plans to
write a new book about their relationship. The 60 love letters that
the princess wrote him emerged this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ought to be hung, drawn and quartered,'' said Iris O'Brien,
63, of Hornchurch, Essex. Her husband, Michael, 69, said: ``As a
young man, I never went around saying what I did with girlfriends
and things like that. He would have been shot in the past. He is
supposed to be an officer and a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two years since his emotional funeral tribute to his
sister galvanized resentment against the royal family, Earl Spencer
has seen his own image battered by coverage of his divorce in South
Africa from a former model, Victoria Lockwood. Among other things,
it emerged that he had scorned her for having eating disorder
problems similar to those of his sister for which he had sought
public sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer observed the second anniversary of Diana's death in
privacy at Althorp House, where Diana spent her teen-age years and
where she is buried. The public exhibit there, which includes a
mock temple, early photographs and home movies, school reports, her
wedding dress, texts of speeches she made and a visit to the
shoreline of the small lake with the island where her grave lies,
closed Monday night and will reopen in July. Of the 150,000 daily
tickets available over the summer, 8,000 remained unsold.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diana frenzy is over,'' columnist Tony Rennell conceded in
The Observer on Sunday. He said it was true that all the bright
predictions of a new, caring Britain had not been realized, but he
said the outcome left him uneasy for another reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``What troubles me is the attempt in some quarters to pretend it
never happened,'' he wrote. ``No one has the right to dismiss those
emotions as cheap or false or unworthy. Puzzle over what happened,
yes, but don't belittle it and don't deny it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
