<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-ART-5     08-31 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-ART-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE RETURNS TO EAST TIMOR FOLLOWING PEACEFUL REFERENDUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ Anti-independence thugs who have terrorized
East Timor for months reasserted themselves Tuesday, one day after
an extraordinarily peaceful referendum on the region's future in
which, officials said, 98.6 percent of eligible voters cast their
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The thugs, who had been mobilized into irregular militias by the
Indonesian military, set up roadblocks in Dili, the tiny capital
city of this territory, and on a number of rural roads.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance they stalled a convoy of 17 vehicles carrying
150 foreign and local workers for the United Nations for several
hours. The convoy, which was traveling from the Ermera area to
Dili, later proceeded without incident, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A militia leader, Eurico Guterres, said his armed men would bar
what he called the East Timorese elite from leaving. He claimed to
have blocked some people from boarding a scheduled flight Tuesday,
but airport officials said all passengers who had tickets had
boarded.
</P>
<P>
   Some promoters of independence said they had received death
threats and were going into hiding. There were also reports that
the militias might harass foreign journalists. But despite the
threats and menacing behavior, there were no confirmed reports of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Fischer, the leader of the Australian observers here, said
he understood that three people had been killed on Monday in the
Ermera area, southwest of Dili. But a U.N. spokesman, David
Wimhurst, said he could not confirm this.
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst said the electoral process was proceeding as scheduled,
with all the blue plastic ballot boxes from around the country
securely gathered, ``all safe and sound'' in a counting center
here. The center is guarded by unarmed U.N. police advisers. The
main police station is next door, although the local force has been
mostly passive in the face of the violence here.
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst said reviewing and counting the ballots would begin on
Wednesday. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is to announce the
result within about a week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the referendum, voters chose whether to accept an offer of a
new, more nearly autonomous status within Indonesia, in which East
Timor would control its own affairs except for foreign relations,
the military and some judicial and financial administration. If the
offer is rejected, President B.J. Habibie has said, Indonesia will
grant full independence to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The choice, after 24 years of warfare that has deeply divided
the territory, brought a new crescendo to the long-running
violence, with the militias acting as surrogates for the Indonesian
military.
</P>
<P>
   The former Portuguese colony was invaded by Indonesia in 1975
and annexed the following year as the 27th province. But it has
never submitted to Indonesian rule, and an estimated 200,000 people
have died in the separatist war.
</P>
<P>
   The strong voter turnout suggested a victory for independence,
and opponents of independence began Tuesday to raise complaints
about the balloting and to balk at a role in a planned commission
of reconciliation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several key pro-autonomy leaders refused to attend an initial
meeting of the commission, which is to include 10 supporters and 10
opponents of independence and five U.N. representatives. They
distributed a letter addressed to the United Nations that claimed
the referendum was biased in favor of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst said, however, that he was not aware that any
complaints about electoral irregularities had been filed through
the official channels set up to review the conduct of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the anti-independence groups, Basilio Dias
Araujo, issued a statement Tuesday asserting that the United
Nations ``is really encouraging the people of East Timor to break
East Timor away from Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the interpretation of a fair and just ballot shall mean
that the pro-independence side should win, then the outcome will
really be just garbage,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst expressed concern that some of the 4,000 East Timorese
who helped the United Nations conduct the vote may be at risk of
reprisals. He called on the Indonesian police to assure their
safety.
</P>
<P>
   He said the successful and peaceful conduct of the referendum
had been a rebuke to the attempt to use violence to block it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could not work, it did not work and it will not work,'' he
said. ``It is imperative that everybody lays down their arms and
ceases all violent actions, as it is completely futile, but instead
focuses their energies on the long process of reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Carina Pirelli, who heads the office of electoral affairs at the
United Nations in New York, said the huge turnout ``shows that
neither fear nor violence nor intimidation can stop the people when
they want to have their voices heard.''
</P>
<P>
   She said most of the people who had been forced by militia
violence to flee their homes in recent weeks and months had emerged
on Monday to vote and then, in many cases, fled again into hiding.
A number who were unable to return to their home regions to vote
had since come to the U.N. office here, she added, telling
officials: ``I couldn't vote. Can I vote? I want to vote.'' But it
was too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
