<P>
   TIMOR-KILLINGS (Dili, East Timor) _ Three UN staff reported
killed in East Timor. Pro-Jakarta militias serve notice that they
haven't given up despite indications of an overwhelming vote for
independence. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIT-STUDENT-DIES (Cambridge, Mass.) _ A third-year physics
student, Richard Guy, 22, of California, dies after suffocating
while using a plastic bag to inhale laughing gas. By Thomas
Farragher. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MIT-ASPHYXIATE (Undated) _ Nitrous oxide, the colorless,
sweet-tasting gas, has been used for decades as both a legitimate
form of anesthesia and, not so legitimately, as a drug to induce
euphoria. By Judy Foreman. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-SAT-SCORES (Undated) _ The SAT scores from last year are out
and it looks like Massachusetts' results are the highest they've
been in 10 years. However, education agency remains perplexed about
a persistant gender gap, with boys outscoring girls by a wide
margin. By Doreen Iudica Vigue. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUN-INTERNET (Undated) _ Sun Microsystems wants to shift use of
spreadsheets and word processors onto the Internet and away from
the PC desktop dominated by Microsoft. But analysts say Sun will be
hard-pressed to wean everyday computer users from Microsoft's
ubiquitous desktop software. By Alex Pham. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HKN-BRUINS (Wilmington, Mass.) _ Goalie Byron Dafoe meets with
Bruins' general manager Harry Sinden, trying to break his contract
stalemate. By Nancy Marrapese-Burrell. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN (New York) _ By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ROYALS (Boston) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
