A6271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MVP01-COX     08-31 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MVP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elway hopes for TD with MVP.com site
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Football legend John Elway is already one of the
game's most valuable players. Now he wants to repeat on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The former Denver Broncos quarterback, along with the
Atlanta-based J.W. Genesis Co., are 50-50 partners in a new online
venture called MVP.com set to launch on Super Bowl Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The site _ at www.mvp.com _ plans to focus on finances, sports,
fitness and lifestyles. It's a concept similar to the
woman-oriented site iVillage.com but aimed at men, something Elway
says hasn't been done before.
</P>
<P>
   MVP.com hopes to use Elway's connections and J.W. Genesis
financial know-how to build a high-end Web site featuring the
``most valuable'' goods and services for its users.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a niche that's in high demand and doesn't have much
competition,'' Elway said in an interview Tuesday. ``It's a chance
to do something different and separate ourselves in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   MVP.com's Chief Operating Officer Joel Marks says the idea for
the site evolved gradually with a little nudge from Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier this year we were deciding whether or not to take the
plunge and go into online trading,'' Marks says. ``We've been one
of the real resisters because we couldn't see how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   J.W. Genesis handled Elway's investments from its Denver office,
and Marks briefly considered an online trading business with Elway
as a spokesman. However, once Elway was in the picture, the company
decided to rethink its online strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we did more and more homework, we realized that the
relationships John has established in business, charity
endorsements and personal contacts was opening doors for us,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, it seemed, wanted toto connect to John Elway's
Internet star.
</P>
<P>
   ``What started as an online brokerage became a lifestyle
company,'' Marks says.
</P>
<P>
   Elway admits he doesn't know much about Web development strategy
or business models. Still, he's savvy enough to see the potential
of the Web as a commercial enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at how far the Internet has come in the last few years
and where it is headed,'' Elway says. ``I want to be there on the
cutting edge. It's still early and there's still time and nobody
has figured out how to make money. We'd like to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone with Elway's celebrity stature could have joined forces
with nearly any Internet company he wanted. But he says he chose
J.W. Genesis because it offered him the chance to be involved from
the ground floor. ``I'm not just an endorser,'' Elway says. ``I'm
involved in the shape and the direction the company takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
