<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLASS SLIPPER IS HARD TO FILL AT CBS; `MILLIONAIRE' GAME SHOW IS A
BIG WINNER   AT ABC; PITCHING  ` HAMLET ' AT TNT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though CBS has mainly invoked Cinderella as its
preferred metaphor, the network has, in truth, turned the hunt for
a female co-anchor to pair with Bryant Gumbel on its revamped
morning show into a summerlong game of Clue.
</P>
<P>
   As in: ``Ms. Green (from inexperience) in the news reader nook
with a contingency clause!''
</P>
<P>
   That suspect translates to Jane Clayson, whom CBS apparently was
close to hiring as the news reader for the show, with the
possibility of her being moved up to the co-anchor slot after she
got into the CBS fold. Then ABC, her current employer, blocked that
move, using a clause in her contract that allows ABC to match any
offer for her.
</P>
<P>
   So far the envelope with the right combination of elements to
solve the mystery remains empty on the CBS game board.
</P>
<P>
   Having missed its first planned deadline by not hiring a
co-anchor by July, when CBS could have introduced her to about a
hundred reporters in the same room at a news conference in
Pasadena, Calif., CBS instead told that assemblage of reporters
that Labor Day was the target date for this long-awaited
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Labor Day weekend looming, CBS looks likely to miss
that date as well.
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives said Tuesday that they were about 99 percent
certain that the selection would spill over at least into the
middle of next week, perhaps to the beginning of the following
week. That will leave CBS only seven weeks to work the chosen one
into its plans for the show, which is set to have its premiere the
morning of Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   More important, perhaps, it only gives CBS seven weeks to mount
a recognition campaign for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The news of morning television is bound to get cluttered during
the next two weeks. NBC will start ``Later Today,'' its 9 a.m.
follow-up program to ``Today,'' the day after Labor Day, and the
following Monday ABC is to open up its news studio overlooking
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   CBS did announce one new addition to ``The Early Show'' on
Tuesday. Laurie Hibberd, a correspondent for ``Good Morning
America'' and a former co-anchor of a morning show on the cable
channel FX, will become a correspondent, doing twice-monthly
reports on popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESSFUL `MILLIONAIRE'
</P>
<P>
   The success of ABC's summer game show ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' has been so staggering _ it was the No. 1-rated show
again last week and led ABC to a resounding weekly ratings victory
_ and apparently so unexpected, that it left the air on Sunday
night after its two-week run without being able to tell viewers
when to tune in next.
</P>
<P>
   Regis Philbin, the host (and truly the show's biggest winner of
all), did tell viewers the show would return in November. But
exactly when and at what time is apparently still up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   So is the format for the new editions, though several ABC
executives said Tuesday that it was almost certain that the network
would present the show in a tournament style at least one more
time: a burst of editions on consecutive nights over two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If that works, ABC may face tougher choices about whether to
make the show a weekly series or perhaps turn it into a syndicated
show, which could be highly lucrative for the television production
company. ABC executives said Tuesday that though some calls were
being made to television stations this week about possible
syndication interest, these were not made by ABC, and ABC owns the
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives acknowledged that uncertainty remained about the
show's long-range potential. In Britain, for example, where it
originated and has become a phenomenon, it has only been on for a
year. So no one knows how long the public appetite for the show
will last.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in the best American television tradition, every effort
is being made to ride this suddenly popular horse and, inevitably,
beat it to death. Other networks and producers are pitching game
show ideas all over Hollywood. CBS had hoped to broadcast a new
version of the ancient game format ``What's My Line'' this summer
but got started too late and put off the show until next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has other games in the works, including a comedy game
concept with Norm MacDonald called ``Have I Got News for You.''
</P>
<P>
   But having turned summer television upside down with
``Millionaire,'' ABC is looking at its options with a lot of
caution, said Edward L. Dandridge, the vice president for network
communications. ``I can tell you a concern about cannibalization
exists,'' Dandridge said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   'TIS NOBLER TO SYNOPSIZE
</P>
<P>
   The TNT cable network has been building a reputation for
acquiring rights to first-run movies and giving them their
commercial television premieres. Normally they have been popular
movies like ``Space Jam'' or ``Ghosts of Mississippi,'' but this
Sunday night, TNT will present Kenneth Branagh's 1996 ``Hamlet'' in
its full four-hour production.
</P>
<P>
   The film will have just one corporate sponsor, Mercedes-Benz,
which will interrupt it only four times for brief commercial
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, even with Branagh starring and other celebrities in
minor roles (Robin Williams, Jack Lemmon, Billy Crystal),
``Hamlet'' is unusual fare for TNT. So the network hired a
freelance writer to synopsize the text for television writers and
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Her one-page summary explains that ``Hamlet has been seeing
Ophelia, Polonius' daughter,'' and that, believing the young prince
is ``out of his mind,'' Polonius and Claudius ``decide the best
thing to do is to have his mother talk some sense into him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fortinbras storms the castle in the final scene to find
Hamlet, Gertrude, Claudius and Laertes all dead, the summary says,
``By process of elimination, he assumes the throne of Denmark.''
</P>
<P>
   The synopsis seems accurate. But what does it say about TNT's
view of the nation's television critics?
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
