this has nothing to do with the president.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE KITCHEN OF THE FUTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A lot is cooking in the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's
Kitchen of the Future lab, where, says the latest issue of
Smithsonian magazine, the following concepts are being explored:
</P>
<P>
   - An oven mitt that tells its user whether the food is hot and
ready to eat.
</P>
<P>
   - A pH meter, to be embedded in a spatula, that measures acidity
or alkalinity, thereby indicating that salad dressing, for example,
is ``mild,'' ``getting spicy'' or ``sour.''
</P>
<P>
   - A laser cutter that can slice a bagel and write or make
drawings on cut fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   - A kitchen drawer that serves as a washer and storage space for
dishes and tableware.
</P>
<P>
   - A spoon able to ``taste'' food by recognizing the ingredients
in it.
</P>
<P>
   - A countertop scale that counts calories when food such as ice
cream, for example, is spooned into a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   - A microwave oven that reads the bar code on a food package and
cooks it for the right amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   - A counter that becomes a cooking surface when you put a pot on
it.
</P>
<P>
   - Mr. Java, an espresso machine that fills orders transmitted by
a tag embedded in the bottom of the user's cup.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers told the magazine that the laboratory focuses on
kitchens because they are the site of the home's most complicated
tasks. ``Offices have a fairly modest set of interactions compared
to the kitchen, where you have recipe timing, guests arriving, food
temperatures, ingredients and a lot of other complexities most of
us take for granted,'' said researcher  &UR; Michael Hawley &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Denny Delk  &LR; asked a teacher to explain this week's report
that the skills of California high school students are lagging. Her
response: ``Well, like, DUH!''
</P>
<P>
   - In a story labeled gossip and told with no geographical
reference, Vogue reports that when a security guard wouldn't allow
a shopper entry to a recent invitation-only sale on Manolo Blahnik
shoes, the shopper bit him. Aside from the wound, it couldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   - The Smithsonian Institution bowed to pressure from  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Gielgud &LR; , PETA and others and canceled its foie gras event.
Officials quoted in the Wall Street Journal said they feared
``something untoward'' would occur.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CATCHING UP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a New Yorker Talk of the Town piece about the Illtop Journal,
Harvard's new black counterpart to the humor magazine the Lampoon,
its founder  &UR; Chris Rock &LR;  proclaims, ``Our comedy-writing skills are
far behind that of the white man.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not shy about admitting a link to prior generations of
humorists. ``When I got to `Saturday Night Live' '' said Rock, ``I
robbed  &UR; Mike Myers &LR;  of everything he did. He'd do `Wayne's World'?
All right, I'll do `I'm Chillin'.' Everything he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you do. White, black, whoever you are, I don't
care _ if you want to be good, you steal. ... They've done it to us
for centuries, well, we can do it to them!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys always say to me, `I just want a girl with a great sense
of humor,' forgetting, perhaps, that I make a career of being
funny. Then I see them a week later with a gorgeous girl who has
nothing to say, &LR;  but who laughs uproariously at their jokes. That's
when I lean into the guy and say, `You really scored with this one.
She's friggin' hilarious.' They never like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  -  &UR; Cheri Oteri  &LR; of ``Saturday Night Live'' in Harper's Bazaar.
</P>
</TEXT>
