<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6295 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-AIDS01-COX     08-31 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young men expanding HIV rates
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because as little as 10 percent of young Americans infected with
the AIDS virus are aware of their status, many continue high risk
behaviors, thus fueling the epidemic, new research shows.
</P>
<P>
   Young people, especially young gay and bisexual men, make up at
least half of all new cases of HIV infection. Yet perhaps only 10
percent of HIV-infected people in their teens or early 20s have
been tested for the virus that causes AIDS, researchers estimate.
And most young HIV-positive people aren't aware of their status,
according to research presented Tuesday at the National HIV
Prevention Conference in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that risky sexual behaviors were common among the
HIV-positive youth we studied,'' said Dr. Paul Denning of the HIV
surveillance branch of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, which co-sponsored the conference.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS trackers have known for some time that people under 25, as
well as minorities and women, are on the leading edge of the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, research from the CDC and several universities confirms
suspicions that a growing complacency regarding AIDS is
contributing to the high infection rates. Many people falsely
perceive AIDS as a manageable disease because of recent advances in
HIV drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers estimate that at least 100,000 and possibly as many
as 225,000 people 13 to 24 are HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention of
3,492 gay or bisexual men aged 15 to 22 years found that 41 percent
of them had engaged in unprotected anal sex within the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Of the young men in the survey who turned out to be
HIV-positive, only 18 percent already knew they were infected.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that research shows young people seem to
respond well to youth-savvy prevention programs. A condom marketing
program aimed at teens in Seattle and Portland, Ore., and San Jose,
Calif., resulted in fewer sexually active teens and higher rates of
condom use.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
