<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-WEEKEND01-COX     08-31 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-WEEKEND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP weekend to include speech by Gingrich, award for Barr
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Annie Taylor went over Niagara Falls in an oaken
barrel and lived to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   The next election will tell whether Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) can
survive the rough and tumble journey of leading the way on
President Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Barr and two colleagues who also served as House
managers in Clinton's trial in the Senate will receive the Annie
Taylor Award at the fourth annual Weekend in Colorado Springs,
Colo. The gathering is the conservative alternative to the
Renaissance Weekend that draws President Clinton to Hilton Head,
S.C., each New Year's holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a Michigan schoolteacher, braved the falls in 1901
hoping for fame and fortune. She died destitute.
</P>
<P>
   But David Horowitz, executive director of the Center for the
Study of Popular Culture in Los Angeles, the organizer of the
weekend, suggested that the award carry her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of represents bravery,'' said John Campbell, the
center's managing director, explaining Horowitz's reasoning. ``Or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's lineup features leading Republicans and
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich will give the keynote speech
at the conference's first breakfast Friday. It will be Gingrich's
first public appearance that is open to the media since he filed
for divorce from his wife, Marianne, in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the program are seminars on the 2000 presidential
campaign and the Chinese espionage scandal. A forum entitled
``Caring About the Inner City'' will include Wayne LaPierre,
executive vice president of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   NRA spokesman Bill Powers said LaPierre will talk about the
group's support for Project Exile, a program that stresses strict
enforcement of federal gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-QACHARLOTTE01-COX     08-31 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QACHARLOTTE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    End of busing in N.C. city will challenge schools' diversity
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any day now, U.S. District Judge Robert Potter is expected to
decide whether three decades of forced busing in North Carolina's
Charlotte-Mecklenburg's schools should end. It would close a
historic chapter in the nation's 23rd-largest school district, the
first in America to use busing to achieve racial integration. It
also would pose challenges, which Superintendent Eric Smith, 49,
discussed with staff writer Chris Burritt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Citing the uncertainty hanging over the judge's ruling, the
Mecklenburg County Commission recently refused the school board's
request for a $365 million bond referendum on November's ballot.
How do school officials reconcile that setback with the need for
new schools and renovations to bring greater equality to the
district's 138 schools?
</P>
<P>
   A: It certainly sent us back to the drawing board. We know that
without question we need additional student capacity in our
high-growth areas. We have a need to bring our older buildings up
to standard. Our long-range master plan calls for 11 new schools
over the next eight years, on top of the 10 that are currently
being built. We estimated needing $1.3 billion over a 10-year span.
We have yet to determine how we are going to bring this about,
possibly with bonds after the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last spring the school board devised a five-year plan that
would end forced busing by creating three to five geographic
clusters in the school district. Each cluster would be diverse by
race and socio-economic factors, allowing children in those
clusters to attend schools near their homes. How might the judge's
ruling affect that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The court might not allow that. We do not know what it is
going to say. It might say that any consideration of race is not
allowed. In that case, even the development of clusters that would
be racially consistent would not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would that wipe out this cluster idea?
</P>
<P>
   A: If we did not base it on race, we could probably base it on
other factors, such as population growth, economics. This would be
dramatically different from what we've done for the last 30 years
under the court's directive that we achieve a balance of 40 percent
black and 60 percent white in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   The real question now is how much time the judge will give us to
make these changes. If he says we have to do the conversion by next
fall, I cannot build new buildings by next fall. I may be
converting pupil assignments and using facilities that are known to
be inferior. The question becomes how quickly can we bring new
facilities on line.
</P>
<P>
   Q: County Commission Chairman Parks Helms said that an end to
forced busing might create schools which are all black or all
white. Explain that.
</P>
<P>
   A: When we are directed to stop using race as a factor in how we
draw boundaries, obviously we are going to stop looking at 40/60
(black-white ratio). Obviously those African-American students (in
the city) who were transported out for the purpose of racial
balance will more than likely be given an assignment close to home.
Those schools become primarily African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would that be widespread?
</P>
<P>
   A: We haven't put numbers to it, but it would be widespread. It
is a major problem from a facilities standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 30 years in Mecklenburg, we have built buildings
based on an integrated school system. If we no longer transport
students out of the city to suburban schools, they will be going to
school closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   We will have to build new buildings. Otherwise, African-American
children would continue to be bused to suburban areas, even after
we receive the court order, because there simply are no schools for
African-American students to go to.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Specifically, a return to neighborhood schools would create
demand for 7,000 additional seats in the inner city, reflecting the
African-American students who would no longer be bused. Explain
that.
</P>
<P>
   A: We currently transport about 7,000 African-American students
out to suburban schools for the purpose of racial balance. If you
are now going to say that students are to go to their closest
school, it works fairly well in the suburbs where we have built
schools for the last 30 years. It does not work well in the city
where we have not built schools for 30 years and where many of the
existing schools have been converted to magnet schools ... in part
as a way to encourage white students to come into the city schools.
With those seats being occupied by magnet-school students, we are
short 7,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you see these schools, which are becoming predominantly
one race, or all one race, over time becoming more diverse?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't necessarily see that happening on a natural basis.
Our experience here is when schools become significantly
identifiable by one race or another, they have a tendency to become
even more that way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At what point does this pattern cause concern that
re-segregation of public schools is happening?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is a major concern today. I think it is going to be a
major concern across the country. The benefits that diversity
brings to individual students and their ability to compete
academically, to compete in the work place, the ability to work
together _ these are things we all need to be concerned about
losing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
