<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WACO-FBI (Washington) _ Acknowledging that the agency's
credibility has been damaged by revelations that incendiary devices
were used at the Branch Davidian compound, FBI Director Louis Freeh
has recommended to Attorney General Janet Reno that an outside
investigator head the renewed inquiry into the fiery end of the
Waco standoff in 1993. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-SCHOOL (Washington) _ With millions of youngsters
returning to school, the White House unveils seven new anti-drug
ads aimed at reaching children in the classroom, on the playing
field, at home and on the Internet. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CATHOLICS (Omaha, Neb.) _ A subtle message of George W.
Bush's proposed new partnership between government and charities is
that he wants support from one of the nation's largest voting
blocs: Catholics. Although far from having the Republican
presidential nomination wrapped up, Bush's campaign staff already
plans to win the general election in 2000 by targeting the
swing-voter bloc of non-Hispanic Catholics. Campaigning at a
Catholic school, the Texas governor said he believed he would
appeal to this group. By R.G. RATCLIFFE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUCATION (Omaha, Neb.) _ Gov. George W. Bush, in another
move away from the social-conservative platform, says he will not
fight to abolish the Department of Education. Bush, who also
advocates local control of schools, says he wants to expand the
successful federal Head Start preschool program. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
