<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-ACCORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO'S REBELS SIGN PEACE ACCORD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUSAKA, Zambia _ The divided rebels in Congo finally signed a
peace agreement Tuesday, a key step toward ending the fighting but
only the start toward reconstructing one of Africa's biggest,
richest and least stable nations.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for a cease-fire within 24 hours. The other
combatants in the war _ Rwanda, Uganda, Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia
and Congo itself _ signed the far-ranging document last month, and
it now goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the rebel groups signed the accord in a hotel ballroom
here, they continued to squabble about how to carry out its first
main provisions. But Tuesday was significant nonetheless, because
the peace process could go no further until the document was
signed, whatever the coming hardships in putting the plan into
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just get those signatures,'' Patrick Mazimhaka, a top
Rwandan official, said impatiently as reporters asked him before
the signing how difficulties could be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Congo started a year ago, when a group of rebels
who had little in common united to oust President Laurent Kabila,
who had himself taken power in a similar rebellion only the year
before. With the backing of Rwanda and Uganda, the rebels, called
the Congolese Rally for Democracy, captured nearly half of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But after months of tensions, both among the rebels and between
Rwanda and Uganda, the rebel group split in May. Then in July, the
rebels declined to sign the accord because one faction refused to
sign if the other did.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday that disagreement was resolved in a chaotic compromise,
which involved not only the faction leaders but all 50 people who
founded the Rally for Democracy in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As a choir of Congolese refugees sang, the rebels sat in
alphabetical order, in two long rows facing each other, and each
signed copies of the accord. Thus the group's first leader, Ernest
Wamba dia Wamba, was nearly last to sign, while his replacement,
Dr. Emile Ilunga, was among the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a ridiculous way of doing things,'' said Amama Mbabazi,
the top Ugandan official at the ceremony. ``But it's their
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the reasons why Ilunga's faction agreed to the
compromise became clear Tuesday: Of the 50 original founders, 41
follow Ilunga in a faction based in Goma, a city in eastern Congo
that includes most of the rebellion's military might. Only nine
have remained loyal to Wamba dia Wamba, who is based in Kisangani,
in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, members of the Goma faction said, they are entitled to
chose both representatives to a powerful military council being
formed that will administer and monitor the peace. Tuesday night
they named their two choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are just following the simple rules of democracy,'' said
Moise Nyuragabu, vice president of the Goma group. ``We can vote,
do an election.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wamba dia Wamba said he expected to name one person to the
council based on informal agreements among the parties before the
signing. ``There is no way we can't get a seat unless you have
amended the agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The poisonous atmosphere that has preceded the signing seems to
jeopardize long-term prospects for peace. ``I'm not too
optimistic,'' said one European diplomat. ``Knowing the guys we are
dealing with, you can't expect everything to be solved. It's just
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   On one level the disagreement appears to be a continuation of
the two groups' vengeful squabbling. Little held the rebels
together from the start, and only two weeks ago they were engaged
in battles in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   But if the accord holds, Tuesday marks the end of the armed
struggle and the beginning of the political one _ and so the
disagreements among the rebels are partly an early struggle to lead
an opposition to try to topple Kabila in elections.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most important deadlines in the agreement is one in 45
days, when the rebels, Kabila and other civic and opposition groups
are to engage in a ``national dialogue,'' as yet ill defined, that
will determine how a new Congo will be structured.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement's other main parts include the establishment of
the military council within seven days; the withdrawal of foreign
troops within 180 days; and deployment of U.N. peacekeepers within
120 days.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Zambia, Frederick Chiluba, who has been the
main force behind the peace talks, said over and again at the
signing that Tuesday was only the beginning, and perhaps the
easiest part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big responsibility that does not end with the
signing,'' Chiluba said. ``It begins with the signing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
