<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAUFMAN-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$18 MILLION TRADING LOSS REPORTED AT KAUFMAN &AMP; BROAD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kaufman &AMP; Broad Home Corp., one of the
nation's largest home builders, said Tuesday that it had lost $18.1
million from unauthorized trading of mortgages by an employee.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company said, it will take an after-tax charge
against earnings of 24 cents a share in its third fiscal quarter,
which ended Tuesday. The charge will reduce the quarter's earnings
by about 25 percent. Analysts had forecast that Kaufman &AMP; Broad
would earn 93 cents a share. The company said that even with the
charge, it expected record earnings for the quarter, exceeding the
68 cents reported in the comparable period last year. It added that
the full extent of the loss had been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman &AMP; Broad, which is based here, said the unauthorized
trading had mainly been conducted in the last 30 to 60 days by a
single person, whom it declined to identify. The employee, who the
company said tried to conceal the trading by falsifying records,
has been dismissed, and it is now considering what, if any, legal
action to take.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to take the news in stride, with the stock
dropping 37.5 cents to $20.4375.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the ultimate scheme of things, it was a relatively modest
one-time event,'' said John Stanley, an analyst at Warburg Dillon
Read, who has been recommending the stock.
</P>
<P>
   The employee who engaged in the unauthorized trading was Kaufman
&AMP; Broad's only mortgage trader. He had worked at the company for
two years and there were no other known problems with him, said
Mary M. McAboy, vice president for investor and public relations.
She declined to discuss his possible motive but said there was no
evidence that the employee had profited personally from the
trading.
</P>
<P>
   The problem occurred at a San Fernando Valley subsidiary that
provides mortgages for about 80 percent of the parent company's
home buyers, the Kaufman &AMP; Broad Mortgage Co. of Woodland Hills,
Calif. It then resells the mortgages in the secondary market.
</P>
<P>
   Because it takes 30 to 60 days from the time a loan to a home
buyer originates until it can be resold, the company makes a
contract to sell the loan at a future date at a specified price.
This locks in the interest rate, insulating the company from any
gains or losses caused by interest-rate fluctuations that might
occur until the mortgage is sold.
</P>
<P>
   The company's policy is to make such forward contracts only for
loans it originates, Ms. McAboy said. But the employee engaged in
speculative trading not connected with such loan origination. While
she was not specific, he might have agreed to sell loans that the
company had not yet originated, hoping that interest rates would
decline before he had to deliver, allowing him to obtain a loan and
resell it at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the employee was the only mortgage trader could
have given him latitude to hide his dealings. Ms. McAboy said the
trading was caught by the company's internal security and audit
procedures, which have since been strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman &AMP; Broad said it expected to be the nation's largest home
builder this year in terms of the number of homes delivered. It has
grown by acquisitions and has benefited from a strong economy in
its territory, primarily California and other Western states.
Orders for the third quarter are up about 35 percent over last
year's period, in part because of an acquisition late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company's stock, like that of many other home
builders, has not performed well; investors fear that rising
interest rates or the eventual end of the economic boom will
depress the housing market, Stanley of Warburg Dillon Read said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6312 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCONNELL-FUNDRAISING     08-31 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCONNELL-FUNDRAISING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR BADGERS GROUP SEEKING CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., one of Congress' most
ardent opponents of a bill that would overhaul the campaign finance
system, has aggressively urged 10 business executives to resign
from an organization that has endorsed a ban on unlimited
contributions to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of letters sent late last month to executives who
are members of the Committee for Economic Development, McConnell
accused the group of trying to ``eviscerate private sector
participation in politics'' by imposing ``anti-business speech
controls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you will resign from CED,'' McConnell, the chairman of
the National Republican Senatorial Committee, scribbled near the
bottom of one letter sent to an unidentified senior executive of a
telecommunications corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Committee for Economic Development, which
includes executives of General Motors, Xerox, Merck and Sara Lee
Corp., refused to identify the executive or the corporation in the
letter. But they did say that McConnell wrote letters to executives
who work for companies that have significant issues pending before
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell also wrote that he was ``astonished'' that the
corporation had ``lent its name, prestige and presumably financial
backing'' to the Committee for Economic Development, which he said
was lobbying on behalf of a ``radical campaign finance agenda.''
McConnell argued that the executive's alliance with such a group
had consequently damaged the reputation of the executive's
employer.
</P>
<P>
   In his public statements, McConnell argues that current
campaign-finance legislation would infringe on free speech
protections of the First Amendment. Critics of the Republican
Party's position on the issue, however, say that Republicans are
motivated by the knowledge that they hold a commanding advantage in
raising campaign money from the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kangas, a co-chairman of the Committee for Economic
Development's panel that studied the campaign finance system, said
Tuesday that McConnell's letter confirmed for him that the
organization, which has enlisted more than 100 current and retired
executives to endorse new campaign finance rules, was beginning to
shape the contentious debate on the subject on Capitol Hill. The
letter was first reported on Sunday on the editorial page of The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've been doing as a group of business leaders is
obviously beginning to have an impact,'' said Kangas, the chairman
and chief executive of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, the accounting and
consulting firm. ``If we weren't having an impact, he would not be
communicating with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kangas said that none of the executives who had received the
letter had resigned and that he did not expect that any would leave
the committee. Indeed, Kangas, and other committee leaders, said
they had already recruited more executives in the past several
days. They said their goal was to have 300 executives endorse their
campaign finance proposals by late autumn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the people at CED have figured how just how
corrupt the campaign finance system is, and this letter is just an
example of what they already knew,'' Kangas said. ``Actually, we
are broadening the constituency of business leaders who recognize
that the campaign finance system is a real problem. Sen.'s
McConnell's letter has not had much impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was seen by some as an attempt to intimidate the
members with the implied message: Resign and keep quiet or don't
count on doing business with Congress. ``The reaction was
interesting,'' Kangas said. ``These guys are running big
enterprises of their own. They are not easily intimidated. They
looked at the letter and most of them just chuckled and filed it
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is a 60-year-old business-led public policy and
research association based in Manhattan. Its leaders pride
themselves that it is fiercely nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kolb, the committee's president, said there was a
growing consensus in the business community that the campaign
finance system is ``out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives on the committee are urging Congress to prohibit
soft money, the unlimited donations that corporations give to
political parties. The committee also advocates increasing the
limit on individual contributions to $3,000 from the current limit
of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business community, by and large, has been the provider of
soft money,'' said Kolb. ``These people are saying: We're tired of
being hit up and shaken down. Politics ought to be about something
besides hitting up companies for more and more money.''
</P>
<P>
   For two years, the committee's members studied the campaign
finance system, and said they were horrified at the public
perception that big donors received special favors in Washington.
In a report released in March, the committee wrote, ``The suspicion
of corruption deepens public cynicism and diminishes public
confidence in government. More important, these activities raise
the likelihood of actual corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   In a response to McConell sent last week, leaders of the
committee wrote, ``We know that a majority of the House and the
Senate supports campaign finance reform. That sentiment is also
shared by a growing number of business community leaders. We hope
that you will reconsider your opposition and enable the issue to be
discussed and voted on this fall in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Warren Buffett, the acclaimed value investor and chief
executive of Berkshire Hathaway, and Jerome Kohlberg, a founder of
the leveraged buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co., have tried
on their own to persuade chief executives of businesses to embrace
campaign finance reform measures. But many, though sympathetic,
refused to speak out because they did not want to rankle the
legislators on whom they depend.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the executives on the committee are speaking for
themselves, and not necessarily on behalf of their companies. But
most of their corporations still continue to give large sums to
political parties and candidates. The American subsidiary of
Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, Kangas' corporation, gave $185,300 to the
Republican Party and $41,725 to the Democratic Party in 1998,
according to Federal Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   Kangas said he disagreed with McConnell's position that campaign
contributions were protected by the First Amendment. ``I was a
little disappointed that he would suggest that freedom of speech
does not apply to us, but it applies to the people who agree with
him,'' Kangas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
