A6315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ATLANTA-CRASH01-COX     08-31 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-CRASH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cause of fatal truck crash may never surface, police say
 &HT;    By R. Robin McDonald
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two Alabama truckers hauling a load from Birmingham,
Ala., to Charlotte, N.C., died before dawn Tuesday, consumed in an
explosion that engulfed their eighteen-wheeler on eastbound
Interstate 285.
</P>
<P>
   The accident, at what DeKalb County police say is one of the
busiest intersections in the Southeast, closed down I-285 in both
directions. And for five hours spanning the morning rush,
interstate commuters in both directions were forced to merge into
one or two lanes of traffic as they made their way around the
burned-out wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, road crews with the state Department of
Transportation will spend the next three days repairing damage to
the underside of the Ashford-Dunwoody Road bridge, police said.
Crews will repair the bridge one lane at a time in an effort to
ease congestion on the already crowded highway.
</P>
<P>
   James Neal Tinker, 39, of Ashville, Ala., and George Kenneth
Thomason of Lincoln, Ga., died in what one witness described as a
terrible fireball that erupted after their semi-tractor trailer hit
the interstate's median wall, careened across the highway, crashed
into a bridge abutment and leaped a second wall into oncoming lanes
of traffic, DeKalb police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe that the truck's diesel fuel tank ruptured,
spilling fuel across the highway and precipitating the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb police found the body of one man in the driver's seat.
The second man was in the truck's sleeping compartment. Tuesday
afternoon, the county's medical examiners were waiting for dental
records that would confirm who of the two was driving the truck
when it crashed about 3:20 a.m., said DeKalb Sgt. Andy Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said that police may never know for certain what first
caused the truck to swerve into the right-hand emergency lane and
hit the median wall.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``It's typical of an accident where someone falls
asleep, drifts to the side, hits the wall, wakes up, and
overreacts.''
</P>
<P>
   After striking the right-hand wall, the truck veered across the
interstate into the far left lane and struck an abutment shoring up
the Ashford-Dunwoody Road bridge, Anderson said. Leaking diesel
fuel, the rig's cab leaped the median wall separating the eastbound
from the westbound lanes and burst into flames. ``The trailer was
still driving it,'' Anderson said. ``It probably drove it (the cab)
up and over the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Because both of the truck's occupants are dead, ``We'll never
know what really happened,'' the traffic investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the truckers were team drivers. The practice _
during which one trucker sleeps while the other drives _ allows
truckers to keep their rigs on the road longer because they can
meet federal requirements that limit a trucker's driving hours
without rest.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were hauling a mixed load of seating, metal
fittings, and nuts and bolts, Anderson said. There were no
hazardous materials found in the truck that might have contributed
to the fire, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing the wreckage from the highway and removing the bodies
was delayed by interstate commuters who jammed into the highway's
single emergency lane in a futile effort to circumvent the
accident, Anderson said. Consequently, state DOT HERO trucks, which
carry traffic cones and other equipment to quickly clear a highway
and re-route traffic around an accident, were themselves caught in
the jam. So was the hearse that transported the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a broom in my hand, sweeping stuff out of the road
because the HERO units couldn't get up there,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
