<HEADER>
A6324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-31 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: FARMERS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and environmentalists demonstrated in several cities to
call for the release of Jose Bove, an activist who was imprisoned
after he led the ransacking of a McDonald's restaurant in the town
of Millau. His group as well as farmers elsewhere in the country
have picked various hamburger outlets as targets in a low-level
trade war between the United States and the European Union.
Washington has imposed sanctions against a range of European
products, including some French food items, in response to a
European Union ban on imports of American meat from hormone-fed
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: BOSNIAN SERB DENIES CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   The chief of staff of the Bosnian Serb army pleaded not guilty
to charges of persecuting civilians during the Bosnian war in 1992.
Gen. Momir Talic, the highest-ranking Bosnian Serb official
detained so far, made his first court appearance at the U.N. war
crimes tribunal in The Hague. The tribunal had secretly indicted
Talic for his responsibility in the campaign in which tens of
thousands of Muslims and Croats were imprisoned, mistreated or
expelled from their land and homes in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIDDLE EAST  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PEACE TALKS CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators worked into the night trying
to hammer out a deal to revive a frozen peace initiative. Both
sides remained optimistic that an agreement could be reached before
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrives in Egypt on Thursday.
Despite the positive tone of negotiations, differences remained.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: COMPENSATION FOR AUSTRALIANS
</P>
<P>
   The government agreed to help compensate Australian Jewish
athletes injured in the collapse of a makeshift bridge at the start
of the Maccabiah Games near Tel Aviv in 1997. Four athletes died
and dozens were injured after they fell into the polluted waters of
the Yarkon River as they marched into a stadium for the opening
ceremony of the Maccabiah.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: POLITICAL KILLINGS?
</P>
<P>
   Police are investigating whether the murders of a young Orthodox
Jewish couple, who were found stabbed to death in a nature reserve,
were politically motivated. Newspapers reported that the woman had
been raped, which is atypical of an organized terrorist act by
Islamic fundamentalists. But the police, who are releasing no
details and have banned the publication of information about the
case, apparently believe that the murders were committed by an
Arab. It is not known whether that is the only factor that has led
them to investigate the deaths as political.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATIN AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: OPPOSITION ASKS FOR HELP
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties who are in talks to form a coalition for
Mexico's July 2000 general elections agreed to invite about a dozen
historians, political scientists, authors and other distinguished
citizens of ``recognized moral stature'' to help them break an
impasse in their negotiations. The eight parties have written a
common electoral platform for the proposed coalition, but have
failed to agree on how to select a joint presidential candidate.
The opposition leaders declined to immediately identify the
committee members.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: STRIKE CALLED
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of labor unions and social movements began what they
called an indefinite nationwide strike to protest President Andres
Pastrana's economic austerity program. The action is supported by
left-wing guerrilla groups, one of which said it had seized an
electrical power plant as a gesture of solidarity. In a speech,
Pastrana called for patience, and announced measures to assure that
public transportation and other services would continue to
function, but many schools and some businesses around the country
closed anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: REFUGEES FLOCK TO KABUL
</P>
<P>
   Refugees fleeing fighting between the ruling Taliban and the
remnants of the government they ousted three years ago have been
arriving daily in Kabul, Afghanistan's capital, where at least
8,000 are crowded into the former Soviet Embassy grounds. Taliban
officials, facing more than 40,000 displaced people on their
territory, say they cannot provide for the basic needs of the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: PLEA TO U.N. ON KASHMIR
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif called on the United Nations to hold
a referendum in Kashmir similar to the one just completed in East
Timor to allow Kashmiris living on territory in dispute between
India and Pakistan to decide their future. India, which regards the
Kashmir Valley as its territory, has not allowed United Nations
resolutions from the late 1940s demanding a plebiscite to be
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA: PREMIER TO MEET ANNAN
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Hun Sen, whose government rejected U.N. plans for
a war crimes tribunal for the Khmer Rouge, will meet
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in New York in September, said Ralph
Zacklin, an assistant secretary-general for legal affairs, in Phnom
Penh. Zacklin was unable to win agreement for a proposed tribunal
with international and Cambodian judges chosen by the United
Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
