<HEADER>
A6327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-EVANDER-LENNOX01-     08-31 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-LENNOX01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield-Lewis II a done deal
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield has been training since early July
hoping to hear he would get a chance to redeem himself _ and unify
the heavyweight championship _ against Lennox Lewis this fall.
</P>
<P>
   That word came Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and Lewis teamed with promoter Don King to announce
that nagging details had been resolved and the Nov. 13 bout at the
Thomas and Mack Center in Las Vegas is on.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy surrounding their draw last March finally can be
resolved in the TVKO pay-per-view bout _ maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the fight was made again,'' Lewis said. ``It came
down to the last minute. Many people stopped me on the street and
said I won the (first) fight. And I'm sure many people stopped
Evander and told him he lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield never conceded as much. He did, however, admit Tuesday
to ``mistakes,'' which included execution of his fight plan and the
uncharacteristic prediction of a third-round knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned from the first fight; now I have to apply it,''
Holyfield said. ``All you can do is your best. My best wasn't good
enough the last time. But I've watched the tape, and I know what to
do.... No, no predictions this time. I just know I'm going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Each fighter will earn $15 million for the rematch, which is $5
million less than before for Holyfield. That pay cut, Holyfield
says, signifies his desire to prove himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only one to take a pay cut,'' he said. ``I wanted
the fight. I'm the type of person who always overcomes his
mistakes. I made some mistakes, and I paid that price. One who can
admit his mistakes can overcome them.''
</P>
<P>
   The March 13 draw triggered inquiries and allegations by boxing
officials and government regulators. Most observers had Lewis
(34-1-1) the winner.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to fulfill his third-round KO prediction,
Holyfield (36-3-1) was inactive and took a pummeling from Lewis.
However, Lewis failed to take out the seemingly vulnerable
champion, and that failure drew criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have better skills to show,'' Lewis said. ``Now that I've
been in there with him, I know what to expect. Things will get
under way quicker. You'll see me a lot more aggressive. I don't
think he'll have the answer for Lenox Lewis again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
