<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV19-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., SEP. 19, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My house has old fashioned double-hung windows with wood
sash. These windows have been painted many times over the years and
two or three of them are now very hard to open, especially the
lower sash. I scraped off some layers of old paint and used a putty
knife to cut through the caked paint around the edges of the sash,
but this only helped a little. The lower sash in each window is
still very hard to move. What else can I do to free up stubborn
sash?
</P>
<P>
   A: Raise the sash all the way up and use a scraper or piece of
sandpaper to clean off caked-on paint from the edge of the stop
molding where it presses against the inside of the sash. Then use a
hammer and block of wood, as shown in the drawing, to slam the
block against the edge of the stop molding. This should move it
just slightly away fromthe sash to provide additional clearance
for the sash inside the window channel. If this helps, but you
still need more clearance, repeat the process. Then do the same on
the other side of the window frame.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many years ago we put up wood panels over the plaster walls
of our family room. Now we would like to remove the wood panels and
go back to painted walls. Should we put up drywall on top of the
wood paneling, or is it advisable to remove the wood panels first?
</P>
<P>
   A: My suggestion would be to remove the wood panels and then
check the condition of the plaster walls underneath. If the plaster
is in reasonably good condition you may be able to simply patch the
plaster and paint directly over it. However, if (as seems likely)
the old plaster is badly cracked and so full of holes that patching
and smoothing is almost impossible, then you would probably be
better off installing the drywall directly over the old plaster.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My house has no basement and is built on a concrete slab. The
floors get very cold in the winter so I'm thinking about some type
of insulation. Is there any way to insulate such a concrete slab?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of the heat lost through a concrete slab floor occurs
through its edges, so the most effective way to insulate an
existing slab is to insulate those edges. This is usually done by
installing a type of rigid insulation that is sold in home centers
and building materials dealers. It can be either a thick
asphalt-like material, or a type of rigid foam insulation board and
is installed by digging a narrow trench around the perimeter of the
slab. Then place the insulating boards in the ground and press them
against the edge of the concrete before replacing the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We unwisely used ice melting chemicals for several years on
our newly installed concrete driveway. The concrete now has a
number of small holes in the surface. How can we repair them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your best bet would be to use one of the vinyl or acrylic
patching cements that are sold in hardware stores and home centers.
Unfortunately, however, chances are that each patch will be visible
when it dries because it will probably cure to a slightly different
color than the old concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``FREEING UP A STUCK WINDOW'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Hammering with a block of wood against the stop molding
will widen window channel slightly to make sash slide more easily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
