<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE, SINDEN TALK ABOUT CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Byron Dafoe, the Bruins' free agent goalie, has
maintained that if he doesn't have a contract by the end of the
week, he will board a plane for his offseason residence in Southern
California and train there until he receives a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Well, put those airline reservations on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe Tuesday sat down with Bruins president/general manager
Harry Sinden for about 30 minutes in an effort to break the
stalemate, and if progress is made in the next 24 hours, it's
possible the entire situation could change.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said the meeting was initiated by coach Pat Burns, who
also got involved last year when negotiations broke down with
center Jason Allison. Dafoe said Burns wasn't in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully something will come in the next couple of days,''
said Dafoe. ``There's a little bit of communication going on, so
that's a good sign. It was just a quick meeting to kind of hear
each other out. We explained both sides. Obviously we didn't talk
numbers because I don't want to do that without (agent Ron Salcer)
but Harry explained why they are there and I explained why I am
here. We both didn't see why the other was there but I wasn't going
to get into statistics. I was going to let Ronnie do that. That's
kind of where we left it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, with star players such as Cam Neely, a meeting with
Sinden often has led to a resolution. It hasn't always been
immediate but it usually has started the ball rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for us to see where we're both coming
from,'' Dafoe said. ``It's getting to crunch time now in terms of
do I stay or do I go. Who knows? Maybe something will come of all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden was hoping for the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to do that because if you don't do it, we go further
and further with our comments and all of sudden, we actually piss
each other off,'' said Sinden. ``What happens is one side or the
other, or sometimes both, dig a hole that they want out of but
can't find a way out. At least, we can talk now. If we can't
resolve it, we can't resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden believes there is sincerity on both sides, and they are
bargaining in good faith. The next step is Salcer sending Sinden
some specifics to back up their contract demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait to see what they are,'' Sinden said. ``We
probably think we can tear holes in everything he says. We didn't
want to be in a position with this player where we didn't put our
best foot forward. There's no question, if someone like his agent
or Byron can show us we haven't, we're going to make sure we
correct it. If they can't, we're not going to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said part of the problem in an extended stalemate is that
the communication breaks down and the media get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the sides are not talking, then all they're doing is
reading press clippings,'' Dafoe said. ``That can always get thrown
out of whack or misconstrued. At least when you're face to face,
you're hearing it right from his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The news isn't so encouraging on Hal Gill, who is also a
restricted free agent. Sinden spoke with Gill's attorney, Mark
Witkin, Tuesday morning, but it's unlikely that Gill will be signed
before this weekend's start of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's status quo,'' said Witkin. ``I talked with Harry for a
short time and with Mike (O'Connell) last week. There were no real
offers or anything. A nice, neutral description would be that Harry
told me what was on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the stumbling block is that Gill wants a big bump-up
this year even though he didn't have arbitration rights. In order
to use the collective bargaining agreement effectively, Sinden said
it makes more sense for Gill to get a small raise in a one-year
deal and next summer he can take the club to arbitration, where
he's almost sure to get a big raise. Sinden said Gill would be
taken care of if he signs a two-year contract, which would
eliminate the need for arbitration altogether next year.
</P>
<P>
   Witkin said the Bruins have put forth offers of one, two, and
three years. So far, they don't approach what he's looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've respectfully declined,'' said Witkin. ``I haven't really
heard from them with offers and I would think they're going to wait
a while and hopefully the situation will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he signed his first contract, he said you prove you can
play in the league. They cited where he was drafted and his career
in college was good but not spectacular to their way of thinking
and there were players with much greater profile. They said, `Look,
you show you can play in the league, you have to sign a two-year
deal, and you will be treated appropriately,' and he fulfilled his
part of the bargain. You can argue the CBA different ways but they
promised to treat him fairly and I think they should.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said Witkin told him Gill was going to go live with the
bears in Maine and Sinden resented that because there are only
black bears in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said dealing with the black bears was not as bad as dealing
with me,'' he said. ``I resented that because had there been
grizzly bears in Maine, I would've accepted that. But little black
bears, I've got to be a lot tougher than them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the club spoke to Neil Abbott, attorney for free
agent left wing P.J. Axelsson, but rejected Abbott's latest
proposal. He said the sides are far apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
