<HEADER>
A6342 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-CHURC     08-31 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-CHURCH-$ADV05-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUEENS FACTORY IS BORN AGAIN, AS A CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 5) 
(jt) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The new New York Presbyterian Church, which
officially opens on Sept. 18, is as striking a piece of
architecture as those we once had to go to Los Angeles to see.
Situated in Queens, N.Y., the church can claim a place on the small
list of projects that are helping to lift New York architecture out
of its long creative slump.
</P>
<P>
   The building was designed by Doug Garofalo, Greg Lynn and
Michael McInturf, three whizz kids of the computer generation who
live and work in three different cities _ Los Angeles, Chicago and
Columbus, Ohio _ and who practice together in an office somewhere
in cyberspace. For this trio, design is a paperless enterprise,
aided by software originally developed for automobile styling and
movie animation, and conducted with the playfulness of a video
game. These people are wired.
</P>
<P>
   Computers have long been standard equipment in architectural
offices, but few architects have tried to exploit the potential of
software as an expressive medium. Wes Jones, the Los Angeles-based
architect, has used the term blobmeisters to describe architects
who are pursuing this potential today. Conventional (so-called
orthogonal) buildings are typically rendered by plans and
elevations, two kinds of two-dimensional drawing. Blobs, on the
other hand, are rendered as three-dimensional computer models, like
those we see for cars, bodies or molecular structures. By
collapsing plan and elevation into a single three-dimensional form,
the computer model encourages architects to break out of
orthogonal, right-angled space. Instead, they can manipulate all
dimensions at once. Space becomes as plastic as a hunk of Silly
Putty. It can be pinched, rotated, kneaded, stretched, cut into
sections, shattered or left to ooze. The computer model displays
the impact of each manipulation on the whole.
</P>
<P>
   Blobmeisters use software the way modernists used structure: as
a springboard for form. By way of explanation, Lynn says that a
movie like ``Antz'' came about not because a director wanted to
make a movie about insects, but because a technician discovered
that a particular computer program was effective at depicting
animated bugs. At the Presbyterian Church, the architects used a
program called Alias, developed for movie animation and industrial
design. They have combined new blob elements with the box form of
an older, existing structure to produce a hybrid design, or
para-building _ an addition that radically transforms what came
before.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1970, the Presbyterian Church of New York has a
rapidly growing congregation whose members are mostly of Korean
descent. In addition to the religious services held in the
sanctuary, the new building's largest space, the church functions
as a social and educational center for the Korean community. The
new building, which cost $10 million, contains 80 classrooms, a
banquet hall-cafeteria with seating for 1,000, a wedding chapel,
day care center, library and medical clinic. As an expression of
faith, parishioners fasted one day each week while their church was
in construction.
</P>
<P>
   The church's physical context is almost lyrically gritty, flat
and gray, an area dominated by used-car lots, warehouses, factories
and chain super stores. Grand Opening, pennants fluttering, Nobody
Beats Our Prices: a Northern Boulevard version of Ed Ruscha. Across
the street from the church, Long Island Rail Road trains zip by on
an overpass. Beyond, the leafy streets of Sunnyside, Queens,
emphasize the nearby urban grit. Into this sliced-up,
wrong-side-of-the-tracks setting, Garofalo, Lynn and McInturf have
introduced chop-shop architecture: an assemblage of old and new
industrial parts.
</P>
<P>
   The original structure was built in 1932 for the Knickerbocker
Laundry Factory, a commercial firm that held the franchise for
cleaning Yankee uniforms. A local landmark, the precast concrete
Art Deco edifice later housed a perfume factory. The church retains
the laundry's street facade, though its curving Deco surface, once
white, has been painted black. The architects call it the Shroud.
</P>
<P>
   In the original building, a two-story industrial shed lay behind
the Deco facade. For the remodeling, the architects have added a
new structural framework that doubles the height of the shed. They
have sheared away three of the existing walls _ chop, chop _ and
replaced them with new ones: two finished with a purple-gray
stucco, the third made of translucent fiberglass panels inset with
clear glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   Blobmeister forms often resemble horror movie monsters. Earlier
this year, Lynn presented an installation in Vienna called ``The
Tingler,'' after the old William Castle movie about a
centipede-like parasite. For the church, he and his partners have
invented a form they call Nestor, so named because it is composed
of trapezoidal shapes that appear to nest inside one another, like
a stack of baskets laid on its side. Nestor is not an object, but a
form, a spatial void that is used to define different areas on the
top two floors of the church. Imagine it as the hollow cavity of a
Jurassic fossil.
</P>
<P>
   Nestor's form is reptilian, with a serrated surface that recalls
a lizard's hide. The form is only partly visible from outside, in a
series of zinc-clad, folded canopies that cascade down the northern
facade of the building, sheltering an exterior fire stair of poured
concrete. Admirers of '50s sculpture may see a resemblance of these
canopies to the work of Seymour Lipton. Inside the shed, Nestor
contains the church's main space, the sanctuary, with seating for
more than 2,500 parishioners. The capacity is roughly that of St.
Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn and McInturf both worked in the New York office of Peter
Eisenman and make no effort to cover their tracks. We have seen
lots of work from the generation after Frank Gehry, but it's a
novelty to see second-generation Eisenman, particularly in New
York, where the mentor himself has built only a humble fire
station, and that some years back. There are people who break out
in hives whenever Eisenman's name comes up, but the Presbyterian
Church may persuade them to reconsider. The younger architects give
us Eisenmanesque forms without the Hate me! Hate me! provocation.
That loss is a gain all around.
</P>
<P>
   For the convention center in Columbus, Ohio, Eisenman designed
``snakes,'' curving shapes that turned the roof into a so-called
fifth facade. Lodged within the Presbyterian Church are what the
architects call tubes: three vertical corridors that contain
entrances, hallways, stairs and elevators and provide circulation
throughout the building.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
