u a BC-MIT-STUDENT-DIES-BOS &LR;      08-31 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-STUDENT-DIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT STUDENT FOUND DEAD USED NITROUS OXIDE, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif; with sidebar, MIT-Asphyxiate)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER AND JOANNA MASSEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The hopeful dawn of a new school year was
shattered Tuesday at MIT, where students struggled with the
school's second substance-abuse death in two years.
</P>
<P>
   A 22-year-old MIT student was found dead in his East Campus dorm
room just after midnight after he used a plastic bag to inhale
nitrous oxide, campus police said.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy showed that Richard A. Guy of Mission Viejo, Calif.,
died of asphyxiation. The medical examiner had not determined
whether his death was an accident or suicide, howevere.
</P>
<P>
   Guy was a third-year physics student who apparently lived alone
in his fifth-floor room at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technololgy.
</P>
<P>
   As students arrived on campus Tuesday, they struggled to make
sense of another autumn death tied to the abuse of substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``MIT prides itself on letting people be individuals with free
reign over their own lives, but some people take advantage of
that,'' said Eric Ferreira, a senior from California. ``They have
done an excellent job on drug education and the majority of people
here listen to what they say.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira added: ``MIT students are just getting back and this is
a shock. It's just such a bad way to start off the year.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997 freshman Scott S. Krueger, 18, died after an
alcohol overdose at a fraternity hazing party. His death prompted
MIT, which had long relied on fraternities to deal with a shortage
of dormitory space, to announce plans to build a new dorm and
require freshmen to live on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we came to school, they made a big deal over Krueger's
death,'' said an 18-year-old freshman from New Jersey, who declined
to be named. ``I think MIT was trying very hard to make sure
something like that never happened here again.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT spokesman Kenneth Campbell said that because nitrous oxide _
popularly known as laughing gas _ is used on campus for work in
science and medicine, it is not illegal to possess it. But it is,
he said, unlawful to inhale it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campus police reported that the student apparently had been
using a plastic bag to inhale nitrous oxide (laughing gas),'' MIT
said in a statement. ``This can result in asphyxiation.''
</P>
<P>
   State Police attached to the Middlesex County district
attorney's office investigated Guy's death, but swiftly determined
that it was not a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy results showed that Guy died of ``asphyxiation due to an
obstructed airway due to nitrous oxide intoxication,'' said Anson
Kaye, a spokesman for Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley.
</P>
<P>
   In Mission Viejo, a southern California city located roughly
between Los Angeles and San Diego, neighbors of Guy's family were
shocked and saddened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sad even talking about it,'' said Debra Violette, who
said she learned of the MIT death when a television news crew
knocked on her door Tuesday. ``They're a very nice family. They
travel quite a bit. It's such a terrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although classes at MIT don't start until next week, many
students already have returned to campus. On the grassy quandrangle
outside Guy's dormitory off Ames Street Tuesday, tearful friends
and classmates consoled each other, declining to speak with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Randolph, the senior associate dean of students and
undergraduate education, said that Guy's parents were notified late
Tuesday morning about ``the tragic death of their son.''
</P>
<P>
   Pure nitrous oxide dissolves in the bloodstream. It pushes
oxygen out from the blood into the lungs and deprives the brain and
other organs of oxygen. Dentists often use it as an anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   It is commonly abused by teenagers, who buy small pressurized
containers of the gas, called ``whippets'' because they are used to
power whipped cream containers sold by restaurant supply companies
and gourmet food stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's becoming a lot more popular on campus,'' said one
21-year-old junior Tuesday. ``But the school works really hard to
combat any sort of substance abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. H. Westley Clark, director of the Center for Substance Abuse
Treatment at the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services
Administration in Washington, said the percentage of 18- to
25-year-olds who have used nitrous oxide rose from 6.6 percent in
1997 to 7.9 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use a plastic bag around your head or strap a mask to
your face and you pass out, your body will want oxygen and it won't
be able to get it,'' Clark said. ``And, therefore, you die.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT's move to mandate that freshmen live in dormitories sparked
a student protest. The Undergraduate Association said a campus poll
last fall showed 90 percent of students opposed the move.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger, a fraternity pledge, died after an initiation rite
called ``Animal House Night.'' He and others drank beer and spiced
rum while singing fraternity songs. Krueger passed out, was left in
his basement apartment, and choked on vomit. His blood alcohol
level was .401 _ five times the legal limit used to measure
intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, MIT withdrew the diploma of the fraternity member
accused of leading the forced drinking binge. The school said the
diploma will be reissued in five years. The former fraternity
member, 23-year-old Charles Yoo, has said he will sue to get his
diploma back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6348 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-CHURC     08-31 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-CHURCH-2NDTAKE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sun., Sept. 5)  
 NEW YORK: the building.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shroud, shed, Nestor, tubes: these are the basic components of
the church's organizing system, and it is helpful to keep them in
mind, because it's not immediately apparent that a system is in
operation. The tubes, for example, overlap as they weave through
the structure. The overlapping areas are sometimes, but not always,
articulated by ceiling soffits and by the color of the linoleum
flooring. The building's undulating roof corresponds to Nestor's
bulging contour just below. The canopies are not, as one might
think, arbitrarily sculpted shapes, but Nestor's serrated western
edge.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary is the most impressive interior to be built in New
York in many years. The room's ceiling (Nestor's inner hide) serves
an acoustical function but is mainly an experiment in folded
planes, a device long associated with Eisenman. The space is
asymmetrical, with angled banks of seating that violate the
traditional arrangement around a central axis. The effect is not
weird or Caligariesque. Rather, the asymmetry makes the space more
fluid, its vast size less overwhelming. Chop-chop: a glass wall
slices through the sanctuary along its northern edge, allowing
natural light into the space and dissolving any sense of
confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Other fine moments: a magnificent processional staircase that
leads from the main entrance lobby to the sanctuary two floors
above; the most dramatic feature within the tubes, the stair curves
and narrows slightly as it rises, the deviations accented by strips
of neon lighting overhead. The black asphalt parking lot,
surrounded by white concrete walls, that sets the church off like
an industrial velvet matte. The fixtures and furnishings brought in
by the church itself _ lots of wood, vases with scrolls on them _
that help draw the place into the vernacular. The view of the
church from Northern Boulevard: a free-falling image, pure formal
play, the zinc-covered canopies reverberate across the northern
facade like tolling bells.
</P>
<P>
   Shortcomings in blob architecture might be called glitches,
blips or crashes. The Presbyterian Church has a few. Stairs. In the
balcony aisle, and an exterior stair near the parking lot, the
treads are too long. You have to hop-skip, leading first left foot,
then right. This rhythm is boring and distracts from the irregular
geometries of the space. Such discomforts can be found in many
conventional buildings, but it's screwy when formalist architecture
does not work with the geometry of human form. The funereal
palette: purple gray; black; mauve. The architects say that their
adaptive reuse replaces the laundering of dirty uniforms with the
cleansing of tarnished souls. A lovely conceit. Why the mourning
dress? One senses the strain of young architects trying to look
sober beyond their years.
</P>
<P>
   Wasted space. The upper landing of the outdoor fire stair,
sheltered beneath the topmost canopy, is a wonderful space, perhaps
the best in the building, with views of the Manhattan skyline and
the sanctuary inside. A perfect place for a garden of
contemplation. Fire codes permitting, the entire staircase, and the
spaces beneath it, would benefit from landscaping. Software-driven
design should maximize what chat rooms cannot provide: habitable
public space for integrated bodies, minds and souls; physical
proximity; tactility; the here as well as the now.
</P>
<P>
   The glitches do not, however, diminish the stature of this work,
as both a fulfillment of historical forces and as a preview of
things to come. Half a century ago, the British historian John
Summerson said that architects should ``learn to study not merely
minimum requirements, but maximum possibilities; to learn not only
how to economize space but how to be extravagant with it; to study
the overtones of architecture and the geometrical discipline of
space as space; to learn not only to use space but to play with
space.''
</P>
<P>
   The words come from an address Summerson delivered to the
Architectural Association in London in 1947. He was responding to
the impact on architecture of modern communications technology.
Radio, television and telephone, Summerson thought, had relieved
architects of the need to create imposing public symbols of social
cohesion. This had liberated them to focus on space, an element
media could not supplant.
</P>
<P>
   Half a century later, however, communications technology has
gone far toward capturing the spatial dimension. The culture now
lives more imaginatively in simulated spaces _ blue screen
backgrounds, VR, SimCity _ than in those created by architectural
means. Obviously, Garofalo, Lynn and McInturf are not opposed to
this development. In fact, their cyberspatial mode of working may
be more revolutionary than their design. They have dealt with
displacement by incorporating new media into their method. The
church is a natural extension of the process the architects used to
design it. That process caused three architects to reconfigure the
spatial relationships between them. The church amplifies those
relationships in architectural terms.
</P>
<P>
   It would be odd if the computer did not set off a spatial
revision comparable to that sparked by Brunelleschi's development
of linear perspective in 15th-century Florence. Indeed, blob
architecture undermines the enduring authority of perspectival
space. While blob architecture has its Baroque aspects, its twists
on axis, symmetry and procession violate classical norms. In
Queens, the classically symmetrical Deco facade accentuates the
anti-classicism of the addition.
</P>
<P>
   It was fortuitous that this project was commissioned by a
church. Faith is supra-rational, like mountain climbing. Believers
throw a line up into the unknown and we haul ourselves skyward, and
it's only when we have done this quite a bit that we know that
faith works: we can look back and see how high we have climbed.
Architecture works the same way. Architects may have no idea what's
up there, but they throw the line anyway, and when this happens
often enough, a history of architecture is revealed. The New York
Presbyterian Church signifies a new stage of ascent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
