A6361 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:YOUNG-ARTISTS-CL     08-31 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:YOUNG-ARTISTS-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLMARK DESIGNER KIDS ALICIA AND DAVID TEMPLIN 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By ALYSON WARD 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a national art contest with 70,000 entries and just a dozen
winners, what are the chances that a brother and sister from
Arlington, Texas, would succeed?
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Templin, 14, and her brother, David, 12, both drew a
winning birthday-card design in the contest for kids sponsored by
Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 winning entries are part of the company's summer lineup
of greeting cards. The pair entered four card designs each.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one they chose was actually my favorite one, so it was
kind of weird that they chose it,'' Alicia said. Her winning
drawing is of a candle bowing from a cake to its candle friends.
</P>
<P>
   David's design is a floppy-eared dog sitting on top of a
birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   The Templins, who go to Grace Preparatory Academy in Arlington,
got to tour the Hallmark Cards headquarters in Kansas City, Mo., as
part of their prize. Last weekend, they traveled to Easton, Pa., to
see the Crayola crayon and marker factory.
</P>
<P>
   The kids' talent for art likely came from their parents. Their
father, Gary Templin, is a graphic design artist, and their mother,
Crystal Templin, is a computer artist. They run an art school
called Art Smart in their home.
</P>
<P>
   David and Alicia already help out with teaching the classes, and
they both picture art in their distant futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to do clay animation,'' David said. ``So I'm not sure,
but I may want to do that when I grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia said: ``I definitely want to do something in art. I might
even want to be an author and illustrator for children's books.''
</P>
<P>
   Check out the Templins' artwork on their Web sites: Alicia's is
at www.polo.8m.com; David's is at www.monsters.8m.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
