<HEADLINE>
DID YOU KNOW ... VENTURA'S BACK IN THE RING! 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 c. 1999 Compiled from reports by The Associated Press and Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura returned to his roots recently,
exchanging a business suit for referee gear to preside over the
World Wrestling Federation's SummerSlam.
</P>
<P>
   His behavior sparked a debate over whether his actions are
appropriate for an elected official and high-profile role model.
</P>
<P>
   Some said Ventura, a former pro wrestler who retired from the
ring in 1986, was abusing and degrading the office of governor.
</P>
<P>
   Others said he was sending the wrong message by appearing at a
WWF spectacle complete with vulgar chants, guitar-shattering
violence and scantily clad women making suggestive gestures.
</P>
<P>
   During much of the three-person title match _ involving Stone
Cold Steve Austin, Triple H and Mankind _ Ventura barked orders,
but didn't join the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in my state now,'' Ventura shouted at Triple H before
the match started. ``I am law and order here.''
</P>
<P>
   The event, attended by 19,404 rowdy onlookers, was carried on
pay-per-view TV. Ventura has said he will donate to charity the
$100,000 fee he was given to referee.
</P>
<P>
   (Source: The Associated Press.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
