A6366 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:MUSIC-MESSENGER-     08-31 0194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:MUSIC-MESSENGER-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 
 MUSIC CD REVIEW: EDWIN McCAIN'S ``MESSENGER''  World rights. 
 By JANE AUSTIN, Student Reporter 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``MESSENGER''
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Edwin McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Category: soft rock.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody forgot to tell Edwin McCain that mellow doesn't have to
equal monotonous. One song sounds like another ... and another. The
lyrics are repetitious and the mostly midtempo music doesn't really
stand out. Even when he's trying to rock, it sounds tired. This guy
can barely trudge from one tune to another, so how can he expect
listeners to hold on for the whole CD?
</P>
<P>
   McCain's husky voice is his best asset. Maybe next time he
should count on someone else's songwriting abilities.
</P>
<P>
   This album feels like it's coming to a climax, but it never gets
there. It's limp. As for his hit ``I'll Be,'' just buy the single.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1 -10 rating: 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
