<HEADLINE>
SUN AIMS AT MICROSOFT WITH FREE SOFTWARE VIA INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why pay hundreds of dollars for word-processing software when
you can get it for free?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question Sun Microsystems Inc. posed Tuesday to
millions of consumers accustomed to forking over hundreds of
dollars apiece for word processing, spreadsheet and other software
sold by, among others, Sun's archrival, Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In what is widely perceived to be its first substantial assault
on Microsoft, Sun said that it has acquired Star Division Corp. and
is distributing Star's word processing, database, spreadsheet,
graphics and presentation programs free over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft derives about 40 percent of its nearly $20 billion in
annual revenues from selling a similar suite of programs, called
Microsoft Office, for about $500 to $800 each, depending on the
version. About 100 million people worldwide currently use Microsoft
Office, making it the number one office software.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, with $11.7 billion in sales for the 12 months ended last
June 30, is better known for its network-focused hardware and
software, including the Java programming language that has become
integral to Internet operations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft countered by noting that Sun's latest offering is not
new, nor is it entirely free to users.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's free software on the market today. That's not new,''
said Phyllis McNeice, a Microsoft spokeswoman. ``Offering it for
free doesn't mean that everyone will want it. There will be other
costs associated with owning that software, like maintenance and
support.''
</P>
<P>
   While consumers can download the Star Office software from the
Internet at no cost, users may have to pay another firm to store
documents created by Star Office.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, based in Palo Alto, Calif., acquired Star Division, of
Fremont, Calif., on Aug. 5. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Sun downplayed its rivalry with Microsoft, saying the move is
not intended to unseat the Redmond, Wash., software giant. Instead,
Sun executives say, it's about Sun's long-held strategy to move the
center of technology universe away from the personal computer to
the Internet, where Sun's role in selling high-powered machines,
called servers, is much more prominent.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's strategy is not altruistic. By giving away software, the
company says it hopes to build sales of its servers to businesses
that store and manage data for clients, much as banks hold money
for depositers. Sun's plan would also create a stream of revenue
from customers wanting technical help in using the software, said
Marko Boerries, former CEO of Star and now a Sun vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will need and want our services,'' Boerries said. ``To
get that, you can buy subscriptions from us, and we continually
update and support you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun's stock gained 3 7/8 to close at 79 1/2 on the Nasdaq.
Microsoft stock, also on the Nasdaq, edged up 5/16 to 92 9/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
