u i BC-TIMOR-KILLINGS-BOS &LR;      08-31 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-KILLINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO-JAKARTA MILITIAS CONTINUE INTIMIDATION DESPITE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ Pro-Jakarta militias renewed in earnest their
anti-independence campaign of intimidation Tuesday, just one day
after East Timor's residents voted in relative peace to choose
between independence and autonomy within Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian police and military had earned praise on Monday
for reining in the paramilitary groups, whom they are widely
believed to support. But the militias were back out in force
Tuesday, setting up roadblocks, barring East Timorese from leaving
the territory and laying siege to 150 election officials and
observers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite months of violence and intimidation, nearly 99 percent
of East Timorese cast their ballots Monday in a vote that is widely
expected to favor independence.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from election day violence, meanwhile, was put at
three Tuesday. A Brazilian UN election officer in the town of
Atsabe, 20 miles southwest of Dili, said local members of his staff
were stabbed before his eyes as he carried the ballot box to his
car.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents cast doubt on the peaceful transition planned for
this island territory the size of Connecticut, from a province
annexed by Indonesia to either a semi-autonomous state or an
independent nation.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, this agrarian territory was a far-away, neglected
colony of Portugal at the edge of the Indonesian island chain,
until 1975 when the Portuguese withdrew and Indonesia invaded. In
the five years that followed, one-quarter of the population
perished in civil war, starvation and disease.
</P>
<P>
   The international community never recognized Indonesia's rule
over East Timor, and early this year, Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie agreed to let East Timorese determine their future. The
run-up to the ballot was plagued by massacres of independence
supporters and clashes between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Eurico Gutteres, an erstwhile independence activist who
was captured and reputedly tortured years ago before becoming a
pro-Indonesia militia commander, kept his pledge to block land, sea
and air borders so that East Timorese could not ``flee'' before
vote results are announced next week.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, black-shirted members of his Aitarak (Thorn)
militia were seen preventing locals from boarding ferries at Dili
harbor, setting up airport roadblocks and confiscating air tickets
from East Timorese.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the UN, which is administering the referendum and
transition in East Timor, were called to the airport to intervene,
but were apparently unable to stop the militias from blocking
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesian law guarantees freedom of movement. Whoever wants
to leave East Timor can do so,'' said an Indonesian government
spokesman, Dino Djalal, who promised to raise the issue immediately
with local police.
</P>
<P>
   But local police and the military seemed in no mood to rein in
the militias. Armed civilians were allowed to run roughshod over
the town of Gleno, 16 miles southwest of Dili, burning seven houses
and offices of independence supporters, blocking a UN helicopter
from picking up ballot boxes and surrounding election officials and
observers.
</P>
<P>
   UN mission spokesman David Wimhurst confirmed that 17 vehicles
and 150 election workers and observers _ 100 foreigners and 50
local staff _ were trapped in Gleno most of the day before the UN
police commissioner and senior Indonesian police were able to
negotiate the convoy's return to Dili. Militias fired shots, twice
preventing a UN helicopter from landing to fetch ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots will be counted at a central location in Dili starting
Wednesday to minimize fraud and protect secrecy of ballots cast in
each town and village.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 p.m. Tuesday, the detained convoy arrived at UN
headquarters in Dili, disgorging relieved election workers who at
one point had to huddle on the floor of their Gleno office to avoid
being shot through the window.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
