<HEADLINE>
YOUNG, GIFTED STUDENTS GET A GIFT _ SUMMER CLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.J., Mass., N.C., Ill., Britain)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOHN BUDRIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Stephanie Monteiro spent the month of August in a
college classroom with the likes of Einstein, Newton and Euclid as
she investigated the everyday applications of algebra. She is an A
student. Her math score on the College Board exams, 520, ranks her
above the national average for university-bound seniors.
</P>
<P>
   She is also just 13, and in September she will enter the
eighth-grade at the Ann Street School in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't ever felt a challenge like this before,'' Miss
Monteiro said on the way to her final presentation on fractals at
Washington College, near Chester River in Maryland. ``I see math
differently now _ it's come alive, almost like music,'' she said,
also marveling that ``grass was everywhere when we went outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Monteiro was plucked from the inner city by the Geraldine
R. Dodge Foundation to join some of the nation's highest achieving
junior high school scholars at Johns Hopkins University's Institute
for the Academic Advancement of Youth, where for up to six weeks
students with stratospheric College Board scores immerse themselves
in everything from calculus to Renaissance art at one of a dozen
campuses nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, which celebrates its 20th anniversary in October,
draws top students from 25 states and 36 countries. More than 8,000
students, 70 percent of them from public schools, take part in the
summer residential program, at which seventh- through 10th-graders
compress a full high school or college course into a three-week
session. Some students master two courses. This year, in response
to criticism of its low black and Hispanic participation _ about 2
percent _ the institute stepped up its search for academic talent
in underrepresented urban areas, particularly school districts in
Newark, N.J., and Brooklyn. Sixty-five New York-area participants,
including Stephanie Monteiro, were awarded full scholarships. The
average income of the families was under $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set our sights on Newark and Brooklyn because of the high
probability that this area would contain a large group of
underserved students,'' said Stephen L. Gessner, the institute's
director of programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Geraldine R. Dodge Foundation, based in Morristown, N.J.,
has contributed about $300,000 over the last two years to find and
foster gifted students, and the institute waives $500,000 in fees
and tuition annually to reach capable students with limited means.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are pioneers in more ways than one,'' said Ann
Wilson, gifted and talented coordinator for the Newark Public
School District.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 21 Newark students in the program in August, it
was their first experience away from home. Adjusting to dormitory
life and enduring the rigors of a year's curriculum crammed into
several weeks is all part of the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The institute scouts middle and junior high schools, primarily
in the Northeast and on the West Coast, for students who score
above the 97th percentile on standardized exams like the California
Achievement Tests or Iowa Tests. The students are then invited by
the institute to take the College Board exams.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh-graders scoring in the 500-and-up range in either the
verbal or math part of the College Boards _ numbers comparable to
the national average for high school seniors _ are eligible for the
program. Tenth-graders must score close to 700 in the math or
verbal tests, the average score of seniors bound for Ivy League
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   For chemistry and biology students, the laboratories of a
research complex like Johns Hopkins afford opportunities
unavailable even at the finest private schools. Neuroscience
students examine human brains. Budding biologists inject
genetically altered material from luminescent squid into bacteria
and chart the glowing results.
</P>
<P>
   Although weekdays are crammed with seven hours of class,
laboratory and study time, nights and weekends are full of
supervised bedlam _ a kind of ``Doogie Howser'' meets ``Camp
Run-Amok.'' By the end of the term, pizza boxes and soda cans
avalanche from dresser tops, and most students will have danced,
sung and giggled to exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   That bonding experience is often the most precious opportunity
these academically precocious students take away from the
institute.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Cooper, 11, says he often feels like an outcast back home
in Newark, N.J. ``I fit right in this summer,'' he said, ``but
that's not always been the case.''
</P>
<P>
   During his ``writing and imagination'' course at the program's
site at Mount Holyoke College in South Hadley, Mass., he sailed
through much of a college survey syllabus, examining Hemingway's
demons and the philosophical ideas of 19th-century
transcendentalists like Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that in a world of scarce resources, money is
better spent on less able students, presuming that gifted students
will excel no matter what. But educators note that addiction and
failure rates among highly intelligent students exceed the norm,
and may even be higher in urban areas where outlets for their
educational energies are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not just bright kids who get good grades,'' said
Julian C. Stanley, who founded the program in 1979 to expand on his
work with mathematically advanced children. ``They are different,
and they learn differently,'' Stanley said. ``The rapid pace at
which they learn and their capacity to absorb large amounts of
material quickly must be respected. Yet, I'm sad to say, it's
become politically incorrect to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Levin, 15, who attends the American School in London
and studied genetics and neuroscience this summer on the Johns
Hopkins campus, agrees. ``It's exhausting sometimes, whether the
attention is positive from teachers or negative from other kids,
dealing with it takes a lot of work that is just wasted,'' he said.
``When we are here for the summer we can finally converse in our
native language, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Shennen Bersani of Brockton, Mass., believes that the naysayers
misunderstand the special needs of gifted children. She said her
son was shy and withdrawn before he attended the institute two
years ago. ``He came back very social and confident, so much so he
was auditioning for plays and musicals,'' Ms. Bersani said.
</P>
<P>
   With costs for each of the two three-week sessions at about
$2,500, some parents also look to the institute and similar
programs at Duke University and Northwestern for a competitive edge
to the Ivy League. Some see these programs as pressure cookers into
which aggressive parents push their already stressed children.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley takes issue with that idea. ``You don't push a rolling
bowling ball down the hill, you just get out of its way,'' he said.
``These kids come because they want to, and they thrive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
