<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CORRUPTION LEADS TO QUESTIONS FOR WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, pressed by
investigations into money laundering and capital flight out of
Russia, is being forced anew to justify its policies of bold
economic assistance to Moscow over the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   This time the reassessment has raised questions of what the
administration knew about Russian corruption and what should have
been done differently, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Some figures inside the administration, as well as outside
critics, said that the indications of corruption were put aside to
ensure President Boris Yeltsin's support for American national
security interests, including the safekeeping of Russia's nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   These officials also assert that the administration played down
what it knew about corruption at the top levels of the Russian
government and chose instead to trumpet success stories as the
country limped toward a free-market system.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, when the administration asked Congress for $18
billion in new contributions for the International Monetary Fund at
a time when the fund was considering increasing its loan program to
Russia, the administration knew about the problem of corruption in
Russia but was reluctant to talk about it on Capitol Hill,
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who through his close
relationship with President Clinton is considered the architect of
much of the Russia policy, said in an interview: ``There are
legitimate questions about how much and by what mechanisms the
money left Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that one of the consequences of money's being
secreted out of the country was the impoverishment of many of the
Russian people.
</P>
<P>
   A former American diplomat who served in Moscow until recently
said that the administration failed to consistently criticize the
corruption for fear that doing so would jeopardize Russian
cooperation on national security interests, including Russian
behavior toward Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of explaining this trade-off, he said the administration
tried to oversell the ``success'' of Russian reform and the
``partnership'' relationship that Treasury Department officials and
others boasted about.
</P>
<P>
   An administration economist said his agency was often asked by
the State Department for success stories in Russia that could be
cited to Congress and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the Clinton policy was the decision to help
Russia, through loans from the IMF and other sources, to lift
itself out of communism and privatize the economy as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   When a handful of Russians emerged almost overnight as the newly
rich owners of major natural resources and industrial enterprises _
some of them by questionable means _ they were acceptable to the
Clinton administration because they largely backed Yeltsin against
the threat of a Communist comeback.
</P>
<P>
   With the assistance of campaign contributions from these
so-called oligrachs, some of whom are now under investigation in
the West, Yeltsin was victorious in 1996 over a Communist
candidate, Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   The United States recognized the assistance the oligarchs
provided in re-electing Yeltsin, a senior administration
policymaker said, but chose to de-emphasize their dark side and
their maneuvers intended to strip the country of many of its
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication of reluctance to face the corruption
problem, Vice President Gore was shown evidence by the Central
Intelligence Agency in 1995 of what it considered the personal
corruption of Russia's prime minister at the time, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, with whom Gore chaired a joint American-Russian
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officials said late last year that Gore rejected
their report, a move that these analysts said led them to
understand that Gore was not interested in any further information
on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   One official who worked on economic reform in Russia said that
as it became clear that the IMF's conditions for macro-economic
reforms were not working, it also became clear that efforts by the
Clinton administration to introduce micro-reforms were not working
either.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a report by PricewaterhouseCoopers concluded that the
Central Bank lied to the IMF in 1996 about the level of its foreign
exchange reserves to encourage the fund to continue lending to the
country. The report said that the Central Bank channeled assets
through Fimaco, a company based in the Channel Island tax haven of
Jersey. The first deputy managing direct of the fund, Stanley
Fischer, said after the audit was released that the Central Bank
reserves had been overstated by $1.2 billion in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since the release of the report, several administration
officials said that there was now a serious question of trust with
senior Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   In another reform effort that went awry, Washington tried to
help Russia develop a Russian money-laundering law. Again, experts
from the Comptroller of the Currency and the FBI were sent to
Moscow. They worked on a bill intended to enable prosecutors to
investigate money laundering. The legislation passed the Duma twice
but was twice vetoed by Yeltsin, most recently in July.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the administration had expressed its disappointment
about Yeltsin's veto, Talbott said: ``We did the obvious.'' But he
said he could not provide the details. Talbott asked one of his
deputies, Stephen Sestanovich, ambassador at large for the Newly
Independent States, to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Sestanovich said that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had
urged Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov to restart the process
of getting the bill enacted. Administration officials have
acknowledged in the past that Ivanov has little influence with
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   As it became clear in 1998 that the Russian government was not
getting the necessary tax revenue, the Gore-Chernomyrdin commission
was used by the administration as a vehicle for trying to deal with
corruption, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   An official knowledgeable with the workings of the commission
said that Gore's people raised the corruption issue in 1998 but
could not find any interlocuters in Russia with whom they could
regularly follow up. This effort, too, frittered away, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as the State and Treasury departments and the
National Security Council reviewed yet again their Russia policy,
one irony was already apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The jettisoning of the money-laundering bill by Yeltsin meant
that there is no serious money-laundering law. Thus, American
law-enforcement officials investigating money flowing through the
Bank of New York will not have a legal basis on which to work with
Russian law-enforcement agencies, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
