</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-INQUIRY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCIES SUGGEST INDEPENDENT HEAD FOR WACO INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This is now the lede of the paper on NYT A1, replacing
DOLLAR, which has moved inside.) 
(EDS: 2nd take with additional information will follow by 10 p.m.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to head off any impression of a conflict of
interest, Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis J.
Freeh are strongly leaning toward an outside investigation into
their agencies' failure to disclose the use of incendiary devices
at the 1993 siege of the Branch Davidian compound, officials said
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh wholeheartedly backs an inquiry without involvement of the
FBI, a bureau spokesman, Tron Brekke, said Tuesday evening. ``We
would welcome a qualified group of independent investigators to do
that,'' Brekke said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Justice Department official said Reno too had all but
decided that an exhaustive inquiry with total independence is the
best way to find out why the use of the incendiary devices _
heat-generating tear-gas canisters _ during the April 19, 1993,
federal assault on the compound near Waco, Texas, had gone
unacknowledged for six years.
</P>
<P>
   The recent disclosure that two such incendiary tear-gas devices
had been used at Waco _ albeit without success and a good six hours
before flames consumed the cult's compound _ has caused the bureau
and the Justice Department acute embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Reno conceded last week that the disclosure, coming after six
years of statements to the contrary, had caused her to lose
credibility. Officials at the Justice Department and the bureau
have worried aloud that the backtracking would provide grist for
anti-government extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Another signal that the 1993 raid, which ended in about 80
deaths, including that of the cult's leader David Koresh, is still
an explosive issue in Washington was a statement Tuesday night that
Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, is weighing a proposal to create a joint House-Senate
commission to delve into the episode.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
