A6433 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MARCH-NYT &LR;      08-31 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES CONTENT OF SPEECHES CANNOT BE USED TO PREVENT HARLEM
RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge ruled Tuesday that Khallid Abdul
Muhammad, the leader of the New Black Panther Party, may hold a
youth rally in Harlem on Saturday, saying that city officials had
no right to use the content of Muhammad's inflammatory speeches as
a basis for denying him a rally permit.
</P>
<P>
   In his 31-page decision ordering the city to grant the permit,
U.S. District Judge Judge Denny Chin said it was ``understandable''
that the city would seek to deny Muhammad a platform, given the
``hateful, violent and frightening'' nature of many speeches by him
and other organizers of the rally, called the Million Youth March.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least as frightening as the rhetoric of Muhammad is the
possibility of a society where the right to speak publicly can be
denied on the basis of administrative whim, personal dislike, or
disapproval of anticipated content,'' Chin wrote in a clear rebuke
to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whose comments about Muhammad have
ranged from scorn to ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even hateful, racist and offensive speech,'' Chin added, ``is
entitled to First Amendment protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Brooklyn on Tuesday night, Giuliani
angrily denounced the judge's decision as a ``distortion of
reasoning'' and ``totally unwarranted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example,'' he said, ``of a judge putting his head
in the sand and somehow being so overwhelmed with the inability to
make a distinction between a proper First Amendment demonstration
and an excuse for violence that he really just can't see the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city immediately appealed the decision to the
2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan, which set arguments
for 9 a.m. Wednesday. But the march organizers celebrated the
ruling, one of several over the last year in which judges have
chided city officials for refusing to grant rally permits to the
Million Youth March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Chin is our brother,'' said Malik Shabazz, a lawyer for
the march.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tuesday's ruling was not a complete victory for the march
organizers. Chin rejected Muhammad's request for a parade to the
site of the rally, scheduled to take place on Saturday afternoon at
the intersection of 118th Street and Malcolm X Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to order city officials to use fewer police
officers than the several thousand who were assigned to last year's
rally, a four-hour event that ended in bloody clashes between
hundreds of participants and platoons of officers in riot gear who
moved in swiftly to enforce a 4 p.m. deadline to end the rally.
</P>
<P>
   With ``two final observations,'' Chin made it plain that he
disapproved of each side's conduct last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``First,'' he wrote, ``the violence that occurred last year
cannot be repeated, and both sides should make every effort to
reduce hostilities. Second, excessive numbers of police officers in
riot gear, rigid enforcement of deadlines, and helicopters swooping
over the crowd can only increase, rather than lessen, tension.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that videotapes of last year's rally, which was also
held on the first Saturday in September, left him ``with the
disquieting impression'' that if the Police Department ``had simply
been patient and given the participants a few minutes to disperse,
the risk of violence would have been substantially reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and other city officials have long contended that
Muhammad incited the violence when, for example, he instructed
rally participants that ``if anyone attacks you, already decide who
will be the one to disconnect the railing where you are and beat
the hell out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the City Corporation Counsel, Michael D. Hess, argued
that these words _ and a slew of equally provocative statements _
constituted ``fighting words'' unworthy of First Amendment
protection. The possibility that Muhammad would make similar
remarks at this year's rally, Hess said, was more than enough
reason for the city to deny a rally permit.
</P>
<P>
   Chin firmly rejected this assertion. First of all, he said, he
did not agree that Muhammad's speech contained fighting words _
that is, words that ``by their very utterance inflict injury or
tend to incite an immediate breach of the peace.'' He noted that
Muhammad, the former spokesman of the Nation of Islam, who
routinely refers to Jews as bloodsuckers and whites as devils, was
careful to call for violent resistance only as a means of
self-defense in the face of an attack by the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the contrary,'' he wrote, ``one of the videotapes shows
that at the time the conflict broke out, Muhammad was telling the
demonstrators to `go home to (their) families,' to `go in the word
love,' to `go in the word peace,' and that the crowd had already
begun to disperse. Indeed, the words that the city contends are
undeserving of First Amendment protection had actually been uttered
at some time before the disturbance broke out.''
</P>
<P>
   But even assuming that Muhammad's speech last year incited
violence, that still would not be a proper basis for denying a
permit now, Chin ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `fighting words' doctrine has not been used as a basis for
justifying a `prior restraint' on future speech, and to deny
plaintiff a permit this year based on comments made by the speakers
at last year's rally would constitute an unlawful prior restraint
on speech,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Muhammad has often compared himself to Malcolm X,
another Nation of Islam outcast who rose to national prominence by
insisting upon the right of black people to violently resist white
oppression. Last week, when asked why many black politicians in
Harlem were calling on residents to boycott his march, Muhammad
again linked himself to Malcolm X, saying Malcolm X was also
shunned by ``bootlicking, Uncle Tom'' black politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Chin ordered city officials and march organizers to ``promptly
meet'' to discuss the specifics of the rally, and ``to agree on
measures to avoid the confrontation that occurred last year.'' But
at a news conference Tuesday, Hess said he did not see any purpose
in meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything more to sit down and talk about
at all,'' Hess said. Nor, he said, would the city commit to
reducing the police presence at this year's rally, saying in a
defiant manner, ``The Police Department will do what it sees fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rally leaders have complained bitterly _ and with some merit,
Chin said _ about the Police Department's decision last year to
clear the rally area a few minutes after their permit expired at 4
p.m. Under questioning by Chin, city officials had been unable to
cite a single other rally or parade that was subjected to such a
strict standard.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with Chin's admonition for both parties to be reasonable,
Shabazz and other lawyers for the march again pressed city
officials to be more flexible about this year's event. But Hess
said that if the city loses its appeal, it will not grant a minute
more than the four hours alloted to the Million Youth March under
Chin's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a four-hour event, and that's all it will be,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
