<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOLLAR-530&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      08-31 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLLAR SLIDES AS ECONOMIES IN EUROPE AND ASIA STRENGTHEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan)  (js) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. dollar has begun to slide against the Japanese yen and
the 11-nation euro as investors turn their attention to rebounding
economies in Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar fell Tuesday below 110 yen, the second time it has
done so since 1996. In January, it briefly pierced that level
before rebounding. Against the euro, which made its debut in
January as Europe's single currency, the dollar is falling after a
15 percent gain in a rally that ended in July.
</P>
<P>
   Though the U.S. economy continues to expand, growth slowed in
the second quarter. And investors now expect higher interest rates
to prove a further drag on it this year. Meanwhile, Asian
economies, many of which fell into recession after the currency
turmoil of 1997, show signs of life, as does Europe. So the
potential for growth in the near term may be just as good or better
outside the United States, investors reason, causing dollars to
flow out of the country and into foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past year or so the dollar has leveled off, and we
are in an environment now in which the dollar should start a
moderate slide,'' said James McCormick, currency strategist at J.P.
Morgan Securities. ``It's not a question of a weaker dollar. It's a
stronger rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said he expects the dollar to fall about 5.6 percent
against the euro to $1.12 by the end of the year while the yen
could move to 105, a decline of 4.2 percent from current levels.
</P>
<P>
   A weaker dollar means prices of imported goods, from televisions
to toys, will rise, increasing inflationary pressures. It also
makes travel abroad more expensive for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts are not worried about this impact because the
falling dollar will also have positive effects. At the same time, a
weakening dollar will make U.S. goods more competitive abroad,
which could aid economic growth here and help America's
manufacturers recover from a slump induced by the global financial
crisis that began two years ago in July. More exports, combined
with a slowdown in imports, would also help reduce the country's
ballooning trade deficit, which set a record in June.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this weakening of the dollar is a policy problem for the
Clinton administration is not clear yet. The former treasury
secretary, Robert E. Rubin, had supported a strong dollar, in part
because it helped restrain inflation. His successor, Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers, says he is supportive of that policy
but some analysts wonder how committed he is to it.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve will also be looking at the dollar because
its weakness could add to inflationary pressures. But other
factors, including consumer spending that is being fed by a strong
stock market and gains in home values, are a bigger concern. The
central bank traditionally has paid close attention to the dollar
only if it is considered to be drastically out of line with where
it should be or if it moves so fast as to destabilize other
financial markets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The big move against the dollar this year has come from the
Japanese yen, which is up 11.8 percent since early July. In trading
Tuesday, the yen finished at 109.59 to the dollar, up from 110.73
Monday. (When the dollar losses value it buys less foreign
currency.) The last time it was below 110 was on Jan. 11, at
108.89.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the move this year has been caused by the rush of
foreign investors into Japanese stocks as they bet that a
turnaround in the Japanese economy will improve corporate
performance and push that moribund stock market higher. McCormick
said that so far this year foreigners have made about $54 billion
in net purchases of Japanese stocks, compared with $17 billion in
all of 1998. To buy the stock, foreigners have to sell their local
currency and buy yen, pushing up its value.
</P>
<P>
   Though the weakening dollar may not be a major problem for the
United States, economists say it could become one for Japan. As the
yen strengthens, Japanese goods become more costly abroad. And if
this cuts into sales by Japanese companies, the long-sought
economic recovery could run into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, Japan tried to slow the rise of the yen by
intervening in the currency market to sell yen six times in June
and July. But suddenly last month, Japanese officials indicated
that they were abandoning this policy, at least for now. The policy
shift opened the door for the yen to move below 110.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the government relented is that intervention, without
the participation of the United States, is unlikely to work. In
addition, Japanese officials are hoping that their economy is on
the rebound, which would make the rise in the yen less worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   The test of that economy will come on Sept. 10, when the
Japanese government releases data on growth for the quarter ended
in August. If the data are strong enough to confirm that the
recovery signaled in the first quarter is continuing, worries about
the rally in the yen could subside. Comments from Japanese
officials Tuesday indicated that the growth outlook is still
positive.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the yen is below 110, currency traders will be on
the lookout for any sign that Japanese policy makers are ready to
intervene again. Investors are showing some signs of concern too,
as the stock market rally has stalled.
</P>
<P>
   The euro rose Tuesday to a value of $1.0578, from $1.0471
Monday. Since mid-July, when there were the first sure signs of a
turnaround in the German economy, the euro has risen 4.4 percent.
Yet it is still down 9.3 percent against the dollar for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The relative strength of the dollar against the euro and some
other major currencies suggest that there is no serious dollar
swoon in the making now.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Federal Reserve's vigilance against inflation is not
helping the dollar. By moving to raise short-term interest rates,
the Fed aims to slow growth here before the economy overheats to
the point that prices and wages spiral upward. While higher
interest rates can sometimes support a currency, they are negative
for the dollar in this case because investors are betting that a
slowdown here will make U.S. investments a little less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a further rate increase by the Fed when it meets
in October along with comments about rising asset prices made last
Friday by Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, also put downward
pressure on stock prices this week as foreign investors fled the
market and hence the currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
