u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS-AR     08-31 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK PAIN FORCES SAMPRAS TO WITHDRAW FROM U.S. OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A devastated Pete Sampras, unshaved, unhappy and
unable to make sense of the stabbing pain that settled into his
lower back during a Sunday morning practice, announced his
withdrawal from the U.S. Open Tuesday because of a herniated disk
in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Sampras, a four-time Open champion who came into
this event poised not only to tie Jimmy Connors' record of five
Open victories but also to pass Roy Emerson's career Grand Slam
title record of 12, seemed stunned that his history-making mission
had been canceled by an injury he termed ``kind of a fluke thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm obviously very overwhelmed; the way that I'd
been playing the last two months, I liked my chances here,'' said
Sampras, who tied Emerson's record in July by capturing his sixth
Wimbledon crown, compiled a 24-match undefeated streak over the
summer and came into this Open with heady expectations. But he
never got to play a match. ``I'm not saying I was going to win here
or whatever. But to break the all-time record was a dream that I
had, to do it here in New York. As competitive as I am, I was
hoping to do it here, but it's obviously not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said he planned to fly home to Los Angeles right away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disk problem, which requires rest and rehabilitation
treatments twice a day, will keep him off the circuit for six to
eight weeks, an absence that will inevitably cost him the year-end
No. 1 ranking he has held for a record six years.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras was more concerned that his plans for the Open, the
tournament where he made history at 19 by defeating Andre Agassi in
the 1990 final to become the youngest male champion, dissolved
before this campaign, his 12th consecutive appearance at the Open,
even began.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras skipped this year's Australian Open to concentrate on
solving the French Open (the only Grand Slam event he hasn't won),
kept his Wimbledon title a third straight year and ended his Grand
Slam season with his first Open title since 1996, said: ``I'm sure
these next two weeks will be tough emotionally because I want to be
here,'' he said. ``I've been part of the U.S. Open for every year
of my career, and there's no question I'm going to miss playing
here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who hadn't withdrawn from a Grand Slam tournament since
the 1992 Australia Open because of a shoulder injury and who had no
history of problems with his vertebrae, added: ``I couldn't think
of a worse time for this to happen. I've never had serious back
problems like this one; I've had chronic stuff, and if it was
chronic I'd play tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   He won Wimbledon six years ago despite a shoulder so sore he had
trouble lifting his toothbrush.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Californian sustained the back injury one game
into a friendly Sunday practice session with fifth-seeded Gustavo
Kuerten of Brazil. ``It was on a return of serve,'' Sampras said.
``I didn't hear anything, but I felt something go. I felt my back
just got, you know, stabbed by a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said he went straight to his changeover chair, told
Kuerten he needed to quit, and asked his coach, Paul Annacone, to
find a doctor for him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Hainline, the U.S.Open medical director, initially
dismissed the injury as a minor back strain when he examined
Sampras at the National Tennis Center that same day. But when the
worried Sampras continued to experience overnight discomfort, the
physician reconsidered and scheduled the player for a CAT scan and
magnetic resonance imaging examination on Monday. The results,
Hainline said, showed an injury that, while not career-threatening,
would have posed the danger of chronic future pain had Sampras
tried to play here at his usual level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate in being able to diagnose the herniated disk
very early, before it became anything serious,'' said Hainline, who
located the disk tear between the fifth lumbar vertebrae and the
sacrum. ``When we look at his mri, his disks look very healthy.
There's a very focal tear right in the center; it's not pressing on
any nerves. It's just pressing on a pain-sensitive ligament. It's
really about a month of rest, and then the proper rehabilitation,
then it should heal completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the prognosis was positive, the timing of the injury
was puzzling for Sampras, a believer in destiny. ``It wasn't from
overplaying,'' he said. ``It wasn't from overstress. It was just a
bad move at the wrong time. Everything happens for a reason; these
last couple days I've been trying to figure out that reason.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the last three days had been tough to endure, ``the
worrying about not playing and the stress, then finally getting
some tests done on it. That was the last straw that said, `That's
it. It's over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Annacone said: ``More than anything, he's pretty crushed by
this. He really wanted it to happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' withdrawal stunned the rest of the field, which
suddenly lost its heavy favorite. Even Patrick Rafter, the Open's
two-time defending champion, had referred to Sampras as the man to
beat. Sampras' loss was Mikael Tillstrom's gain. Thursday, the
130th-ranked Swede will face Russia's Marat Safin in the first
round, replacing Sampras in the draw. Kuerten, like Rafter a
possible semifinal opponent for Sampras in the original draw, said
the injury was ``sad for him because he was playing great, but
maybe it's easier for us now.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi, seeded second and Sampras' victim in two Open
finals (and most recently losing to him in this year's Wimbledon
final), learned the news from his coach, Brad Gilbert, who was
sitting in the tournament director Jay Snyder's office when Sampras
called and confirmed his withdrawal. Agassi then called Sampras to
commiserate, a gesture Sampras called classy.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, whose chances for winning this tournament have now risen
abruptly, said: ``It's sad. It's too bad. It really is. It's tough
for so many people, the fans, myself and ultimately for Pete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
