u a BC-BARTON-WILL01-COX     08-31 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTON-WILL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruel killing and careful paperwork
 &HT;    By Alan Judd, Lyda Longa and Jay Croft
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About five hours before embarking on the worst murder
spree in Georgia history, Mark O. Barton conducted one last bit of
macabre business: He changed his will to provide a burial place for
his children, whom he had killed the previous night.
</P>
<P>
   The account of Barton's final morning were among the details
that emerged Tuesday when Atlanta police reluctantly released a
report of their investigation into the nine slayings that the
disgruntled day trader committed before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   The 208-page police file, provided to The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution after a lengthy debate over whether it is a
public record, describes the shootings at Momentum Securities Inc.
and All-Tech Investment Group Inc., the two brokerages where Barton
had traded since early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The file includes sketches of both offices after the shootings
and statements made by witnesses, victims and investigators.
</P>
<P>
   It also reveals that police officers discovered several capsules
of the anti-depressant drug Prozac in Barton's car after he
committed suicide, that he carried a stun gun along with other
weapons and that a handcuff key dangled from the key chain in his
car's ignition when he committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in his will provided the most dramatic new
information in the report, however, demonstrating an orderliness in
Barton's life hours before he threw Atlanta into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, July 26, three days before the shootings, Barton went
to his lawyer in Douglasville, Joseph Fowler, to remove his wife,
Leigh Ann, as the beneficiary of his estate, the attorney told
police. Instead, all Barton's property would go to his children,
Matthew and Michelle.
</P>
<P>
   Barton indicated to Fowler that his day trading activities were
causing problems between him and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did mention that day, when I asked how he was doing, that
he had lost money in trading,'' Fowler told the police. ``I don't
know a lot about that, but he did say that his wife was concerned
about the loss of the money. I did the will, he signed it, and
left.''
</P>
<P>
   The following night, Tuesday, according to police reports,
Barton killed his wife in their Henry County apartment. Then on
Wednesday, he killed his children.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Thursday, July 29, Barton called Fowler from
his car phone about 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe, you left something out,'' Barton told Fowler, the
attorney recalled during an interview Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later, Barton arrived at Fowler's office in
Douglasville and said he wanted to make two changes: He wanted his
mother, not his children, to be his beneficiary, and he wanted to
make sure his children would be buried in Douglas County with their
mother, Debra, who was murdered in Alabama in 1993. Barton had been
the prime suspect in Debra's murder, but he was never charged.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a ``relatively unusual provision,'' Barton's
request to provide a burial place for his children ``did not strike
me as being unusual or out of order'' since their mother was
deceased, Fowler said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you ask a question,'' he said, ``but it's not that
big of a question.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Fowler said, he noticed nothing unusual about Barton's
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear to my staff and myself that Mr. Barton was fully
aware of what he wanted to do with respect to the relatively minor
change he made,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, he said, Barton's wishes will be followed. His
children were buried where he wanted, and his mother, Gladys
Barton, 76, of Sumter, S.C., is named as the beneficiary of his
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
