<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA'S PRESIDENT PUTS ALLY IN CHARGE OF OIL COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 8th graf, Since its election ... to clarify, election
was in July.) 
 (smw) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ President Hugo Chavez moved to solidify his
control over the powerful state-run oil monopoly Tuesday by naming
an ally as the company's new chief.
</P>
<P>
   The previous leader had resigned Monday, saying that an internal
dispute had made it impossible for him to stay at Petroleos de
Venezuela, which controls the largest reserves of oil outside the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez appointed Hector Ciavaldini to head the company, saying
the move would correct ``the erroneous policy of the previous
government.'' He said he would announce other ``small changes at
the board level'' soon.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate for president last year, Chavez, a former army
colonel who in 1992 led an unsuccessful coup attempt, criticized
PDVSA, as the company is known here, as an uncontrollable ``state
within the state.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to eliminate its extravagant ``gold-card culture,'' to
cut production to help drive prices up and to seek closer ties with
other members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a process of integrating PDVSA within the economic and
political model of Venezuela,'' Chavez said Tuesday. ``We are going
to strengthen OPEC,'' he also promised, referring to a meeting here
last weekend in which the Venezuelan, Saudi and Mexican oil
ministers resolved to continue production cuts into next year.
Prices of Venezuelan oil have risen from $7 to more than $17 a
barrel since Chavez took office in February.
</P>
<P>
   Ciavaldini takes over from Roberto Mandini, an industry veteran
who led the company for less than seven months. Company officials
said his departure grew out of a dispute over management and
production policies. But it took place at a moment of political and
constitutional crisis that has raised questions about the future of
democracy in this nation of 23 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Since its election in July, a constitutional assembly dominated
by supporters of Chavez has taken over the court system and
stripped Congress of its power to pass laws. Leaders of the panel
said Tuesday that within days they would begin debate on a related
proposal to declare an emergency giving them authority to dismiss
the governors of Venezuela's 23 states and hundreds of mayors.
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped statement shown to employees on Monday and
broadcast on national television Tuesday, Mandini said that his
decision to step down had nothing to do with any discrepancy with
the government over strategy or objectives. Rather, he said, he and
other officials whom he did not identify could not agree ``how to
achieve them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot have a commercial corporation divided into
factions, because that is something that inevitably leads to
failure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent allusion to the populist economic policies
favored by some members of the Chavez administration, Mandini also
warned against regarding the oil company as ``the goose that lays
the golden eggs or a cash cow.''
</P>
<P>
   The company accounts for 80 percent of all the nation's exports
and one-third of government revenues. It is the largest exporter of
oil to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A group of employees recently issued a manifesto complaining
that ``people committed to revolutionary change have been
threatened with early retirement, dismissal or demotions'' under
Mandini's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these revolutionary times it is necessary to resolutely and
implacably demolish the control and power of the old PDVSA
establishment,'' their document concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ciavaldini, in contrast, is said to be a close friend of Jorge
Giordani, Chavez's minister of planning, and has clashed with top
management at the company. In 1995, he was fired from his post as
an adviser to a company affiliate, but appealed the decision,
eventually won his job back after a long court case, and in
February was named the company's vice president for planning. He
was appointed, along with three military officers, to its
seven-member board.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the newspaper Economia Hoy published
Tuesday, Virgilio Avila, a former chairman of the Energy Committee
of the Venezuelan Senate who is now a member of the constitutional
assembly, urged the Chavez government to ``prevent the
politicization of PDVSA, as that would cause terrible harm.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez said such fears were misplaced. ``We will respect the
meritocracy'' that has governed promotions within the oil giant, he
promised.
</P>
<P>
   He added that what is taking place is ``the Venezuelanization''
of the company, to ``bring it in tune with new times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
