<SLUG> BC-R-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLOSION IN MOSCOW INJURES 30, PROVOKES FEARS OF TERRORISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to delete map note)  (smw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A powerful explosion rocked Moscow's fanciest shopping
center Tuesday night, bringing the threat of terrorism to the foot
of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 people were wounded in the underground Manezh shopping
center, a marble and glass showcase of glitzy stores and a popular
gathering place for teenagers and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion coincided with an upsurge in the fighting in
Dagestan and provoked anxious speculation that Islamic militants
might have begun a series of terrorist attacks against the seat of
Russian power. The latest fighting has left eight Russian soldiers
dead and many more wounded, just days after Russia declared victory
over Islamic rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also possible that the blast was the work of a lone
fanatic, the result of gang warfare or perhaps even a pretext to
justify a ``state of emergency'' that would enable the Kremlin to
suspend the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   No one claimed responsibility for the explosion and officials
said there had been no warning.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesmen said initially that they did not know what
caused the explosion. But Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov said it was
caused by a bomb, containing about five ounces of TNT.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that comes to mind is the situation in
Dagestan,'' Luzhkov said Tuesday. ``But a more serious examination
is needed to make an accusation. Tonight we shall find out what
kind of bomb it was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of the Kremlin and near Red Square, the Manezh
complex is a favorite hangout for young Muscovites, who go there to
socialize, window shop and eat at its fast-food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The blast took place near a crowded fountain at 7:59 p.m.,
ripping apart a video arcade and sending shards of glass flying
through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Blood was smeared across the floor of a McDonald's restaurant.
Of the nearly 30 people who were wounded, five were reported to be
in grave condition.
</P>
<P>
   The blast occurred amid a new wave of fighting in Dagestan.
Tuesday, the Russian military unleashed artillery barrages and air
strikes near the villages of Karamakhi and Chabanmakhi, close to
the Dagestan capital of Makhachkala.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian attacks took place barely a week after Moscow
declared that it had triumphed over Islamic militants who have
crossed into Dagestan from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The raids Tuesday were directed against the Wahhabis, an Islamic
sect in Dagestan that has been sympathetic to the militants. Some
of the militants are even believed to have hidden in Wahhabi
villages.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wahhabis have also been generally content to govern
their own territory, and some specialists said that the attacks
might further inflame the already unstable Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previous Russian policy had been to leave the Wahhabis
alone,'' said Dmitri Trenin, deputy director of the Moscow office
of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. ``My own feeling
is that the situation will deteriorate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian offensive has already been costly. The Russian
military acknowledged Tuesday that eight of its soldiers had been
killed and 31 wounded. Russian officials said 80 ``militants'' had
been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The ORT television network observed dryly Tuesday night that
``the operation in Dagestan may take longer than initially
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether terrorism will be a part of the conflict is still
unclear. Although contract killings are virtually routine in
Russia, Moscow has generally been safe from terrorists. And Tuesday
evening jittery residents turned to the live news broadcasts from
the Manezh and wondered whether that has changed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Heavily promoted by Luzhkov and opened in 1997 during the
celebrations of the city's 850th anniversary, the Manezh is a
symbol of the nation's new freedoms and excesses. It is also just a
place to people watch and relax.
</P>
<P>
   As word of the explosion spread, television crews and ambulances
raced to the scene. Security forces took up positions in Red Square
and nearby streets.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion could prompt Moscow police to detain more people
from the Caucasus region. Already, dark-skinned people are often
stopped by the police and harassed. The Manezh mall, however, is
managed by Umar Dzhabrailov, an ethnic Chechen, who is close to
Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have often complained that President Boris Yeltsin, who
resides at a government complex outside the city, is out of touch
with events. So Yeltsin's spokesman made a point Tuesday of saying
that the president had been informed about the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, a potential presidential candidate, did better. He
rushed to the Manezh, toured the complex and then appeared before
the television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   With school classes set to resume on Thursday, the fact that so
many young people were among the injured prompted special concern.
The culprits, Luzhkov told reporters, were ``not human.'' No normal
person, he said, could have planted a bomb where children and young
people gathered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
