<SLUG> BC-FELLS-ACRES-JUDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN AMIRAULT CASE WANTS HER SENTENCE REDUCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The judge whose ruling freed Cheryl Amirault LeFave
from prison believes she should not be sent back and was prepared
to ask prosecutors to reduce her sentence and free her, the Globe
has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been allowed to meet this week with both sides in the
Fells Acres child sex-abuse case, Superior Court Judge Isaac
Borenstein planned to ask Middlesex District Attorney Martha
Coakley to consider reducing LeFave's prison sentence to time
served _ eight years _ which would have allowed her to walk out of
prison, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting of the minds never took place, because the
Supreme Judicial Court _ which last month reinstated LeFave's child
abuse conviction _ said Borenstein no longer had jurisdiction in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein's suggestion that LeFave be freed after serving eight
years in state prison is in line with his strong views that LeFave,
her late mother, Violet Amirault, and her brother, Gerald, were
wrongly convicted of abusing children at the family's Malden
day-care center in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It was Borenstein who overturned the convictions of LeFave and
her mother in two decisions in 1997 and 1998, ruling that
over-zealous investigators and prosecutors had coerced and coached
child witnesses, accepting too readily the often-fantastic tales of
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC reinstated the convictions, saying Borenstein was wrong
in ordering new trials for the pair.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of LeFave now rests with whichever judge in Middlesex
Superior Court is assigned her case. It will be up to that judge to
reinstate the original conviction and 8- to 20-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The judge _ as Borenstein has already demonstrated _ would have
the power of persuasion, but little else.
</P>
<P>
   Any move to shorten LeFave's sentence would have to come from
Coakley, who refused to discuss the case Tuesday, or from LeFave's
attorneys, who would need to file a motion to revise or revoke the
original sentence. The only other route to freedom would be a
successful appeal to the Massachusetts Parole Board, which has
previously refused to release LeFave early.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in a somewhat surprising admission, the original
prosecutor in the Amirault case said parents of Fells Acres victims
probably would not insist that LeFave be returned to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if any of the families feel she needs to go back
to prison,'' said Laurence Hardoon, who is now in private practice
specializing in civil suits by sexual abuse victims, ``but I think
everybody agrees that the Parole Board has to resolve it. That's
the appropriate method; it should not be resolved by a judge or the
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   In return for LeFave's release, Borenstein intended to ask
LeFave's attorneys to consider dropping any planned appeals to
federal court or seeking clemency from Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   James L. Sultan, a defense lawyer for LeFave, called
Borenstein's suggestion ``a creative solution which we certainly
would have given the most serious consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sultan said he will file a petition Wednesday asking
the SJC to re-hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan said that if LeFave is sent back to prison he would ask
for an early parole hearing. But he said LeFave does not intend to
admit to any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Parole Board requires, as a condition of granting her
parole, that she admit to crimes she didn't commit, then she won't
be paroled,'' Sultan said. ``She's innocent, and she'll never say
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   During their imprisonment, LeFave and her mother, who died of
cancer in 1997, were repeatedly denied parole, apparently because
they refused to admit guilt. An admission of guilt is typically
required for sex offenders to be paroled.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Amirault was convicted in 1986 and is serving a 30- to
40-year sentence. He has lost three appeals of his conviction and
remains in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
