<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-AIDS-INFECTED-ART     08-31 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-INFECTED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG, NONWHITE, FEMALE AND COMPLACENT ABOUT AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ga.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she goes out dancing on Saturday nights, Mercedes Rios
often finds herself listening to young women talk about how they
will never get AIDS. It hurts her, she says, because they will
never know by looking at her that she contracted HIV well over a
decade ago, and how vulnerable they really are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them `Hey, girls, be careful, use condoms,''' said Ms.
Rios, 41, who lives in Albany, N.Y. ``They think the only people
who have AIDS have marks in their arms and are skinny. And when you
see me, you would never never think I have this.''
</P>
<P>
   That, it turns out, may be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Death rates from AIDS in the United States are no longer falling
as rapidly as they did from 1995 to 1997, health officials at a
national AIDS conference in Atlanta said this week. New infections
of the virus that causes it were characterized by these officials
as ``dangerously high'' among minority gay men and heterosexual
women, especially minority women.
</P>
<P>
   Health care and policy experts who work with people infected
with HIV said Tuesday that those findings were consistent with what
they have been seeing in their clinics and hospitals, where
swelling ranks of teen-agers and black and nonwhite Hispanic men
and women have been walking through their doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our patient base is about 3,000 patients, and only 70 percent
male and only 12 percent white,'' said Matt Baney, the
administrator of the Comprehensive HIV Center at St. Vincents
Hospital and Medical Center in Manhattan. Five years ago, he said,
there were about 1,700 patients, and 90 percent of them were male
and nearly 65 percent were white.
</P>
<P>
   After a short period where all the news on the AIDS front
appeared to be optimistic, these figures are sobering to those who
work with people with AIDS. The reasons for the figures are many,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers were too young at the height of the AIDS epidemic to
be able to identify with the disease, they said. Others believe,
erroneously, that the latest drug therapies have turned AIDS into a
manageable disease, like diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are hearing from the kids is that AIDS is an illness
for adults,'' Baney said. ``They think it is finished, or that
there are medications, so what is the big deal? People in their 30s
and 40s remember people dying left and right and a time when it was
impossible not to know someone who was ill or who had died. Kids
just haven't seen that.''
</P>
<P>
   What is more, many older infected people are finding a
vulnerable audience in these young people. ``Gay boys often don't
fit into their own social background,'' Baney said. ``So they go
into an environment where they feel comfortable and accepted and
that is gay places where older adults take advantage of them. They
are very gullible.''
</P>
<P>
   Another significant factor is that public health campaigns to
promote safe sexual practices have not been directed at the
communities that need them the most, advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become complacent about our prevention messages,''
said Ronald S. Johnson, the managing director for public policy at
the Gay Men's Health Crisis center in Manhattan. ``Most ads were
designed for white gay men. We were very slow over all in targeting
gay men of color and women, and that speaks to the kinds of
differentials in the rates we see today.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the barriers to AIDS prevention are different for
different groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women tend not to participate fully in their own health
care,'' said Steven Fisher, a spokesman for AIDS Action, a national
AIDS policy organization in Washington with 3,200 members. ``They
are taking care of children, the household, others, and they can't
focus on their own care, which is not the case with gay men.''
</P>
<P>
   Cultural issues that have not been considered in the current
prevention literature prevent other groups from practicing safe sex
or getting tested for HIV, said Michael Saunders, who runs the HIV
prevention program for young adults at Gay Men of African Descent,
an AIDS education organization. Immigrants, Saunders said, may have
no access to information about prevention in their own language.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated drug therapies advanced in recent years are
starting to fail for many users, which has contributed to the
slowdown in falling death rates. AIDS workers are concerned that
the public's interest in the disease may have started to evaporate
already.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important aspect of the story is that the dramatic changes
we saw in the progression from HIV to AIDS has plateaued,'' said
Dr. Victoria Sharp, the director of the center for comprehensive
care for the AIDS programs at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center
in Manhattan. Sharp, who has studied the disease around the world
through a group called Doctors of the World, said, ``We now know
those therapies only work for certain people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that like with so many diseases,'' she said,
``the public attention turns away and therefore funding will not be
there. That is particularly true today looking at these
demographics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
