<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-CAPTRIATI-     08-31 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-CAPTRIATI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPRIATI OUSTS A MUTUAL OPPONENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The Netherlands, Italy, France, Croatia)   By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At age 14, Jennifer Capriati became the youngest
tennis player to be ranked in the top 10 world ranking. At age 19,
Iva Majoli was seeded ninth in the French Open and became the
lowest-seeded player to win a Grand Slam tournament in the era of
open tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Both players, however, have had trouble dealing with early
success.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati dropped out of the sport for two years while enduring
personal and legal problems. Majoli has suffered through
complacency and injuries. Now these two players _ good friends off
the court _ are seeing their careers move in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   While Capriati is on the upswing, Majoli is still trying to
straighten out her game. Their current level of play was evident
Tuesday when the 23-year-old Capriati and the 22-year-old Majoli
met in Louis Armstrong Stadium in the first round of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati won comfortably, 6-1, 7-5, largely because of Majoli's
40 unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my best friend,'' Majoli said after the match. ``We hang
out together. We have dinner and go to the movies. We talk about
everything: movies, restaurants, boys. In April, we spent a few
days on holiday in Jamaica. Most of the time, there's no friendship
among players.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati is ranked 40th in the world, Majoli 97th. Majoli has
been ranked as high as fourth, Capriati as high as sixth.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Capriati has won a tour tournament in Strasbourg,
France, and the A.&AMP;P. exhibition tournament in Mahwah, N.J. Under
the coaching of Harold Solomon, she feels her game keeps improving
.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just gone up,'' Capriati said. ``I don't think it
could get any lower than where I was at. My game is just getting
better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, at 14, Capriati made her U.S. Open debut, winning her
first three matches before falling to Steffi Graf. Capriati thinks
she is wiser now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a lot younger then,'' she said. ``I think obviously I
would have a different kind of attitude _ I would hope I do _ 10
years later. Maybe I'm not as, like, goofy as I was before. That's
changed. You know, I'm not going to go around saying I'm so excited
after I win a match here.''
</P>
<P>
   Majoli, a Croat, was not excited about losing her match Tuesday.
She is trying to resurrect a career that went downhill because, she
said, of a different kind of immaturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I won the French Open,'' she said, ``nobody expected me
to win. I didn't expect me to win. Then I won and discovered that
every opponent wants a piece of you. I didn't say to myself,
`You're playing good, but now it's going to be much tougher.'
Instead, I let myself be content when I lost. It was no big deal. I
told myself I would win the next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was bad thinking. I have regrets, but I was the one who
did all this. I have talent. I was there. To get to the top is
hard, but to stay on the top is harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when Majoli had straightened out her thinking, her body
betrayed her. Late last year a stress fracture in her right foot
sidelined her for two months. She returned, played three
tournaments and hurt her right shoulder. That put her out for four
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played maybe five tournaments this year,'' Majoli said,
``and this was my fourth straight first-round loss. I've had so
much rehab it's tough to play. I wish I could have played some more
before coming here. Tennis is my life, and when you play bad, it's
so bad you can't express it.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati's second-round opponent will be Seda Noorlander of the
Netherlands, the world's 93d-ranked player. Noorlander is 24 and
uses two-handed forehands and backhands. She beat Laura Golarsa of
Italy, 6-2, 6-1, Tuesday. She also defeated Capriati, 6-1, 6-3, in
the second round at Wimbledon this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The score looked easier than the match was,'' Noorlander said.
``I felt I had nothing to lose and the grass surface suited me
better than her. There's no real pressure on me now. She's an
American and she's expected to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati dismissed any talk of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to look ahead and see what your chances are,
just kind of, like, think about, you know, the rounds ahead and
stuff,'' she said. ``I'm confident I can compete with the best
players. I think I really believe that. I know I really believe
that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
