<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KORDA LOSES FINAL APPEAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland, Britain)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Petr Korda, the 31-year-old Czech player who tested
positive for an anabolic steroid last year, lost his final appeal
Tuesday. The Court of Arbitration for Sport in Lausanne,
Switzerland, ruled that Korda had to forfeit all prize money since
July 1998, when he tested positive for the bodybuilding steroid
nandrolone at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   The court also suspended him for a year and stripped him of
computer ranking points earned since the 1998 Wimbledon tournament.
That was academic because Korda retired last month.
</P>
<P>
   When Korda won the 1998 Australian Open, his world ranking
jumped from seventh to second. Six months later, Tim Henman of
Britain eliminated him in the quarterfinals at Wimbledon. Korda's
drug test there proved positive, and the International Tennis
Federation, following its rules, suspended him for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Korda appealed, citing ``exceptional circumstances.'' An
independent appeals panel agreed with him, saying he was unaware
that he had ingested a steroid. Instead of a suspension, the panel
stripped him of his prize money and ranking points from Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Other players were upset by what they considered undue leniency
by the appeals panel. They were also upset by the legal battle in
British courts before the case went to the Court of Arbitration for
Sport.
</P>
<P>
   During the litigation, Korda played, but not well. His ranking
fell so far that it did not get him into this year's Wimbledon.
Tournament officials refused to give him a wild-card berth, so he
entered the qualifying tournament. When he did not qualify there,
he retired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
