</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-3, 08-31
-- Orthodox Jewish residents of Brooklyn's Borough Park section
surround a vehicle carrying civil rights activist Al Sharpton on
Tuesday. Sharpton was attempting to show his support to the
community following a shooting by police of an emotionally
disturbed man Monday night. However Sharpton had to drive off
without getting out of his vehicle as demonstrators shouted
``Anti-semite, go home.'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani defended the fatal
police shooting of the man, who police say was weilding a hammer,
which brought hundreds of angry Hasidic protestors into the streets
of the heavily Orthodox neighborhood. (Don Hogan Charles/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- COLLEGE-GOODBYE-FLOATER,
08-31 -- Marilyn Kessler and her daughter Lisa,18, of Ridgewood,
N.J. say goodbye on the sidewalk in front of Barnard College on
Tuesday. Classes begin next week. In a ritual being carried out in
campuses across the nation, thousands of freshmen parents are
bidding farewell to their children as they head off to higher
learninig. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) BALTIMORE -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- YOUNG-SCHOLARS, 08-31 --
Julian C. Stanley, who founded the Institute for the Academic
Advancement of Youth, with Rachel Fischer, who attended on a
scholarship. ``These are not just bright kids who get good
grades,'' he says. ``They are different, and they learn
differently.'' (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- WORST-TABLES, 08-31 --
Tables on the side of the staircase at Babbo. Eat out enough in
this city and chances are some maitre or maitresse d'hotel is going
to stick you in Siberia. Once slang for the tourist-trap second
floor at the old Russian Tea Room, the term Siberia has become a
metaphor for second-class seating. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) MARIN COUNTY, Calif. -- Aug. 31, 1999 --
UKRAINE-LAZARENKO, 08-31 -- This 41-room mansion was purchased last
September for $6.75 million in cash by Pavlo Lazarenko, a former
Ukrainian prime minister. Lazarenko has been unable to join his
family at the estate however because federal authorities are
detaining him while they consider requests from Switzerland and
Ukraine that he be extradited on charges of embezzling state funds
and money laundering. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) HAMILTON, N.J. -- Aug. 31, 1999 --
SCHOOL-SHOPPING-FLOATER, 08-31 -- In preparation for her daughter's
first day of fourth grade next Tuesday, Robyn Wilk, of Hamilton,
N.J., tries to outfit Alyssa with new clothes at a department store
as her son Joseph watches closely. The back-to-school shopping
season is well under way, and the nation's stores and malls are
filled with parents and children seeking out the must-have fashion
items of the new school year. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-2, 08-31
-- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York speaks to reporters on
Tuesday about Monday night's shooting by police of a man in
Brooklyn as Police Commissioner Howard Safir looks on at left.
Giuliani and Safir defend the fatal police shooting of an
emotionally disturbed Hasidic man a day after protests roiled
through the borough. Jewish leaders in the neighborhood are split
in their reaction to the shooting, with critics saying the police
did not need to use deadly force. (Frances Roberts/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) SKANEATELES, N.Y. -- Aug. 31, 1999 --
NY-CLINTONS-FLOATER, 08-31 -- Chelsea Clinton holds Brooke Coleman,
2, from Charlotte, N.C., after a visit to the town's library on
Tuesday. Chelsea went on a sightseeing trip through the village in
Upstate New York and stopped to shake hands. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-3, 08-31 --
American Lindsay Davenport during her match against Corina Morariu
at the U.S. Open on Tuesday. Davenport, the No. 2 seed, launched
her defense of the women's title with a 6-0, 6-3 victory over her
compatriot and doubles partner. (Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 08-31 -- In
second day action at the U.S. Open on Tuesday, No. 6 seed Tim
Henman of Britain was ousted by unseeded Guillermo Canas. The
Argentine, ranked 68th in the world, took full advantage of
Henman's 52 unforced errors to post a 7-6 (7-1), 6-4, 6-3 victory.
(Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-1, 08-31 -- In
second day action at the U.S. Open, No. 7 seed Todd Martin narrowly
escaped a stunning upset. Martin squandered four match points in
the third set and struggled through a joyless five-set fight before
outlasting 154th-ranked French qualifier Stephane Huet 6-4, 6-3,
6-7 (2-7), 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-3). (Steve Berman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS-2, 08-31
-- A visibly upset Pete Sampras during a news conference Tuesday
announcing his withdrawal from the United States Open because of a
herniated disc. The four-time U.S. Open champion would have been
gunning for a record 13th Grand Slam title. The last time a No. 1
seed withdrew from the Open was in 1950 when Budge Patty injured
his ankle. (Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- NY-CLUBS-2, 08-30 --
Security guards checking identification documents at the Tunnel, a
dance club in Manhattan. Long a mecca for anything-goes night life,
New York and its big-box dance clubs have become heavily regulated
places. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) LIVINGSTON, N.J. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- BASEBALL-MEMORABILIA-2, 08-31 -- Barry Halper, who is
selling much of his collection of baseball memorabilia, in his den
office in Livingston. About 20 per cent of it was sent to the
Baseball Hall of Fame; most of the rest will be sold at a weeklong
auction at Sotheby's in Manhattan, begining Sept. 23, which might
break the house record of $34.4 million set by the sale of the
Jackie Kennedy Onassis estate. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LIVINGSTON, N.J. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- BASEBALL-MEMORABILIA-1, 08-31 -- A baseball signed by
Billy Martin and a record cover signed by Mickey Mantle are part of
Barry Halper's collection. About 20 per cent of it was sent to the
Baseball Hall of Fame; most of the rest will be sold at a weeklong
auction at Sotheby's in Manhattan, begining Sept. 23, which might
break the house record of $34.4 million set by the sale of the
Jackie Kennedy Onassis estate. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- MCCONNELL-FUNDRAISING,
08-31 -- Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., one of Congress's most ardent
opponents of a bill that would overhaul the campaign finance
system, has aggressively urged 10 business executives to resign
from an organization that has endorsed a wide array of reforms,
including the banning of soft money. McConnell is seen speaking to
reporters in this June 1999 photo. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) OCEAN CITY, Md. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- HURRICANE-DENNIS,
08-31 -- Ashley Smith and Rob Bostick of Gettysburg, Pa., shield
themselves from the stinging beach sand whipped up by gale force
winds near the boardwalk in Ocean City on Tuesday. A weakening
Hurricane Dennis stalled off North Carolina's Outer Banks on
Tuesday, but tropical storm warnings remained posted along the
mid-Atlantic coast and forecasters said the storm could still turn
back toward shore. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ATLANTA -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- ATLANTA-CRASH, 08-31 --
Traffic is backed up on I-285 following a tractor-trailer wreck
which killed two people on Tuesday. The truck, which was carrying
galvanized steel, struck the median wall under the Ashford Dunwoody
Road bridge and caught fire, the Georgia Department of
Transportation said. Police shut down the interstate in both
directions, as well as prevented traffic from crossing the Ashford
Dunwoody bridge over I-285. Police had not determined what caused
the wreck and had not released the names of those killed. (John
Spink/Atlanta Journal-Constitution) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- RAW-FISH-2, 08-31 --
Tiradito, thin slices of raw fish tossed with citrus juice, at
Nobu. Ceviche has expanded the world of flavors and textures
created in fish when no cooking is involved. (Fred R. Conrad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- WINE-TALK, 08-31 -- Charles
Scicolone, the wine director at I Trulli restaurant, with a $450
1989 barbaresco from Angelo Gaja and an $18 1995 Salice Salentino
Riserva from Cosimo Taurino of Puglia. Scicolone uses subterfuge to
introduce his customers to the restaurant's least expensive wines,
putting them in the tasting programs at the wine bar. (Don Hogan
Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-SHOOTING, 08-31
-- Two Orthodox Jewish men light candles early Tuesday near the
site of where police shot and killed a man hours earlier in
Brooklyn. A mentally disturbed man wielding a hammer was fired upon
at least 12 times and killed by the police, authorities said. The
shooting of the man, an Orthodox Jew identified by the police as
Gidone Busch, brought several hundred angry residents of the
largely Hasidic neighborhood into the streets to protest what they
said was excessive force by the police. (Aaron Lee Fineman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) FLORENCE, Mass -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- CARTOONIST-PRICE,
08-31 -- Hilary Price, who draws the syndicated cartoon strip
Rhymes With Orange which draws humor from the mundane affairs of
life, uses a mirror in her studio to check facial expressions while
drawing. A native of Weston, Mass., Price earned a bachelor's
degree in English literature from Stanford University. At 25, she
became the youngest woman ever to have a syndicated cartoon strip.
Today she is in her fifth year of a 10-year contract with King
Features Syndicate, based in New York. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CHATHAM, Mass. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- FISHING-CONFLICT-BOS,
08-31 -- Bruce Kaminski, a cod fisherman for 21 years, unloads the
day's catch at the pier. Five years of tough conservation measures
have helped fish populations to rebound, but regulators continue to
add new limits. Meanwhile, the families that have fished these
waters for generations say they're seeing their way of life dying
before their eyes. Kaminski says that the new 2,000 pound catch
limit on cod forces him to dump part of his load before returning
to the docks. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- RAW-FISH, 08-31 -- The
ceviche platter at Isla, which is to open next month in Greenwich
Village, features raw tuna, scallops in coconut milk, squid in an
herb dressing and oysters with onion and chilies. Ceviche has
expanded the world of flavors and textures created in fish when no
cooking is involved. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- COLD-NOODLES-2, 08-31 --
Soba noodles in broth at Honmura An in Soho. The cool, delicately
flavored broth plays the briny tang of bonito flakes and soy sauce
against the sweetness of sake and mirin, a sweet rice wine. (Boyd
Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- COLD-NOODLES-1, 08-31 --
Some of the best cold soba noodles this side of Tokyo can be found
in SoHo, at Honmura An. In this cool, Zen-like space, with its high
ceilings and uncluttered decor, you can watch the buckwheat noodles
being kneaded, rolled out and cut by hand. (Boyd Hagen/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CLINTON CORNERS, N.Y. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- GARLIC-2, 08-31
-- Several varieties of garlic are organically grown by David and
Ruth Nosonowitz at La Terre Garlic Farm in Clinton Corners. ``It's
frightening what they spray on garlic,'' Mrs. Nosonowitz says of
more traditional garlic farming methods. (Don Heiny/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CLINTON CORNERS, N.Y. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- GARLIC-1, 08-31
-- Several varieties of garlic are grown at La Terre Garlic Farm in
Clinton Corners. This is the peak of the garlic season. Growers in
the Northeast have harvested their crop and have either just
finished curing it, or will soon. (Don Heiny/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- DIANA-ANNIVERSARY, 08-31 --
``Where's Diana's memorial?'' reads a placard outside Kensington
Palace, the former home of Princess Diana, on Tuesday. The sign
summed up what many people feel about today's second anniversary of
Diana's death in a Paris car crash. A memorial committee set up
last year had proposed a commemorative garden near Kensington
Palace, but the plan was quietly put on hold after local residents
objected. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- CHILD-COOKS-BOS,
08-31 -- Samir Abu-Eid, 6, is served some scrambled eggs made by
his sister Salena, 11, while their mother was getting ready for her
job as an assistant teacher in a preschool. Call it the convergence
of time crunch and convenience. In an era of microwave magic,
dual-earner homes, and single-parent families, surveys show an
increasing number of children and teenagers fixing meals not only
for themselves but also for their families. (Janet Knott/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS, 08-31 --
Pete Sampras hits a forehand against Patrick Rafter in
September1998, during the U.S. Open. Sampras withdrew from this
year's open on Tuesday before his first match because of a back
injury. The last time the No. 1 seed withdrew from the U.S.
championships was in 1950 when Budge Patty injured his ankle.
(Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-BOS-2,
08-31 -- Members of the U.S. Ryder Cup team, from left, Justin
Leonard, team captain Ben Crenshaw, Bill Rodgers, Payne Stewart and
Steve Pate on the 18th green during a practice round on Monday.
Since watching the favored Americans fall apart in Valderrama in
1997 - their second consecutive loss - team captain Ben Crenshaw
has stressed teamwork and camaraderie as a key to taking back the
trophy. (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-BOS-1,
08-31 -- Members of the U.S. Ryder Cup team from left, Phil
Michelson, David Duval, Hal Sutton and Jeff Maggart, at far right,
during a practice round on Monday. Since watching the favored
Americans fall apart in Valderrama in 1997 - their second
consecutive loss - team captain Ben Crenshaw has stressed teamwork
and camaraderie as a key to taking back the trophy. (Frank
O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- SPIDERMAN-DRUGS, 08-31 --
Barry McCaffrey, director of the Office of National Drug Control
Policy, poses with a man dressed as Spiderman during a news
conference in Washington on Tuesday. Starting in September, Marvel
Comics will launch the first of a four-part comic book series with
an anti-drug theme featuring Spiderman and his superhero friends.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- OBIT-SUGARMAN-B&AMP;W, 08-30 --
George Sugarman, whose animated, meandering polychrome sculptures
are among the most inventive if least appreciated three-dimensional
artworks of the early 1960s, at the installation of one of his
works in Manhattan's City Hall Park. Sugarman, 87, died on
Wednesday at Cabrini Medical Center in Manhattan. (Eddie
Hausner/New York Times Photo, 1978)
</P>
