</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 08-31 -- In
second day action at the U.S. Open on Tuesday, No. 6 seed Tim
Henman of Britain was ousted by unseeded Guillermo Canas. The
Argentine, ranked 68th in the world, took full advantage of
Henman's 52 unforced errors to post a 7-6 (7-1), 6-4, 6-3 victory.
(Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-1, 08-31 -- In
second day action at the U.S. Open, No. 7 seed Todd Martin narrowly
escaped a stunning upset. Martin squandered four match points in
the third set and struggled through a joyless five-set fight before
outlasting 154th-ranked French qualifier Stephane Huet 6-4, 6-3,
6-7 (2-7), 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-3). (Steve Berman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Aug. 31, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS-2, 08-31
-- A visibly upset Pete Sampras during a news conference Tuesday
announcing his withdrawal from the United States Open because of a
herniated disc. The four-time U.S. Open champion would have been
gunning for a record 13th Grand Slam title. The last time a No. 1
seed withdrew from the Open was in 1950 when Budge Patty injured
his ankle. (Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
