<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES END MIXED AFTER MANUFACTURING REPORT ADDS FEAR OF FED RATE
AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices gyrated sharply Tuesday, ending mixed in
a session that traders said was almost impossible to interpret.
</P>
<P>
   After opening higher, stocks fell sharply along with bond prices
around midday after a monthly survey of the nation's purchasing
managers showed that conditions in the manufacturing sector were
stronger than expected during August, reinforcing worry that the
Federal Reserve Board will again push short-term interest rates
higher.
</P>
<P>
   From its morning high to its low, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell about 200 points, only to recoup all its loss, and
then fall again near the close on computer-generated sell programs.
By the end of the day, the Dow was down 84.85, or 0.8 percent, to
10,829.28. Big declines in stocks like Caterpillar Tractor,
International Paper and Dupont more than offset gains in computer
stocks like Hewlett-Packard and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Strength in technology shares helped limit losses in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index, which closed at 1,320.41, down
3.61, or 0.3 percent. The Nasdaq composite index, which has many
more technology stocks than the S&AMP; P or the Dow, gained 26.66, or 1
percent, to 2,739.35. And the Russell 2000 index of small company
stocks eked out a gain of 0.5, or 0.1 percent, to 427.83.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three main market measures, the Nasdaq composite
performed the best last month, rising 3.9 percent. The Dow average
rose 1.9 percent, but the S&AMP;P 500 fell by 0.5 percent during
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think prices have further to fall, but I wouldn't put too
much emphasis on anything the market does this week,'' said Bill
Allyn, head of listed trading at Jefferies &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 861.7 million shares changed
hands, partly because of end-of-the-month window dressing. On
Monday trading volume did not reach 600 million. On the Nasdaq
stock market, 964 million shares were traded.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said he expected that by the middle of next week conditions
would seem more normal ``because all of the various players in the
market will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks got a lift early in the day after IBM said it
had agreed to sell $2 billion worth of parts to Cisco Systems over
the next five years and to help maintain computer networks for
Cisco customers. IBM shares rose 1] to 124 9/16. Cisco, an S&AMP; P 500
and Nasdaq composite component, gained 1 1/16, to 67 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems was another big winner, rising 3~ to 79{ after
a Merrill Lynch analyst upgraded his rating on it.
</P>
<P>
   Other big technology issues also did well. Apple Computer gained
3 3/16 to 65\ after it unveiled a new Power Macintosh professional
personal computer, and Computer Associates International, the
computer software designer, jumped 5 5/16, to 56{.
</P>
<P>
   Office Depot, which issued an earnings report late Monday, fell
1/16 to 10 7/16. Its major competitor, Staples fell 3/16, to 21}.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
