A6477 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      08-31 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Bills May Affect Business 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Q: With the end of the California legislative session only a week
and a half away, what bills still are being considered that will
impact my business?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: According to the California Chamber of Commerce, there still are
many bills being considered by the Legislature that would affect
California's small businesses. These are some of the more critical
measures:
</P>
<P>
   _AB633, by Assemblyman Darrell Steinberg, D-Sacramento, would
allow employees, trial attorneys and other third parties to bypass
the labor commissioner's office and sue employers over wage issues.
The bill also includes a ``bounty provision'' that for the first
time makes employers liable for civil penalties in wage disputes.
The California chamber says this bill would increase the filing of
``nuisance suits'' and opposes this measure.
</P>
<P>
   _SB320, by Sen. Hilda Solis, D-La Puente (Los Angeles County),
would increase workers' compensation benefits by $2.7 billion. This
bill contains no offsetting changes that would cut costs, and it is
expected that the $2.7 billion increase would be passed directly to
employers in the form of higher premiums. The chamber also opposes
this measure.
</P>
<P>
   _Health care changes. Gov. Gray Davis and the Legislature still
are negotiating the final package that Davis will sign into law.
The California chamber opposes changes that dramatically would
increase the price of health care and force employers, particularly
small businesses, to drop coverage or pass along the additional
costs to employees who might not be able to afford it.
</P>
<P>
   _SCA3, by Sen. John Burton, D-San Francisco, would let
individual communities raise and control local transportation funds
through a dedicated half-cent sales tax. It is estimated that
California's overall transportation needs will be somewhere between
$70 billion and $80 billion over the next decade. This proposed
constitutional amendment needs approval from two-thirds of the
Assembly and then would need to be voted on by Californians in
November 2000. The California chamber supports this measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature always waits until the last few weeks of the
session to deal with many of the significant bills,'' said
California Chamber of Commerce President Allancq &LR;  Zaremberg. So far
this year, organized business has taken some lumps. In July, for
example, Davis signed a bill that restores overtime rules requiring
employers to pay workers time and a half for the first four hours
after an eight-hour shift, and double time for anything over 12
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you take the chamber side on pending issues or oppose
it, there still is time to contact your state legislators and Davis
and to tell them where you stand. To find out who your state
legislators are and how to reach them, you can visit the California
Chamber Web site (www.calchamber.com) or the state government's
site (www.ca.gov/s /govt/legisca.html).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
READER RESPONSE
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Online marketing. After reading last week's item on ways to
promote an online business without spending big bucks, Chronicle
reader Nicole Kidd recommends another easy-to-read,
resources-packed guide called ``Poor Richard's Internet Marketing
and Promotions _ How to promote yourself, your business, your ideas
online'' by Peter Kent/ Tara Calishain (1999, $29.95). Also check
out Kent's ``geek-free, common sense'' advice at Poor Richard's Web
site (www.poorrichard.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Kids 'n contracts. Responding to another item last week, Pillsbury
Madison &AMP; Sutro attorney Steven Saxe notes that although minors can
get out of most contracts until a short time following their 18th
birthdays, adults who enter into agreements with them are legally
bound by the terms of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   If adults are willing to contract with someone under 18, the
minor does not need to obtain a parent's signature before the other
party is committed to the deal it has made. One of the few
exceptions is real estate mortgage contracts, which would not be
binding on either party.
</P>
<P>
   Further, banks can open accounts for minors without the parents'
knowledge or approval. Banks also can make a loan contract with a
minor. But because the minor would not be bound by terms of the
loan, most banks &UR;  &LR; won't loan money to a child without a parent's
signature. However, some lenders do make small loans to minors for
Junior Achievement and similar projects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
