<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6479 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-BIRD-HEART-BOS &LR;      08-31 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BIRD-HEART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD, REVEALING HEART CONDITION, HINTS AT END TO COACHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY AND BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Larry Bird reveals in an upcoming book that he has a
heart problem, one that surfaced occasionally in the offseason
while he was with the Celtics and still requires medication. In an
interview Tuesday, Bird declined to talk about the condition, but
indicated this would be his last season as head coach of the
Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   The heart condition, known as atrial fibrillation, is
controllable with medication, proper attention to diet, exercise,
and moderated alcohol consumption, Celtics team physician Arnold
Scheller said.
</P>
<P>
   Bird never told the Celtics about his heart ``episodes'' while
he was playing, and they occurred only during his sometimes-brutal
summer workouts. It was after he retired in 1992, and well after
the death of Reggie Lewis from a different, more serious heart
problem in 1993, that he finally went to Scheller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Reggie's episode precipitated it,'' Scheller
said. ``Larry and I basically dealt with it as if it was no big
deal. He had been running a lot, 6 miles a day, and he called me up
one day and said he felt lightheaded. I ran him through some tests
and we found it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheller said there was never any indication of heart problems
while Bird played.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's episodic. It comes and goes,'' Scheller said. ``But it's
related to alcohol consumption and proper conditioning. It was not
a serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached Tueday night, Bird said he could not talk about the
condition because of his arrangement with his publisher. He
described it in the book, called, ``Bird Watching: On Playing and
Coaching the Game I Love,'' as saying his heart would start
``jumping around . . . I always knew there was something wrong with
my heart.'' The book is excerpted in the current Sports
Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bird did talk briefly about his job situation. When
asked what he thought about rookie Jonathan Bender, Bird said, ``I
don't know. I'm not going to see him play much, anyway.'' He then
said that this was his final season and that he had said as much to
Pacers president Donnie Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Bird's comments, Walsh said: ``He didn't say it flat
out. I never expected him to coach beyond the three years, but it's
not like he has come in here and told us that this is it. The idea
was that we'd talk at the end of this season and see what he wanted
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird signed a three-year contract to coach the Pacers with the
expectation that he'd move into the front office after that,
possibly to take Walsh's job. Walsh said the two have discussed
such a move for next season and that Bird has seemed interested in
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with Larry, you never know,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Bird's decision, it will not hinge on his heart
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Atrial fibrillation is a much more common, and much less severe
heart arrhythmia, than ventricular fibrillation, which is what
Lewis had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ventricular fibrillation is an arrhythmia that can be
life-threatening,'' said Scheller. ``Atrial fibrillation is a much
more common type of arrhythmia and related to conditioning and
metabolic changes in the body.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bird was diagnosed, Scheller put him on medication and told
him to moderate his alcohol intake as well as be more vigilant
about his diet and his exercise. He also said there is an ongoing
concern about blood clots, but the medication is designed to deal
with that.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Bird, the conditioned worsened when he was
named coach of the Pacers in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little scared because it didn't seem like it was going
away,'' Bird wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said Bird told him about the heart situation during the
interview process. Walsh said he was ``nervous at first'' because
doctors found it difficult to determine exactly what dosage of
medication Bird needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once they found that, it was fine,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said he was not aware of an episode Bird described in the
book about nearly fainting during a March 17, 1998, game against
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Bird wrote, ``I was standing on the sideline and hoping for a
television timeout because I felt like I was gonna pass out.
Finally, the ref whistled time. Whenever we have a timeout, they
always put a chair on the court for me so I can sit down and talk
to the guys. This time I fell into that chair because I was going
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said he has consulted with Bird and the Pacers' medical
staff and is convinced that Bird's condition is not serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't become concerned until he or the doctors become
concerned,'' Walsh said. ``And the doctors all tell me that if he
takes his medication, he'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Bird wrote that, at one point, Pacers cardiologist King Yee used
defibrillator paddles to jolt his heart back to a normal rhythm.
Yee told Bird to be more serious about his condition and
medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Dr. Yee was trying to scare me,'' Bird wrote. ``I'm
not going to be stupid about this heart condition, but I'm not
going to live my whole life in fear of this thing, either. If it
goes, it goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
