<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-SUN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Sun Offers Free Office Software 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Stein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a strike against Microsoft's stranglehold on desktop computer
software, Sun Microsystems Inc. yesterday confirmed plans to offer
word processing and spreadsheet software applications for free over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, the Palo Alto firm which makes computer workstations,
network servers and software, said yesterday it had purchased Star
Division Corp., a small Fremont company that produces office
productivity software that can be accessed over the Net with a
standard Web browser. Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's free office software applications, which also include
presentation software, e-mail and calendar programs, are remarkably
similar to the applications in Microsoft's best-selling Office
Suite, which costs $400 and has be to loaded onto a personal
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has been the undisputed leader in office software. Its
Office Suite has attracted about 100 million customers and accounts
for approximately 40 percent of the company's total revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers believe Sun may be making a tactical error by
going after Microsoft in the office software market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Sun will make an impact, because 75 percent of
office software is bought by corporations, not individuals,'' said
Laura Lederman, an analyst with William Blair &AMP; Co. ``Corporations
will stick to Windows-based products because they have made huge
investments in the stuff, and it works.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that technology managers are typically quite
conservative and may be reluctant to embrace the idea of
Internet-based productivity software because of the inherent
bandwidth and reliability issues. ``I don't know if Sun has enough
power on its own to change the office software market,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite clear evidence to the contrary, Sun officials insist
they are not targeting Microsoft. ``We're going after the future,
not (Microsoft),'' insists Brain Croll, a senior director of
product marketing for Sun. ``There is a massive trend toward
Internet applications, and the next logical step is to bring the
office environment into this domain.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, for its part, does not yet have a plan to offer its
software over the Internet. The Sun-Star Division model poses a
dilemma for the company, because if it starts offering its software
for free on the Web, it will lose an important revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   But if the concept of Web-based computing catches on, Microsoft
could be left in the cold and could lose valuable market share.
Microsoft could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Star Division was founded in Germany in 1985, but founder Marco
Boerries later moved the company headquarters to Fremont. It
employs 155 people, and all will be offered jobs with Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the majority of Star Division's workers will
remain in Germany. Meanwhile the 25-odd sales and marketing
employees in Fremont will be integrated into Sun's facilities in
Menlo Park, according to Croll.
</P>
<P>
   Boerries will join Sun as vice president and general manager of
Web-based appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Sun said yesterday that it is creating its own Internet portal
where users can go to access Star Division's office applications on
an as-needed basis. The so-called StarPortal will become
operational in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sun said users can download desktop versions of
StarOffice for free at www.sun.com/staroffice. The StarOffice
software runs on the Linux, Window, OS/2 and Solaris platforms.
</P>
<P>
   The market for Internet-based computing applications is gaining
steam. To date, high-end software for such tasks as manufacturing
and accounting _ as well as e-mail and calendaring applications _
have been offered over the Web in a hosted environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun-Star Division deal represents the first time that more
 &LR; basic applications like word processing and spreadsheets have
moved to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last holdout, it seems, has been office productivity
software,'' said Sun chief executive Scott McNealy in an open
letter posted on Sun's Web site. ``You might describe today's
announcement as one small step for office software, one giant leap
for the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun is hoping to gain broader acceptance of its Web-based
computing initiative by forging alliances with Internet service
providers and other Web-based companies. Sun is giving these
potential partners StarOffice for free so that they will
incorporate the software into their normal services.
</P>
<P>
   One such partner, Portera Systems Inc. in Campbell, said it will
combine StarOffice with its own line of software. ```We don't
expect our customers to move off of Microsoft Office,'' said
Portera chief executive Gary Steele. ``But if they need to use,
say, a spreadsheet tool, they can now do that within our software,
instead of having to switch out of our program, go into Microsoft
Excel and then transport the data back.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Sun is offering StarOffice for free, it expects to make
money. First, it plans to charge corporations and service providers
for installation, maintenance and technical support.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Web-based applications like StarOffice provide greater
impetus for companies to buy Sun's core server products, which are
needed to run the software.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
