<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIAN-CANADIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Optical Networks has gone the extra mile to import scarce 
 engineers to Silicon Valley 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Most Silicon Valley companies have a hard time attracting talent,
but Optical Networks of San Jose faced a special hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bay Area is loaded with electronics engineers, it
has relatively few fiber optics experts working on the next
generation of technology to increase the capacity and speed of
telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these so-called photonics experts happen to work for
companies like Nortel Networks in Canada, Lucent Technologies in
New Jersey and other companies along the East Coast and a few in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that in Silicon Valley, everything is built on
electronic integrated circuits, while most of the talent in moving
light down fiber is in Canada and the East,'' said Optical Networks
chief executive Hugh Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report, the American Electronics Association said
that while California had 784,000 high-tech jobs in 1997 (more than
Texas and New York combined), New York employed five times as many
workers as California in optics technology.
</P>
<P>
   Optical Networks is hiring both electronic and optical engineers
to create products that metropolitan phone networks can use to
bridge the gap between fast, high-capacity electronic data networks
operated by companies and long-distance telecommunications networks
based on fiber optics technology.
</P>
<P>
   The company did the usual things to attract outside talent. It
offered recruits big pay raises, signing bonuses, help with rent
and private school tuition and, of course, bountiful stock options.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Optical Networks sweetened the pot with perks that
would make recruits and their families not just willing to come,
but happy to stay. The company organizes regular whale-watching,
bocce ball and other outings, sponsors an amateur hockey team and
helps Canadian engineers deal with visa hassles. It even grants
time off for weddings in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 55 of the company's 130 employees are imported
engineers, including 35 from Canada. Over the next year, Optical
Networks plans to grow to 275 employees, including 70 additional
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The company knew that recruiting nonlocal engineers would be a
challenge. In Silicon Valley, the rule of thumb is that about 50
percent of the engineers offered new jobs accept them and within a
year or so half of this group quit to take yet another job.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the risks, Optical Networks felt it had no other option.
Unlike software companies that often can hire engineers at remote
locations and get work done by computer links, Optical Networks is
developing hardware and needs people on site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't build our products if we couldn't attract people
from outside the area,'' said Human Resources director Lisa
Blos-Johnson, who previously consulted with 20 startups.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who formerly was president of the 3DO video game
software company and headed desktop computer engineering at Apple
Computer, set his No.1 priority as ``recruiting optical talent''
when he became CEO 20 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   That has meant flying out to meet prospective employees and
their significant others as well as flying them in. Last January,
for example, Martin joined his head of human resources and
engineering and a previous Canadian hire on a poaching trip to
Canada to capitalize on Nortel Networks' recent acquisition of
Cambrian Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Martin figured that Cambrian engineers who had left Nortel to
create their own optical technology company might be unhappy about
returning to the corporate fold. At the same time, Nortel engineers
might be worried about having their own research projects canceled.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fruitful trip. Optical Networks interviewed 36
engineers, offered 10 of them jobs and hired all of them, five from
Cambrian and five from Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   The company's efforts to go the extra mile to land talent comes
at a time when business is booming. Telecommunications and
networking companies are rushing to buy new equipment to allow
faster, cheaper transmission of voice, data and video. They also
are gobbling up the companies that are developing innovative
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   No.1 phone equipment-maker Lucent Technologies has made several
acquisitions, including Nexabit Networks and Excel Switching Corp.
Main rival Nortel Networks has bought a bunch of companies, too,
including Santa Clara's Bay Networks.
</P>
<P>
   While Nortel opted to buy Bay to gain some of the electronics
expertise it was lacking, Optical Networks decided to import talent
rather than buy a distant company.
</P>
<P>
   Martin opposes having two research staffs, two cultures and two
locations. ``We have guys working 18 hours a day and don't want to
have them three time zones and 3,000 miles apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Optical Networks has raised $50 million in venture capital,
including $15 million in the next week from Kleiner Perkins
Caufield &AMP; Byers, Mohr Davidow and Fidelity Capital. U.S. and
European telecommunications companies will begin testing its
networking products next month.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston analyst James Parmelee calls Optical
Networks one of the ``most interesting acquisition candidates.''
But Martin said the company is not interested in selling out. The
company is expected to go public by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   When Canadians brought up the fact that they could buy a nice
house for $80,000, Martin's pat response was, ``Come to Silicon
Valley. Rent for a while and within two years, you can buy a house
anywhere you want.'' He also was quick to point out that the U.S.
dollar is 50 percent stronger than its Canadian counterpart and
that U.S. income taxes are lower than Canada's flat 50 percent
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of depending on executive recruiters to find talent, and
paying them about 35 percent of the first year's salary, Optical
Networks has relied on referrals to hire seven out of eight
employees. To do this, it offers rich rewards to employees who help
recruit talent.
</P>
<P>
   For simply submitting a referral for a current job opening,
employees can win prizes from concert tickets to digital cameras.
If a candidate is hired for a full-time position, the company pays
a $1,500 referral bonus and also hands out free trips to those who
make the most referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Martin figures Optical Networks has spent about $750,000 more in
hiring expenses than high-tech companies that hire mostly local
candidates. But he believes that it is well worth it. While the
overall acceptance rate for job offers in Silicon Valley is 50
percent or less, Optical Networks says it lands 85 percent of those
to whom it makes job offers and has lost only three employees to
other companies since Janaury 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jalal Habelrih, a transplanted engineer from Tellabs in Canada,
finds it costs as much for a one-bedroom apartment in San Jose as a
penthouse in Montreal. But the senior director of hardware said he
is happy with most everything but California cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mitalas, who calls himself ``a double relo'' because he
relocated from Ottawa to Nortel's facilities in North Carolina
before jumping to Optical Networks, also is gung ho about his new
job, even though he, his wife and three kids are renting a house
that is one-third smaller than his former house.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Canada, an engineer makes a modest income and works toward
retirement,'' said Mitalas, the senior director of software
development. ``But here, I can be in a startup, build something
huge and participate in the glory and goodness.''
</P>
<P>
   Yves Lacroix, another Nortel veteran, also accepted the Optical
Networks challenge early this year after being wined and dined at
Montreal's swank Opus 2 restaurant and flown to the Bay Area for a
visit, including an all-expense-paid weekend with his fiancee,
Nathalie.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix received a TN (transnational) visa, which under the
North American Free Trade Agreement allows certain professionals
from Canada and Mexico to work in this country.
</P>
<P>
   But Nathalie encountered problems with U.S. immigration
officials after repeated visits from Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   After missing one flight because of lengthy grilling over
whether she really was just a tourist, Nathalie and Yves decided to
speed up their wedding plans. Optical Networks provided legal
counseling on visa issues, and at the end of April, the two took
off for a weekend wedding at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Nathalie was a computer project manager for L'Oreal in Canada
but does not have a work permit in the United States. Nevertheless,
she said she currently is content studying English, enjoying the
Bay Area and Optical Networks outings, and occasionally Web surfing
at the company's offices on weekends when Yves is working.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yves Lacroix is paying three times the rent he paid in
Canada, he pays lower taxes, got a good raise and received a bunch
of stock options. ``I call it `the beautiful risk,''' he said.
``The worst case is, I'm a California guy for a year or two.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
