<SLUG> BC-BKN-BIRD-CONDITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD'S HEART AILMENT COMMON, NOT AS DEADLY AS LEWIS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEAH R. GARNETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Atrial fibrillation, the heart condition Larry Bird
says he has, is a far more common and far less serious type of
irregular heartbeat than the one that killed Reggie Lewis, but it
is not a benign condition.
</P>
<P>
   It was once considered a relatively harmless cardiac arrhythmia,
but doctors now know that people with atrial fibrillation have a
fivefold greater risk of stroke than others.
</P>
<P>
   The condition affects about 2 million Americans, but, unlike
Bird, most people don't develop it until they are 50 or older.
</P>
<P>
   When the heart is functioning properly, its four chambers beat
in a well-orchestrated way. A chamber contracts, or beats, when
triggered by an electrical impulse. In atrial fibrillation, the
heart's electrical impulses get out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   This causes the atria (the upper two chambers) to quiver
erratically instead of beating forcefully at a regular rate. As a
result, blood isn't pumped completely out of the atria, and it can
pool and clot. If a piece of a clot breaks off and travels to an
artery that feeds the brain, the blockage of blood flow likely will
cause a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The most common triggers of atrial fibrillation are high blood
pressure, congestive heart failure, and prior heart attack. Other
causes include valvular heart disease, an overactive thyroid,
infections, and excessive alcohol consumption. Sometimes doctors
can find no apparent cause.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, a person experiences heart palpitations, chest
discomfort, shortness of breath, exercise intolerance, fatigue, or
lightheadedness.
</P>
<P>
   Although the condition is usually chronic, in some it occurs
only occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs such as warfarin and aspirin, which prevent blood clots
and thus stroke, are generally prescribed for people with atrial
fibrillation, as are medications to slow the heart rate.
</P>
<P>
   Most people live completely normal lives with the condition. It
is not considered a major cause of sudden death, as is ventricular
fibrillation, which, in addition to causing Lewis's death, killed
two-time Olympic gold medalist Sergei Grinkov, a figure skater who
in 1995, at age 28, collapsed on the ice rink and died hours later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
