<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SAT-SCORES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE SAT SCORES RISE; GENDER GAP REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The sweat and angst of studying for the SATs appears
to be paying off for Massachusetts students: Their scores are
better this year than they have been in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Students' scores averaged six points higher overall this year
than last, according to data released Tuesday by the State
Department of Education, and scores have been steadily climbing
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And the news is even better in math, with students tying the
average score of their national classmates for the first time in 12
years. The state also is third in the nation in the percentage of
students taking the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   State officials point to the improvements as a sign that
students are better prepared, parents are more supportive, and
educators are pushing students to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that students, and their parents and teachers are
focused on achievement,'' said State Education Commissioner David
P. Driscoll. ``A six-point increase is statistically significant.
Whether this is a one-time gain or a more fundamental trend, we'll
have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The average scores for Massachusetts students jumped three
points in both the math and verbal categories _ from 508 in 1998 to
511 this year. Nationally, students averaged 505 in verbal and 511
in math.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the good news for Bay State students, a troubling gender
gap remains. Girls continue to lag behind boys on the entire exam
and, of the 59 Massachusetts students who scored a perfect 1,600 on
the SAT, only 14 were girls.
</P>
<P>
   Boys continue to out-perform girls on the math portion of the
exam by 43 points, a puzzling difference to educators who say girls
do better than boys in advanced placement math courses and get
better math grades than boys overall.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll called the gender gap ``problematic'' and said the
state will continue to track the data and insist that the number of
programs to attract women to math and science is increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to make extra efforts where we can,'' Driscoll
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists say the test is unfairly designed to favor a
male problem-solving process and has been for years. They say
colleges should place more emphasis on a student's educational
portfolio _ grade-point average, honors courses, extracurricular
activities, sports _ during the admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear there is a good deal of test bias going on with the
SAT,'' said Jeff Rubenstein, senior director of research and
development at the Princeton Review. ``Women take just as much or
more math than men and score just as high or higher on GPAs. So, in
every other way women do just as well as men except on the SATs
There is test bias that favors the way boys typically think.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Griffis, a program associate in gender bias at FairTest
in Cambridge, said her testing watchdog group is trying to get more
colleges to look beyond the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   She said although higher SAT scores may indicate an improved
educational system, it may also prove that more students are taking
SAT preparation courses.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, 78 percent of high school students took the
SAT, nearly double the national rate, placing it third in the
nation behind Connecticut and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to know more specifically who is taking the SAT,
because the scores go up and down depending upon how well coached
students are,'' she said. ``We don't believe the blanket statement
that because students are performing better that the test is fair.
It could mean more students who took it could afford to take
preparation courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Kaplan Education Centers, a national chain of
SAT-preparation stores, said business has increased by 130 percent
in Massachusetts in the last decade and that business is up
nationwide by 30 percent in the past year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts, in particular, it seems that more and more
parents and students are becoming aware of the benefits of
prepping,'' said Trent Anderson, executive director for pre-college
programs at Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of advanced placement courses have also not been
lost on Bay State students. The Department of Education reported
Tuesday that advanced placement test scores for Massachusetts
students also are outpacing the national average. Those grades are
reported at five levels, with Level 5 being the highest.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, 71 percent of graduates scored in the top
three levels, nearly eight points higher than the national average
of 63.5 percent. And, 19.6 percent of Massachusetts students had
scores in the highest Level 5, compared to 13.9 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 90 percent of all state public schools had students who
took the 1999 AP tests compared to 60 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping this is an indication of the result of the
seriousness of purpose we're seeing across the state from parents,
teachers, and administrators that public education is their number
one issue,'' Driscoll said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
