<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINFUL TIME FOR SAMPRAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Was it a totally meaningless shot heard by nobody
that is echoing around the world?
</P>
<P>
   Did the wound caused by that scrimmage shot scramble tennis
history yet to be written, and jam the guy who intended to write
it?
</P>
<P>
   The guy's morose face told Tuesday's story at the US Open, and
described the alteration of days to come in the sport he has held
in his right hand for practically a decade. Pete Sampras wouldn't
have had to open his mouth to his inquisitors. The fact of his
disabling back wound still would have been apparent.
</P>
<P>
   It was the face of a guy hemorrhaging all over the place _
emotionally, physically, professionally, financially. No blood
evident. No, but the pain was across his drooping countenance, and
in his wavering, even teary, voice. Sampras was not going to race
victoriously across Flushing Meadow for a fifth time. He was not
going to set the record for major championships, not in this
century, anyway. And maybe never.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras loses this championship on a technical knockout _
herniated disc _ even before he goes into the rectangle. That never
has happened to a No. 1 before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought of even picking up a racket . . .,'' he said, his
voice trailing off.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the money part, though. Sampras won't even notice the
$750,000 he could have won, or the resulting endorsements. No pain
there.
</P>
<P>
   Good health billionaires can't buy, and that suddenly vanished
Sunday afternoon in one flick of a racket, the shock of how quickly
everything changed for him that contorted his handsome face. The
pain is bodily actual _ ``everything I do, even ordinary stuff, and
any bending, is limited and hurts'' _ and brain-straining, too.
``I'm bummed,'' he said. ``It couldn't have come at a worse time,
the way I've been playing.''
</P>
<P>
   He has won 24 of 25 starts, including a sixth Wimbledon title.
</P>
<P>
   A three-day beard told you both sides. Even the simple movements
of shaving hurt.
</P>
<P>
   It all started during a routine practice session at the Meadow
with Gustavo Kuerten, the Brazilian winner of the French Open a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was good and warm, we'd hit for a half-hour,'' said Sampras.
``No problem there. We started playing points.''
</P>
<P>
   And along came the shot that immediately wrecked the Open for
him and kept 62-year-old Roy Emerson's men's record of 12 major
singles titles from being eclipsed in its 33d year. It may also
prevent Sampras from extending his own pro record to a seventh
successive year of camping on the pinnacle of No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a return of serve, a backhand,'' he said. ``I hit the
ball and I felt something go. The pain _ it was like being stabbed
by a knife. I was scared. I walked off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had back spasms that night. I was very sore. But I've had
some back problems before. Spasms. I played through them. I wasn't
too worried. The doctor thought I'd be fine after a couple of days'
rest, ready to go Wednesday. So did I.''
</P>
<P>
   But when there was no improvement, Dr. Brian Hainline wisely
prescribed an MRI and a CAT scan, discovering the slight rip in the
disk.
</P>
<P>
   When a spine carrying a great athlete is stricken, a disk
herniates, a career can hang like a curveball: vulnerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caught it early,'' said Hainline. ``Pete'll be back after
rest and work with a spinal therapist, in one or two months.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the career of a Sampras predecessor on the Flushing
throne, Ivan Lendl, champ in 1985-86-87, was ended by a similar
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fluke,'' said Sampras. ``I've had injuries, but
nothing like this. I'm not unlucky. There's a reason for it, a
reason for everything, and I'll figure it out in a while. I'll be
back. There's plenty of tennis left in me.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a guy who has enjoyed such good fortune at the Meadow _
titles in 1990, '93, '95-96 _ he also has been very unlucky. Never
has a brilliant champion been so brittle. This was his fifth
accident at the Meadow, mishaps that have cost him possibly four
more titles.
</P>
<P>
   Dehydrated by his 1992 semifinal win over Jim Courier, he was
IV'd but didn't have enough juice left for the final, a four-set
loss to Stefan Edberg. Bursting blisters made his feet a bloody
mess in a fourth-round loss to Jaime Yzaga in 1994, yet Sampras
battled gamely for five sets. His famous upchucking quarterfinal
against Alex Corretja in 1996 didn't get him chucked, though, and
he hung on through illness and a match point to proceed to the
title. But a strained thigh last year may have cost him the
five-set loss to champ Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is a fragile champ, but an overcoming one even though he
probably doesn't train as hard as he should. Touched by a genetic
dysfunction, thalassemia, causing anemia, he tires quickly and
fears overextending himself. This may account for his refusal to
play singles in the Davis Cup loss to Australia in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his grittiness is unquestionable and the record shows him
rising through fatigue and injury to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Prime guys, No. 1's, have lost early at other Opens. Stefan
Edberg fell to Russian Aleksandr Volkov in the first round of 1990,
and John Newcombe was beaten at the outset by Jan Kodes in 1971.
But Sampras, a first in so many departments, is the first to fall
before the national anthem. His inability to enter the starting
gate opens the tournament spectacularly, particularly for Andre
Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   After numerous grimaces, Sampras drew the only laugh of a dour
press conference, reporting that Agassi had phoned in his sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a classy act,'' Sampras said, smiling for the only
time. ``And he didn't call to tell me about his first-round win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
