<SLUG> BC-MA-AUTO-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTHARDT DECISION COULD BOOST AUTO INSURANCE PREMIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts auto insurers say a decision last week
by Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt on workers' compensation
shows she made a mistake in computing this year's auto rates that
could pave the way for a hefty increase in auto premiums next year.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance officials and consumer advocates say Ruthardt's
workers' compensation decision took a pro-industry position on
company profits that is sharply at odds with the profit section of
this year's auto rate case.
</P>
<P>
   If Ruthardt sets auto rates for next year using the same profits
methodology she employed in the workers' compensation case,
officials say consumers will have to pay an extra $150 million in
overall premiums. If she takes a different approach, she opens the
door for an industry appeal on the grounds of inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess,'' said Stephen J. D'Amato, a lawyer and consumer
advocate on insurance issues. ``The commissioner is in a bind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt was not available for an interview, but in response to
inquiries from the Globe she left a brief telephone message
indicating she believed the auto and workers' compensation cases
were unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both cases were looked at individually based on the evidence
presented,'' she said. ``They offer very different lines of
insurance. They have in fact different regulations governing how
the hearings are held.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ruthardt in the workers' compensation case, which
resulted in a 20.3 percent reduction in rates (partly because of
reduced claims and less lost work time), rejected arguments put
forth by the State Rating Bureau that she was bound by her earlier
decision on auto insurance profits.
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials say the two conflicting rulings place
Ruthardt in an awkward position. Daniel Johnston, president of the
Automobile Insurers Bureau of Massachusetts, said the workers'
compensation ruling shows Ruthardt made a mistake with last year's
auto rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's any difference between the two lines of
insurance,'' he said. ``The philosophies are the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said the industry, which is seeking a 7.8 percent
increase in auto insurance rates next year, would probably appeal
any Ruthardt ruling on profits that is not consistent with her
latest ruling on workers' compensation.
</P>
<P>
   According to insurance industry officials, state regulators in
the past have always taken the same approach in calculating profits
for workers' compensation and auto insurance. That approach held
that investing in the insurance business is risky and investors
need to be properly rewarded for bearing that risk.
</P>
<P>
   But in her auto rate decision last year, Ruthardt accepted the
argument put forth by the State Rating Bureau that investors in the
insurance industry are willing to accept lower returns because
those investments tend to act as a hedge against stock market
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said Ruthardt's ruling effectively meant that insurance
industry investors were entitled to a lower return than if they
invested in US Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
   In the workers' compensation case, the insurance industry argued
that the approach put forth in the auto insurance case lacked
credibility. Ruthardt's ruling effectively endorsed that argument,
although she insists the two cases are unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said the contradictory rulings create the potential for
confusion with this year's auto rate hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she rules against the insurers, they can be expected to
claim that the result is inconsistent with the recent workers'
compensation decision,'' he said. ``If she rules in favor of the
insurers, the attorney general can rightfully claim that the result
is inconsistent with the last auto decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, there would be uncertainty and confusion,'' he
said. ``An appeal wouldn't be decided until the middle of 2000 at
the earliest. And insurers would have to make blind decisions about
safe driver and group discounts long before then.''
</P>
<P>
   One way out of the mess would be for the industry, the State
Rating Bureau and the attorney general's office, the three parties
involved in the rate-setting process, to come to an agreement on
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the attorney general's office declined comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2203EDT &QL; 
