<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-INTERNET-FUTURE-BOS &LR;      08-31 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURDLE TO NET GROWTH SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Poll some of the Internet's top technical gurus and
each might name a different issue as the chief impediment to the
growth of the on-line medium.
</P>
<P>
   But when just such a group was assembled at Harvard University
Tuesday, there did seem to be a near-consensus that one of the
biggest problems isn't technical so much as social: the large
number of people who presently lack the skills to make full use of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be a big bottleneck, more than any technology,'' said
Leonard Kleinrock, a professor at the University of California at
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Just how to solve the problem was a matter of some dispute _ and
the point of the panel discussion held in Sanders Theatre, part of
a conference sponsored by the Association for Computing Machinery.
</P>
<P>
   The technical organization, based in New York, held a special
meeting to review the technical history and outlook of the Internet
and drew some of the chief academic and industry figures whose work
in the 1960s through the 1980s laid the foundations of the
international computer network.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasting the outlook for the new medium would seem a
formidable task, in an era when many advances are made by obscure
Internet start-ups rather than in famous university labs.
</P>
<P>
   But conference organizer Lyman Chapin, chief technology officer
of GTE Internetworking in Cambridge, said young entrepreneurs might
gain some insight into the process through which the Internet has
evolved _ a goal that seemed to be borne out by the several hundred
twenty and thirtysomethings who turned out to hear the public
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to think of the people who invented the Internet as
a bunch of graybeards,'' Chapin said. ``But I think there's a lot
of room to combine their energy and ideas with what's happening
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's discussion touched on many technical issues, such as
how to improve current Internet codes to express Asian language
characters, or the most economic ways to connect masses of
individual homes to high-speed data networks.
</P>
<P>
   Some fundamental themes came up as well, chiefly just how much
knowledge designers of new networks and Web sites should assume
among the general population.
</P>
<P>
   Not much, implied Kleinrock, the UCLA professor, best known for
developing ways to move data quickly over high-speed digital
networks. He argued the increasing complexity of software has
already begun to discourage many potential new users. They suffer
from what he called ``feature shock,'' or a disinclination to
relearn fancy new software programs every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of just how much ability humans have to learn
a new technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Kahn, who began a key networking program as a
Pentagon official in 1973, suggested the opposite: that more people
might be trained with programming skills of their own. Such steps,
said former IBM researcher Paul Green, would help bring populations
on line in poorer areas and in the developing countries. The issue
is not more to distribute more expensive hardware, he said, but
rather how much it costs general users to ``get friendly'' with
software and technology in general.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ultimate academic answer came from Dave Clark, a
senior researcher at MIT, who called for more research into exactly
what Internet users want. ``We techies tend to be presumptuous,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of Tuesday's conference featured war stories from
the senior scientists, told in what the conference program
described as ``a collective oral history format.''
</P>
<P>
   One popular speaker was David Walden, a retired engineer who
once helped Cambridge-based BBN Corp. build computers used to send
the first digital messages over a West Coast data network 30 years
ago next month.
</P>
<P>
   The devices were built to the specifications of the University
of California researchers who conducted tests of the system, Walden
recalled. But at the same time, the machines were configured to
specifications set by the US military agencies who paid for the
early research _ and who were wary of curious academics who might
make changes without permission, what would later be known as
``hacking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked very hard at trying to have this thing run in what
they consdered the hostile university environment,'' Walden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DETROIT-TEACHERS-NYT &LR;      08-31 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY PARENTS IN DETROIT SUPPORT STRIKING TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ There is nothing like a last-minute teachers strike to
throw parenthood into chaos, but in this heavily unionized city,
many parents lined up Tuesday to support the strike that left them
unexpectedly spending the day with their children.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was supposed to be the first day of school, but instead,
it became the first day of a nasty labor standoff between the
teachers union and the school board appointed this year to fix
Detroit's ailing school system. Across the city, teachers headed to
school as planned. But they picketed outside rather than set foot
in their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents applauded them. ``If they get more money, it is all
right with me,'' said Warren D. Wright, 47, a Detroit resident with
three children in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Because Wright was not scheduled to head for his union job at a
nearby Chrysler factory until late afternoon, he spent the morning
watching as his children took turns buzzing around a vacant lot in
a go-cart and talked about why he supports teachers fighting for a
raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to watch all these crazy kids,'' Wright said. ``I
think they deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, against union leaders' recommendations, members of
the Detroit Federation of Teachers rejected a 10-day contract
extension that would have allowed negotiations to continue after
Detroit's 178,000 students returned to school. Teachers want
smaller classes, the relaxation of a rigid attendance policy and
raises of 2 percent to 10 percent that would bring Detroit
teachers' pay up to the median for those in the three-county area.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit School Board had offered raises amounting to 95
percent of what the union asked for, which would translate to
salaries of $35,600 to $64,000 a year depending on seniority for
teachers with master's degrees. The board announced Tuesday that
classes would be canceled on Wednesday because most teachers went
on strike.
</P>
<P>
   With classes canceled, Elouise King spent the day watching four
nieces and nephews, along with a neighbor's child. Nonetheless, Ms.
King said, ``I think the teachers deserve more money, and they
shouldn't work without a contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who had to go to work scrambled for a place to leave
their children. About 25 children spent Tuesday at Camp Detroit, a
summer cultural arts camp that was scheduled to close last week,
but was kept open because of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those children otherwise would be stuck in front of TV's or
cared for by siblings who aren't really old enough,'' said Njia
Kai, 44, the camp's director.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan A. Blakey, a high school gym teacher who worries about
safety when he takes the 62 students in his class swimming, said
that Detroit teachers are dedicated and care deeply about their
students, but that they are frustrated that the school board has
not agreed to class size reductions and raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not appreciated and we're not given the material to
enhance the students' learning ability,'' Blakey said as he
picketed in front of Osborn High.
</P>
<P>
   Passing drivers honked in support of the pickets, as is the
custom here when striking auto workers picket in front of factory
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 7,000 teachers, so they're not going to replace
everybody,'' said Blakey, 37. ``It's not like people are jumping
for the jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In this long-troubled school district, where half of all
students do not graduate from high school, nearly a page of the
union contract covers how teachers can be sure to get paid if they
must miss work because a student has assaulted them. Such
provisions are not seen as necessary in most suburban districts,
where teachers are paid more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do their job; can they do ours?'' asked Michael
Casteel, 48, the union's representative at Osborn High, where there
are about 2,300 students and 120 teachers, whose pay ranges from
$32,000 to $59,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Casteel described the special challenges he and other teachers
faced _ beyond the regular annoyance of having roughly one car a
month stolen or vandalized in the teachers' parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get kids that come to us that don't read, that can't do
basic math,'' Casteel said, and there are some students ``that are
out of class because of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers said the strike was the fault of the Detroit School
Board that was appointed in March after the Republican-controlled
state Legislature voted to transfer control from an elected school
board to the mayor and governor. The union had supported the
change. But many strikers accused Republican Gov. John Engler and
the school board's interim leader of trying to bust the union, and
others said the new school board has shown little support for those
on the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are imposing a lot of things on the teacher, but so far
they haven't made any new demands on the administrators or on the
students' parents to get the kids to school,'' said Bernard A.
Sutter, 40, a ninth-grade science teacher at Osborn who last year
won the Detroit-area educator of the year award from the state
science teachers' organization.
</P>
<P>
   The science lab is so poorly equipped that he uses makeshift
equipment. ``The most sophisticated things I used last year were
stopwatches,'' Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   The school board leader, David Adamany, said emotions are
running high here in part because of Detroit's history as a union
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we have a school district in educational distress,
change is going to be necessary,'' Adamany said. ``I would hope
that the teachers would join in for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question for every big city in the industrial states of
the Northeast is the same: Does being a union town mean you can't
have a quality public school system?'' he said in an interview
Tuesday. ``The answer to that question must be no or the children
in the industrialized, union cities are lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers said they were no more eager for a strike than Adamany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a horrible thing to be on strike _ we all have
mortgages, we all have kids to support,'' said Kathleen A.
McComsey, 49, a fifth-grade language and math teacher at Fleming
Elementary. ``But this is a union town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
