<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SAT-SCORES-ART-NYT &LR;      08-31 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAT-SCORES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE BOARD SCORES VARY LITTLE FROM PREVIOUS YEAR'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Puerto Rico)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scores on the College Board exams remained roughly constant last
year compared with the previous year, as boys continued to outscore
girls by more than 40 points and white students continued to do
better than underrepresented minorities, according to figures
released Tuesday by the College Board.
</P>
<P>
   Scores for graduating seniors remained relatively flat despite
the larger number of students taking advanced placement courses,
which cover college-level material. The number of students taking
those courses jumped 11 percent, to 704,298, including 349,300
graduating seniors. The number taking the the tests themselves rose
to a record 2 million, including 1.2 million graduating seniors, 4
percent more than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Boys who graduated from high school this year received an
average of 509 on the verbal exam and 531 on the math, the same as
in 1998. Girls who graduated this year scored an average of 502 on
the verbal and 495 on the math test. Their verbal score was the
same as a year earlier, but their math score fell a point. (Scores
on each test range from 200 to 800.)
</P>
<P>
   The one-point decline in the girls' math score widened the
difference between girls and boys to 43 points. That is the highest
since 1993, when the difference was 47 points.
</P>
<P>
   College Board officials say that a major reason that boys
continue to outscore girls in math is that boys still take more
math courses. Also, a higher proportion of girls take the College
Board exams than boys, so they represent a broader group of
students with wider-ranging abilities, which tends to pull down
average scores.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board's new president, Gaston Caperton, the former
governor of West Virginia, played down the gender gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differential is so small, and the number of women at
selective colleges is more than the number of men, so I don't think
it has had much of an effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Monty Neill, executive director of Fairtest, an advocacy
group based in Cambridge, Mass., said the gap is ``clearly
significant because college admissions are in part decided on these
tests and a lot of special programs and scholarships are largely
awarded based on test scores.'' ``Our view is that the test itself
is biased,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   White students also continued to do better than most
underrepresented minorities. White students showed a one-point gain
on the verbal test and no gains on the math test over last year's
results. Scores for black students remained the same on the verbal
test and fell four points in math. Overall scores for Hispanic
students were also lower, except for Puerto Rican students, whose
scores were up three points in verbal and one point in math.
</P>
<P>
   The Educational Testing Service, the company that administers
the College Board tests, is in the early stages of developing a
formula to help colleges adjust scores for members of minorities
and other students who have fewer educational advantages, providing
a kind of handicapping system.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts, College Board officials said Tuesday, did not
suggest that the current scores were less valid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at SAT scores in a broader context is something
admissions people have done for years,'' said Gretchen Rigol, vice
president for special projects at the College Board. ``Though there
are lots of people interested in this research, it is far from
being operational.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, which reported on the ETS project
Tuesday, said the proposed formula would try to identify
``strivers'' whose scores were significantly above what they might
be expected to score given their education and socioeconomic
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington Tuesday, Caperton
acknowledged that some students have more advantages than others,
which is likely to be reflected in their test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SAT's are a measure of a student's readiness for college
and describes what currently exists,'' he said. ``What currently
exists is a system where people of different races and backgrounds
are not getting the same opportunities, and that is reflected in
the SAT scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Caperton said the College Board had no plans to change the exams
in the way it changed the preliminary College Board tests, which
are used in determining candidates for National Merit Scholarships,
in 1997. At that time, under pressure from the U.S. Department of
Education's Office of Civil Rights, the board added a third section
_ a writing test _ to the math and verbal tests that made up the
exam. The change has resulted in girls winning a larger proportion
of merit scholarships than they had previously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
