<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FANS WILL MISS PETE SOON ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fans scurry around the premises, looking for
upsets, looking for interesting new players, chasing down phenomena
like Alexandra Stevenson suffering a sundown massacre. They can
convince themselves that Master Pete is still in there, whacking
down somebody in three sets, in front of a few thousand die-hards
in Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For now, they can overlook that a bad disk in Pete Sampras' back
forced him to withdraw from this year's U.S. Open, giving Good Old
Emmo, Roy Emerson, at least a few more months with a half share of
the record of 12 Grand Slam championships.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Pete was only a flurry of bad news in the air. Getting
the most from their day-session tickets, the spectators stayed out
in the bright sun and refreshing breeze from 11 a.m. to the dinner
hour. There was always a brisk trade at Louis Armstrong Stadium,
named for the great jazz trumpeter and gravel-voiced singer who
lived in nearby Corona for decades. Once the concert hall of the
World's Fair of 1964-65, it was later converted expediently but
clumsily into the main court of the new National Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong Stadium is where Bjorn Borg played his last match,
where Steffi Graf won her Grand Slam, where Pete Sampras retched
and John McEnroe kvetched and Jimbo Connors mugged opponents and
officials with equal-opportunity gall.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Arthur Ashe Stadium towering just to the west _ too big
to generate any warmth _ Armstrong Stadium has been scaled back to
a human dimension of 10,000 seats, the bulk of them first-come,
first-served. People go there because they want to go there.
</P>
<P>
   Given the country-club roots that tennis is still trying to get
past, it is more than a little cool that the two main stadiums at
the United States Open are named for African-Americans. Now why not
go for the trifecta and name the charming little grandstand, still
attached to the Armstrong, after Althea Gibson, the first great
black female player?
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the fans flocked to Armstrong Stadium for an upset loss
by Tim Henman to Guillermo Canas, stayed for Jennifer Capriati's
big victory over Iva Majoli, enjoyed a romp by Gustavo Kuerten over
Bohdan Ulihrach, then cheered Monica Seles' defeat of Barbara
Rittner in the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the sunset smiling obliquely, a few thousand
hard-core fans postponed dinner for the fifth match. The show-court
placement could have been represented as a tribute to Nathalie
Tauziat of France, the 11th-seeded player, but nobody was kidding
anybody. Since Alexandra Stevenson burst into the public domain at
Wimbledon this summer, Open fans have been waiting for a glimpse of
her.
</P>
<P>
   At Wimbledon, while she was blasting her way into the
semifinals, Stevenson became famous through the revelation that her
father is the American basketball star, Julius Erving. Stevenson is
now being inspected for the looks and athletic ability of her
father, while her mother, Samantha Stevenson, who has written for
The New York Times, has been analyzed extensively without receiving
nearly enough attention for rearing an accomplished young woman.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball icon, who has been married since 1972, has been
criticized for denying, at first, his relationship to the young
tennis player; it is just possible that Erving's short public
stonewall was his way to maintain his silent commitment to
providing support for the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to be a public figure. It is not easy for a
tennis player to have so much height to control. It is not easy to
be 18. The fans who stayed at Armstrong Stadium did not see the
same cannonball serve that glanced capriciously off the pressed
lawns of Wimbledon. Tauziat sliced and diced on Stevenson,
returning her best forehands to the huge gap near Stevenson's
sluggish feet.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the fans suddenly remembered they had been outdoors for
seven-plus hours. As famously polite as New Yorkers are, a few of
them even bolted without benefit of change-overs, while Tauziat was
dispatching Stevenson, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost to a tough player,'' Stevenson said, adding: ``Grass is
definitely a different game. My game is great on grass and it will
be great on hardcourt.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the fans had come to peer, but they would have also
liked to cheer. One day they will come to watch Alexandra Stevenson
for her forehand. The sooner the better. The Open goes on. Sometime
around Labor Day, the fans will swarm into Ashe Stadium and realize
it's true: Pete is not there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
