<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALPERS PLANS TO INVEST MORE AGGRESSIVELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The California Public Employees' Retirement System said Tuesday
that it would invest as much as $11 billion in hedge funds and
other aggressive investments that have not been widely used by
public pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   Although hedge funds are popular with wealthy people and
endowments, only a handful of large state or other public funds
invest in them. Calpers, the nation's largest public pension
system, said it was doing so to increase returns.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds, with total assets under management estimated at as
much as $350 billion, are partnerships that, unlike mutual funds,
can borrow large sums of money, speculate in foreign currencies and
make big bets that stocks will decline.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Calpers, a $160-billion fund and pioneering
shareholder activist that is closely watched by other institutional
investors, could lead other public pension-fund managers to invest
greater amounts in hedge funds. The move also highlights how much
worries about hedge fund investing have eased in the year since the
near-collapse of Long-Term Capital Management L.P. Despite recent
poor returns from managers of some of the biggest hedge funds,
including George Soros and Julian H. Robertson Jr., many funds have
outperformed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-Stock index, which has
returned 8.33 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Calpers board voted on Aug. 16 to raise the ceiling for
hedge funds and other ``hybrid'' investments to 25 percent of the
pension fund's $45-billion actively managed portfolio. The board
also approved the fund's first hedge fund investment, a commitment
of as much as $300 million to Pivotal Partners, a San Francisco
fund, managed by Pivotal Investment Management, that invests in
technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Calpers defines hybrid funds as including market-neutral funds,
arbitrage funds and ``corporate governance'' funds that seek to
improve returns by influencing company managements. So far, it has
only $900 million invested in hybrid funds _ all in three corporate
governance funds. Calpers also has $7.5 billion invested in or
committed to alternative investments, including venture capital and
private equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   The pension fund cautioned that it was unlikely to invest
anything close to the full $11 billion anytime soon. ``Clearly,
that's just a ceiling for us,'' said Brad Pacheco, a Calpers
spokesman. ``We're slowly venturing into this.'' The fund will not
invest in highly leveraged funds or ``macro'' funds that make big
bets on currencies or global trends, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco said that Calpers' outlook for stocks and the market's
high current valuations were ``not even a factor'' in the decision.
The pension fund's officials were simply looking to increase
returns, he said. Calpers returned 12.5 percent in the year ended
in June and 16.8 percent annualized for the five years ended in
June, far below returns for the S.&AMP; P. 500 of 22.8 percent and 27.8
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   And while many hedge funds charge fees of 1 percent to 2 percent
of assets annually, and 20 percent of profits, Pacheco said Calpers
would seek to negotiate lower fees.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last year by Greenwich Associates found that only 2
percent of public funds used hedge funds, compared with one-third
of endowments and 15 percent of big corporate pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly larger investments in hedge funds by public funds
could be detrimental to other hedge fund investors, said Jim
Hedges, managing director of LJH Global Investments, a hedge fund
consultant in Naples, Fla. ``It means,'' Hedges said, that ``more
of the `A' players will have their coffers filled with capital,''
making the best managers less available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
