<HEADER>
A6536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-KEYES-PROFILE-1STLD-W     08-31 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYES-PROFILE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNORING THE ODDS, KEYES INSISTS HIS IS THE VOICE OF MORAL
VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: S.C., Iowa, N.H., Texas, Md.)  (Eds: SUBS lede to change `primary' to presidential nomination.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ As he wanders the nation prophesying a
political apocalypse, Alan L. Keyes, the staunchly conservative
radio talk show host, is the invisible man in the race for the
Republican presidental nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He gets few cameras at his events. Political analysts tend to
forget him in their prognostications. Polls show him receiving one
percent of the vote or less. And when the Log Cabin Republicans, a
homosexual group, issued a news release last week attacking
religious conservatives for intolerance, Keyes didn't even merit a
mention.
</P>
<P>
   But to his small yet devoted cadre of followers, Keyes is the
best kept secret of the campaign. To them, Keyes, a former Reagan
administration diplomat with a Harvard Ph.D., has something his
fellow conservatives lack: mesmerizing oratorical skills twinned
with a messianic vision.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the heart of the Keyes for President campaign.
With little money, name recognition, organization or governing
experience, Keyes is running on his powerful voice, breathlessly
wooing far-right voters with Boschian word pictures of schools that
are ``places of death,'' taxpayers who are ``enchained slaves'' and
children who have fallen into a ``howling moral void.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he is given little chance of winning _ he finished
seventh of nine candidates in the Iowa straw poll _ winning is not
what he promises his followers. What he offers is the chance to
feel morally correct on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusion I've reached is that no one is doing what I
believe needs to be done,'' Keyes said in a recent interview,
speaking of the moral issues. ``If I were satisfied that anyone
else was addressing it, I would not run.''
</P>
<P>
   His campaign chairman in South Carolina, Hal W. Stevenson, said,
``If you only care about your chances of winning, you don't back a
guy like Alan. You back him because you like what you hear. You'll
feel better when the election is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes did win the Alabama Republican straw poll last Saturday,
but other than Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, who finished second, he
was the only candidate who competed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time when several Republican candidates, including
the front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, are trying to downplay
divisive issues like abortion and gay rights, Keyes provides an
eloquently uncomfortable reminder that, to some dedicated
conservatives, ideological purity matters more than victory in
November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a struggle going on in the party,'' said
Keyes, 49, who also ran for president in 1996. ``It's a struggle
between the Money-is-God Republicans and the God-is-God
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Keyes aims the sharpest barbs at Bush, whom he
considers a tepid-tongued pragmatist. In Greenville, he mocked
Bush's slogan of ``compassionate conservatism,'' saying, ``You
don't prove you are compassionate by talking about it.'' He accused
Bush of exploiting moral issues, ``without being seriously
committed to facing the moral challenges.'' And he ridiculed the
Texan for saying he would not demand that all his nominees to the
federal bench share his opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it true we need leaders who will be vague in their response
to the most compelling moral issues we face as a people?'' Keyes,
who is black, asked the virtually all-white crowd in Greenville.
``No!'' many of them responded.
</P>
<P>
   Though his campaign has received little media attention, Keyes
has consistently drawn hundreds of people to his ``Renewing
America'' speeches in South Carolina, Iowa and New Hampshire.
Marietta Kaiser, 72, of Greenville, walked out a convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a breath of fresh air,'' she said following Keyes'
appearance here two weeks ago. ``We've heard the cliches of the
other candidates, and they just don't move the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   But his against-all-odds campaign has drawn questions from some
rivals and analysts, who suggest that he is using the race to draw
attention to his speaking-for-hire business and to gain listeners
for his radio program, which until recently was syndicated to about
75 stations in more than 43 states.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, Keyes gave about 20 paid speeches a year,
typically to corporations or college groups, charging between
$12,000 and $15,000 for each, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But the aides scoffed at the assertion that he profits from
running for office. They said that he suspended the radio show
during the campaign and has scaled back his paid speaking
engagements to about 15 this year. They added that most of his
speeches are given free to benefit pregnancy counseling centers and
anti-abortion groups.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics have asked whether Keyes is living off his
campaign account, as he did during his losing 1992 U.S. Senate race
in Maryland when he paid himself more than $8,000 a month from
campaign donations. Though the practice was legal, it prompted
criticism even from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes says he is not drawing a salary from his campaign fund,
which had raised $1.9 million as of June 30 and had $172,497 on
hand. But he argues that the practice is legitimate and that his
critics are ``wealthy oligarchs.''
</P>
<P>
   In private, Keyes cuts a different figure from the acid-tongued
talk show performer who has amazed even the most combative hosts
with his ability to shout them down. With his goatee and newly trim
build _ he has lost 70 pounds in two years _ he can come across as
a genial academic. An opera buff, he confesses to relaxing with
westerns and action films or ``Star Trek'' re-runs.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, the youngest of five children, is the son of a career
Army officer who moved the family repeatedly through Italy and the
United States. Raised a Roman Catholic, Keyes attended parochial
schools for much of his youth, though he graduated from a public
high school in San Antonio, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, he was already demonstrating his powerful
speaking skills, winning the American Legion's national oratorical
competition and getting elected president of the Legion's Boys
Nation, the first black to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Though his parents were die-hard Democrats who admired John F.
Kennedy, Keyes became a Republican while attending Cornell
University in the late 1960s, where he viewed Vietnam War
protesters as repugnantly anti-American. He transferred to Harvard,
where he earned a doctorate in government.
</P>
<P>
   While serving as a State Department official in India during the
Reagan administration, he met Jeane J. Kirkpatrick, who later
called him ``one of the most dramatically articulate people'' she
had ever met. After she became chief delegate to the United
Nations, Ms. Kirkpatrick made Keyes the ambassador to the U.N.
Economic and Social Council. Reagan later appointed him assistant
secretary of state for international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In India, Keyes also met his wife, Jocelyn Marcel Keyes, who is
Indian. They have three children and live in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Keyes' speeches are aural spectacles, part revivalist sermons,
part Oprah. With a microphone on his lapel, he wanders through the
audience, talking _ sometimes in a whisper, sometimes in a shout _
for an hour or more without notes, weaving incandescent images of
an America going to Hell in a high-speed handbasket.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that a collective loss of faith in God's authority has
caused a panoply of social ills, from the breakdown of
``marriage-based families'' to the Columbine shootings to failing
schools to ``immoral'' military interventions abroad, including in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Without God in their lives or their politics, Americans are
allowing an increasingly authoritarian central government to tax
and regulate them into submission, he says. Likening Americans to a
frog that sits calmly in a pot while the water gets hotter, he
argues that Americans are passively watching their freedoms erode.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're past medium rare and headed toward well done,'' he said
in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, he prescribes some strong medicine. He would
eliminate the income tax and finance the government on tariffs,
duties and excise taxes. He would end welfare and outlaw abortion.
He has even endorsed the public paddling of parents who abandon
their children.
</P>
<P>
   But in private conversation, Keyes reveals more nuanced views.
And that makes for some interesting paradoxes.
</P>
<P>
   Though he ridicules targeted tax cuts as ``marionette strings,''
he also endorses federally subsidized mortgages for families and
tax breaks for banks that invest in poor neighborhoods. And while
he warns that ``perpetual war'' is a means by which totalitarian
governments control their citizens, he is not an isolationist,
having strongly supported America's involvement in Vietnam,
Cambodia, Grenada and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   There are interesting nuances in Keyes' views on race as well.
He is an ardent opponent of affirmative action and other race-based
social programs. But he also speaks passionately about the need to
address urban poverty through private investment, and has often
lambasted the Republican Party for not recruiting more blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans vacillate between trying to buy off black
voters with programs, trying to out-Democrat the Democrats, and
just writing them off,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Keyes says, his revulsion for slavery has intensified
his conservatism, not weakened it. As a teenager, he voraciously
read books about slavery, weeping while he wondered why more slaves
did not revolt. Lincoln became his hero. Even his stump-speech
language _ ``We need to strike off our chains,'' is a favorite
phrase _ is drawn from the peculiar institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered, why didn't people resist to the point of
fighting and dying?'' he said. ``Why would human beings let
themselves be oppressed, when they could have said, `give me
liberty or give me death,' and gone out in a blaze of resistance?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
