<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE RECENT OIL-REVENUE RISE, MEXICO WILL LIMIT SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Despite a jump in crude oil prices, the Mexican
government will reap enough of a windfall this year only to
stabilize its accounts, and it plans no spending sprees, Energy
Minister Luis Tellez said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The international oil market has taken Mexico on a dizzying ride
in 1999. In February, the price of Mexican crude oil for export _
which sells well below London and New York prices _ dropped to less
than $7 a barrel, the lowest real price ever. But by Aug. 19, more
than a year after Mexico joined forces with Venezuela and Saudi
Arabia to curb production, the country's crude oil reached a high
for the year of $19.24 a barrel, a 175 percent rebound.
</P>
<P>
   So far in 1999, Mexico has earned $1.3 billion more from
petroleum exports than budget planners anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in advance of President Ernesto Zedillo's state of the
union address on Wednesday, when he will tell Mexicans what he
intends to do in the coming year, Tellez said the government is
taking a sober view of the upturn in its oil fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of government income comes from levies on
petroleum sales. Increased oil revenue will allow Mexico to meet
its promises to hold the budget deficit to 1.25 percent of the
gross domestic product, but not to give more help to the nation's
poor.
</P>
<P>
   When oil prices were falling, Zedillo cut about $1 billion from
social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the oil boom will only plug holes left in this year's budget
by slow progress in the selling of Mexican airports to private
owners, finance officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico also continues to look warily at the world oil markets,
Tellez said, because much of the inventories that led to the price
collapse last year and early in 1999 still exist. Almost all the
world's producers have reduced their output, bringing about the
steepest and longest-running decline in world oil production ever
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   But even if producers maintain their discipline, the supplies
will come down slowly, Tellez said, dropping by the end of this
year only to the level of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In Caracas last weekend, Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico
agreed to maintain current production cuts until April.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way that Mexico is going to jump up and take any
decisions without the other countries,'' Tellez said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to fix the estimate of the average price of Mexican
crude oil for 2000 at $12 to $14 a barrel, a conservative figure
far below current levels. Mexico's estimate of the average annual
price of its petroleum exports is a cornerstone of the government's
budget projections. Finance officials revised the figure downward
twice when oil prices plunged, and it now stands at $9.25 a barrel.
Each dollar added to the price of a barrel of oil is worth about $1
billion to the Mexican Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders have accused Zedillo of concealing huge
unexpected oil earnings this year in the labyrinth of the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Garcia Sainz, the chairman of the budget committee in
the lower house of Congress, said the government was hoarding money
to spend it without congressional approval on an unpopular bank
bailout and on programs to benefit the ruling party in the coming
election year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
