<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL AND THE UMPIRES SAID TO BE CLOSE TO A DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Pa.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A long day in a judge's chambers in Philadelphia brought lawyers
for Major League Baseball and its umpires close to a deal Tuesday
on the status of umpires who face the loss of their jobs Wednesday,
a lawyer familiar with the general outline of the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers were in U.S. District Court for a hearing before
Judge J. Curtis Joyner on the umpires union request for an
injunction that would keep 22 umpires in their jobs beyond
Wednesday. However, Joyner summoned the lead lawyers for both sides
to his chambers, and they spent more than six hours negotiating a
possible settlement of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're done for the evening,'' Joyner said by telephone at 8:30
p.m., ``and there's no further comment with reference to what is
happening.'' He added that a hearing was set for 10:30 a.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the hearing on the umpires' request for an injunction
will take place only if the two sides cannot complete the deal they
worked on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer who said the two sides had moved close to a deal did
not attend the sessions in Joyner's chambers and didn't know the
substance of the talks. But the lawyer understood that they had a
general structure of an agreement, needed more time and discussion
to conclude it and had to have it approved by Commissioner Bud
Selig. ``They've talked, and they're close,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers who were involved in the talks declined to comment
on them.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Silverman, the New York regional director of the National
Labor Relations Board, said earlier in the day that he expected to
have a decision Wednesday on the unfair labor practice charges the
umpires union filed with the board Aug. 3. However, an agreement
between baseball and the union could alter that plan.
</P>
<P>
   The union could withdraw the charges, it could agree to let an
arbitrator decide the issues or it could agree to make them part of
the negotiations for a new agreement to replace the current labor
contract, which expires Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   No one was saying, but it was possible that at least one element
of the deal being negotiated under Joyner's watchful eyes involved
baseball's thought of expanding umpiring crews next season from
four umpires to five. Four umpires would continue to work games,
but the extra umpire would give each member of the crew every fifth
week off.
</P>
<P>
   To have five-man crews, baseball would have to hire about eight
more umpires, and they could come from the corps of 22 who are
scheduled to be out of work after Wednesday's games.
</P>
<P>
   Those 22 umpires, 13 from the National League staff and nine
from the American League staff, were among more than 50 umpires who
signed letters of resignation July 14. All of the umpires
ultimately rescinded their resignations, but those who acted later
than others found theirs being accepted by the leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those umpires were in Philadelphia on Tuesday to testify
at the scheduled hearing. Bob Davidson came from Houston, where he
was umpiring the series between the Astros and the Mets, presumably
his last. Rich Garcia flew in from Detroit, and Ed Hickox stopped
there en route to his assignment in Baltimore. Eric Gregg had been
scheduled to work the series in San Francisco but was in
Philadelphia instead.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of testifying, the umpires waited as the lawyers talked.
Susan Davis was the lead lawyer representing the union, and Howard
Ganz was the chief lawyer for Major League Baseball. He was joined
by Rob Manfred, baseball's executive vice president for labor
relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
