<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS EDUCATION DEPARTMENT SHOULDN'T BE ABOLISHED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
broke ranks with the Republican right Tuesday by saying he would
not dismantle the U.S. Department of Education if he is elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it should be abolished. It ought to be made more
effective,'' said Texas' governor, who has touted local control of
schools throughout his political career.
</P>
<P>
   All the GOP presidential candidates in 1996 promised to
dismantle the department if elected, and the issue remains dear to
the GOP's right wing. So far this year, only commentator Pat
Buchanan has embraced the issue. Many Republicans see the
department as symbolic of efforts to put the federal government in
control of education nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The education department ought to be a place for sound
science, sound thought, and ought to recognize that passing power
back to the states and local authorities is the best way to lead to
education reform,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his declaration of support for the federal agency as
he previewed elements of his education proposals that will be
included in a major policy speech scheduled for Thursday to the
Latin Business Association in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we ought to federalize education,'' Bush said.
``I trust local people to make the right decisions. But there is a
place for the federal government to make sure people don't get left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who toured the Our Lady of Guadalupe and St. Agnes Mission
School, said a president can set a tone for education standards so
that schools can be held accountable for their success and failure.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1994 campaign for governor, Bush said he wanted to
abolish the Texas Education Agency. He later modified that position
to abolishing only the regulatory functions of the agency after
learning a local agency is a required element of receiving federal
funds.
</P>
<P>
   But many social conservatives in Texas have criticized Bush for
not keeping his promise because he backed efforts in 1995 to
increase the power of the agency and the Texas education
commissioner, who is appointed by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Tuesday he has worked to increase local control in
Texas by creating charter schools and supporting a pilot private
school voucher program, even though the voucher program died in the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also plans to outline Thursday how he would
overhaul the Head Start preschool program to make it more academic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government spends a lot of money on Head Start.
Head Start does a good job of providing healthy meals. I believe it
ought to be an education program as well,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would like to see Head Start begin teaching
reading, particularly the phonics method. Bush said he wants to see
Head Start aggressively push a reading program included in a law
passed by Congress ``that fundamentally changed Head Start's focus
to become a platform for reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also toured the ConAgra Global Training Facility and later
held a rally in Council Bluffs &UR; ,  &LR; Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The governor declined to confirm a report in The Dallas Morning
News that his presidential campaign has now raised more than $50
million, but said he has raised ``a lot'' since reporting that his
campaign had hauled in $37 million by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are some who are talking about my capacity to
raise money, particularly my opponents. I suggest if you ask them,
they would like to trade places,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
