u f BC-INTEL-PROCESSORS-NYT &LR;      08-31 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-PROCESSORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL'S NEW PROCESSOR LINE TO FOCUS ON INTERNET LINKS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SARA ROBINSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Trying to expand its core personal computer
business into a new market, the Intel Corp. will announce a new
family of processors on Wednesday capable of powering the devices
that route data through corporate networks and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement follows an initial public demonstration Tuesday
of Intel's much-ballyhooed Merced chip, designed around a new
64-bit architecture, which Intel has been developing with the
Hewlett-Packard Co. and expects to begin shipping in volume in
mid-2000. All the activity was timed to coincide with the Intel
Developer Forum in Palm Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Both developments reflect Intel's increasing expansion of its
core business _ processors for personal computers and work stations
_ into three new areas, all connected to the Internet: network
processors; servers, computers that manage network resources, and
what Intel calls ``bit factories,'' networks of computers housed
and managed by Intel that power electronic-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are investing heavily in developing all of those efforts,''
said Pat Gelsinger, vice president and general manager for the
Intel Desktop Products Group.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to base its new line of network-oriented
processors on what it is calling the Intel Internet Exchange
Architecture, or IX, an open specification for the design of a
system of hardware components that can be linked together to
provide the framework for Internet devices.
</P>
<P>
   An open architecture allows the system to be connected easily to
devices and programs made by other manufacturers. The blueprint for
the design will be released to enable systems designers to build
products compatible with the Intel products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been the brains of the personal computer; now we want to
become the brains of the Internet,'' said Mark Christensen, vice
president and general manager of Intel's Network Communications
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The flagship component of the new Intel line is a network
processor that, rather than being built for a specific function, is
flexible and can be programmed to perform different tasks.
Christensen said the new processor would make possible a
fundamental shift in networking and communications system design,
an area that has typically relied on a development cycle of one to
two years for custom chips hard-wired for very specific tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The network processor is designed to allow greater flexibility
for manufacturers of devices _ routers, switches and access
concentrators _ that control the flow of information through the
Internet. Companies designing products that work on top of the
Intel framework could add features to networking products after
they have been deployed, Christensen said, thereby speeding the
development process and potentially extending product life.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it was now shipping samples and would be in
production in the fourth quarter, with the network-processor-based
systems costing significantly less than custom-built systems
typically used today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel is saying let's move away from a hardware-intensive
model and move toward something more software intensive,'' said
John Armstrong, an analyst at Dataquest, based in San Jose, Calif.
``The opportunities here are very big.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and officials of other companies said they expected IBM
to announce its own initiative in the network processor field this
week.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Intel will establish a $200 million fund that will
be used in part to invest in companies developing hardware and
software based on the IX architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that Intel said plan to endorse the Intel architecture
or announce specific products that incorporate elements of it are
Broadband Access Systems; Cabletron; CAG; Cisco, and Newbridge
Networks.
</P>
<P>
   One company already in the business of making building blocks
for network systems is the C-Port Corp., a start-up based in North
Andover, Mass. C-Port announced an open architecture for network
processors in February and followed last week with a programmable
chip that fits into their architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're changing the business from being hardware based to being
software and service based,'' said Larry Walker, the company's
chief executive. ``We invite Intel to work with us.'' He said
C-Port would soon announce a collaboration with IBM for a standard
for their architecture so that software compatible with IBM
hardware will also work with C-Port's hardware.
</P>
<P>
   At the Palm Springs conference Tuesday, Intel's president and
chief executive, Craig Barrett, demonstrated the Merced processor,
whose 64-bit chip architecture will process data in longer chunks
than the current standard 32 bits. The chip is intended both for
high-end work stations and for Internet server applications. Intel
said that it had begun shipping engineering samples of the Merced
to computer companies for testing and that it remains on track for
production in mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's stock closed down 6.25 cents Tuesday, at $82.1875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990831.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-YOUNG-WORKERS-NYT &LR;      08-31 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASKING ITS VIEWS, LABOR WOOS THE YOUNG  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the nation's labor unions struggle to reverse their decline,
they are focusing increasingly on an immense group that they have
long overlooked: young workers.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the labor movement took a new tack in seeking to court
that group, releasing a survey that it had commissioned on young
workers' attitudes toward their jobs, the economy and unions.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the survey of 752 workers from the ages of 18
to 34 showed that those workers were concerned about many of the
same issues unions have been emphasizing.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, conducted in June by Peter D. Hart Research
Associates, workers said their biggest worries were falling behind
the cost of living, lacking time for family responsibilities and
being unable to afford to educate their children.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that only 45 percent of young workers had
employer-sponsored health insurance, while just 43 percent had
pension plans to which their employers contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see today's jobs as failing to meet the most basic needs:
health care, retirement security and time to spend with family,''
said John J. Sweeney, president of the American Federation of Labor
and Congress of Industrial Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO said that in commissioning the study, it was showing
that it listens to young workers and can articulate their concerns
to employers and the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to grow, we obviously have to make young
workers aware that unions are an option for them,'' said Kirk
Adams, the AFL-CIO's organizing director. ``We know they don't know
too much about unions because the labor movement didn't do a very
good job talking to them or to their parents over the last 25
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions are also seeking to improve ties to the young by
working closely with anti-sweatshop groups on college campuses and
by recruiting hundreds of people in their 20s to work as union
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, young workers were less sanguine about the
booming economy than were older workers _ 45 percent said the
economic climate was good, while 58 percent of workers over 35
described it that way. The survey, which had a margin of error of
4.1 percentage points, found that more than 90 percent of workers
under age 35 said big corporations, top management and stockholders
were doing well. But 42 percent said their own situation was ``just
fair,'' ``not so good'' or ``poor.''
</P>
<P>
   With the percentage of workers belonging to unions slipping to
less than 14 percent now from 35 percent in the 1950s, the labor
movement is acting on many fronts to recruit members. In addition
to focusing on the young, it has made special efforts to reach out
to low-income workers, women and minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders see young workers as a fertile ground for
organizing efforts because while there are 45 million people under
age 35 in the work force _ roughly a third of the total _ just 9
percent of them belong to unions. Surveys also show they are more
favorably disposed to unions than are older workers.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO survey found that 54 percent of young workers said
that, if given a chance, they would definitely or probably vote for
a union, compared with 36 percent for workers over age 35.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the labor movement attribute this difference to the
unhappy experience many older workers have had with unions, but
Adams, the AFL-CIO organizing director, had a different
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people,'' Adams said, ``are thinking in terms of what
will be not an immediate fix, but a long-term fix to build a better
future with job security and pensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders say there is a misguided perception that most
young workers are entrepreneurs at Internet companies or day
traders making overnight fortunes. The AFL-CIO report found that
often, the three-fourths of young workers who lack college degrees
are just scraping by.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 64 percent of workers without college degrees earn
less than $20,000 a year, compared with 32 percent for college
graduates. And 39 percent of nongraduates have employer-provided
health insurance compared with 67 percent for young college
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The labor movement is pushing several organizing drives that
would bring tens of thousands of young people into unions, among
them flight attendants, health-care workers, hotel workers and
graduate teaching assistants at schools from the University of
California to New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Johnson, a 26-year-old doctoral candidate in American
studies at New York University, said the school's 1,500 teaching
assistants need a union because ``it would give us some say in
working conditions like pay and health coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found especially tough conditions for young workers
from minority groups. While 39 percent of young white workers earn
less than $20,000 a year, 48 percent of young blacks workers and 52
percent of young Hispanic workers do. The poll found that 51
percent of young white workers were covered by employer-sponsored
health coverage, considerably more than the 36 percent for young
black workers and 39 percent for young Hispanic workers.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 56 percent of workers from 18 to 24 said
opportunities for advancement were more important than job
security, while 63 percent of workers over 35 said job security was
more important.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
