<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6547 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     08-31 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY CLEVELAND AND NOT L.A.?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twelve days before the start of the pagan orgy that is the NFL
season, I have a simple question: Beyond the obvious, what does
Cleveland have that Los Angeles does not?
</P>
<P>
   It must have something that we're not being told about. Los
Angeles is much bigger. We have more TV sets. Take a straw poll of
NFL owners and you'd get a 31-0 resolution that Super Bowl parties
in L.A. are much more fun. The only thing Cleveland has on L.A. is
a lack of pretense.
</P>
<P>
   So why does Cleveland have a NFL team while we stand on the
sidelines for a fifth straight season? Why did Cleveland return to
the fold after only three years in NFL detox, while we're clinging
to narrowing hopes for a team maybe in 2003?
</P>
<P>
   When Art Modell, theretofore a decent enough guy in the mind of
Ohioans, took his black heart to Baltimore and the cash that
accompanied such franchise shifts, the city of Cleveland responded
with murderous intent and the resolve to litigate the NFL for
years. Our hats go off to the Cleveland politicians who turned
their anger into a tangible asset.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles politicians responded to the departure of the Rams
and Raiders with a sense of relief. L.A. didn't step up with the
same vigor as Cleveland because we were worn out from more than a
decade of dirty dealing with Darth Raider and Madame Ram.
</P>
<P>
   And the league bears a burden for that. NFL execs knew we were
saddled with ne'er-do-wells. Georgia Frontiere inherited her team,
and Al Davis has been working a legal con for 20 years. They've
been just as vexing to Paul Tagliabue as they were the Coliseum
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   So it's wrong that the league supported a hurry-up offense for
the return of the Browns while creating obstacle after obstacle in
L.A., to the point where it is now acting predatory when it comes
to public money. Instead of being on the verge of losing an
expansion opportunity L.A. groups have two-to-four weeks left to
bring the NFL a proposal it will accept we should have been offered
the same kind of deal as Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Roski, the Kings owner who with businessman Eli Broad is
bidding for an expansion team, raised the same question early in
his talks with the league. ``At one time, that was the
discussion,'' said Roski, ``how we could use the Cleveland model to
get a team here.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL executive Roger Goodell was on board this idea, albeit later
in the process. ``We were able to take the risk out (in Cleveland),
then determine the value of the franchise and create a valuable
asset. It's important we do things right in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   And then things changed. The league looked at Cleveland and saw
litigation. It looked at Los Angeles and saw apathy. It may be the
first time someone has ever mistaken L.A.'s ``cool'' for a lack of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (the Rams and Raiders) left, there wasn't a public
outcry,'' said Roski. ``We (meaning L.A.) didn't raise the same
concerns as Cleveland did. If we had, maybe we'd be working in the
same position.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodell said the Cleveland model was complicated. The league
stepped in to start and operate a franchise before an owner was
found. But the only real complication was its novelty.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland officials agreed to build a stadium at a cost of $247
million. The league extended a $100 million line of credit to
assist in construction, $60 million of which would go to Cleveland
directly as the new owner's stake in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The city was able to immediately offset its debt through revenue
streams in the stadium (like PSLs). The league hired an investment
broker to study proposals from interested parties and then conduct
an auction.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Instant franchise. Al Lerner was top bidder at $530
million. According to city officials, Cleveland's debt should be
retired in ten years, and Lerner projects an operating profit in
his first season.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine where L.A. might be today preparing for kickoff? if the
league had been proactive in replacing the Rams and Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1996, a proposed renovation of the Coliseum including
club seats and luxury suites was pegged at $230 million, and that
included parking upgrades. A private marketing firm projected that
L.A. could raise up to $100 million in seed money from PSL sales
for an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   If the league had agreed to finance half of stadium construction
and get reimbursed on the back end from the new owner, L.A. might
have needed all of $75 million in public money the sale of bonds or
incremental tax money to make the Coliseum new and have revenue
streams in place to offset debt.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the projected cost of building a new Coliseum today
stands somewhere between $350 million and $600 million. The league
has refused to submit a magic number for the franchise fee to the
two interested groups. The ``winner,'' if there is one, may be
looking at a $1 billion investment to refurbish the stadium and own
the team. And the issue of public money now supercedes everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   It may be impossible to use the Cleveland model, but the sense
of cooperation under any terms would be a lot better than the
frayed perspectives that now exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a sorry situation that we can't seem to get off
(the ground),'' said Roski. ``We've taken some real setbacks and it
took us some time to get moving again.''
</P>
<P>
   Roski, as dogged a sports owner as you'll ever meet, remains
optimistic that he and Broad can secure a franchise in the
Coliseum. Since Governor Gray Davis' emissary, Bill Chadwick,
excused himself from the fray after the league trashed his parking
plan, Roski has been working with a Davis-appointed consultant on a
plan to use incremental tax money bed and car rental taxes to meet
the league's wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a challenge,'' he said. ``But the Coliseum is still
the most logical site. We're a lot further along there than
anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodell, who has been one of the league's point men in the L.A.
talks, is in Los Angeles today to talk to all of the interested
parties, like Roski, Michael Ovitz, Coliseum officials and
officials from other potential sites, like Carson and Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's expansion committee will meet on September 9, and then
convene another meeting with L.A. representatives Sept. 13, two
days before the league-imposed deadline. But chances are the
deadline will be extended to Oct. 6, which is the next time all 31
owners are scheduled to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles has been through a lot,'' Roski said, noting
Frontiere and Davis, ``and there's a high degree of frustration.
It's why we've taken a PR (public relations) hit. That's why we
have to do this right.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``right way'' would have been the Cleveland way, and it
should have happened three years ago, when the tracks from the
moving vans were still fresh, and the costs a lot cheaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
