<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-INQUIRY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI CHIEF BACKS INDEPENDENT INQUIRY ON WACO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 1st take to recast lede and rewrite to clarify previous text.
No changes in 2nd take. Subs hed to reflect new lede.) (js) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to head off any impression of a conflict of
interest, Director Louis J. Freeh of the FBI wholeheartedly
supports an outside investigation into the bureau's failure to
disclose the use of incendiary devices at the 1993 siege of the
Branch Davidian compound, a bureau spokesman said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official said Attorney General Janet Reno,
too, had all but decided that an exhaustive inquiry totally
independent of the Justice Department was the best way to find out
why the use of the incendiary devices _ heat-generating tear-gas
canisters _ during the April 19, 1993, federal assault on the
sect's compound near Waco, Texas, had been denied for six years.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI spokesman, Tron Brekke, said Freeh believed that the
bureau's credibility was at stake and that the best way to restore
it was by submitting to outside scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would welcome a qualified group of independent
investigators to do that,'' Brekke said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent disclosure that two incendiary tear-gas devices had
been used at Waco _ albeit without success and a good six hours
before flames consumed the cult's compound _ has caused the bureau;
its parent agency, the Justice Department, and Ms. Reno herself
acute embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the devices came to light as agents were being
interviewed in Texas in preparation for a lawsuit arising from the
raid, which ended in about 80 deaths, including that of the cult's
leader, David Koresh.
</P>
<P>
   Reno conceded last week that the disclosure, coming after six
years of statements to the contrary, had caused her to lose
credibility. Officials at the Justice Department and the bureau
have worried aloud that the backtracking would provide grist for
anti-government extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Another signal that the 1993 raid is still an explosive issue in
Washington was a statement Tuesday night that Rep. Henry Hyde of
Illinois, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, is weighing a
proposal to create a joint House-Senate commission to delve into
the episode.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies showed that some cult members died of gunshot wounds,
which the authorities have insisted were self-inflicted, and that
others died as a result of a fire that officials said was started
by the members. Examination of the ashes revealed that gasoline,
charcoal-lighting fluid and camp stove fuel had been spread about.
</P>
<P>
   But the few cult members who survived the fire and many of the
victims' relatives have been skeptical of official conclusions,
including a finding after congressional hearings that there was no
evidence that federal agents started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department officials, who spoke on the condition
that they not be identified, said Freeh and Ms. Reno believe that
nothing new will turn up to alter the official conclusions. But the
attorney general and the FBI director are said to be convinced that
the crisis of confidence is serious enough that only a wholly
outside investigation would be palatable to many who have followed
the Branch Davidian case.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said last week that he was ready to assign 40 bureau
agents to re-interview everyone who was at the cult compound on
April 19, 1993, to determine how the use of heat-generating tear
gas canisters was all but buried in the official paperwork despite
its potential to embarrass the bureau and weaken the government's
position in a wrongful-death suit brought in Texas by some of the
victims' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Tuesday night whether Freeh had changed his
mind about using the 40 bureau agents or whether he had simply
picked them out early on just in case they were needed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday whether the director was in conflict with the
attorney general on the Waco issue, one department official
replied, ``God, no!''
</P>
<P>
   Reno was on her way to Panama Tuesday evening on business and is
to return on Thursday. The department official speculated that Reno
might even make a final decision and have an announcement ready
upon her return, rather than waiting until after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Myron Marlin, a Justice Department spokesman reached at his home
Tuesday night, declined to comment extensively. ``She is still
working through her options,'' Marlin said of Reno. ``She has
pledged to get to the bottom of this, and that's what she will
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general and the FBI director have had policy
differences before, most notably over how to investigate political
fund-raising irregularities arising from President Clinton's 1996
campaign. Freeh strongly favored an independent counsel to conduct
the inquiry but Reno decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Department officials who discussed the Waco episode
Tuesday evening emphasized that there was no such friction between
the two this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Waco controversy has prompted heated reaction in Congress,
as evidenced by Tuesday's signal from Hyde that he might favor a
joint House-Senate commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no final decision'' on the commission, said Sam
Stratman, a House Judiciary Committee spokesman. ``We're trying to
work our way through this and find some solution that might remove
this entire affair from the political fever swamp.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility said to be under discussion was a commission
with subpoena power made up initially of two Republicans and two
Democrats. The four would then pick a fifth, potentially
tie-breaking member.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the staff of the House Government Reform Committee
drew up a new batch of subpoenas Tuesday in its fledgling inquiry
into the Waco matter. A committee spokesman said they would be
served on the FBI, Justice Department and Defense Department. The
committee is said to be interested in what role the Army's secret
Delta Force played in the FBI operation. The Pentagon has said
three Army special forces officers were at the scene but only as
observers.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Government Reform Committee subpoenaed records
held by Texas law-enforcement officials related to the use of the
tear-gas devices in question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
