<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Restored Maddux wins 8-2
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Greg Maddux helped make Monday's loss look like a
freak occurrence and the chipped bone in his wrist like a figment
of everybody's imagination, as he and the Braves answered a blowout
with a blowout in an 8-2 win over the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching for the first time since Aug. 21 after skipping a start
in St. Louis, Maddux pitched seven shutout innings on the way to
his seventh consecutive win. He's now 17-6 on the year, one win shy
of last season's total.
</P>
<P>
   He's still one win behind Jose Lima for the National League
lead, but that was working in his favor, too, as Lima and the
Astros beat the Mets 6-2 on Tuesday for Lima's 18th win.
</P>
<P>
   So the Braves, whose 11-3 loss on Monday snapped a 10-game
winning streak on the season and a seven-game winning streak over
the Reds, were right back where they started this series _ with a 3
1/2 game lead on the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hurt,'' Maddux said. ``I'm not a macho, he-man, stud
muffin. It didn't hurt. ... I was kind of worried more about
swinging the bat than pitching to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux didn't allow a run for the first time in 11 starts, which
prompted him to answer whether it was just a normal start this way:
``It wasn't normal because I didn't give up any runs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the best movement he had the whole year,'' said
catcher Eddie Perez, who did his part offensively with a two-run
homer for a 4-0 lead in the fourth. ``He was throwing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had won his last four starts against the Reds going back
to 1996. For his fifth, he had to outpitch Juan Guzman, winner of
four in five starts since he was traded from the Orioles on July
31.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman had shut out the Braves in a 5-0 win when he was with the
Orioles on June 12 in the middle of the most disastrous weekend of
the Braves season. But these Braves are playing with a lot more at
stake, and they proved it by taking a 5-0 lead on Guzman this time,
the last on the second of three consecutive hits to end his night
in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones chipped in with his 35th home run, which gave him
a new career-high, on a 436-foot two-run shot off Stan Belinda to
give the Braves an 8-0 lead in the seventh inning. That gave the
Braves their most runs scored since the 9-7 14-inning win in
Colorado on Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Guzman) tried to do the same things to us,'' Jones said. ``I
just think maybe the first time we faced him he was on with his
pitches and we were a little bit off. It's a little bit of a
different story when you face somebody the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
