<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6662 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-1S     08-31 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR DEFENDS POLICE SHOOTING OF HAMMER-WIELDING MAN IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 3rd graf and adds new 4th and 5th grafs to include comments
from Dear; subs graf 23 bgng `Busch was committed...' to change
`last night' to `TUESDAY night'; in last graf before optional end,
corrects `Dix Hill' to `DIX HILLS'.) (jt) 
 By JOHN KIFNER and MICHAEL COOPER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani Tuesday defended the fatal
police shooting of a mentally disturbed, hammer-wielding man in the
Borough Park section of Brooklyn, which brought hundreds of angry
Hasidic protesters into the streets of the heavily Orthodox
neighborhood late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be every reason to believe that the police
officers acted in accordance with police procedure, and acted in a
responsible way to save human life,'' the mayor said, cautioning
only that the investigation was still in its early stages.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani moved swiftly to invite City Councilman Noach
Dear and other Jewish leaders from the politically potent Borough
Park neighborhood _ one of his bedrocks of support _ to an early
morning meeting at City Hall, the furor that swelled in the streets
on Monday night continued throughout the day. The killing of the
man, Gidone Busch, was the latest in a series of police shootings
that have put the department under a cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Dear said that the information about the shooting provided by
the Police Department had led him to believe the officers acted
appropriately in the shooting. ``This is something that is very
unfortunate which happened,'' Dear said. ``But we would also like
to thank the Police Department for working together with the
community in containing the situation that happened last night as
best they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the community is asking for is an investigation and at
the end of the investigation, hopefully, we will be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Dov Hikind, who also represents the area and
has frequently been a rival of Dear, was outspoken in his criticism
Tuesday as he had been on the streets Monday night. ``We are told
that the shooting is justified. How? How is a shooting justified.
This is not Dodge City, this is Borough Park, Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Hikind got an unlikely ally in the Rev. Al Sharpton, who also
condemned the shooting, saying ``this city seems to be unable to
deal with people who have medical or mental problems and it seems
to be the policy to shoot first and ask questions later.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Sharpton, who is viewed unfavorably by many Jews in New
York City, attempted to show his support by going to Borough Park,
he had to drive off without getting out of his car, which was
surrounded by a crush of demonstrators shouting `'Anti-semite, go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   As investigators pieced together the deadly encounter _ which
lasted less then 10 minutes from the call to 911 _ a picture
emerged of the dead man, Gidone Busch, as a troubled individual,
frightening to his neighbors, in and out of mental institutions,
who had broken another man's nose with his hammer only last Sunday
and who had been smoking marijuana for hours before he fought with
six police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that the officers followed all standard
procedures for dealing with an emotionally disturbed person _
backing away and calling for help, and trying to subdue him with
pepper spray _ but finally opened fire as a last resort when he
continued to charge them, hitting a sergeant repeatedly with his
hammer and knocking him down.
</P>
<P>
   All 12 of the shots fired by four of the police officers struck
Busch, with injuries to the heart, lungs, liver and intestines, the
autopsy by the Chief Medical Examiner's office found, a
spokeswoman, Ellen Borakove said.
</P>
<P>
   At the City Hall news conference yesterday, Giuliani and Police
Commissioner Howard Safir sought to underscore the danger the
officers faced from Busch's hammer. ``He was in the course of
attacking a police officer with, I think we have a picture of it,
with a hammer _'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   `'A claw hammer,'' Safir interjected.
</P>
<P>
   ``A claw hammer,'' the mayor responded. Although the term ``claw
hammer'' appears to carry a somewhat menacing resonance, it refers
to a standard carpenter's hammer, the ``claw'' part being the two
prongs used to pull out nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``A claw hammer is a very dangerous instrument and had not the
police officers, in my opinion, taken the action, that could have
been planted in one of our sergeant's brains,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did exactly what they were supposed to do, which was to
call Emergency Service and to contain the situation,'' Safir said.
``Unfortunately, Busch came running up the stairs and attacked the
police officers and they had little choice but to defend
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Busch could have been subdued, rather than being shot
to death, Safir replied:
</P>
<P>
   `'When you are being attacked with a claw hammer, you are in
deadly fear of your life. And this isn't the movies. You don't
shoot hammers out of hands, you don't shoot people in the leg. If
you use your weapon...then you shoot to stop the individual who is
exerting that deadly physical force against you. That's what
happened. Had they not, we probably would have had a dead police
officer.''
</P>
<P>
   In Busch's apartment, along with five bags of marijuana, the
police found cryptic scrawls on the walls, including several in
which he made up new acronyms for law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police,'' was broken down to mean ``Pointedly Off-wing
Litigating Intensely Careful Errend deliverers,'' a police official
said. The police were testing the marijuana to see if it might have
been laced with angel dust.
</P>
<P>
   The police also believe that Busch attacked Tamir Khalifa, 21, a
student at the College of Staten Island, on Sunday. Khalifa had
filed a complaint at the 66th Precinct in Borough Park saying that
a man had beaten on his car with a hammer and, when he rolled down
the window to complain, hit him on the nose, breaking it. After the
shooting, the police said, Khalifa picked out Busch from a set of
photographs as his assailant.
</P>
<P>
   Busch was committed at least three times to mental institutions
against his will, something that until recently was very difficult
to do under New York state law, a high ranking police official said
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent commitment was on Dec. 1, 1997, to Stony Brook
Hospital, when he was still living with his parents in Dix Hills,
N.Y.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
