<HEADLINE>
SOWARD PUTS IN EXTRA WORK 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC wide receiver R. Jay Soward is determined to
start the season with a breakout performance against Hawaii on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   So in an uncharacteristic move Tuesday, Soward stayed late after
practice and caught extra passes from quarterbacks Carson Palmer
and Mike Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   Soward needed the extra work, because he has been frequently
dropping passes in the Trojans' past two practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I'm being lazy. As far as my hands, I'm dropping them too
low,'' Soward said. ``I'm not getting my hands up to my eyes. I'm
catching it at my worst point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm catching the easy balls. The long balls I'm going to have
to accelerate and go get it. I've got to get my hands up.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward would like to have a big game to help silence criticism
over his missing summer workouts.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett also has been concerned about Soward's
drops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we know about R. Jay is the concentration level
has to be better so he can play with consistency,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Kickers struggle: Another day of kicking competition between
David Bell and David Newbury accomplished little. Kicking from
between 35-40 yards, the pair went 1 for 6. Newbury converted one
of his three attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been going on all camp,'' Hackett said. ``There's nothing
new. We'll doit again (Wednesday). Yeah, I'm concerned. Real
concerned. We've got to get this resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul on poll: Hackett was perplexed that USC dropped from 19th
to 21st in the Associated Press poll, even though the Trojans don't
play until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you drop two spots without playing a game?'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's ready: Freshman defensive tackle Bernard Riley said his
left ankle is about 80 percent recovered, and he expects to play
Saturday. Riley will play behind sophomore Ryan Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a little weak, but I'm getting there,'' Riley said.
``I feel I'm back where I left off.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie making move: There still has been no decision made at
No. 2 tailback, but Malaefou MacKenzie continues to impress Hackett
as he increases his workload while recovering from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting my stride back right now,'' MacKenzie said.
``I'm just making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rideaux has tests: Freshman cornerback Darrell Rideaux underwent
tests Tuesday for back spasms that kept him out of practice over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said the injury also bothered Rideaux at the state track
championships last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be very cautious,'' Hackett said. ``I think he's
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Where's Brooks? Perhaps the most intriguing player on Hawaii's
roster is 6-5 receiver Attrice Brooks, a highly touted transfer
from City College of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm curious about this Brooks fellow that they're saying can
be the next Randy Moss,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is not listed on Hawaii's depth chart, according to a
Hawaii spokesperson, because he is still learning the offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
