<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-31 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-2N     08-31 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Dix Hills, N.Y.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He thought he was God's last prophet,'' a police report on the
commitment said, adding that he had kicked two holes in a hospital
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Before that he was involuntarily committed on Nov. 3, 1966. The
report on that commitment said he was suffering from ``severe
paranoia'' and that he had been ``making threats against his
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest involuntary commitment that law enforcement
officials have found occurred on June 30, 1996. A report on that
incident said Busch was suffering from ``paranoid schizophrenia''
and ``depression.''
</P>
<P>
   There may have been other commitments, possibly ones in which he
agreed to seek help, the senior law enforcement official said.
</P>
<P>
   Busch voluntarily admitted himself in 1997 to a residence for
men with mental illnesses in Brooklyn operated by the Ohel
Children's Home and Family Services, but checked himself out after
a little more than two months, according to David Mandel, the
organization's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He released himself against our advice,'' Mandel said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Busch's apartment Tuesday afternoon, a woman named
Netanya Ullman, 24, told reporters that she and Busch had recently
become engaged. They had first met, briefly, about five years ago
when studying in the northern Israeli city of Safad, an ancient
center of jewish mysticism, and then ran into each other three
weeks ago at the subway stop at 51st Street and Lexington Avenue,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said he called himself Yisroel Baal Tefilah and was, as she
put it, `'a poet and a dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, the first inkling of the trouble to
come in Borough Park was a 911 call at about 5:40 on Monday
afternoon complaining of two naked men smoking marijuana at 1619
46th Street, where Busch, who is also known as Gary, lives in a
basement apartment. A patrol car found nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But at 6:40, another 911 call reported a man on the street at
the same address, menacing children. Officers Daniel Gravitch and
Martin Sanabria were assigned the call.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement apartment, they saw Busch, brandishing a hammer,
and a second man, identified as Percy Freeman, a sometime drug
dealer, whom the police said had a record of more than a half dozen
arrests and convictions. Freeman later told police he had met Busch
about a week ago in Washington Square Park, that Busch had invited
him to move in.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:45, the first two officers called for an Emergency Service
Unit _ a special weapons and tactics outfit _ and a supervisor. At
6:46, a second car, with Sergeant Terrence O'Brien and Officer
Kieran O'Leary arrived, followed by a car with a second patrol
sergeant, Joseph Memoly and Officer William Loshiavo.
</P>
<P>
   The police say they backed out of the apartment as Busch came at
them screaming and swinging the hammer. Gravitch attempted to use
his canister of pepper spray to subdue Busch, but the police said
it only seemed to enrage him. Officer Gravitch tripped and fell,
and Sgt. O'Brien stepped between them to protect the policeman.
But, the police said, Busch kept hitting the Sergeant with his
hammer on his arm and thigh, until he, too fell down.
</P>
<P>
   That is when Sgt. O'Brien and Officers Memoly, Loshiavo and
Sanabria opened fire, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:49, the police called for an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Chiel J. Tyberg, said Busch had drawn attention to
himself in the neighborhood in recent days by playing loud music
and at one point walking about the streets playing the flute while
wearing a towel as a prayer shawl.
</P>
<P>
   `'He was definitely out of his mind,'' Tyberg said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw the police arrive and repeatedly urge Busch to
put down his hammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was standing on the sidewalk with the hammer in his hand,
swinging it,'' Tyberg said, although he added that from his vantage
point he could not see if any blows landed on the police. ``The
next thing I heard was the shooting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
