<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (smw)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANOTHER LOW-PRICE PLAYER JOINS LONG-DISTANCE FRAY
</P>
<P>
   Undercutting the telecommunications giants, IDT, a small company
based in Hackensack, N.J., plans to begin offering domestic
long-distance calls for 5 cents a minute at any time with a flat
monthly fee of $3.95.
</P>
<P>
   The offer comes a day after AT&AMP;T said it would offer consumers
domestic long-distance calls for 7 cents a minute with a $5.95
monthly fee, intensifying a price war with MCI Worldcom, Sprint and
other companies in the $80 billion long-distance industry.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE INTRODUCES FASTER MACINTOSH
</P>
<P>
   Steven P. Jobs, the interim chief executive of Apple Computer,
introduced the latest, most powerful Macintosh, describing it as a
supercomputer for the desktop. The new Macs were not expected until
next year, but Jobs said shipments of them had begun. Investors
signaled their approval by sending the company's shares up $3.1875,
to $65.25.
</P>
<P>
   DOW FALLS, BUT NASDAQ POSTS GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices declined after a purchasing managers' report
heightened fears that the Federal Reserve might raise interest
rates again. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 84.85 points,
to 10,829.28. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 3.61
points, to 1,320.41. But the Nasdaq composite index, thanks to
strength in technology stocks, gained 26.66 points, or 1 percent,
rising to 2,739.35.
</P>
<P>
   CALPERS TO INVEST IN HEDGE FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The California Public Employees' Retirement System, seeking to
enhance investment return, plans to put up to $11 billion in hedge
funds and what it called other riskier ``hybrid'' investments.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO NOT SPENDING OIL PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Despite a jump in petroleum prices, Mexico will reap only enough
of a windfall to stabilize its accounts this year and plans no
spending sprees, Energy Minister Luis Tellez said. Although Mexico
has earned $1.3 billion more from petroleum exports than budget
planners anticipated, Tellez said, the government is taking a sober
view of the upturn in its oil fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN STRUGGLING WITH PUBLIC DEBT
</P>
<P>
   Japan has some of the worst public accounts in the
industrialized world. The debt situation is so precarious that as
talk of new stimulus plans heats up this fall, there are growing
doubts about how long Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi can continue to
spend furiously in hopes of reviving the economy.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING GROWTH REPORTED
</P>
<P>
   A survey of the nation's purchasing managers, inadvertently
released a day early, showed that the manufacturing sector
continued to grow in August. Manufacturers paid higher prices for
goods and materials, and employment continued to gain.
</P>
<P>
   KAUFMAN &AMP; BROAD SUFFER IRREGULAR LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Home builder Kaufman &AMP; Broad said that it had lost $18.1 million
from unauthorized mortgage trading by an employee.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF EUROPEAN RETAILERS SOAR
</P>
<P>
   The planned merger of the French retailers Carrefour and
Promodes sent shares of other leading European food retailers
sharply higher as investors and analysts wagered on the companies'
chances of merging or being acquired.
</P>
</TEXT>
