<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S RAZZLE   AND FRAZZLE   ON DAY 2 OF THE U.S. OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Argentina, Australia, France, Uruguay)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The U.S. Open Tuesday extracted its usual emotional
baggage from the combatants who took to the wind-blown hardcourts
at the National Tennis Center: frayed nerves, gray hairs, stage
fright and the mean streak that sets in when a defending Grand Slam
champion finds a friend blocking her passage to the second round of
a title defense.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the tournament came down with a case of the blues
after a back injury forced the four-time champion Pete Sampras to
abandon his bid for a record-setting 13th Grand Slam title, his
fellow Americans and even his sixth-seeded British buddy, Tim
Henman, who suffered an atrocious 7-6 (7-1), 6-4, 6-3 loss to
Guillermo Canas of Argentina, seemed to experience repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Martin, seeded seventh, noticed that his gray hairs had
multiplied after four hours and five sets on the Arthur Ashe
Stadium across from the cramping but tenacious Stephane Huet, the
154th-ranked qualifier from France.
</P>
<P>
   The unseeded Michael Chang, a 1996 Open runner-up whose record
in the tournament has since been in steep recession, also needed to
toil through a five-set match to avoid the embarrassment of a
first-round exit against Marcelo Fillippini of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Chang soldiered through, 3-6, 6-3, 2-6, 6-3, 6-2. But another
American veteran, Jim Courier, never got to test his mettle in a
fifth set. The 1991 Open runner-up, now struggling to maintain his
ranking of 36th, was upended, 6-4, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5), by 95th-ranked
Slava Dosedel.
</P>
<P>
   An edgy Lindsay Davenport, the second-ranked defending champion,
had to put her compassion on the back burner and throttle her own
doubles partner, Corina Morariu, 6-0, 6-3, to kick off her title
defense and reactivate the focus and fire that helped her win
Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Like Davenport, seventh-seeded Serena Williams waltzed through
her opening-round match against Kimberly Po, completing a 6-1- 6-0
victory in 49 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Where Davenport and Williams succeeded, the 18-year-old
Alexandra Stevenson, who gained celebrity status as the first woman
qualifier to crash through to a Wimbledon semifinal, did not.
</P>
<P>
   Burdened by the attention that descended on her after Julius
Erving, the former National Basketball Association star, admitted
that he was her father, Stevenson has lost three straight
opening-round matches and failed to pass last week's qualifying
event in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Stevenson was administered a 59-minute hardcourt lesson
by 11th-seeded Nathalie Tauziat, who hammered out a 6-2, 6-2
victory without cracking a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that her footwork on this surface tends to be a liability,
Stevenson had to rely on her booming serve, but Tuesday even that
weapon failed to stabilize her. Tauziat's four aces equaled
Stevenson in the ace stakes, and Stevenson lost her serve four
times while converting neither of the break opportunities allotted
her by the Frenchwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an American at the U.S. Open, there's nothing better than
that, except when you lose,'' the 43d-ranked teen-ager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost to a tough player. I just need to learn some more. I'm
not regretting anything,'' Stevenson said about her tumultuous
tennis coming-out party. ``I would've liked to have kept my private
life private, but some people thought that should have been
discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   After the loss, Stevenson skipped over to the stands and,
exhibiting the sunny body language of a winner, began signing
autographs for a legion of pint-sized fans. For this day, at least,
she proved to be a better actress than player.
</P>
<P>
   Despite emerging on the positive side of his 6-4, 6-3, 6-7
(2-7), 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-3) epic with Huet, Martin was disgusted
with his Open attitude. He was bothered by the wind, bothered by
his tournament-issue freebie haircut, which accentuated his gray
hair, and annoyed that he frittered away four match points in the
third set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an adventure,'' said the usually mild-mannered Martin,
who admitted to cursing his way through the final set's tie
breaker, where he finally ended matters with an ace out wide. ``I
didn't say anything except things that shouldn't be in print.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Henman, who later described his straight-set loss to
Canas as ``an all-time low for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm five in the world at the moment, the highest ranking I've
ever been, and I couldn't be more dissatisfied with my game,'' said
Henman, who called this Open yet another missed moment and
unwelcome proof that he is not yet in the class of the players
ranked just ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   They are Sampras, Andre Agassi, Yevgeny Kafelnikov and Patrick
Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't start knocking on their door, knocking on these
sort of tournaments, then I'm wasting something,'' Henman said.
``My game hasn't changed. I think it's probably _ it's between my
ears. You look at the top four guys at the moment and you're not
going to put me in the same sentence with the way I'm playing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Spain's 13th-seeded Alex Corretja, who reached the final of his
Open tune-up on Long Island on Sunday at the Hamlet Cup, could not
sustain that momentum beyond the first round Tuesday and was upset
by 91st-ranked Wayne Arthurs of Australia, 6-3, 6-4, 1-6, 4-6, 7-6
(8-6). . . . It took only two days for the losers to start griping
about the surface. ``These courts are way too fast,'' said Jim
Courier, who also cast some aspersions on the fans _ Tuesday's
attendance of 28,095 set a record _ in the courtside boxes.
``People in the players' box, two of them, on the cell phone
midmatch. That's pretty cheesy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
