<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP TO 80 FEARED DEAD IN PLANE CRASH IN ARGENTINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ An Argentine Boeing 737 airliner
carrying more than 100 people crashed on takeoff here Tuesday
night, slamming into a golf driving range and catching fire,
officials said. Early reports estimated that as many as 80 people
were killed and at least 23 injured, including motorists and
pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that at least 10 people survived the crash of
LAPA flight 3142 as it took off at 8:30 p.m. for the city of
Cordoba. LAPA is a private airline that provides domestic service
within Argentina and flies to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told local television that one of the engines
exploded, disabling the plane before it could pick up sufficient
speed to lift into the air from Jorge Newberry Airport, which is
situated along the La Plate River on the northeast side of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that 99 passengers were on board, along with
seven crew members. The aircraft exploded only 150 feet from a
gasoline station on the outskirts of the airport, after
successfully veering away from automobile traffic and a restaurant
at a golf range.
</P>
<P>
   Local television reports said the flight had been delayed for
about 20 minutes for repairs on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the turbines giving it speed,'' a survivor, Fabian
Nunez, was quoted as saying by Reuters. ``It rose half a yard into
the air, then all I heard was silence.'' He added: ``Most people
were on fire. Only one door opened.''
</P>
<P>
   An air force spokesman said the plane bounced along the runway
onto a road and dragged passing cars in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injured people have been taken to hospitals, so there are
survivors,'' Mayor Fernando de la Rua told reporters at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the accident could have easily been far worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormous tragedy,'' said Defense Minister Jorge
Dominguez, who arrived at the scene of the crash with President
Carlos Saul Menem and most of the Cabinet. ``We are very, very
concerned. We still have to figure out the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez said that several cars were struck by the crashing
aircraft, ``causing various other deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   City hospitals confirmed receiving 23 injured survivors and two
bodies, accord to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Television images showed bodies on the ground and burning
wreckage at the golf range, adjacent to the airport. The plane
apparently skidded across a busy main road at the end of the runway
and dragged cars in traffic with it to its resting place on the
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five ambulances and 15 fire trucks rushed to the site,
and television reports said the black box was retrieved. Local
hospital officials said many of the survivors suffered major burns
in the crash, while a few people apparently walked away from the
crash with only minor wounds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the flight's pilots reportedly survived the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Identification of the victims and survivors came slowly, as
family members rushed to the Buenos Aires and Cordoba airports
seeking information. Jorge Newberry Airport was closed soon after
the crash, and local flights were forced to land at the Ezeiza
international airport on the outskirts of the capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-31-99 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
